Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-07-22 14:49:33"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	6711	"How is this true when a cop can go undercover to elicit a confession during a suspect's 5A time period? What's the difference?"	"Unwittingly confessing"	"Mult. Choice"		753065	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-22 15:04:49"	1	6711	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  The rule is that once the right to counsel is invoked, the defendant may not be subjected to further interrogation without counsel present. Interrogation is express questioning and any words or actions that the police know or should know are likely to elicit an incriminating response. The question here asks you select the best answer that provides the best factual support in favor of the defendant. In other words, if you want this motion to be granted what additional fact would you want to add to help get the motion granted. Answer choice C establishes that the officers created a situation they knew would elicit incriminating information. Arguably there was no interrogation unless the police were trying to elicit a response by using the parents. Now, one of the exceptions to Miranda is statements made to undercover police. The standard is that Miranda warnings are not required if the suspect being questioned is not aware the interrogator is a police officer. But in that particular situation, the supreme court has decided that it&rsquo;s not a custodial interrogation. In this question, the defendant is in police custody.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-07-22 14:49:33 wrote:  How is this true when a cop can go undercover to elicit a confession during a suspect's 5A time period? What's the difference?"	"Anna Allen"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-07-21 16:18:37"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	8378	"There was a prior question, I don't know the Question ID, explaining that a motion to dismiss on grounds of insufficient service of process does not terminate a defendant's ability to file a motion to dismiss for lack of personal jurisdiction. Am I mistaken on that? Do you know the exception I'm referring to?"	"Motion to dismiss for insufficient service of process"	General		752627	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-21 16:19:11"	1	0	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  I don&rsquo;t know what question you&rsquo;re talking about, but are you talking about waiver? Here is the rule for waiver. Under Rule 12(b), the defenses of lack of personal jurisdiction over the person, insufficiency of process, and insufficiency of service of process must be asserted in a responsive pleading or by motion before a responsive pleading is submitted. A failure to object in accordance with Rule 12 waives the objection. Rule 12(h). Although Rule 12(b) states that a motion asserting one of these defenses must be made before pleading if a responsive pleading is allowed, courts have concluded, based on the waiver provision in Rule 12(h)(1), that a motion to dismiss based on one of these defenses may be filed after an answer is filed if the answer pleads one of these defenses. Although not specifically provided for in the Rules, courts have generally allowed a party to amend a motion to dismiss to raise an omitted ground if the party acts promptly and before the court rules on the original motion. The courts reason that ""an amendment made just a few days following the motion is consistent with the spirit of Rule 12(h) and neither prejudices the plaintiff nor burdens the court.""   I hope this answers your question!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-07-21 16:18:37 wrote:  There was a prior question, I don't know the Question ID, explaining that a motion to dismiss on grounds of insufficient service of process does not terminate a defendant's ability to file a motion to dismiss for lack of personal jurisdiction. Am I mistaken on that? Do you know the exception I'm referring to?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
