Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-07-20 17:27:38"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	8443	"How is this a covenant?"	covenant?			752049	1737	425061	361228	"2022-07-21 10:15:53"	"2022-07-20 18:36:25"	0	0	0	0	"Valentina Palmer"	"  Hi Jonathon,    The call of the question provides &ldquo;If the court finds for the brother, which is the most likely reason?&rdquo; The call indicates that the court did not find this to be a valid real covenant. The answer explanation is referring to the covenant of the brother&rsquo;s promise to pay a percentage of gross receipts from the repair shop, not an enforceable real covenant. As explained in your outline, a covenant linked to real property (i.e. a &ldquo;real covenant&rdquo;) must be in writing, the parties must intend for the rights and duties to run with the land, the covenant must touch and concern the land, and there must be notice and privity. (See pages 86-88 of MBE Real Property Outline). Here, answer choice C is correct because there is no indication that the parties intended the covenant to run with the land. Because the covenant was not created with the requisite intent to run with the land, it is not a valid and enforceable real covenant.  Hope this helps!  -Val     Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-07-20 17:27:38 wrote:  How is this a covenant?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-07-20 13:54:02"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	8444	"The benefited land to a covenant does not need horizontal privity, right? So why is it required here?"	"No horizontal privity for benefited land"	"Mult. Choice"		751836	1737	425061	435564	"2022-07-21 00:09:10"	"2022-07-20 15:33:53"	1	8444	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Jonathan!    For a real covenant to run with the land, it must be1) in writing 2) intended to run with the land 3) must touch and concern the land 4) give notice of the covenant and 5) have privity of estate (horizontal  vertical for burden; vertical only for benefit).       Horizontal privity exists when there is some simultaneous or shared interest in real property between the original parties to the covenant. You will typically see this in land transfers between parties (grantor/grantee; mortgagor/mortgagee; landlord/tenant) where the covenant is in the same instrument (deed, mortgage, or lease). It doesn&rsquo;t have to be a transfer of property, however: horizontal privity exists in easements that benefits both parties (i.e., where two adjoining landowners have a road that runs between their properties, touching both parcels of land).Horizontal privity would also exist among tenants in common who execute and record an agreement related to their property interests.    Even if the parcels the nephews inherited were originally part of one piece of land owned by the uncle, he devised them as separate parcels. In this instance, a covenant not to cut down the trees (a burden, since it is a promise to refrain from doing something) would still not constitute horizontal privity: their agreement would still be one that was merely mutually beneficial to each another as neighbors and only enforceable against one another.    Hope this helps!  Best,  Anna    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-07-20 13:54:02 wrote:  The benefited land to a covenant does not need horizontal privity, right? So why is it required here?"	"Dena Ray"
Wyatte	Jamison	"2022-07-20 00:55:35"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"This is a civil procedure question. What is the difference between a Rule 12 (b) motion to dismiss and a Rule 12(b)(6) motion to dismiss?"	"Civil Procedure Rule 12 b motion"	General		751503	1737	245314	245688	"2022-07-20 19:32:07"	"2022-07-20 09:31:32"	1	0	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Wyatte,  12(b)(6) is just a specific type. Rule 12(b) says that most defenses go in the responsive pleading (i.e. the Answer). But, it says, the following can be made by motion (before the Answer) -- and then it lists seven defenses. So if someone says a ""12(b) motion"" then that's a general reference to any motion that asserts one or more of those defenses. A reference to 12(b)(6) will be specifically referring to a motion to dismiss for failure to state a claim. Similarly, a 12(b)(1) motion would be an MTD for lack of subject-matter jurisdiction, and so on as you'll see in the list.  I'll paste the full sub-section below -- sometimes it makes more sense to read it how it's actually written!  Hope this helps,  -Bryan  The Rule:  (b) How to Present Defenses. Every defense to a claim for relief in any pleading must be asserted in the responsive pleading if one is required. But a party may assert the following defenses by motion:  (1) lack of subject-matter jurisdiction;(2) lack of personal jurisdiction;(3) improper venue;(4) insufficient process;(5) insufficient service of process;(6) failure to state a claim upon which relief can be granted; and(7) failure to join a party under Rule 19.    Wyatte Jamison @ 2022-07-20 00:55:35 wrote:  This is a civil procedure question. What is the difference between a Rule 12 (b) motion to dismiss and a Rule 12(b)(6) motion to dismiss?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Wyatte	Jamison	"2022-07-20 00:44:25"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"In the subject of property, how does the grantor-grantee recording index relates to a wild deed not found in the chain of title?"	"Grantor-Grantee Index"	General		751492	1737	245314	283716	"2022-07-22 17:29:58"	"2022-07-20 09:31:14"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Wyatte,    Fortunately, this is not a heavily tested rule, so don't let this stress you out and distract from the rest of your studies. That said, if you can nail down this rule and spot it on the exam, that gives you an easy point that other students may miss. A ""wild deed"" is any instrument (deed, mortgage, easement, etc.) that is recorded in the right office, but in a way that subsequent purchasers will not be able to find in a typical search of the title index. This puts the deed outside the ""chain of title.""     Most jurisdictions use a grantor-grantee index system for recording deeds. In these systems, when a purchaser wants to search the ""chain of title"" for property they are purchasing, they begin by searching the grantee index for the seller's name. This is to identify when the current seller received the property, and who he received it from. Then they keep following those breadcrumbs, finding the name of each grantor in the grantee index to make sure that no grantor ever claim to transfer property that they had never received. Then, the grantors are searched as grantors to verify that each grantor only transferred the property once, and that there are no ""branches"" in the chain of title that could lead to a competing claim.     Wild deeds generally arise when a grantee records a deed that they received from a grantor who, for whatever reason, was never named in the grantee index. This usually happens when the grantor failed to record their own deed. Let's look at an example:     O sells Blackacre to A on January 1, but A does not record. This means that A will not appear in the grantee index as a grantee of Blackacre at that time. Then, A sells Blackacre to B on February 1, and B records. This means that B will be in the grantee index and A will be in the grantor index on February 1. Then, O conveys Blackacre to C on March 1, who has no notice of the earlier conveyances to A or B. C searches the grantee index for O's name and learns that O has good title. C will also check the grantor index for O's name at any time before March 1, but since A never recorded her deed, O will not appear there. C would have no reason to search the grantor index for A's name, so won't see B's wild deed. Finally, on April 1, A records the deed from O to A. C conveys Blackacre to D on May 1. Now we see why B's deed is essentially lost. D will search the grantee index for C, and will find that C received Blackacre from O on March 1st. D will then search for O in the grantee index before that date to confirm that O had good title. So far, so good. Then, D will look for O and C in the grantor index to confirm that (1) O didn't convey Blackacre before conveying it to C on March 1, and (2) C did not convey it to anyone else between March 1 and May 1. Because D will only be looking for O in the grantor index before March 1, and A recorded on April 1, D will not find that deed. That means D will never know to search the grantor index to see if A ever conveyed the property to anyone, and will never find B' properly recorded deed.     I hope this helps!    Best,          Timothy      Wyatte Jamison @ 2022-07-20 00:44:25 wrote:  In the subject of property, how does the grantor-grantee recording index relates to a wild deed not found in the chain of title?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
