David	Salgado	"2022-07-19 19:19:24"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"Hi,A motion to set aside a judgment for newly discovered evidence must be based on Evidence that was available at the time of trial, right? As I understand it, evidence that was not available at the time of the trail cannot be the basis of the motion. Also, is the same true for motion for a new trial based on Newly discovered evidence?Could you let me know if this the the proper standard?Respectfully,David Salgado"	"Newly Discovered Evidence Standard"			751108	1737	404018	361228	"2022-07-20 16:21:44"	"2022-07-19 19:32:09"	0	0	0	0	"Valentina Palmer"	"  Hi David, I am happy to help you with this question. Both Rule 60(b)(2) and 59(a) permit a party to seek relief from a judgment on the ground of newly discovered evidence.   Under rule 60(b) a court may relieve a party from a final judgment within a reasonable time, and no later than one year following entry of the judgment or order for newly discovered evidence that could not have been earlier discovered with reasonable diligence in time for a new trial under Rule 59(b). A party has one year to file this motion.   Under Rule 59(a), a court may grant a new trial based on newly discovered evidence that existed at the time of the trial that was excusably overlooked and would have altered the outcome of the trial. A party only has 28 days to file this motion.   So, if the evidence comes to light in time to file a motion within a strictly limited 28-day period from the entry of judgment, the party may seek a new trial under Rule 59(a). If the evidence comes to light after the expiration of the 28-day period, but within one year of entry of judgment, the party may seek relief under Rule 60(b)(2).   Hope this helps!  -Val    David Salgado @ 2022-07-19 19:19:24 wrote:  Hi,    A motion to set aside a judgment for newly discovered evidence must be based on Evidence that was available at the time of trial, right? As I understand it, evidence that was not available at the time of the trail cannot be the basis of the motion.     Also, is the same true for motion for a new trial based on Newly discovered evidence?    Could you let me know if this the the proper standard?    Respectfully,    David Salgado"	"Anindita Dutta"
