Nan	Wu	"2022-07-19 16:21:54"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	6361&UWorld#1002216	"Hi Dena,Thanks for the reply!I guess what I am still confused about is that given that both properties were destroyed (i.e., the office and the car were both destroyed), why the businesswoman would be unjustly enriched by the unfinished work while the collector would not be unjustly enriched by the unfinished work?Thank you so much!Best,NanAdmin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE CONTRACTS  SALESQuestion ID: 6361UWorld#1002216Hi Nan –  In 1002216, the painter contracted to paint the businesswoman's office and after one day completed a one-half of the office before it was destroyed by fire. Because it was impossible for the painter to finish, the painter's duties are discharged as are the businesswoman's. Although there is no longer a contract under which to recover, but the painter completed ½ of the work and may recover under quasi-contract in order to prevent unjust enrichment when party receives benefit (here of the painter's time and services) from another who reasonably expects compensation (the painter expected to be compensated for his services.  In 6361, the collector and restorer's contract was for the complete restoration of the exotic vehicle. But the vehicle was destroyed and the collector never received the benefit bargained for – i.e., a completely restored vehicle.  Hope this helps!  Dena   Nan Wu @ 2022-07-16 17:37:22 wrote: Hi,  I have a question regarding question #6361 and UWorld MBE #1002216. I think these two questions are really similar but the answers are different. 6361 prohibits recovery because there is no unjust enrichment while 1002216 allows recovery because there is a quasi-contract. But under both questions, the properties to perform the contract on are destroyed.  Thank you so much!  Best, Nan"	"RE: Unjust enrichment/quasi-contract "		NULL	750921	1737	350171	387010	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-19 16:21:54"	0	0	0	0	"D