Alexander	Ronen	"2022-07-19 14:50:17"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"WILLS AND DECEDENTS' ESTATES"		"Hi,Doesn't the UPC follow the ""harmless error"" rule, rather than substantial compliance, when it comes to balancing the intent of the testator with Wills' Act formalities requirements? On the exam, can we apply either substantial compliance or the harmless error rule in a UPC jurisdiction?Thanks,Alex"	"UPC: Substantial compliance or harmless error"	General		750824	1737	336764	159137	"2022-07-19 19:57:54"	"2022-07-19 19:33:10"	1	0	"WILLS AND DECEDENTS' ESTATES"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Alexander!  Yes. This is the same rule that is cited in the outline as substantial compliance -- Unif. Probate Code &sect; 2-503. Either wording would be fine on the exam.  Steve    Alexander Ronen @ 2022-07-19 14:50:17 wrote:  Hi,  Doesn't the UPC follow the ""harmless error"" rule, rather than substantial compliance, when it comes to balancing the intent of the testator with Wills' Act formalities requirements? On the exam, can we apply either substantial compliance or the harmless error rule in a UPC jurisdiction?Thanks,Alex"	"Anindita Dutta"
Hafsa	Tout	"2022-07-19 11:23:56"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"Hi, I'm wondering why a life tenant is only responsible for paying the interest on an existing mortgage, but not the principal?"	"Life tenant duties to pay interest"	General		750536	1737	400503	435070	"2022-07-20 14:17:47"	"2022-07-19 15:48:00"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"^Krista Corley"	"Hi Hafsa,   The responsibilities for interest payments and principal payments are split between the holder of a life estate and the future interests holder based on the differences between what their ownership interests include. The life estate holder only has an interest in possession of the property for a period of time. Therefore, the life estate holder is only responsible for paying the interest because it represents a payment in exchange for possession of the property over time (the time to pay off a mortgage over a period of years).   By contrast, the future interest holder has an interest in the full value of the property, to be realized at a later date. The future interest holder is responsible for the principal payments because they will eventually receive the full benefit of the principal value of the property. If the life estate holder had to pay for the principal as well as the interest, neither they, nor their heirs, would ever receive the benefit of the value of the property.   I hope this makes sense!   -Krista     Hafsa Tout @ 2022-07-19 11:23:56 wrote:  Hi, I'm wondering why a life tenant is only responsible for paying the interest on an existing mortgage, but not the principal?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-07-19 10:00:40"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"		NULL	"Any advice regarding when clear/convincing evidence is applied?Admin wrote:Hello Ty, I think the easiest simplification would just be that if a party has to show it in court, it's probably a preponderance standard (other than BRD in criminal as you already note). Probable cause/reasonable suspicion aren't burdens of proof exactly, but you seem to have that down. For negligence, it's a duty to act as a reasonably prudent person, not reasonable belief. Also not a burden of proof, but I do understand the difficulty in keeping it all straight. Beyond that, unfortunately there isn't a grand or unified theory I can point you towards to make sense of it all. These things are determined based on how laws/the consitution have developed or are written, and a lot of factors and/or logic go into that to figure out what the best standard is to apply to a situation. That's just the nature of the law. -Bryan  Ty Zhang @ 2022-07-16 15:06:44 wrote: Do you have any advice how I can keep all the standards of proof straight? I know beyond a reasonable doubt applies to criminal and preponderance of the evidence applies to civil cases. And reasonable suspicion for stop and probable cause for arrest/warrant. Reasonable belief for negligence. But almost everything else I'm unsure if their applicability. For example, expert testimony must be reliable based on preponderance of the evidence.Any shortcuts for what standards to apply in certain scenarios, even if they're not full proof?"	"RE: Standards of proof"	General	NULL	750427	1737	421938	245688	"2022-07-19 11:32:54"	"2022-07-19 10:00:40"	1	0	"CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"When the statute says, basically. I suppose there's more or less a majority rule that if you're alleging fraud in a civil case, you have to prove that by clear and convincing evidence. See section (1) on page 8 of your MBE Evidence outline. That's the only thing I can think of off