Yiwei	Jiang	"2022-07-18 22:11:32"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"		"Hello,Is the prosecution allowed introduce specific instances of conduct during the cross-examination of the defendant? Or is the prosecution only allowed to introduce specific instances of conduct during the cross-examination of non-defendant witnesses?Can you also please point to where in the evidence outline I can find this information? Thanks!"	"Cross-examination questioning of specific instances of conduct"	General		750196	1737	347506	435564	"2022-07-19 22:49:40"	"2022-07-19 11:07:12"	1	0	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Yiwei!  I&rsquo;m assuming your question pertains to character evidence for a particular trait. If the defense put on witnesses who testified to the general character of the defendant on a specific character trait, the prosecution can cross examine the witnesses with specific instances of conduct to impeach them. The same would be true if the defendant stated on the stand that they had a particular character trait (i.e. I&rsquo;m a truthful/honest/peaceful person). Then, the prosecution could use specific instances in cross examination to impeach the defendant. More information can be found at Evidence Outline &sect; II.B.2.    Hope this helps!    Best,   Anna  Yiwei Jiang @ 2022-07-18 22:11:32 wrote:  Hello,    Is the prosecution allowed introduce specific instances of conduct during the cross-examination of the defendant? Or is the prosecution only allowed to introduce specific instances of conduct during the cross-examination of non-defendant witnesses?    Can you also please point to where in the evidence outline I can find this information? Thanks!"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Hafsa	Tout	"2022-07-18 20:15:02"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	398	"Hi! I'm confused about when, for the purposes of the Sixth Amendment right to effective counsel and/or right to speedy trial, a court-appointed public defender's error is considered attributable to the state. Is this just issue-specific i.e. attorney error that causes delay is not attributed to the state but other error that meets the Strickland test for IAC would?Thanks!"	"IAC error attributable to state"			750059	1737	400503	436051	"2022-07-19 22:21:22"	"2022-07-18 22:02:40"	0	0	0	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Hafsa,    The Sixth Amendment right to a speedy trial is substantive different from the Sixth Amendment right to effective counsel, so I will address the right to a speedy trial as that is the subject of the MBE practice question you provided.    A trial could be delayed, and it could be attributable to the state even if it appears that it is the fault of the public defender, if the state has interfered with or withheld necessary resources from the public defender&rsquo;s office such that there are significant delays due to understaffing, lack of investigatory resources, policy changes, etc. Here, the facts state that the delay was solely because of the attorney, and not the public defender&rsquo;s office or the state interfering with the public defender&rsquo;s office, so the state did not violate the defendant&rsquo;s right to a speedy trial.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Hafsa Tout @ 2022-07-18 20:15:02 wrote:  Hi! I'm confused about when, for the purposes of the Sixth Amendment right to effective counsel and/or right to speedy trial, a court-appointed public defender's error is considered attributable to the state. Is this just issue-specific i.e. attorney error that causes delay is not attributed to the state but other error that meets the Strickland test for IAC would?    Thanks!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Cate	Baskin	"2022-07-18 16:58:47"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	2245	"Would promissory estoppel be entirely irrelevant to discuss in this answer response? Likely would not be an effective defense for the Chef, but to suggest that he might try to enforce the K based on promissory estoppel (his detrimental reliance on the May 1 negotiation even though that was not enforceable because SoF)."	"Promissory Estoppel/SoF"	Essay		749720	1737	420821	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-18 17:08:26"	1	2245	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Cate,  A promise that the promisor should reasonably expect to induce action or forbearance on the part of the promisee or a third person and that does induce the action or forbearance is enforceable notwithstanding the Statute of Frauds if injustice can be avoided only by enforcement of the promise. The remedy may be limited as justice requires. Restatement (Second) of Contracts &sect; 139. Here, there was nothing in the facts to indicate that chef acted in some manner or refrained from acting in reliance on the oral promise. So, although promissory estoppel can be an exception to the SOF, there&rsquo;s really no factual basis for discussing promissory estoppel here.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey     Cate Baskin @ 2022-07-18 16:58:47 wrote:  Would promissory estoppel be entirely irrelevant to discuss in this answer response? Likely would not be an effective defense for the Chef, but to suggest that he might try to enforce the K based on promissory estoppel (his detrimental reliance on the May 1 negotiation even though that was not enforceable because SoF)."	"Lindsey Hallam"
