Emily	Salomone	"2022-07-18 13:13:00"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	360	"Question 360’s answer states - Answer choice C is correct. Even with a warrant, most states and federal law mandate that a police officer who is making an arrest in a home must generally knock and announce his purpose before entering the home.I thought that knocking and announcing was not required. That it was advised, but would not make evidence inadmissible. Can you explain where I’m misunderstanding?Thank yiou."	"Criminal Procedure Question about Knock and Announce"	"Mult. Choice"		749365	1737	393540	436051	"2022-07-19 17:18:38"	"2022-07-18 19:31:36"	1	360	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Emily,    The relevant section of your Themis MBE Criminal Procedure outline is section (I)(C)(3)(e)(3) &ndash; Manner of Execution &ndash; Knock and Announce. Both the federal government and most states require that law enforcement officials who are making an arrest or performing a search pursuant to a warrant announce their purpose before entering. For a minority of states, this rule is advised upon but not required.    It is my theory that the knock and announce rule is perpetually confusing for law students because it is a rule where, if it is broken, generally nothing happens. While it is required, failing to knock and announce will have no effect on the admissibility of evidence or implicate any of the suspect's Constitutional rights. In other words, failing to knock and announce will have no impact on the criminal case. Here, while the police officer technically failed to properly execute the arrest warrant, there are no consequences for failing to properly execute the warrant in this way.     Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Emily Salomone @ 2022-07-18 13:13:00 wrote:  Question 360&rsquo;s answer states - Answer choice C is correct. Even with a warrant, most states and federal law mandate that a police officer who is making an arrest in a home must generally knock and announce his purpose before entering the home.I thought that knocking and announcing was not required. That it was advised, but would not make evidence inadmissible. Can you explain where I&rsquo;m misunderstanding?Thank yiou."	"Anindita Dutta"
Cate	Baskin	"2022-07-18 12:19:35"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	"Question 5974"	"I'm confused as to how the father in this question is not an ""anticipated"" trespasser, and therefore the owner of the land has a duty to warn about hidden dangers (such as falling in the hole). The answer description explains that the father was an undiscovered trespasser, which is true given the owner was not home at the time, but the fact pattern clearly indicates that the ball ""regularly"" sailed over the fence into the neighbor's yard, so much so that the father was told not to enter the land. How does this not make the father an anticipated trespasser, subjecting the owner to a duty to warn of hidden dangers? Thanks."	"Anticipated Trespasser"	"Mult. Choice"		749269	1737	420821	245688	"2022-07-18 22:56:49"	"2022-07-18 18:08:29"	1	5974	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Cate,  The fact pattern only states that the son often threw the ball too high. It doesn't say that throwing the ball over the fence had been a regular occurrence. If that additional fact were there, and if the neighbor knew about it, I think it would turn out the way you're looking at it, but I don't think we have enough here to establish that the father was an anticipated trespasser.  The standard for an anticipated trespasser is at section (b) on page 23 of your MBE Torts outline:  ""When a land possessor should reasonably know that trespassers are consistently entering his land (e.g., frequent trespassers using a footpath to cut across the corner of the property)...""  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Cate Baskin @ 2022-07-18 12:19:35 wrote:  I'm confused as to how the father in this question is not an ""anticipated"" trespasser, and therefore the owner of the land has a duty to warn about hidden dangers (such as falling in the hole). The answer description explains that the father was an undiscovered trespasser, which is true given the owner was not home at the time, but the fact pattern clearly indicates that the ball ""regularly"" sailed over the fence into the neighbor's yard, so much so that the father was told not to enter the land. How does this not make the father an anticipated trespasser, subjecting the owner to a duty to warn of hidden dangers? Thanks."	"Anindita Dutta"
