David	Salgado	"2022-07-18 00:50:55"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"		"Hi,It's my understanding that an officer does not have to give Miranda warnings during a terry stop because the terry stop is not considered to be a time when the suspect is in custody. Could you let me know if that is accurate?Best, David Salgado"	"Terry Stops and Miranda"	General		748900	1737	404018	395418	"2022-07-19 11:33:20"	"2022-07-18 14:21:41"	1	0	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Andreanna Jones (Ed)"	"Good morning David,     Great question. You are correct. Under the Supreme Court case of Howe v. Fields, the Court held that the temporary and relatively nonthreatening detention involved in a Terry stop does not constitute Miranda custody. I hope this helps !    Best,   Ann    David Salgado @ 2022-07-18 00:50:55 wrote:  Hi,    It's my understanding that an officer does not have to give Miranda warnings during a terry stop because the terry stop is not considered to be a time when the suspect is in custody. Could you let me know if that is accurate?    Best,    David Salgado"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
ericka	juarez	"2022-07-17 21:37:55"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	7304	"I thought that as long as one occupant of the house consented to the search, there was no violation. Officers in other cases have waited until the non-consenting party left just to come back and ask the other party for consent. I'm confused. Is it because it's a room mate arrangement?"	"co-occupied spaces and warrantless searches."	"Mult. Choice"		748798	1737	202255	159081	"2022-07-18 15:33:15"	"2022-07-18 10:41:46"	1	7304	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Dan Smith (Ed)"	"Hi, Ericka,  Good question! The key here is that a third-party can consent to the search of jointly-controlled property, but not to a search of the defendant's solely-controlled property - i.e., the defendant's room. In this case, the roommate consented to the search of the whole apartment, including the defendant's room. The defendant's room belonged to the defendant and was not jointly-controlled with the roommate, in contrast to other areas in the apartment like the living room or kitchen, which would be considered jointly-controlled.  Moreover, even if joint control existed over the defendant's bedroom due to the roommate paying the full amoutn of rent, the call of the question asks whether the defendant had standing - meaning, did the defendant have a reasonable expectation of privacy in his room? The defendant clearly has such an expectation of privacy, and though his challenge may not be successful, the defendant has standing to challenge.  I hope this helps! Best of luck on the exam!  Best,  Dan    ericka juarez @ 2022-07-17 21:37:55 wrote:  I thought that as long as one occupant of the house consented to the search, there was no violation. Officers in other cases have waited until the non-consenting party left just to come back and ask the other party for consent. I'm confused. Is it because it's a room mate arrangement?"	"Diana Brown"
