Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-17 17:28:35"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	3270	"But why is the law here not narrowly tailored? It just says twice that the law isn't narrowly tailored but does not explain why?"	"con law"	"Mult. Choice"		748551	1737	413801	245688	"2022-07-18 19:04:47"	"2022-07-17 22:05:42"	1	3270	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Nick,  Because it will extend to speech directed at adults rather than just minors, so it will prohibit substantially more speech than the governmental interest justifies. The thousand foot radius of a school would effectively prohibit advertisements anywhere in many densely-populated places. The fact pattern here is taken directly from Lorillard v. Reilly, see the grey box in section 5. Commercial Speech on page 80 of your MBE Con Law outline.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-17 17:28:35 wrote:  But why is the law here not narrowly tailored? It just says twice that the law isn't narrowly tailored but does not explain why?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-17 14:56:23"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	369	"If the officer would have immediately given the defendant his Miranda warnings, would both pieces of evidence be admissible?"	"crim pro"			748395	1737	413801	436051	"2022-07-18 19:49:03"	"2022-07-17 21:46:26"	1	369	0	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Nick,    The relevant section of your Themis MBE Criminal Procedure outline is section (III)(A)(5)(a) &ndash; Waiver. A defendant who receives proper Miranda warnings will be consider sufficiently apprised of his Sixth Amendment rights and the consequences of abandoning those rights. So long as the defendant makes a knowing, voluntary, and intelligent waiver of his right to counsel, the police would be able to interrogate the defendant in the absence of his attorney, and the evidence would likely be admissible.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-17 14:56:23 wrote:  If the officer would have immediately given the defendant his Miranda warnings, would both pieces of evidence be admissible?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-17 14:34:16"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	8577	"Is the same true for criminal actions made by a president before they took office?"	"con law"	"Mult. Choice"		748383	1737	413801	245688	"2022-07-18 00:02:41"	"2022-07-17 21:43:41"	1	8577	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Nick,  There's no case law that has addressed that, but the president's immunity due to his position will probably prevent the bringing of such charges until he or she leaves office. I can tell you that under international law and English law that would be the case, and I'm fairly certain that it would be if SCOTUS ever had to opine on it.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-17 14:34:16 wrote:  Is the same true for criminal actions made by a president before they took office?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Julius	Zavala	"2022-07-16 22:09:01"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	7244	"1) I am unclear on whether inconsistent statements from plea negotiations may be offered to impeach a defendant during trial. Question 7244 made clear that those types of statements would not be admissible if made during a compromise negotiation.2) The restaurant owner's statement is a compromise agreement rather than an offer to pay medical expenses because the offer to pay medical expenses was conditioned on the critic not bringing legal action. Is that correct? And is there any other distinction between a compromise agreement and an offer to pay medical expenses?"	"Compromise Negotiations vs Plea Negotiations"	"Mult. Choice"		748089	1737	336927	245688	"2022-07-17 16:18:15"	"2022-07-17 13:50:33"	2	7244	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Julius,  They aren't admissible for impeachment purposes, they're protected. They can be admissible in a subsequent prosecution for perjury (e.g. if you say something at the plea negotiation, then contradict that in trial testimony, you might get prosecuted for perjury at the trial). There's a separate section that deals with this, compare section B.2. on page 37 of your MBE evidence outline with section B.4. on the next page.  (2) Yes, it's a compromise offer because of that. A bare offer to pay medical expenses with no seeking to offer that in order to resolve or settle the matter would still be protected, but statements surrounding it would not have protection without there being an attempt to settle or compromise the claim.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Julius Zavala @ 2022-07-16 22:09:01 wrote:  1) I am unclear on whether inconsistent statements from plea negotiations may be offered to impeach a defendant during trial. Question 7244 made clear that those types of statements would not be admissible if made during a compromise negotiation.    2) The restaurant owner's statement is a compromise agreement rather than an offer to pay medical expenses because the offer to pay medical expenses was conditioned on the critic not bringing legal action. Is that correct? And is there any other distinction between a compromise agreement and an offer to pay medical expenses?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Kyla	Randle	"2022-07-16 22:05:35"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2614	"For easement by implication, does the new owner of the dominant estate have to make prior use in an open and continuous manner or is that referring to the previous owner. For example, in this question it says that Sue used the road in an open and continuous manner for 18 years. I though that, Dan would have to use the easement in an open and continuous manner AFTER he purchased the property from sue to acquire the easement by implication or is it referring to previous owners ""prior use"""	"Easement by implication  "	Essay		748086	1737	336618	159111	"2022-07-18 14:58:27"	"2022-07-17 17:35:20"	1	2614	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Kathleen Schandler"	"Hi Kyla,  An easement by implication is created by operation of law rather than by written instrument. It is an exception to the Statute of Frauds. There are only three types of implied easements:  1) an intended easement based on a use that existed when the dominant and servient estates were severed,  2) an easement implied from a recorded subdivision plat or profit a prendre,  and  3) an easement by necessity. This easement terminates when the necessity does.    There should be an analysis for 1) and 3) for this hypo.    Your ""open and notorious"" language sounds like you may be talking about acquiring an easement by prescription, which is analogous to acquiring property by adverse possession. Many of the requirements are the same.  Something to think about is an easement by necessity whose necessity has ended, the easement would end as well, but if use continues then the use is adverse from that point forward.  I hope this helps!  Best,  Katie    I hope this helps! Regards, Katie    Kyla Randle @ 2022-07-16 22:05:35 wrote:  For easement by implication, does the new owner of the dominant estate have to make prior use in an open and continuous manner or is that referring to the previous owner. For example, in this question it says that Sue used the road in an open and continuous manner for 18 years. I though that, Dan would have to use the easement in an open and continuous manner AFTER he purchased the property from sue to acquire the easement by implication or is it referring to previous owners ""prior use"""	"Lindsey Hallam"
Kyla	Randle	"2022-07-16 20:09:16"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	4985	"I was wondering if for the first question it would be incorrect to do a negligence per se analysis? For example, I stated that she did not breach her duty because she was not speeding, but she could still be held liable for failure to exercise reasonable care"	"Torts essay"	Essay		748034	1737	336618	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-17 13:43:31"	1	4985	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Kyla,  The elements of negligence per se are i) A criminal or regulatory statute (or an administrative regulation or municipal ordinance) imposes a specific duty for the protection of others; ii) The defendant violates the statute by failing to perform that duty; iii) The plaintiff is in the class of people intended to be protected by the statute; and iv) The harm is of the type the statute was intended to protect against. You could discuss negligence per se, but the sample answer notes that speed limits are established for ideal road and driving conditions, not hazardous weather conditions. Also, compliance with a statute does not mean, as a matter of law, a person cannot be found negligent. Generally, compliance with a statute, a regulation, or an ordinance does not prove the absence of negligence. Here, the thinking is a reasonable person would have slowed down more than just 10 mph below the posted speed limit.   Hope this helps!  Lindsey     Kyla Randle @ 2022-07-16 20:09:16 wrote:  I was wondering if for the first question it would be incorrect to do a negligence per se analysis? For example, I stated that she did not breach her duty because she was not speeding, but she could still be held liable for failure to exercise reasonable care"	"Lindsey Hallam"
kathryn	hayes	"2022-07-16 17:50:09"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	"7741 & 7326"	"Hello,So I am having some confusion in criminal law regarding when someone has an honest belief that an item that another person has is theirs. In question 7741, the answer states that although the person had an honest belief, the claim of right cannot serve as a justification for robbery because there was the use oof force or intimdation to gaine possession of the property from the person or presence of the victim. However, in question 7326, the answer states ""A mistake of fact is a defense to a specific-intent crime, even if the mistake is unreasonable.Here, the aficionado had a reasonable and honest belief that the bicycle in question was his bicycle. Consequently, he did not have the specific intent to take the personal property of another and therefore did not commit larceny,""  could not be guilty of the greater offense of robbery.I just am confused on why these answers are different and how to answer a question regarding robbery when there is an honest belief that the property belonged to you.Thank you in advance!"	"Honest Belief to theft crimes"	"Mult. Choice"		747911	1737	351798	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-16 19:59:20"	1	7741	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Kathryn,  In both MBEs there was a reasonable belief that the property was theirs. They key difference is one is repayment for a debt. In 7326, the aficionado had a reasonable and honest belief that the bicycle in question was his bicycle. Consequently, he did not have the specific intent to take the personal property of another and therefore did not commit larceny. In 7741, we are dealing with a repayment of debt. If a defendant takes property with the honest belief that she is entitled to the property as repayment of a debt (i.e., a claim of right), then the taking does not constitute larceny. However, most states hold that debt collection is not a justification for what would otherwise amount to robbery. A ""claim of right"" is a narrow concept that is typically used in the context of repayment of a debt. If a person takes property with the honest belief that it is repayment of a debt that is owed to them, then they can use that as a defense to larceny. However, most jurisdictions draw the line there. If a defendant uses force or a threat of force to collect a debt, the claim of right is simply not available as a defense for the subsequent robbery charge. This rule is a matter of public policy because states do not want people to use force to collect on monetary debts.   Hope this helps!  Lindsey     kathryn hayes @ 2022-07-16 17:50:09 wrote:  Hello,    So I am having some confusion in criminal law regarding when someone has an honest belief that an item that another person has is theirs. In question 7741, the answer states that although the person had an honest belief, the claim of right cannot serve as a justification for robbery because there was the use oof force or intimdation to gaine possession of the property from the person or presence of the victim. However, in question 7326, the answer states ""A mistake of fact is a defense to a specific-intent crime, even if the mistake is unreasonable.Here, the aficionado had a reasonable and honest belief that the bicycle in question was his bicycle. Consequently, he did not have the specific intent to take the personal property of another and therefore did not commit larceny,""  could not be guilty of the greater offense of robbery.    I just am confused on why these answers are different and how to answer a question regarding robbery when there is an honest belief that the property belonged to you.    Thank you in advance!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Nan	Wu	"2022-07-16 17:37:22"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	6361&UWorld#1002216	"Hi,I have a question regarding question #6361 and UWorld MBE #1002216. I think these two questions are really similar but the answers are different. 6361 prohibits recovery because there is no unjust enrichment while 1002216 allows recovery because there is a quasi-contract. But under both questions, the properties to perform the contract on are destroyed.Thank you so much!Best,Nan"	"Unjust enrichment/quasi-contract "			747900	1737	350171	387010	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-16 22:27:06"	0	0	0	0	"Dena Ray (Ed)"	"Hi Nan &ndash;    In 1002216, the painter contracted to paint the businesswoman's office and after one day completed a one-half of the office before it was destroyed by fire. Because it was impossible for the painter to finish, the painter's duties are discharged as are the businesswoman's. Although there is no longer a contract under which to recover, but the painter completed &frac12; of the work and may recover under quasi-contract in order to prevent unjust enrichment when party receives benefit (here of the painter's time and services) from another who reasonably expects compensation (the painter expected to be compensated for his services.    In 6361, the collector and restorer's contract was for the complete restoration of the exotic vehicle. But the vehicle was destroyed and the collector never received the benefit bargained for &ndash; i.e., a completely restored vehicle.    Hope this helps!    Dena      Nan Wu @ 2022-07-16 17:37:22 wrote:  Hi,    I have a question regarding question #6361 and UWorld MBE #1002216. I think these two questions are really similar but the answers are different. 6361 prohibits recovery because there is no unjust enrichment while 1002216 allows recovery because there is a quasi-contract. But under both questions, the properties to perform the contract on are destroyed.    Thank you so much!    Best,  Nan"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-07-16 15:06:44"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"			"Do you have any advice how I can keep all the standards of proof straight? I know beyond a reasonable doubt applies to criminal and preponderance of the evidence applies to civil cases. And reasonable suspicion for stop and probable cause for arrest/warrant. Reasonable belief for negligence. But almost everything else I'm unsure if their applicability. For example, expert testimony must be reliable based on preponderance of the evidence.Any shortcuts for what standards to apply in certain scenarios, even if they're not full proof?"	"Standards of proof"	General		747791	1737	421938	245688	"2022-07-18 16:58:02"	"2022-07-18 14:18:44"	1	0	"CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Ty,  I think the easiest simplification would just be that if a party has to show it in court, it's probably a preponderance standard (other than BRD in criminal as you already note).  Probable cause/reasonable suspicion aren't burdens of proof exactly, but you seem to have that down.  For negligence, it's a duty to act as a reasonably prudent person, not reasonable belief. Also not a burden of proof, but I do understand the difficulty in keeping it all straight.  Beyond that, unfortunately there isn't a grand or unified theory I can point you towards to make sense of it all. These things are determined based on how laws/the consitution have developed or are written, and a lot of factors and/or logic go into that to figure out what the best standard is to apply to a situation. That's just the nature of the law.  -Bryan    Ty Zhang @ 2022-07-16 15:06:44 wrote:  Do you have any advice how I can keep all the standards of proof straight? I know beyond a reasonable doubt applies to criminal and preponderance of the evidence applies to civil cases. And reasonable suspicion for stop and probable cause for arrest/warrant. Reasonable belief for negligence. But almost everything else I'm unsure if their applicability. For example, expert testimony must be reliable based on preponderance of the evidence.Any shortcuts for what standards to apply in certain scenarios, even if they're not full proof?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Julius	Zavala	"2022-07-16 14:48:03"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	7539	"Can a defendant be questioned about specific acts regarding character on cross-examination if the defendant is acting as a character witness on their own behalf?"	"Defendant Character Testimony + Specific event evidence"	General		747770	1737	336927	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-16 16:57:09"	1	7539	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Julius,  Here defendant ""opened the door"" to character evidence when ""the defense called a character witness who testified that the defendant had a reputation as a peaceful and nonviolent person."" Once the defendant puts their character in issue by having a witness testify as to the opinion of the defendant or the defendant's reputation, the prosecution may rebut in the following manner: Cross-Examination The prosecution may test the character witness by cross-examination regarding the basis for his opinion or knowledge of the reputation he has testified about. In most jurisdictions, one is allowed to inquire on cross-examination whether the reputation witness has heard of or knows particular instances of the defendant's misconduct pertinent to the trait in question. Note that if the witness denies knowledge of these specific instances of conduct, the prosecutor may not prove them by extrinsic evidence. he is limited to inquiry on cross-examination. Testimony of Other Witnesses as to Defendant's Bad Reputation The prosecution may rebut the defendant's character evidence by calling qualified witnesses to testify to the defendant's bar reputation or their opinion of the defendant's character for the particular trait involved. Here the defendant then takes the stand. So this is a new other witness, so the prosecution can only ask about reputation or opinion. If the prosecution had as the ""character witness"" on cross, they could have asked if that witness knew of or heard of particular instances. Now, the defendant does not &ldquo;open the door&rdquo; to character evidence merely by taking the stand, but as a witness, the defendant is subject to impeachment. Generally, a defendant's own testimony is not permissible as character evidence through opinion or reputation testimony, so this situation where a testifying defendant ""opens the door"" does not occur. Nevertheless, a defendant cannot be cross-examined about specific instances of conduct generally. However, when a defendant's bad act is not being used to show the defendant's criminal propensity but is being used for another purpose (i.e., MIMIC evidence), such instances of conduct may be admissible for that purpose.   I hope this helps!  Lindsey     Julius Zavala @ 2022-07-16 14:48:03 wrote:  Can a defendant be questioned about specific acts regarding character on cross-examination if the defendant is acting as a character witness on their own behalf?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Stacy	Massey	"2022-07-16 14:36:30"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	7177	"For this question, I got the answer correct but perhaps for the wrong reason. I thought it was the P+I clause that would make this unconstitutional because it impermissibly discriminates against an out of stater. But the video explanation says it implicates the Dormant commerce clause, not P+I.My guess is that P+I is implicated for individuals (albeit individuals engaged in economic activity) and since this question involves a manufacturer, it goes under the commerce clause? Is that right or is there another way I should be thinking about this?"	"Dormant CC & P+I"	"Mult. Choice"		747755	1737	396230	245688	"2022-07-17 18:54:48"	"2022-07-16 16:55:08"	1	7177	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Stacy,  Yes, I think that's the correct reason. It isn't entirely clear that these manufacturers are necessarily entities rather than individuals, but I think that's a fair inference based on the discussion of them moving their headquarters from one state to another -- you wouldn't normally say an individual has a headquarters.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Stacy Massey @ 2022-07-16 14:36:30 wrote:  For this question, I got the answer correct but perhaps for the wrong reason. I thought it was the P+I clause that would make this unconstitutional because it impermissibly discriminates against an out of stater. But the video explanation says it implicates the Dormant commerce clause, not P+I.    My guess is that P+I is implicated for individuals (albeit individuals engaged in economic activity) and since this question involves a manufacturer, it goes under the commerce clause? Is that right or is there another way I should be thinking about this?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Samuel	Gordon	"2022-07-16 13:15:30"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	6318	"The explanation for this question seemed contradictory on whether the felony needed to be completed for a defendant to be successfully charged for felony murder and I was hoping for clarification on the issue.Answer choice B is correct. Felony murder is an unintended killing proximately caused by and during the commission or attempted commission of an inherently dangerous felony. To convict a defendant of felony murder, the prosecution must establish the underlying felony and that the defendant committed that felony. Theft crimes, such as robbery, are specific intent crimes. If the man did not intend to actually take property from his girlfriend, then he has a defense to the crime of robbery. If the man could not be found guilty of the underlying felony, then he could not be found guilty of the crime of felony murder. .....Answer choice C is incorrect because the underlying felony does not need to be completed in order for a defendant to be guilty of felony murder."	"Is a felony required to be completed for the defendant to be charged with felony murder?"	"Mult. Choice"		747667	1737	336226	245688	"2022-07-16 20:35:32"	"2022-07-16 16:42:42"	1	6318	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Samuel,  Felony murder is a killing proximately caused by and during the commissionor attempted commission of a felony.  So you don't have to be able to be convicted of the completed felony -- e.g. if you try to rob someone, and fail, but kill someone during the robbery -- it's still felony murder.  But if neither the thing you did, nor the thing you were attempting to do were felonies, then there can't be a predicate felony or attempted felony to give rise to felony murder. Another form of homicide may be appropriate.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Samuel Gordon @ 2022-07-16 13:15:30 wrote:  The explanation for this question seemed contradictory on whether the felony needed to be completed for a defendant to be successfully charged for felony murder and I was hoping for clarification on the issue.    Answer choice B is correct. Felony murder is an unintended killing proximately caused by and during the commission or attempted commission of an inherently dangerous felony. To convict a defendant of felony murder, the prosecution must establish the underlying felony and that the defendant committed that felony. Theft crimes, such as robbery, are specific intent crimes. If the man did not intend to actually take property from his girlfriend, then he has a defense to the crime of robbery. If the man could not be found guilty of the underlying felony, then he could not be found guilty of the crime of felony murder. .....Answer choice C is incorrect because the underlying felony does not need to be completed in order for a defendant to be guilty of felony murder."	"Lindsey Hallam"
