Sarah	Flagel	"2022-07-15 12:04:39"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	4895	"Dear Professor,I have in my outline that claims by multiple Plaintiffs against one Defendant cannot be aggregated to reach the minimal requirement of over $75K for diversity jurisdiction, unless supplemental jurisdiction applies. Here, it looks like supplemental jurisdiction applies, since there is complete diversity and the causes of action arise from a common nucleus of operative fact.Having seen the answer to this question, it looks like I'm missing something. Please clarify.Thanks,Sarah"	"Aggregation of claims - supplemental jx"	"Mult. Choice"		746585	1737	350016	245688	"2022-07-15 23:41:37"	"2022-07-15 14:43:46"	1	4895	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Sarah,  There's no diversity jurisdiction for either plaintiff because even the owner of the car is claiming only $75k -- diversity jurisdiction requiresmore than $75k in controversy.  Further, the amounts cannot be aggregated to get over that amount, because multiple plaintiffs cannot aggregate their claims unless they are enforcing a single right or title. Here, each plaintiff is only enforcing their own property right in their respective automobile. Enforcing a single right or title would involve, for example, two co-owners of a single car suing for damage to that car.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Sarah Flagel @ 2022-07-15 12:04:39 wrote:  Dear Professor,  I have in my outline that claims by multiple Plaintiffs against one Defendant cannot be aggregated to reach the minimal requirement of over $75K for diversity jurisdiction, unless supplemental jurisdiction applies. Here, it looks like supplemental jurisdiction applies, since there is complete diversity and the causes of action arise from a common nucleus of operative fact.  Having seen the answer to this question, it looks like I'm missing something. Please clarify.  Thanks,  Sarah"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Hyojeong	Son	"2022-07-15 10:27:23"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"Hello,With respect to the rule regarding when the class is closed (in the class gift situation), what is the default rule for MBE? Is it rule of convenience?Thank you"	"Default rule for the MBE"	General		746476	1737	337791	369848	"2022-07-18 10:50:04"	"2022-07-15 12:56:04"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Pamela Prieto"	"Hi Hyojeong,  The rule of convenience closes the class when any member of the class becomes entitled to immediate possession of the propertyonly when there is no closing date (or when there is no date until when it should remain open). Yes, the rule of convenience is the default rule for the MBE in class gift cases where it is applicable.When it applies, the rule bad as to one bad as to all does not apply. Unless told otherwise, the rule of convenience should always be applied to class gifts that have no closing date.  Hope this clarifies things!  Best,  Pam    Hyojeong Son @ 2022-07-15 10:27:23 wrote:  Hello,    With respect to the rule regarding when the class is closed (in the class gift situation), what is the default rule for MBE? Is it rule of convenience?    Thank you  "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Max	Lupin	"2022-07-15 08:28:28"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"Hello, as you’re probably aware, this term, in Kennedy v. Bremerton School District, Justice Kennedy, writing for the Court, wrote that the Court “long ago abandoned Lemon and its endorsement test offshoot.” While I realize that we are not responsible for the Court’s holdings this term, this opinion implies (or holds?) that the test had been abandoned before this term. Given that fact, is it still the best approach to apply the Lemon test to establishment clause questions?Thank you!"	"Lemon Test & Establishment Clause"	General		746400	1737	418912	283716	"2022-07-19 21:01:58"	"2022-07-15 08:33:17"	1	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Max,    Yes, theLemontest, found at XVII.A.1. of the MBE Constitutional Law outline, is good law for purposes of the bar. Note the gray box found at the same section that states the following:    ""Though still applied, the Lemon test has often been modified or set aside in the Supreme Court&rsquo;s more recent Establishment Clause cases. See, e.g., Am. Legion v. Am. Humanist Ass'n, 588 U.S. ___, 139 S. Ct. 2067 (2019) (presumption of constitutionality for longstanding monuments, symbols, and practices); Good News Club v. Milford Central School, 533 U.S. 98 (2001) (permitting Christian organization to use public school cafeteria for after-school meetings did not violate Establishment Clause); Bd. of Educ. v. Grumet, 512 U.S. 687 (1994) (creation of school district to serve distinctive religious population violated Establishment Clause).""    Keep up the good work!    Best,          Timothy    Max Lupin @ 2022-07-15 08:28:28 wrote:  Hello, as you&rsquo;re probably aware, this term, in Kennedy v. Bremerton School District, Justice Kennedy, writing for the Court, wrote that the Court &ldquo;long ago abandoned Lemon and its endorsement test offshoot.&rdquo; While I realize that we are not responsible for the Court&r