Kaycee	Miller	"2022-07-14 21:39:09"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	CORPORATIONS		"Hi - I have a question about the director's notice to meet.In the outline, it says that a regular meeting may be held without notice and a director may waive notice. Could you explain this concept?So - a director is not needed to be at the meeting, or a director could still object for lack of notice. Without notice, would any proposal made during the regular meeting turn void or improper?"	"Director - Notice - Regular Meeting "	General		746186	1737	357799	159137	"2022-07-15 12:47:58"	"2022-07-14 22:08:50"	1	0	CORPORATIONS	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Kaycee!  No. This just means that formal written notice doesn't have to be sent before the meeting, as it would be for a special meeting of the directors. Regular meetings don't need notice because they are ""regular."" They occur at a fixed time and place every week or month, so directors already know to show up. Usually the bylaws set the fixed time and place.  Hope this helps!  Steve    Kaycee Miller @ 2022-07-14 21:39:09 wrote:  Hi - I have a question about the director's notice to meet.    In the outline, it says that a regular meeting may be held without notice and a director may waive notice. Could you explain this concept?  So - a director is not needed to be at the meeting, or a director could still object for lack of notice. Without notice, would any proposal made during the regular meeting turn void or improper?  "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-07-14 20:58:48"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"WILLS AND DECEDENTS' ESTATES"		"I'm confused about the extent of the conscious presence test. Do witnesses/testators have to be in the same room, or will phone call/Zoom call suffice? If they have to be in the same room, how is this different from line of sight test?"	"Conscious presence"	General		746157	1737	421938	159137	"2022-07-15 12:06:22"	"2022-07-14 21:04:29"	1	0	"WILLS AND DECEDENTS' ESTATES"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Ty.  Most jurisdictions define conscious presence as the testator being conscious of where the witnesses were and what they were doing when they signed. Under the conscious-presence test, the testator must be able to sense the presence or actions of another but need not actually be able to see the witness. Phone calls and Zoom won't suffice, though.  For example:Georgia signs her will while lying in a hospital bed. A vinyl screen separates her from the doorway where the witnesses are standing, which is 12 feet away. A nurse takes the will around the screen to the witnesses where they sign. Since Georgia was conscious of where the witnesses were and of what they were doing, the witnesses signed in her presence even though they were not in her line of sight.  Under the line of sight test, a person is present only if she could have seen the signing. (There is an exception for blind people). So, if a witness signs from his office, while the testator signs in her home, the attestation requirements are not satisfied. This does not mean that the signing must actually have been observed, but only that the person was in such close proximity that she could have seen the signing had she looked. Again, phone calls and Zoom won't work.  Steve    Ty Zhang @ 2022-07-14 20:58:48 wrote:  I'm confused about the extent of the conscious presence test. Do witnesses/testators have to be in the same room, or will phone call/Zoom call suffice? If they have to be in the same room, how is this different from line of sight test?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Kyla	Randle	"2022-07-14 19:47:25"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	7149	"I thought a destination contract involved a third party carrier. I also thought that when a party involves a merchant, the risk of loss does not pass to the buyer until he or she physically accept them. I considered the carpenter a merchant."	Contrct	"Mult. Choice"		746076	1737	336618	245688	"2022-07-14 23:57:37"	"2022-07-14 20:56:45"	1	7149	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Kyla,  No, you don't have to ship via a third-party carrier. The contract need either requireor authorize shipment by a third-party carrier. But even if the contract authorizes it, the seller can still deliver themselves. So this can still be a destination contract. See section 3.a.1.b. on page 71 of your Contracts outline. With that being the case, the rule on buyer-taking-possession does not apply, as that's a catchall for when this option and the goods-held-by-bailee option do not apply.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Kyla Randle @ 2022-07-14 19:47:25 wrote:  I thought a destination contract involved a third party carrier. I also thought that when a party involves a merchant, the risk of loss does not pass to the buyer until he or she physically accept them. I considered the carpenter a merchant."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Kaycee	Miller	"2022-07-14 19:31:36"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	NULL	"Thank you so much for the clarification!Following up, the difference between an equitable servitude and real covenant is the need for a horizontal/vertical property for the benefit and/or burden to run with the land; such that a real covenant is stricter in a sense?Please let me know if this is incorrect! Also, this is the only real difference I see between the two conceptual difference I see between equitable servitudes and real covenants so please let me know if I am missing anythingAdmin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYHi Kaycee:  To run the burden to a successor, the original parties to the promise must have been in horizontal privity. Horizontal privity refers to privity of estate, where the estate and covenant are contained in the same instrument (e.g., the deed). Look for a transfer of property between the original parties that contains a covenant in it. The key is to look for the original parties to the agreement. This is for a burden to run, you do not need horizontal privity to run a benefit. Professor Kramer gives a good example in his handout:  Oliver owns Blackacre and Whiteacre. He conveys Whiteacre to Caleb. The deed says “Oliver and Caleb promise to use their property for residential purposes only.” Are Caleb and Oliver in horizontal privity? Yes. Why? There was a transfer and the covenant was included in the transfer.  To run the burden of the covenant to the successor, the successor must take the original party’s entire interest. This is strict vertical privity. To run the benefit of the covenant to the successor, the successor need only take an interest that is carved out of the original party’s estate. This is relaxed vertical privity. Again, Professor Kramer gives some good examples in his handout:  Oliver and Caleb have in their deeds to Blackacre and Whiteacre a promise not to build a shed on their properties. Oliver conveys his fee simple interest to Marsha, who plans to build a shed on the property. Can Caleb recover against Marsha? Ask first if you’re running the benefit or the burden and then what kind of vertical privity is needed. Here we’re running the burden. To run the burden, you need strict vertical privity. So here, because Marsha took Oliver’s fee simple interest (strict vertical privity), we have enough to run the burden, provided there is horizontal privity.  Would there still have been vertical privity if Oliver had conveyed a life estate to Marsha? No, because she took an interest carved out of the fee simple interest rather than the whole fee simple interest.  So, horizontal privity is between the two original parties to the promise. Horizontal privity is not necessary to run a benefit, only a burden. Vertical privity is how the promise gets transferred to one of the original parties’ successors.  Good luck!  Nicole  Kaycee Miller @ 2022-07-13 20:47:52 wrote: Hi -  I still don't quite get the difference in horizontal and vertical privity. Is there any way I could a more thorough explanation and some examples?"	"RE: Horizontal Privity v. Vertical Privity"	Follow-up	NULL	746063	1737	357799	397561	"2022-07-17 17:46:43"	"2022-07-14 19:31:36"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Nicole Werner"	"Hi Kaycee:    Yes, you are correct. Enforcement of a real covenant is more stringent than that of an equitable servitude. Enforcement of either require: it be in writing, intent, touch and concern, and notice. However, a real covenant also require privity.    Another difference between the two would be the type of damages sought. When damages are sought to enforce the covenant, the covenant is called a real covenant. When an injunction is sought to enforce a covenant, it is called an equitable servitude.    Good luck!  Nicole    Kaycee Miller @ 2022-07-14 19:31:36 wrote:  Thank you so much for the clarification!    Following up, the difference between an equitable servitude and real covenant is the need for a horizontal/vertical property for the benefit and/or burden to run with the land; such that a real covenant is stricter in a sense?    Please let me know if this is incorrect! Also, this is the only real difference I see between the two conceptual difference I see between equitable servitudes and real covenants so please let me know if I am missing anything    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTY  Hi Kaycee:    To run the burden to a successor, the original parties to the promise must have been in  horizontal privity. Horizontal privity refers to privity of estate, where the estate and covenant are contained in the same instrument (e.g., the deed). Look for a transfer of property between the original parties that contains a covenant in it. The key is to look for the original parties to the agreement. This is for a burden to run, you do not need horizontal privity to run a benefit. Professor Kramer gives a good example in his handout:    Oliver owns Blackacre and Whiteacre. He conveys Whiteacre to Caleb. The deed says &ldquo;Oliver and Caleb promise to use their property for residential purposes only.&rdquo; Are Caleb and Oliver in horizontal privity? Yes. Why? There was a transfer and the covenant was included in the transfer.    To run the burden of the covenant to the successor, the successor must take the original party&rsquo;s entire interest. This is strict vertical privity. To run the benefit of the covenant to the successor, the successor need only take an interest that is carved out of the original party&rsquo;s estate. This is relaxed vertical privity. Again, Professor Kramer gives some good examples in his handout:    Oliver and Caleb have in their deeds to Blackacre and Whiteacre a promise not to build a shed on their properties. Oliver conveys his fee simple interest to Marsha, who plans to build a shed on the property. Can Caleb recover against Marsha? Ask first if you&rsquo;re running the benefit or the burden and then what kind of vertical privity is needed. Here we&rsquo;re running the burden. To run the burden, you need strict vertical privity. So here, because Marsha took Oliver&rsquo;s fee simple interest (strict vertical privity), we have enough to run the burden, provided there is horizontal privity.    Would there still have been vertical privity if Oliver had conveyed a life estate to Marsha? No, because she took an interest carved out of the fee simple interest rather than the whole fee simple interest.    So, horizontal privity is between the two original parties to the promise. Horizontal privity is not necessary to run a benefit, only a burden. Vertical privity is how the promise gets transferred to one of the original parties&rsquo; successors.    Good luck!    Nicole    Kaycee Miller @ 2022-07-13 20:47:52 wrote:  Hi -    I still don't quite get the difference in horizontal and vertical privity. Is there any way I could a more thorough explanation and some examples?"	"Kaycee Miller"
Yiwei	Jiang	"2022-07-14 14:44:40"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	6026	"Hello, I encountered the following question (reproduced below). I thought that class action certification or denial was immediately appealable as a matter of right. Therefore, the correct answer should be (D) instead of (C). Thanks!Question6026A group of plaintiffs who claimed to have been injured by a corporate defendant's negligent design of its product sought certification as a class in federal district court for a class-action lawsuit against the corporate defendant. The federal district court entered an order certifying the class on August 1. The corporate defendant seeks to appeal the certification of the class. Which of the following is most accurate regarding an appeal by the corporate defendant?Answers:The defendant is precluded from filing an appeal of the order because of the final judgment rule.The defendant is precluded from filing an appeal of the order because the order is interlocutory.Correct Answer:If the defendant timely files a petition for permission to appeal, the court of appeals may hear the appeal in its discretion.You Selected:The defendant may appeal the order as of right.Rationale:Answer choice C is correct. A court of appeals has discretion to permit an appeal from a district court order granting or denying class action certification. The petition for permission to appeal must be filed with the circuit clerk within 14 days after the order is entered. Answer choice A is incorrect. While the final judgment rule would normally prohibit the appeal of an interlocutory order, Rule 23(f) allows for the discretion to permit an appeal regarding class action certification. Answer choice B is incorrect for the same reason. Answer choice D is incorrect. There is no right of appeal here. Rather, the court of appeals has discretion to permit an appeal from a district court order granting or denying class action certification."	"Why is appellate review of a class action certification not as of right?"	"Mult. Choice"		745661	1737	347506	395418	"2022-07-15 11:27:03"	"2022-07-14 14:57:56"	1	6026	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Andreanna Jones (Ed)"	"Good morning Yiewi,    Thank you for your question. Though an order granting or denying a class action is immediately appealable, whether one can appeal this order is discretionary&mdash;not a right. The party seeking to reverse the order must first file a petition for permission to appeal with the circuit clerk within 14 days after the order is entered. The court of appeals then has the discretion to permit the appeal from the district court's order. Be sure to take a look at IX.B.5.&mdash;Class Action Certification in the MBE Civ Pro outline for further guidance. I hope this clarifies!     Best,   Ann     Yiwei Jiang @ 2022-07-14 14:44:40 wrote:  Hello, I encountered the following question (reproduced below). I thought that class action certification or denial was immediately appealable as a matter of right. Therefore, the correct answer should be (D) instead of (C). Thanks!  Question6026  A group of plaintiffs who claimed to have been injured by a corporate defendant's negligent design of its product sought certification as a class in federal district court for a class-action lawsuit against the corporate defendant. The federal district court entered an order certifying the class on August 1. The corporate defendant seeks to appeal the certification of the class. Which of the following is most accurate regarding an appeal by the corporate defendant?  Answers:    The defendant is precluded from filing an appeal of the order because of the final judgment rule.  The defendant is precluded from filing an appeal of the order because the order is interlocutory.  Correct Answer:If the defendant timely files a petition for permission to appeal, the court of appeals may hear the appeal in its discretion.  You Selected:The defendant may appeal the order as of right.    Rationale:  Answer choice C is correct. A court of appeals has discretion to permit an appeal from a district court order granting or denying class action certification. The petition for permission to appeal must be filed with the circuit clerk within 14 days after the order is entered. Answer choice A is incorrect. While the final judgment rule would normally prohibit the appeal of an interlocutory order, Rule 23(f) allows for the discretion to permit an appeal regarding class action certification. Answer choice B is incorrect for the same reason. Answer choice D is incorrect. There is no right of appeal here. Rather, the court of appeals has discretion to permit an appeal from a district court order granting or denying class action certification."	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Jenae	Longenecker	"2022-07-14 12:49:54"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	4243	"Why does the second person taking the cash from the first person constitute larceny? It was given to him willingly to put in the car."	Larceny/Embezzlement	"Mult. Choice"		745493	1737	345376	395418	"2022-07-15 10:53:46"	"2022-07-14 12:58:39"	1	4243	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Andreanna Jones (Ed)"	"Good morning Jenae,    Thank you for your question. This all centers around the theory of accomplice liability. Under the modern and MPC approach, an accomplice is a person who, with the purpose of promoting or facilitating the commission of the offense, aids or abets a principal prior to or during the commission of a crime. And an accomplice is liable to the same extent as the principal.    Here, the bank teller (i.e., the principal) committed larceny when he took and carried away the personal property of the supervisor with the intent to deprive the supervisor of that property. And the colleague aided and abetted by transferring the money into the car. This made him an accomplice. As an accomplice, he was guilty to the same extent as the bank teller. Thus, he is guilty of larceny. I hope this clarifies!    Best,  Ann     Jenae Longenecker @ 2022-07-14 12:49:54 wrote:  Why does the second person taking the cash from the first person constitute larceny? It was given to him willingly to put in the car."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jenae	Longenecker	"2022-07-14 12:40:37"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	4246	"The explanation states that the man is liable for the larceny as both an accomplice and as a co-conspirator. I understand why he is liable as an accomplice, but wouldn't his statements to the friend stating that he is no longer onboard with the plan be sufficient to make him not liable as a co-conspirator?"	"Co-conspirator liability"	"Mult. Choice"		745482	1737	345376	245688	"2022-07-14 22:50:32"	"2022-07-14 12:56:49"	1	4246	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Jenae,  He isn't liable for the actual larceny as a conspirator, he is only liable for the offense of conspiracy to commit larceny. His withdrawal from the conspiracy was not effective because it occurred after the overt act.  However, by getting to the point where he became an accomplice, we have to consider if he can avoid liability for the larceny itself on an accomplice theory. If an accomplice aids or abets the crime, but seeks to withdraw before it is completed, then they have to (i) repudiate aid, (ii) do all in their power to countermand their prior assistance, and (iii) do this before the chain of events leading to the completed crime is unstoppable. See section (d) on page 9 of your MBE Crim Law outline. Because the man, at best, only did the first of those things, his withdrawal as an accomplice is ineffective and he will still be guilty of the completed larceny.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Jenae Longenecker @ 2022-07-14 12:40:37 wrote:  The explanation states that the man is liable for the larceny as both an accomplice and as a co-conspirator. I understand why he is liable as an accomplice, but wouldn't his statements to the friend stating that he is no longer onboard with the plan be sufficient to make him not liable as a co-conspirator?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jenae	Longenecker	"2022-07-14 11:04:41"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	3081	"Should we assume that larceny is a felony for MBE purposes? Doesn't it depend on the value of the thing taken? Here it was a stuffed animal."	"Is larceny always a felony?"	"Mult. Choice"		745340	1737	345376	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-14 12:48:31"	1	3081	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jenae,  All larceny was a felony at common law, so if the fact pattern does not state otherwise, entering a home with the intent to commit larceny of an item worth any amount will be with the intent to commit the felony of larceny. Where states have reduced larceny of smaller amounts to misdemeanors only, they have also expanded the ""intent to commit"" element to include any larceny/theft/etc. regardless of whether it is a felony or misdemeanor.   I hope this helps!  Lindsey     Jenae Longenecker @ 2022-07-14 11:04:41 wrote:  Should we assume that larceny is a felony for MBE purposes? Doesn't it depend on the value of the thing taken? Here it was a stuffed animal."	"Lindsey Hallam"
