Brandon	Akers	"2022-07-13 16:40:26"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"Other than immunity decisions, what other decisions trigger the collateral order doctrine?Personal jurisdiction? Venue?Waiver of privilege? Discoverability or Admissibility of Evidence?Thank you,Brandon"	"Collateral Order Doctrine"	General		744542	1737	375081	436051	"2022-07-14 18:58:32"	"2022-07-13 18:33:45"	2	0	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Brandon,    The relevant section of your Themis MBE Civil Procedure outline is section (IX)(B)(3) &ndash; Collateral-Order Doctrine. The collateral-order doctrine is intended to be used in a narrow scope of claims that are too important to be denied review and too independent from the cause of action itself to require deferment until a final judgment has been made. Decisions involving immunity and double jeopardy are the primary candidates for use of the collateral-order doctrine, but orders involving payment of attorney&rsquo;s fees, payment of costs of discovery devices like depositions, and payment of costs for noticing members of a class can be challenged using the collateral-order doctrine. Typically, the collateral order doctrine is only applied when a party is ordered to do something or pay for something.    Personal jurisdiction, venue, waiver of privilege, and discoverability or admissibility of evidence are not collateral issues &ndash; they cannot be decided without considering the underlying claim, and therefore are subject to the final judgment rule.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Brandon Akers @ 2022-07-13 16:40:26 wrote:  Other than immunity decisions, what other decisions trigger the collateral order doctrine?    Personal jurisdiction? Venue?  Waiver of privilege? Discoverability or Admissibility of Evidence?    Thank you,    Brandon  "	"Lindsey Hallam"
