Stacy	Massey	"2022-07-13 14:22:03"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	369		"Crim Defendants talk to police"	"Mult. Choice"		744296	1737	396230	397056	"2022-07-18 12:28:26"	"2022-07-13 16:16:23"	2	369	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Kendra Frazier"	"  Stacy,  If the defendant in this Question would have been Mirandized, that would have cured the 5th Amendment violation but not the 6th Amendment Violation.  If a Criminal Defendant has been Questioned And Confessed After the 6th Amendment Right to Counsel has attached, I consider whether there has been an effective waiver of that right. If not, there has been a violation of the Sixth Amendment. If there has been a waiver, I would look to see whether there was a custodial interrogation. If so, and there were no Miranda warnings, there would still be a violation of the 5th Amendment.  I would advise you to review the relevant portions of the Outline to determine whether your statements of law are correct. See Large Outline at 26-33. I would point out one piece of this that I think is particularly significant on p. 33 of Large Outline:  Even after Sixth Amendment rights attach, the police may initiate non-custodial interactions with  the accused outside the presence of his lawyer, and there will be no presumption  that any knowing waiver of the right to have counsel present for the interaction is  involuntary.  Kendra    Stacy Massey @ 2022-07-13 14:22:03 wrote:  Q1: Can criminal defendants in custodial interrogation validly waive their rights to counsel and voluntarily speak to police? I.e. do Miranda warnings do anything for police questioning criminal defendants once they have counsel?  Q2: Is below a correct statement of the law? 369 really turned me around!  Crim &Delta; questioned, confesses, 6th Amend has attached. Are statements admissible?  First ask: custodial interrogation or not?      Non-Custodial: even after Sixth Amendment rights attach, the police may initiate non-custodial interactions with the accused outside the presence of his lawyer. If deemed voluntary, incriminating statements will be admissible.  For custodial interrogations: Statements made by crim &Delta; outside the presence of &Delta;'s attorney and after the right to counsel has attached are presumed involuntary if made in response to police-initiated interaction.  Voluntary statements made by crim D in interactions initiated by crim D: admissible bc not considered the product of interrogation and thus not subject to 5th and 6th Amendment rights?      "	"Anindita Dutta"
