Stacy	Massey	"2022-07-13 12:19:20"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	1000147	"That does help. Thank you!Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDUREQuestion ID: 1000147Good morning Stacy,  Good question. In Nardone v. U.S., the issue involved was whether evidence procured through the tapping of telephone wires by federal officers (i.e., government agents) was admissible. Here, when the woman obtained the first set of photographs, she was operating as a private individual. Because the exclusionary rule applies only to the actions of government agents, these photos were admissible. However, when she obtained those additional photographs, she was acting on behalf of a federal law enforcement agency. Therefore, the exclusionary rule applied. The difference between Nardone and this case is that the woman was operating as a private individual when she obtained the first set of photographs whereas the federal officers who wiretapped in Nardone were always acting as government agents. I hope this helps.  Best, Ann  Stacy Massey @ 2022-07-12 19:15:24 wrote: Hello - I am reaching out to clarify a rule about the admissibility of evidence that is (1) obtained in violation of a federal statute (2) by a private citizen. The question is from UWorld. The answer is D, suppress only the second set of photos because it is the only set that was collected at the behest of the police. However, the answer cites Nardone v. US and says that case stands for the fact that evidence collected in violation of a federal statute is subject to the exclusionary rule (and is thus inadmissible?). Given that, why would the first set of photos be admissible?  I realize that the woman collected the evidence without direction from the police, so it's not excludable under the 4th amendment. But isn't it still excludable because it was collected in violation of a federal statute?"	"RE: Admission of Evidence Collected by Private Actor in Violation of Federal 