lation. Strict scrutiny only gets applies when the law says ""this class of people have a restriction on this fundamental right, whereas this class does not."" Here, the impact on a fundamental is incidental and not intended, so substantive due process is the better route to take.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Robert Weiss @ 2022-07-12 18:34:39 wrote:  I have two questions about this multiple-choice PQ. First, I am confused how to tell that the law here (barring people will felonies from living together) is a regulation that affects everyone, and not a regulation that affects only certain types or classes of people. Doesn't it treat people with felonies different from people without felonies? Or is a class of people only something like an immutable characteristic? What's the rule for why people with felonies are not a class of persons?    Second, I'm confused why the answer explanation says that: ""Answer choice B [the equal protection clause] incorrect because the law does not employ a suspect classification, and thus any equal protection claim would be subject to rational basis review."" When a law that impacts a fundamental right, like the right to live together with your family, discriminates between different classes of people, it is subject to strict scrutiny regardless of whether the classification is suspect or not. So if this same law in the question was, for example, applied to people based on their age (not a suspect classification) it would nevertheless be subject to strict scrutiny, not rational basis analysis -- right?    Thank you,  Rob  "	"Dena Ray"
