Chloe	Bell	"2022-07-12 17:44:32"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2205	"Hi - I have a question on one of the practice essay questions [ID: 2205]. The sample answer shown allocates 10% of the points to discussing priority of property interests under the common law when no recording statute applies. I do not understand why this needs to be addressed, specifically because the facts say that a notice statute does apply. Additionally, there is a nearly identical example on page 60 of the MBE Real Property outline [Sec. IV.B.3.f, Subsec. 1(ii)] that suggests that the Purchaser would prevail over the Daughter due to the notice statute and wild deed.Could you please clarify why you would need to discuss the Daughter's rights under the common law and not the recording act when the notice statute does, in fact, apply. Aside from mentioning the common law rule to show an understanding of the law, I do not understand why the common law is applied rather than the notice statute.Thank you in advance!Chloe"	"Property Priority on Practice Essay"	Essay		743375	1737	387512	283716	"2022-07-15 02:01:05"	"2022-07-13 10:50:58"	1	2205	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Chloe,    The key to this essay is a little difficult. The recording act is essentially thrown out here because Daughter isn't a buyer. But she wins under the common law rule of first to have legal title to the property.     In this fact pattern we know that Daughter has been given a gift (she did not pay value), and Purchaser paid value for the property. We have also been given a notice statute. Now let's look at the rules: Only a grantee who pays value for an interest in real property is entitled to protection under the recording statutes. Grantees who acquire title of property by gift, intestacy, or devise are not protected by the recording act against prior claims, even those who fail to record their claims to the same property.     Therefore, when looking at Daughter's interest, she did not pay value, so she is not entitled to protection under the recording statute. Thus, we look at her interest under the common-law rule. This is why you need to analyze both the common law (which will apply to the gift if the recording statute does not), and the recording statute (as it is mentioned in the fact pattern). Accordingly, the recording act would not apply to Daughter generally, regardless of the type of recording act. Further, a bona fide purchaser is someone who purchases land for value and without notice that another individual has prior claim to the land.     Here, Purchaser can be held to have had constructive notice only for prior conveyances that were properly recorded. Railroad and Daughter recorded their interests but Sam, from whom they received the conveyances, did not record. The state records under a grantor-grantee indexing system, as indicated in the essay. Here, a ""wild deed"" is present (i.e., deed not within the chain of title) because Sam did not record the deed. Therefore, Purchaser had no constructive notice and could prevail over Railroad and Daughter's interests.     However, going a step further, it is unlikely that Purchaser would prevail because there exists a strong argument that he had inquiry notice. Had Purchaser viewed the property and performed a reasonable investigation, he would have seen railroad tracks left by Railroad, which would have put him on notice to inquire as to whom owned the property prior. Thus, Purchaser is not a bona fide purchaser; the easement is not terminated. If there were no inquiry notice, the easement would likely be terminated without constructive notice (the wild deed is still the issue).     I hope this helps!    Best,          Timothy    Chloe Bell @ 2022-07-12 17:44:32 wrote:  Hi - I have a question on one of the practice essay questions [ID: 2205]. The sample answer shown allocates 10% of the points to discussing priority of property interests under the common law when no recording statute applies. I do not understand why this needs to be addressed, specifically because the facts say that a notice statute does apply. Additionally, there is a nearly identical example on page 60 of the MBE Real Property outline [Sec. IV.B.3.f, Subsec. 1(ii)] that suggests that the Purchaser would prevail over the Daughter due to the notice statute and wild deed.    Could you please clarify why you would need to discuss the Daughter's rights under the common law and not the recording act when the notice statute does, in fact, apply. Aside from mentioning the common law rule to show an understanding of the law, I do not understand why the common law is applied rather than the notice statute.    Thank you in advance!  Chloe"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Matthew	Seafield	"2022-07-12 16:29:58"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	NULL	"Thanks, KJ!Admin wrote:Lecture: Criminal Procedure Ch. 7Subject Outline: MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDUREHello Matthew,  Yes, a defendant will still benefit from the “presumption of prejudice” if the conflict of interest actually affects the attorney’s behavior even if an affirmative waiver was given, but will not benefit from the “presumption of prejudice” due to the mere existence of an actual conflict of interest if the co-defendants gave the judge an affirmative waiver that they would prefer to go forward with joint representation.  In other words, if one of the defendants appeals his conviction on the grounds of ineffective assistance of counsel, the defendant would need to show that there was an (1) actual conflict of interest and that the (2) conflict adversely affected the attorney’s performance. If the defendant signed a knowing waiver, it would only apply to the actual conflict of interest prong – the defendant would still be entitled to the presumption of prejudice if the attorney acted adversely regarding this defendant due to the conflict.  Hope this helps, and bon voyage! - KJ  Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-10 15:08:36 wrote: The lecture states that the judge must get an affirmative waiver from co-defendants if they prefer to go forward with joint representation (because of the actual conflict of interest). It also states that there is a presumption of prejudice if a conflict of interest actually affects counsel's behavior, and the defendant is not required to show innocence in order to be granted a new trial. However, does a defendant still benefit from this ""presumption of prejudice"" even if the defendant provided the judge with an affirmative waiver acknowledging the conflict and preferring to go forward with the joint representation?"	"RE: Presumption of Prejudice when Conflicts of Interest Exist"		"Criminal Procedure Ch. 7"	743274	1737	30