Gabriela	Heizer	"2022-07-12 15:55:17"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	7145	"Hi,I am confused why C could not be a correct answers to this question. I understand that the man was not a merchant, however to create an option, there is not a requirement that the party be a merchant, as long as consideration is given to keep the offer open. If that is correct, I don't understand the explanation to Question 7175 that states since the man is not a merchant, there was no option."	"Consideration to Keep an Offer Open"	"Mult. Choice"	"Simulated Exam (Afternoon)"	743230	1737	398318	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-12 16:45:47"	1	7145	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Gabriela,  Remember that here in ID 7145, you're looking for the man's best defense. It is a stronger defense that the offer was revoked because someone else accepted it and the museum was aware of this. So, the museum knew the offer was no longer available when it tried to accept. You can't learn that an offer is unavailable, attempt to accept anyway, and then sue when you can't accept, unless you specifically paid to have the option irrevocable. Because the offer was not a firm offer or made irrevocable with consideration, the man was free to revoke and accept another offer- the man did nothing wrong. This line of reasoning is stronger than the man attempting to say that because the museum didn't give him any consideration to keep the offer open, he didn't have to. Even if he didn't receive consideration to keep the option open, and it was just a plain revocable offer, he still would have had to actually revoke the offer to the other museum. In other words, this defense doesn't go far enough, because just saying that he didn't have to keep the offer open doesn't make it ok that he does not now accept the museum's offer. The revocation is what makes it- the offer was effectively revoked when he accepted the library's offer, and the museum was made aware.   I hope this makes sense!  Lindsey     Gabriela Heizer @ 2022-07-12 15:55:17 wrote:  Hi,    I am confused why C could not be a correct answers to this question. I understand that the man was not a merchant, however to create an option, there is not a requirement that the party be a merchant, as long as consideration is given to keep the offer open. If that is correct, I don't understand the explanation to Question 7175 that states since the man is not a merchant, there was no option."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Brandon	Akers	"2022-07-12 12:13:04"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	PARTNERSHIPS		"Hello,1) For a limited partnership, a new general partner is not liable for partnership acts completed before the new general partner joined.i. Does this rule apply for partners in a general partnership?ii. Does this rule apply for limited partners? Or, are limited partners liable up to their investment in a partnership regardless of when an act occurred?2) For Dissolution of a Partnership At Will, say there is a 3 person partnership: if 1 partner intends to dissolve, but 2 partners wish for the partnership to continue, is the result dissolution of the original partnership or mere dissociation of the 1 partner?Thank you,Brandon"	"Partnership Liability for Prior Acts"	General		742962	1737	375081	159137	"2022-07-13 14:51:48"	"2022-07-13 09:44:28"	3	0	PARTNERSHIPS	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Brandon!  Responses to your 3 questions are noted below. Hope this helps.  Steve  1)For a limited partnership, a new general partner is not liable for partnership acts completed before the new general partner joined. Does this rule apply for partners in a general partnership?A person admitted as a partner into an existing partnership is not personally liable for any prior partnership obligations. However, any capital contribution made by an incoming partner to the partnership is at risk for the satisfaction of such partnership obligations. RUPA 306(b).    2) Does this rule apply for limited partners? Or, are limited partners liable up to their investment in a partnership regardless of when an act occurred? Same rule as above.    3)For Dissolution of a Partnership At Will, say there is a 3 person partnership: if 1 partner intends to dissolve, but 2 partners wish for the partnership to continue, is the result dissolution of the original partnership or mere dissociation of the 1 partner?. You are using very technical terms. So I am not sure I entirely follow what you mean. But if partner 1 dissociates, that dissolves the at will partnership. During wind-up, the partners (including any properly dissociated partner) must agree to continue the partnership if they want it to continue. So if partner 1 wrongfully dissociated, 2 and 3 could vote to continue the partnership without her. If partner 1 properly dissociated, she would need to agree to the continuation without her. Let me know if I am not answering what you are looking to know.    Brandon Akers @ 2022-07-12 12:13:04 wrote:  Hello,    1) For a limited partnership, a new general partner is not liable for partnership acts completed before the new general partner joined.      i. Does this rule apply for partners in a general partnership?        ii. Does this rule apply for limited partners? Or, are limited partners liable up to their investment in a partnership regardless of when an act occurred?      2) For Dissolution of a Partnership At Will, say there is a 3 person partnership: if 1 partner intends to dissolve, but 2 partners wish for the partnership to continue, is the result dissolution of the original partnership or mere dissociation of the 1 partner?    Thank you,    Brandon"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
