Gabriela	Heizer	"2022-07-11 18:50:12"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	4936	"Hi,I wanted to reach out regarding Question4936 from the afternoon simulatedexam. I got the question right but I got it right purely by eliminating wrong answers. So I wanted more clarification because the explanation was not clear to me. It states ""A TRO may issue without notice to the adverse party if (i) the moving party can establish, under written oath, that immediate and irreparable injury will result prior to hearing the adverse party’s opposition; and (ii) the movant’s attorney certifies in writing any efforts made to give notice and the reason why notice should not be required."" The explanation further states that ""In this case, the company did not make any effort to provide its competitor with notice and failed to certify in writing the reasons that notice should not be required. For this reason, the TRO was improper.""However, I am confused because the fact pattern states: ""The company signed a written oath establishing that immediate and irreparable injury would result unless the TRO was granted."" Is that not a certified writing stating the reason?Thanks in advance for your help!"	"Civil Procedure TRO"	"Mult. Choice"	"Simulated Exam (Afternoon)"	742413	1737	398318	369848	"2022-07-12 19:29:28"	"2022-07-11 22:22:59"	1	0	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Pamela Prieto"	"Hi Gabriela,  I checked MBE question 4936 and it was not a question about TRO. Can you check and provide me with the correct question ID number?  I will try to answer based on the facts and choices you gave me below.  The answer to your question is no, it is not a certified writing by the attorney required by the second requirement.  It is correct that the rule is that""A TRO may issue without notice to the adverse party if (i) the moving party can establish, under written oath, that immediate and irreparable injury will result prior to hearing the adverse party&rsquo;s opposition; and(ii) the movant&rsquo;s attorney certifies in writing any efforts made to give notice and the reason why notice should not be required.""   You stated that the explanation further states that ""In this case, the company did not make any effort to provide its competitor with notice and failed to certify in writing the reasons that notice should not be required."" You also stated that the fact pattern states: ""The company signed a written oath establishing that immediate and irreparable injury would result unless the TRO was granted.""  However, the fact that ""thecompany signed a written oath establishing that immediate and irreparable injury would result unless the TRO was granted"" does not fulfill the two requirements (i and ii) above for a TRO without notice. It only fulfills the first requirement ""(i) the moving party can establish, under written oath, that immediate and irreparable injury will result prior to hearing the adverse party&rsquo;s opposition.""   It does not fulfill the second requirement that ""(ii) the movant&rsquo;s attorney certifies in writing any efforts made to give notice and the reason why notice should not be required."" The facts does not state that the attorney provided any certified writing that they made efforts to provide notice and why notice should not be required.  Since the second requirements was not met, notice was required.  Please submit a follow-up question with the ID number of the problem if you need me to explain further. Thank you.  Sincerely,  Pam    Gabriela Heizer @ 2022-07-11 18:50:12 wrote:  Hi,    I wanted to reach out regarding Question4936 from the afternoon simulatedexam. I got the question right but I got it right purely by eliminating wrong answers. So I wanted more clarification because the explanation was not clear to me. It states ""A TRO may issue without notice to the adverse party if (i) the moving party can establish, under written oath, that immediate and irreparable injury will result prior to 