Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-11 16:30:04"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	7327	"How do we know which crimes are felonies? I got this answer wrong because I did not think that assault was a felony, but it was, here, a felony to support a felony murder."	crim	"Mult. Choice"		742229	1737	413801	369936	"2022-07-13 15:21:28"	"2022-07-11 17:31:48"	1	7327	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Colten Hall"	"Hi Nick,  I'm not am seeing a felony murder charge in this question, but instead a burglary, which also requires an intent to commit a felony. Let me know if the Question ID is incorrect. For now, I will tackle assault as a felony with regard to burglary.  The distinction between felony and misdemeanor generally is defined as afelony being a crime punishable by death or imprisonment for more than one year; while a misdemeanor is a crime punishable by imprisonment for one year or less or by a fine or by both. BARRK crimes are felonies that traditionally were considered inherently dangerous. While a BARRK crime would be sufficient for burglary the proper use of the categorization is for felony murder. Burglary is typically going to cast a wider net on what crimes will be sufficient as many states have broadened the scope of the crimes intended to be committed to include misdemeanors, like assault. Whether or not the crime being committed is actually a felony is rarely the focus of the bar question. They tend to focus/test more on when the intent to commit the felony arose or some other prong, like in this question (not an unlawful breaking).  Best,  C    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-11 16:30:04 wrote:  How do we know which crimes are felonies? I got this answer wrong because I did not think that assault was a felony, but it was, here, a felony to support a felony murder."	"Anindita Dutta"
