Gabriela	Heizer	"2022-07-11 12:18:53"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	356	"Hi Lindsey,This definitely helps explain the difference between undercover cops in the 5th Amendment and the 6th Amendment context. I guess now I am just confused as to how and why we know the 6th Amendment rights apply in this case as opposed to the 5th Amendment?Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDUREQuestion ID: 356Hi Gabriela, Post-indictment statements that a defendant makes to a police informant are inadmissible when the police intentionally create a situation likely to induce the defendant into making incriminating statements about the crime for which he was indicted without the assistance of counsel. United States v. Henry, 447 U.S. 264, 274–275 (1980). There is no Sixth Amendment violation, however, if the police place an informant in the defendant's cell simply to listen and report the defendant's statements, without questioning the defendant. Kuhlmann v. Wilson, 477 U.S. 436, 456 (1986). Here, the police then placed the man in a holding cell in the police station with an undercover police officer who was posing as a man arrested for drunken driving. The undercover officer asked the man several questions in an attempt to elicit information about the crime and discover where the man's accomplices might be hiding. So, because the police intentionally placed the informant in the cell to create a situation likely to induce the defendant into making incriminating statements, then there was a sixth amendment violation. If the informant was placed in the cell to simply listen and report what is said, then there would be no violation. As for the fifth amendment, Miranda warnings are not required if the suspect being questioned is not aware that the interrogator is a police officer. Illinois v. Perkins, 496 U.S. 292, 294 (1990). Example: The police placed an undercover officer, posing as a criminal, in the defendant’s jail cell, and the undercover officer engaged the defendant in a conversation designed to elicit details of the crime for which the defendant was suspected. Such statements were admissible in the absence of Miranda warnings. Illinois v. Perkins, supra. I hope this clarifies! Lindsey  Gabriela Heizer @ 2022-07-07 17:56:04 wrote: Hi. I am confused on the use of undercover cops in this case. I understand why my answer is wrong, upon reviewing this questions. However, upon reviewing this question I thought the correct answer should be B. In the MBE Crim Pro Outline II(B)(3)(c), it states that undercover questioning is okay. I am confused as to why the answer choice here relies on the 6th Amendment right to Counsel as opposed to the 5th Amendment Miranda's undercover cop explanation. Thanks in advance for your help!"	"RE: Undercover Cops (Afternoon Simulated Exam Question)"	Follow-up	NULL	741730	1737	398318	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-11 12:18:53"	1	356	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"They aren't mutually exclusive -- i.e. the Fifth Amendment right doesn't end and then the Sixth Amendment start at the time of charging. After charging, both rights apply. Miranda, of course, only applies when the individual is in custody. So, you just have to look at the fact pattern and determine which one applies and which one was violated. Here, none of the answer choices deal with the Fifth Amendment, so that tells you that the question isn&rsquo;t testing that.       Gabriela Heizer @ 2022-07-11 12:18:53 wrote:  Hi Lindsey,    This definitely helps explain the difference between undercover cops in the 5th Amendment and the 6th Amendment context. I guess now I am just confused as to how and why we know the 6th Amendment rights apply in this case as opposed to the 5th Amendment?    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDUREQuestion ID: 356  Hi Gabriela,  Post-indictment statements that a defendant makes to a police informant are inadmissible when the police intentionall