t states that undercover questioning is okay. I am confused as to why the answer choice here relies on the 6th Amendment right to Counsel as opposed to the 5th Amendment Miranda's undercover cop explanation. Thanks in advance for your help!"	"Gabriela Heizer"
Kaycee	Miller	"2022-07-11 12:06:14"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"Hi -Under R26(a)(2) it requires the disclosure of expert witnesses who may testify. I have a question dealing with this rule. If a party does consult with an expert witness, receives an expert report but the party decides not to use the expert - do they still have to disclose the information. I believe there was a multiple choice question on this; however, I don't remember the answer - I think the answer was along the lines that they still had to disclose but I could be wrong"	"Disclosure of Expert Testimony "	General		741700	1737	357799	245688	"2022-07-11 12:28:47"	"2022-07-11 12:09:36"	1	0	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Kaycee,  I'm familiar with one particular question in this area, yes, as many students have questions about it. There, the expert report is obtained but the expert isn't used, and the other side wants the report turned over.    The general rule is that all relevant information is discoverable, and that would be relevant.  As an exception to #1, work product (material prepared in anticipation of litigation, regardless of whether by an attorney or not) is not discoverable.  As an exception to #2 (an exception to the exception...), however, an expert report of a expert witness that is going to testify is excluded from the work product protection -- so it becomes discoverable again.    In the case of the non-testifying expert, you hit work product protection at #2 and stop, as #3 doesn't apply. There are other exceptions that could make it discoverable but typically not for a non-testifying expert's report.  Hope this helps,  Bryan    Kaycee Miller @ 2022-07-11 12:06:14 wrote:  Hi -    Under R26(a)(2) it requires the disclosure of expert witnesses who may testify. I have a question dealing with this rule. If a party does consult with an expert witness, receives an expert report but the party decides not to use the expert - do they still have to disclose the information. I believe there was a multiple choice question on this; however, I don't remember the answer - I think the answer was along the lines that they still had to disclose but I could be wrong"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Phyu-Sin-Lin	Than	"2022-07-11 11:56:58"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	283	"For Crim Law MEE, when the fact pattern provides a statute, do we analyze common law as well? In this particular model answer, there seems to be a mix of jurisdiction's statute as well as common law elements. I was under the impression that if the fact pattern provides the statute, we don't use common law elements."	"Criminal Law Practice Essay (ID 283)"	Essay	Essay	741692	1737	376188	245688	"2022-07-11 19:23:30"	"2022-07-11 12:09:20"	1	283	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Phyu-Sin-Lin,  The sample answers are samples of a passing answer; they are not model answers. Your essay may have different arguments or even reach a different conclusion and still receive a passing score. The most points are awarded for spotting the major issues, providing the relevant rules, and applying those rules to the facts. So you don't need to follow the sample answer's example of discussing some common law elements. It may be useful, in order to compare and contrast the respective rules in order to demonstrate or explain the proper interpretation of the statute, but it isn't necessary when the question gives you a different applicable law.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Phyu-Sin-Lin Than @ 2022-07-11 11:56:58 wrote:  For Crim Law MEE, when the fact pattern provides a statute, do we analyze common law as well? In this particular model answer, there seems to be a mix of jurisdiction's statute as well as common law elements. I was under the impression that if the fact pattern provides the statute, we don't use common law elements."	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Amna	Haque	"2022-07-11 00:15:14"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	5907	"Why does the journal entry not fall under the recorded recollection exception to hearsay?"	"Evidence Question #5907"	"Mult. Choice"		741424	1737	394355	395418	"2022-07-11 11:58:53"	"2022-07-11 10:12:57"	1	5907	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Andreanna Jones (Ed)"	"Good morning Amna,    For the journal entry to be admitted as evidence the witness first must be unable to testify about a matter for which the records exists and the lawyer must establish a foundation for it s admissibility. The lawyers must establish (1) that the record is on a matter that the witness once knew about, (2) it was made or adopted by the witness when the matter was fresh in the witness's memory, (3) the record accurately reflects the witness's knowledge, and (4) the witness states that he/she cannot recall the event well enough to testify fully and accurately, even after consulting the record on the stand.    Here, the defendant failed to establish that foundation for before seeking to introduce the journal entry as evidence. So while the defendant can impeach the witness with the journal at the time that he sought to introduce it as evidence, it cannot be admitted into evidence as a recorded recollection because no foundation for its admissibility has been established. Be sure to take a look at section VII.B.5.&mdash;Recorded Recollection in the MBE Evidence outline for more guidance. I hope this helps!    Best,  Ann    Amna Haque @ 2022-07-11 00:15:14 wrote:  Why does the journal entry not fall under the recorded recollection exception to hearsay?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
David	Salgado	"2022-07-11 00:11:23"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"WILLS AND DECEDENTS' ESTATES"		"Under the UPC, are witnesses that sign the will supposed to be in the presence of each other, or just in the presence of the testator?Best.David Salgado"	"Witnesses to a Will Under UPC"	General		741422	1737	404018	159137	"2022-07-12 06:54:23"	"2022-07-11 10:12:25"	1	0	"WILLS AND DECEDENTS' ESTATES"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi David!  The UPC does not require the witnesses to sign the will in either the presence of the testator or the presence of the other witnesses. Rather, each witness must sign only within a reasonable time of the original signature by the testator, at his direction, or while observing the testator's acknowledgment of the will. Unif. Probate Code &sect; 2-502(a)(3).  Steve    David Salgado @ 2022-07-11 00:11:23 wrote:  Under the UPC, are witnesses that sign the will supposed to be in the presence of each other, or just in the presence of the testator?    Best.    David Salgado"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
