pe this helps,  -Bryan    Hafsa Tout @ 2022-07-10 18:44:56 wrote:  Hi, I just completed the civpro essay in the MEE practice exams #2 and I was confused about the answer to part (b) of the question. I understand that we were supposed to focus on the court's jurisdiction over the third party complaint by the defendant to the original action in doing the jurisdiction analysis, but I was confused by the sample answer. I had ruled out diversity jurisdiction for the underlying claim because the woman-plaintiff in the fact pattern was a citizen of State A, and the defendant MedForms was incorporated and a citizen of State A. So when I was doing the subject-matter jurisdiction analysis for the claim that defendant MedForms then filed against a third-party company, I quickly eliminated diversity jurisdiction as the basis for the underlying claim because the parties in the original action were not diverse. I'm having trouble understanding how diversity jurisdiction is the basis for this claim when the original plaintiff and defendant are citizens of the same state. Thank you so much!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-07-10 17:10:28"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	PARTNERSHIPS		"The outline states: ""unless there is also a judgment against the partner, a judgment against a partnership cannot be satisfied from a partner's assets, only from the partnership's assets."" How does this make sense with the fact that generally partners are personally liable for partnership obligations?"	"Effect of judgment on partnership"	General		741122	1737	421938	159137	"2022-07-10 18:50:01"	"2022-07-10 18:38:40"	1	0	PARTNERSHIPS	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Ty!  This just means that you have to sue both the partnership and the partner. Ajudgment against a partnership cannot be satisfied directly from a partner's assets, only from the partnership's assets. However, partners are not protected from personal liability for the partnership's obligations, no matter who is named in the judgment. See Partnerships Outline, I.A.3.a. A partner is jointly and severally liable for all partnership obligations. See Partnerships Outline, I.C.3.a. A judgement against the partnership is a partnership obligation, so the partners are jointly and severally liable for this liability. But because the judgment is not a judgment against the partners individually, a plaintiff cannot immediately bring the judgment against the partners to obtain their private funds or a lien on their personal property. Instead, the plaintiff will likely need to exhaust the partnership's assets before bringing a separate claim against the partners. The partners are still on the hook for these liabilities. It just remains to be seen how that liability will be enforced (e.g., separate action by plaintiff or contribution claim from partnership).   Hope this helps.  Steve    Ty Zhang @ 2022-07-10 17:10:28 wrote:  The outline states: ""unless there is also a judgment against the partner, a judgment against a partnership cannot be satisfied from a partner's assets, only from the partnership's assets."" How does this make sense with the fact that generally partners are personally liable for partnership obligations?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
