Matthew	Seafield	"2022-07-10 15:08:36"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"		"The lecture states that the judge must get an affirmative waiver from co-defendants if they prefer to go forward with joint representation (because of the actual conflict of interest). It also states that there is a presumption of prejudice if a conflict of interest actually affects counsel's behavior, and the defendant is not required to show innocence in order to be granted a new trial. However, does a defendant still benefit from this ""presumption of prejudice"" even if the defendant provided the judge with an affirmative waiver acknowledging the conflict and preferring to go forward with the joint representation?"	"Presumption of Prejudice when Conflicts of Interest Exist"	General	"Criminal Procedure Ch. 7"	741022	1737	302806	436051	"2022-07-12 15:11:24"	"2022-07-10 18:26:12"	1	0	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Matthew,    Yes, a defendant will still benefit from the &ldquo;presumption of prejudice&rdquo; if the conflict of interest actually affects the attorney&rsquo;s behavior even if an affirmative waiver was given, but will not benefit from the &ldquo;presumption of prejudice&rdquo; due to the mere existence of an actual conflict of interest if the co-defendants gave the judge an affirmative waiver that they would prefer to go forward with joint representation.    In other words, if one of the defendants appeals his conviction on the grounds of ineffective assistance of counsel, the defendant would need to show that there was an (1) actual conflict of interest and that the (2) conflict adversely affected the attorney&rsquo;s performance. If the defendant signed a knowing waiver, it would only apply to the actual conflict of interest prong &ndash; the defendant would still be entitled to the presumption of prejudice if the attorney acted adversely regarding this defendant due to the conflict.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-10 15:08:36 wrote:  The lecture states that the judge must get an affirmative waiver from co-defendants if they prefer to go forward with joint representation (because of the actual conflict of interest). It also states that there is a presumption of prejudice if a conflict of interest actually affects counsel's behavior, and the defendant is not required to show innocence in order to be granted a new trial. However, does a defendant still benefit from this ""presumption of prejudice"" even if the defendant provided the judge with an affirmative waiver acknowledging the conflict and preferring to go forward with the joint representation?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
