Yiwei	Jiang	"2022-07-09 16:53:25"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"Hello, I encountered the following question in the Morning Session of Practice Exam #3 (please see below). I was wondering why the defendant is allowed to remove the case from state to federal court.The defendant is a citizen of State A (has its principal place of business there) and defendants can't remove a case if it is filed in the state in which they are a citizen. Thus, I thought that the defendant can't remove and answer choice (A) would be wrong since the removal shouldn't be successful. Thanks!Question 85Question Text:A potential renter, a resident of State A, was searching for an apartment. The renter completed an application for a lease at an apartment complex located in State A, which was owned and managed by an apartment management company. The apartment management company’s principal place of business was in State A, but it was incorporated in State B. The renter fulfilled all the requirements detailed in the application, yet the management company refused to offer her a lease. Suspecting that the management company refused to rent to her because of her ethnicity, the renter filed a claim under the Federal Fair Housing Act in State A state court seeking damages of $100,000. If the management company seeks to remove the action to the federal district court located in State A, will it be successful?Answer Choices:Yes, because the federal district court has original federal question jurisdiction.Yes, because the federal district court has original diversity jurisdiction.No, because, as a landlord-tenant dispute, the case is properly in state court.No, because when the state courts and federal courts have concurrent jurisdiction, the plaintiff holds the right to choose where to file the claim.Learner Selected Answer:No, because when the state courts and federal courts have concurrent jurisdiction, the plaintiff holds the right to choose where to file the claim.Correct:Correct Answer:Yes, because the federal district court has original federal question jurisdiction.Rationale:Answer choice A is correct. Any civil action commenced in a state court that is within the original jurisdiction of a U.S. district court may generally be removed by the defendant to the district court for the district and division in which the state court action is pending. Answer choice B is incorrect. There is no complete diversity of citizenship, as the corporation is a citizen of both States A and B. Answer choice C is incorrect. The case involves a federal statute, the Federal Fair Housing Act. Therefore, removal is proper under federal question jurisdiction. Answer choice D is incorrect. Although the plaintiff originally files the claim in his court of choice, the defendant may remove the action to federal district court under certain circumstances.Subject Outline:Mbe Civil ProcedureChapter:Subject Matter JurisdictionSection:Removal Jurisdiction"	"Why can the defendant remove to federal court?"	"Mult. Choice"		740489	1737	347506	436051	"2022-07-09 23:03:36"	"2022-07-09 18:30:11"	1	0	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Yiwei,    The relevant section of your Themis MBE Civil Procedure outline is section (I)(E)(4) &ndash; Limitation of Removal in Diversity Cases. Any civil action commenced in a state court that is within the original jurisdiction of a district court may generally be removed by the defendant to the district court in which the state court action is pending. If removal is sought solely based on diversity jurisdiction, then the claim may be removed only if no defendant is a citizen of the state in which the action was filed. However, there is no similar requirement for removal based on federal question jurisdiction. Because the removal here is being sought under federal question jurisdiction, the citizenship of Defendant is not relevant.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Yiwei Jiang @ 2022-07-09 16:53:25 wrote:  Hello, I encountered the following question in the Morning Session of Practice Exam #3 (please see below). I was wondering why the defendant is allowed to remove the case from state to federal court.The defendant is a citizen of State A (has its principal place of business there) and defendants can't remove a case if it is filed in the state in which they are a citizen. Thus, I thought that the defendant can't remove and answer choice (A) would be wrong since the removal shouldn't be successful. Thanks!  Question 85    Question Text:  A potential renter, a resident of State A, was searching for an apartment. The renter completed an application for a lease at an apartment complex located in State A, which was owned and managed by an apartment management company. The apartment management company&rsquo;s principal place of business was in State A, but it was incorporated in State B. The renter fulfilled all the requirements detailed in the application, yet the management company refused to offer her a lease. Suspecting that the management company refused to rent to her because of her ethnicity, the renter filed a claim under the Federal Fair Housing Act in State A state court seeking damages of $100,000. If the management company seeks to remove the action to the federal district court located in State A, will it be successful?    Answer Choices:    Yes, because the federal district court has original federal question jurisdiction.  Yes, because the federal district court has original diversity jurisdiction.  No, because, as a landlord-tenant dispute, the case is properly in state court.  No, because when the state courts and federal courts have concurrent jurisdiction, the plaintiff holds the right to choose where to file the claim.      Learner Selected Answer:  No, because when the state courts and federal courts have concurrent jurisdiction, the plaintiff holds the right to choose where to file the claim.    Correct:  Correct Answer:  Yes, because the federal district court has original federal question jurisdiction.    Rationale:  Answer choice A is correct. Any civil action commenced in a state court that is within the original jurisdiction of a U.S. district court may generally be removed by the defendant to the district court for the district and division in which the state court action is pending. Answer choice B is incorrect. There is no complete diversity of citizenship, as the corporation is a citizen of both States A and B. Answer choice C is incorrect. The case involves a federal statute, the Federal Fair Housing Act. Therefore, removal is proper under federal question jurisdiction. Answer choice D is incorrect. Although the plaintiff originally files the claim in his court of choice, the defendant may remove the action to federal district court under certain circumstances.    Subject Outline:Mbe Civil Procedure  Chapter:Subject Matter Jurisdiction  Section:Removal Jurisdiction  "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-07-09 16:50:08"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	5015	"What is the priority of the clause in the contract in determining choice of law? Would the answer still be State D if State B had a different choice-of-law rule, because of the clause?"	"Choice of law"	"Mult. Choice"		740486	1737	421938	245688	"2022-07-09 23:03:25"	"2022-07-09 18:29:44"	1	5015	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Ty,  No, the State B federal district court is required to apply state B conflict of law rules here. See section 4 on page 37 of your MBE Civ Pro outline. This is because (1) it's a diversity case, and (2) state B's rules comply with the full faith and credit clause.  If State B applies a different rule and does something other than what the contract says, then the federal court will have to follow that provided it complies with the full faith and credit clause.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Ty Zhang @ 2022-07-09 16:50:08 wrote:  What is the priority of the clause in the contract in determining choice of law? Would the answer still be State D if State B had a different choice-of-law rule, because of the clause?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Stacy	Massey	"2022-07-09 16:14:13"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	10573	"Hello - for this one, it was my understanding that if a plaintiff puts their physical condition at issue in a personal injury trial, a DR can be called to testify as to the plaintiff's condition notwithstanding any DR/patient confidentiality. Does this not come into play in this question because the thing the DR will testify about is a statement rather than the condition of the plaintiff's body? Please help me better understand when to apply the rule that DRs can be called to testify about a plaintiff's condition in a personal injury suit"	"DR testimony in personal injury case"	"Mult. Choice"		740460	1737	396230	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-09 16:17:13"	1	10573	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Stacy,  The rule is that when a client is examined by a doctor at the attorney's request, the communications involved between the client and the doctor (and the doctor and the attorney) are not covered by the physician-patient privilege because no treatment is contemplated. These communications are, however, covered by the attorney-client privilege because the examination is necessary to help the client communicate her condition to the attorney. Note that this privilege would be waived if doctor is later called as an expert witness by the same client. In this hypo were told ""Prior to filing suit, the plaintiff's attorney had the plaintiff visit a physician to determine the extent of her injuries for purposes of determining the damages to be claimed in the lawsuit. "" Since this was at the direction of the attorney it was at the attorney's request and thus the rule will apply.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Stacy Massey @ 2022-07-09 16:14:13 wrote:  Hello - for this one, it was my understanding that if a plaintiff puts their physical condition at issue in a personal injury trial, a DR can be called to testify as to the plaintiff's condition notwithstanding any DR/patient confidentiality. Does this not come into play in this question because the thing the DR will testify about is a statement rather than the condition of the plaintiff's body? Please help me better understand when to apply the rule that DRs can be called to testify about a plaintiff's condition in a personal injury suit"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-07-09 15:39:47"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	4909	"I had thought this was a prototypical quasi-in-rem jurisdiction case. Since answer D is wrong, does this mean there is no such thing as quasi-in-rem jurisdiction in modern cases? If quasi-in-rem jurisdiction requires minimum contacts, then we would have to look for either in personam or in rem jurisdiction, right?"	"Quasi-in-rem jurisdiction"	"Mult. Choice"		740442	1737	421938	159111	"2022-07-10 13:08:46"	"2022-07-09 16:12:56"	1	4909	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Kathleen Schandler"	"Hi Ty,  Quasi in rem jurisdiction exists when the court has power to determine whether particular individuals own specific property within the court's control. Here there is no dispute as to ownership of the property in the forum.  When the dispute is unrelated to the ownership of the property, jurisdiction cannot be based solely on the presence of property in the forum state; there must be minimum contacts between the defendant and the forum.  Example:  A, a Maine resident, flies to Ohio and enters into a contract with B, an Ohio resident. All performance is to occur in Ohio. A flies home. B breaches. A does not want to fly to Ohio to sue B, but he discovers that B has a boat docked in Main. Traditionally, A could have sued on his contract claim in Maine by attaching the boat (his remedy being limited by the value of the boat). Today, he would have to show minimum contacts between B and Maine.  I hope this helps!  Best,  Katie      Ty Zhang @ 2022-07-09 15:39:47 wrote:  I had thought this was a prototypical quasi-in-rem jurisdiction case. Since answer D is wrong, does this mean there is no such thing as quasi-in-rem jurisdiction in modern cases? If quasi-in-rem jurisdiction requires minimum contacts, then we would have to look for either in personam or in rem jurisdiction, right?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
