Ty	Zhang	"2022-07-08 23:57:18"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	629	"Why is the record not a present sense impression?"	Hearsay	"Mult. Choice"		740072	1737	421938	436051	"2022-07-09 18:22:41"	"2022-07-09 11:56:02"	1	629	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Ty,    The relevant section of your Themis MBE Evidence outline is section (VII)(B)(1) &ndash; Present Sense Impression. A present sense impression is a statement made contemporaneously with the event in question. As with many legal concepts, there is no defined timeframe for when something is/is not a present sense impression, but we know it is a statement made simultaneously, or immediately after the event at issue. That does not leave much room for delay. I like to think of a present sense impression as a play-by-play sportscaster calling the game as it is being played (""he swings, and he misses"") or immediately after an event (""He hit a home run!""). And, depending on the circumstances provided, the passage of 15, 10, or even 5 minutes might be too long for a statement to be a present sense impression. And here, the store owner had time to instruct the employee to write a report and the employee then took time to draft the report, so the report was not contemporaneous with the event.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Ty Zhang @ 2022-07-08 23:57:18 wrote:  Why is the record not a present sense impression?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Matthew	Seafield	"2022-07-08 20:13:31"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2205	"Following up my reply just a minute ago, I know you mentioned that Purchaser was likely not a BFP due to inquiry notice. I meant to ask that, hypothetically, if Purchaser were a BFP, would she have been able to take the land interest despite being granted a quitclaim deed from a grantor with no interest? In other words, being a BFP overrides the fact that one received a quitclaim deed from a grantor with no interest to convey.Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 2205Hi Matthew, O sold to Sam who did not record. Sam conveyed as a gift to Daughter who did record. Since Daughter received as a gift, she is not a BFP and therefore even though she recorded she will not be protected by the recording statutes against PRIOR grantee, but at this point in the hypo, she is the owner of the land. Then we have O convey to Purchaser. At first glance Purchaser looks like a BFP. But is she? BFPs take without notice (actual, constructive or inquiry). So while it is true is that Purchaser gave valuable consideration, we need to determine his purchase had notice. While no one has a legal duty to perform a title search, a subsequent purchaser will be charged with the notice that such a search would provide, whether or not they actually searched. The issue is whether Purchaser would have had notice of the deed that Daughter recorded. The fact that a deed has been recorded does not always mean that a purchaser will be charged with notice of it. A subsequent purchaser will be held to have record notice only if the deed in question is recorded ""in the chain of title,"" which means that it is recorded in a fashion that a searcher could reasonably find it. In this hypo we have an example of a ""wild deed."" A ""wild deed"" in a recorded deed that is not connected to the chain of title. It does not give constructive notice because the subsequent bona fide purchaser cannot feasibly find it. We have this because Sam failed to record. Therefore the link back to O is not present! So she doesn't have constructive notice, next we look to see if she has inquiry notice! A grantee has inquiry notice if a reasonable investigation would have disclosed the existence of prior claims. In the majority of states quitclaim deeds are not charged with inquiry notice from the mere fact that a quitclaim deed was used. If Purchaser had done a reasonable investigation she would have seen the tracks on the land and discovered the easement. If a recorded instrument (here the easement) makes reference to an unrecorded transaction (here the O to Sam transaction) the grantee is bound to make inquiry to discover the nature and character of the unrecorded transaction. So Purchaser had notice and thus Purchaser is not a BPF. Therefore, neither Daughter nor Purchaser can use that nice recording statute that the hypo gave us. Thus we are left we each having to rely on common ""first in time."" I hope this helps! Katie  Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-08 13:47:18 wrote: In the facts of the question, Purchaser received a quitclaim deed from the executor of Oscar's estate. As such, per the definition of a quitclaim deed, the executor was only transferring Purchaser the title that Oscar's estate possessed with no warranties, correct? If so, since Oscar actually had no interest in the land because he previously conveyed it in fee simple to Sam, then his estate should also have no interest in the land and could not convey any interest to Purchaser. This is how I thought the question would go, but the sample answer indicates that Purchaser may prevail if he did not have inquiry, constructive, or actual notice. By contrast, I thought the fact that Oscar's estate conveyed the land by quitclaim deed would be dispositive since Oscar's estate really did not have any interest in the land. Could you please help me understand where my thought process is awry? Thank you."	"RE: Question re Real Property Essay Sample Answer for MEE Essay Exam #1"	Follow-up	NULL	739929	1737	302806	159111	"2022-07-09 15:16:11"	"2022-07-08 20:13:31"	1	0	0	0	"Kathleen Schandler"	"Hi Matthew,    Yes, BFPs are entitle to prevail against prior transferee under notice and race-notice statutes.  Best,  Katie    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-08 20:13:31 wrote:  Following up my reply just a minute ago, I know you mentioned that Purchaser was likely not a BFP due to inquiry notice. I meant to ask that, hypothetically, if Purchaser were a BFP, would she have been able to take the land interest despite being granted a quitclaim deed from a grantor with no interest? In other words, being a BFP overrides the fact that one received a quitclaim deed from a grantor with no interest to convey.    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 2205  Hi Matthew,  O sold to Sam who did not record. Sam conveyed as a gift to Daughter who did record. Since Daughter received as a gift, she is not a BFP and therefore even though she recorded she will not be protected by the recording statutes against PRIOR grantee, but at this point in the hypo, she is the owner of the land. Then we have O convey to Purchaser. At first glance Purchaser looks like a BFP. But is she?  BFPs take without notice (actual, constructive or inquiry). So while it is true is that Purchaser gave valuable consideration, we need to determine his purchase had notice. While no one has a legal duty to perform a title search, a subsequent purchaser will be charged with the notice that such a search would provide, whether or not they actually searched.  The issue is whether Purchaser would have had notice of the deed that Daughter recorded. The fact that a deed has been recorded does not always mean that a purchaser will be charged with notice of it. A subsequent purchaser will be held to have record notice only if the deed in question is recorded ""in the chain of title,"" which means that it is reco