Amna	Haque	"2022-07-08 18:56:30"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"CONFLICT OF LAWS"	313	"Regarding whether the federal judgment should be given full faith and credit in question 2, doesn't lack of proper jurisdiction render a judgment invalid, even if final? I answered that because the federal court lacked subject matter jurisdiction, the judgment was not valid so it wouldn't be given full faith and credit."	"Question about sample answer to Civ Pro/Conflicts Essay #313"	Essay		739858	1737	394355	159137	"2022-07-08 21:30:56"	"2022-07-08 20:10:47"	1	313	"CONFLICT OF LAWS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Amna!  No.A special rule applies. Objections to subject-matter jurisdiction&mdash;which may be raised at any time, even on appeal&mdash;must be raised while the original lawsuit is still pending; they may not be raised for the first time by way of collateral challenge in a subsequent action. A party that had an opportunity to litigate the question of subject-matter jurisdiction' in the original proceeding may not reopen that question in a collateral attack. It has to be done at the latest on the appeal of the original action. So the State Court in State X can't look at subject-matter jurisdiction and has to enforce the judgment.   Hope this clarifies for you. Keep up the good work!  Steve    Amna Haque @ 2022-07-08 18:56:30 wrote:  Regarding whether the federal judgment should be given full faith and credit in question 2, doesn't lack of proper jurisdiction render a judgment invalid, even if final? I answered that because the federal court lacked subject matter jurisdiction, the judgment was not valid so it wouldn't be given full faith and credit."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Timothy	Griffin	"2022-07-08 18:51:15"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"Hi!For strict scrutiny, when stating the standard, is the use of ""necessary"" and ""least restrictive means"" interchangeable? For example, if I am stating the strict scrutiny standard, and I state that ""the law must be necessary to achieve a compelling government interest"", or I state that ""the law must be the least restrictive means to achieve a compelling governmental interest"", is one way right or wrong? I see them often used interchangeably and I wanted to be sure that they don't have different meanings.Thanks!"	"Constitutional Law - Strict Scrutiny "	General		739853	1737	428651	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-08 20:10:22"	1	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Timothy,  The difference in wording is due to the context in which the standard is being applied. Substantive due process cases define the strict scrutiny standard as ""least restrictive"" + ""compelling government interest."" Equal protection cases tend to say ""necessary"" + ""compelling government interest."" The ""narrowly tailored"" language is generally used in freedom of speech and expression cases. The tests are very similar in that the goal is to make sure that the regulations aren't infringing upon constitutionally protected behaviors.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Timothy Griffin @ 2022-07-08 18:51:15 wrote:  Hi!    For strict scrutiny, when stating the standard, is the use of ""necessary"" and ""least restrictive means"" interchangeable? For example, if I am stating the strict scrutiny standard, and I state that ""the law must be necessary to achieve a compelling government interest"", or I state that ""the law must be the least restrictive means to achieve a compelling governmental interest"", is one way right or wrong? I see them often used interchangeably and I wanted to be sure that they don't have different meanings.    Thanks!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
