Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-08 15:58:02"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2021	"I know we are not supposed to think about this, but how does the junior mortgagee get their money back if their mortgage was extinguished by the foreclosure sale? (Q 119 on sim)"	property	"Mult. Choice"		739707	1737	413801	435724	"2022-07-11 00:56:50"	"2022-07-08 16:03:22"	1	2021	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Colleen Scrocca"	"This is a great question.  In this question the other mortgage holders were provided notice of the foreclosure and made parties to the foreclosure action. Here the third mortgage holder &ldquo;purchased&rdquo; the property. In order to do so, that third mortgage holder would have had to pay off those with a senior interest. Here it is stated that there are three mortgages and the third purchased at foreclosure so the senior two had to have been paid off and the third now owns the property and can sell, rent, lease, etc to obtain their money back.   That &ldquo;purchase&rdquo; does not necessarily mean that the first two were paid in full. The question doesn&rsquo;t get into those specifics. It could have been a foreclosure auction with the third mortgage holder being the highest bidder. But say the first two mortgages were $100,000 each ($200,000 total) and the foreclosure auction price was $150,000. The first mortgage holder would be fully paid and the second mortgage holder would only receive half their amount due. This is why order/priority matters because it&rsquo;s not divided equally, the first must be fully paid before the next get anything.  This is kind of talked about on page 76 of your MBE Real Property outline, Section (V)(E)(3)(d)(1)&rdquo;Junior Interests&rdquo;.  I hope this makes sense.  Best of Luck!  Kelley      Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-08 15:58:02 wrote:  I know we are not supposed to think about this, but how does the junior mortgagee get their money back if their mortgage was extinguished by the foreclosure sale? (Q 119 on sim)"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-07-08 15:23:17"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"My understanding is that the Eleventh Amendment bars states from suits in federal court. I also see in the outline that states retain their sovereign immunity from private suits brought in the courts of other states. So, may a citizen bring a suit against a state in the state's court for an alleged violation of either state or federal law?"	"Eleventh Amendment"	Outline		739672	1737	421938	435073	"2022-07-11 07:54:43"	"2022-07-08 15:59:19"	1	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Amy Grover"	"Good Morning,    I hope that this message finds you well.    With a few notable exceptions, the Eleventh Amendment generally protects the states from being sued by citizens in federal (or state) court on issues of federal law. Unless an exception applies, a citizen may only bring suit against a state in the state's court for an alleged violation of federal law if the state has consented (i.e., by passing a law giving the citizen a right to sue). However, if it was a state law in question, then the citizen might likely be able to bring suit in the appropriate state court.    If you would like some more information, &sect; I.A.3. of the Themis MBE Constitutional Law outline goes into some more nuances.    I hope this helps!    Amy G.      Ty Zhang @ 2022-07-08 15:23:17 wrote:  My understanding is that the Eleventh Amendment bars states from suits in federal court. I also see in the outline that states retain their sovereign immunity from private suits brought in the courts of other states. So, may a citizen bring a suit against a state in the state's court for an alleged violation of either state or federal law?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
