Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-08 12:50:53"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	7791	"Fromm does not talk about why the forum selection clause doesn't control in this question. Is it because the defendant should have brought a motion to transfer instead of a motion to dismiss for improper forum?"	"civ pro"	"Mult. Choice"		739535	1737	413801	436051	"2022-07-09 14:38:48"	"2022-07-08 13:01:27"	1	7791	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Nick,    A forum selection clause does not render other forums legally improper. I&rsquo;m not sure what the defendant should have done because there are no facts regarding the defendant&rsquo;s intent &ndash; if they were seeking to dismiss the case, then filing a motion for transfer of venue would not help the defendant, it would only transfer the case to a different venue. However, if the defendant was seeking to enforce the forum selection clause then yes, the defendant should have brought a motion to transfer.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-08 12:50:53 wrote:  Fromm does not talk about why the forum selection clause doesn't control in this question. Is it because the defendant should have brought a motion to transfer instead of a motion to dismiss for improper forum?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-08 12:30:57"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	6543	"Okay I knew and considered the Shopkeeper's privilege when answering this question, but I got this answer wrong because the event took place at a trade show, not in a typical shop/store and because the defendant was a vendor at the trade show. To what extent does the shopkeepers privilege extend then? Is a hotdog vendor in NYC a shopkeeper that can use this privilege? Is the person holding a garage sale a shopkeeper?"	torts	"Mult. Choice"		739512	1737	413801	436051	"2022-07-09 14:24:09"	"2022-07-08 12:57:52"	3	6543	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Nick,    Shopkeeper&rsquo;s privilege applies to individuals who are reasonably detaining a suspect that the shopkeeper reasonably believes is shoplifting. &ldquo;Shoplifting&rdquo; is distinct from the general term larceny because it is typically defined as the unauthorized removal of merchandise without paying for it, and therefore only applies in situations where the individual is selling something. Here, the &ldquo;shopkeeper&rdquo; in question is a vendor who is in the business of selling microchips. While a tradeshow is not a typical place where actual purchases are directly made, the item that was taken was a product that the vendor sells, which would make the actions of the entrepreneur (had then been true) shoplifting. Therefore, the shopkeeper&rsquo;s privilege applies.    A hotdog vendor is a shopkeeper, even if he does not have a physical shop in which to sell his goods. However, a private person selling items out of their personal garage is unlikely to have shopkeeper&rsquo;s privilege because state statutes usually require some kind of &ldquo;commercial establishment&rdquo;, like a business or a store or a vendor cart, to qualify larceny as shoplifting.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-08 12:30:57 wrote:  Okay I knew and considered the Shopkeeper's privilege when answering this question, but I got this answer wrong because the event took place at a trade show, not in a typical shop/store and because the defendant was a vendor at the trade show. To what extent does the shopkeepers privilege extend then? Is a hotdog vendor in NYC a shopkeeper that can use this privilege? Is the person holding a garage sale a shopkeeper?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
