Emily	Motin	"2022-07-07 19:55:18"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	640	"For this question, Fromm said the defendant could not introduce a specific act concerning the defendant's peacefulness in the trial for battery. I know when character or a character trait is an essential element of the crime charged, the defendant may introduce relevantspecific acts inconsistent with the crime. Which crimes include character or character traits as an essential element?"	"Crimes where character trait is an essential element"	"Mult. Choice"		739006	1737	397583	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-07 21:12:55"	1	640	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Emily,  Character evidence can be tricky, so let's walk through the rules. When a criminal defendant is trying to introduce evidence of his good character, he can only do so through opinion or reputation evidence, not through specific instances of conduct. An exception to this rule is that when character is an essential element of the crime charged, then the defendant may introduce evidence of his good character through specific acts. It's rare that character is an essential element of a charge, claim, or defense. A way to conceptualize this is by asking yourself whether character is an element that must be proved in order to convict a criminal defendant, win a civil claim, or successfully argue a defense? Among the few instances where courts agree that character is an essential element are the character of a driver in an action for negligent entrustment of an automobile, the character of a party in a suit for defamation, a criminal defendant's predisposition to commit a crime after he/she has asserted an entrapment defense, and the character of an employee in a negligent hiring cause of action. In these types of cases, character can be proved using both reputation/opinion testimony or specific instances of conduct.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Emily Motin @ 2022-07-07 19:55:18 wrote:  For this question, Fromm said the defendant could not introduce a specific act concerning the defendant's peacefulness in the trial for battery. I know when character or a character trait is an essential element of the crime charged, the defendant may introduce relevantspecific acts inconsistent with the crime. Which crimes include character or character traits as an essential element?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Gabriela	Heizer	"2022-07-07 17:56:04"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	356	"Hi. I am confused on the use of undercover cops in this case. I understand why my answer is wrong, upon reviewing this questions. However, upon reviewing this question I thought the correct answer should be B. In the MBE Crim Pro Outline II(B)(3)(c), it states that undercover questioning is okay. I am confused as to why the answer choice here relies on the 6th Amendment right to Counsel as opposed to the 5th Amendment Miranda's undercover cop explanation. Thanks in advance for your help!"	"Undercover Cops (Afternoon Simulated Exam Question)"	"Mult. Choice"		738886	1737	398318	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-07 17:57:30"	1	356	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Gabriela,  Post-indictment statements that a defendant makes to a police informant are inadmissible when the police intentionally create a situation likely to induce the defendant into making incriminating statements about the crime for which he was indicted without the assistance of counsel. United States v. Henry, 447 U.S. 264, 274&ndash;275 (1980). There is no Sixth Amendment violation, however, if the police place an informant in the defendant's cell simply to listen and report the defendant's statements, without questioning the defendant. Kuhlmann v. Wilson, 477 U.S. 436, 456 (1986). Here, the police then placed the man in a holding cell in the police station with an undercover police officer who was posing as a man arrested for drunken driving. The undercover officer asked the man several questions in an attempt to elicit information about the crime and discover where the man's accomplices might be hiding. So, because the police intentionally placed the informant in the cell to create a situation likely to induce the defendant into making incriminating statements, then there was a sixth amendment violation. If the informant was placed in the cell to simply listen and report what is said, then there would be no violation. As for the fifth amendment, Miranda warnings are not required if the suspect being questioned is not aware that the interrogator is a police officer. Illinois v. Perkins, 496 U.S. 292, 294 (1990). Example: The police placed an undercover officer, posing as a criminal, in the defendant&rsquo;s jail cell, and the undercover officer engaged the defendant in a conversation designed to elicit details of the crime for which the defendant was suspected. Such statements were admissible in the absence of Miranda warnings. Illinois v. Perkins, supra.  I hope this clarifies!  Lindsey    Gabriela Heizer @ 2022-07-07 17:56:04 wrote:  Hi. I am confused on the use of undercover cops in this case. I understand why my answer is wrong, upon reviewing this questions. However, upon reviewing this question I thought the correct answer should be B. In the MBE Crim Pro Outline II(B)(3)(c), it states that undercover questioning is okay. I am confused as to why the answer choice here relies on the 6th Amendment right to Counsel as opposed to the 5th Amendment Miranda's undercover cop explanation. Thanks in advance for your help!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
