Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-07 17:09:06"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	6695	"I know we're not supposed to think about this, but what exactly is the crime when a person is committing a ""continuing trespass'? Like what could the girl be charged with here?"	crim	"Mult. Choice"		738813	1737	413801	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-07 17:20:10"	1	6695	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Nick,  I&rsquo;m not sure if I understand your question &ndash; the continuing trespass rule is not a separate crime from larceny. Here, the woman cannot be charged with larceny because she did not have the requisite intent at the time of the initial taking. Larceny is the trespassory taking and carrying away of the personal property of another with the intent to permanently deprive that person of the property. Under the ""continuing trespass"" rule, if a person takes property without the owner's consent, but with no intent to permanently deprive, larceny may be committed at a later time if the intent to steal is later formed. However, the original taking must have been wrongful. The initial taking occurred when the woman picked up the box from the street. At the time that she picked it up, she did not have the intent to steal, but planned to return the box to the owner as was required by law. Due to the fact that she did not have the intent to steal the box at the time of the initial taking, she cannot be charged with larceny. So, for larceny, you have to have a wrongful taking that occurs at the same time as the necessary intent to permanently deprive. If someone takes property wrongfully, but without the intent to permanently deprive (for example, if someone takes a car just to go for a joyride, intending to return it), that wouldn't be larceny. But if they later decide that they really like the car, and form the intent to permanently deprive, then the continuing trespass rule provides for the previously-wrongful taking to be ""occurring"" at the time they now develop the intent to permanently deprive, and larceny has been committed. But if the initial taking was not wrongful -- as is the case here, since the person intended to return the lost property -- then the continuing trespass rule does not apply. Instead, it would (potentially) be embezzlement.  Hope this helps!  Lindsey    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-07 17:09:06 wrote:  I know we're not supposed to think about this, but what exactly is the crime when a person is committing a ""continuing trespass'? Like what could the girl be charged with here?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-07 17:06:11"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	3081	"So is the monetary value of the object that the burglerer intends to steal irrelevant? I hesitated with this question to choose burglary because I did not know if taking a stuffed animal was a felony? Should we just assume for the bar that the breaking and entering of a dwelling at night with intent to steal anything at all is a felony?"	crim	"Mult. Choice"		738805	1737	413801	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-07 17:19:08"	1	3081	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Nick,  All larceny was a felony at common law, so if the fact pattern does not state otherwise, entering a home with the intent to commit larceny of an item worth any amount will be with the intent to commit the felony of larceny. Where states have reduced larceny of smaller amounts to misdemeanors only, they have also expanded the ""intent to commit"" element to include any larceny/theft/etc. regardless of whether it is a felony or misdemeanor.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-07 17:06:11 wrote:  So is the monetary value of the object that the burglerer intends to steal irrelevant? I hesitated with this question to choose burglary because I did not know if taking a stuffed animal was a felony? Should we just assume for the bar that the breaking and entering of a dwelling at night with intent to steal anything at all is a felony?"	"Anindita Dutta"
