Eric	Walliser	"2022-07-07 14:38:08"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	4949	"I don't know why A is not the right answer. The question says ""can the court grant the motion"", not must grant the motion. The court could grant this motion since the other district is proper. "	"Why isnt A the right answer"	"Mult. Choice"		738548	1737	336767	435564	"2022-07-07 22:11:26"	"2022-07-07 14:58:56"	1	4949	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Eric!    In general, venue is proper in either:   1) A judicial district in which any defendant resides, if all defendants reside in the same state in which the district is located; OR  2) A judicial district in which a substantial part of the events or omissions on which the claim is based occurred; or where a &ldquo;substantial part of the property&rdquo; that is the subject of the action is located.  If there is otherwise no judicial district in which the action may be brought, then the fall-back alternative is that venue is proper in a judicial district in which any defendant is subject to personal jurisdiction. See Civil Procedure Outline &sect; III.C.    In question 4949, the plaintiff filed in the judicial district where the defendant resides. The employer filed a motion to dismiss the action due to improper venue, however, the court cannot grant the motion, because venue is not improper. The fact that there are two options available means whichever one the plaintiff chooses to file her action in is proper.     Hope this helps!   Best,   Anna    Eric Walliser @ 2022-07-07 14:38:08 wrote:  I don't know why A is not the right answer. The question says ""can the court grant the motion"", not must grant the motion. The court could grant this motion since the other district is proper. "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Emily	Motin	"2022-07-07 13:31:32"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	2367	"Hello,I am struggling with this question. I understand that an offer to purchase goods can be accepted by either a shipment of goods or a promise to ship. In this question, the manufacturer seems to have accepted by shipping the sofas. However, with the first shipment, the accompanying invoice includes a new term. Can merchants not include new terms in their acceptance if accepting via shipment? The lecturer for the simulated bar review simply states that there is offer and acceptance and THEN the additional term is introduced. But isn't the new term being introduced in conjunction with the acceptance? Just looking for further clarification because the lecture and explanation aren't making the distinction clear for me. Thank you in advance."	"Acceptance via Shipment and New Terms "	"Mult. Choice"		738480	1737	397583	283716	"2022-07-11 23:47:06"	"2022-07-07 14:52:27"	1	2367	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Emily,    Additional terms included in an acceptance of an offer do not automatically constitute a rejection of the original offer. Generally, for a sale of goods, an acceptance that contains additional or different terms with respect to the terms in the offer is nevertheless treated as an acceptance rather than a rejection and a counteroffer. While the retailer rejected the additional term, this would not be considered a rejection of the original offer. So the terms of the original offer would still be enforceable.     Whether the additional or different terms are treated as part of the contract depends on whether the parties are merchants. When the contract is for the sale of goods between nonmerchants or between a merchant and a nonmerchant, a definite and seasonable expression of acceptance or written confirmation that is sent within a reasonable time operates as an acceptance of the original offer. The additional terms are treated as a proposal for addition to the contract that must be separately accepted by the offeror to become a part of the contract. In this fact pattern, the contract was between a merchant and a nonmerchant. Since the retailer rejected the additional term, it did not become enforceable under the contract. (Please see Contract Sales Outline Section I. A. 2. d. 2. a.).     I hope this helps!    Best,          Timothy    Emily Motin @ 2022-07-07 13:31:32 wrote:  Hello,    I am struggling with this question. I understand that an offer to purchase goods can be accepted by either a shipment of goods or a promise to ship. In this question, the manufacturer seems to have accepted by shipping the sofas. However, with the first shipment, the accompanying invoice includes a new term. Can merchants not include new terms in their acceptance if accepting via shipment? The lecturer for the simulated bar review simply states that there is offer and acceptance and THEN the additional term is introduced. But isn't the new term being introduced in conjunction with the acceptance? Just looking for further clarification because the lecture and explanation aren't making the distinction clear for me. Thank you in advance."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Samuel	Gordon	"2022-07-07 12:52:13"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	10436	"Hi Bryan, thanks that helps I think I was combining those two things in my head.Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAWQuestion ID: 10436Hello Samuel, I think what you're talking about is the principle that someone can challenge a statute as being overbroad on first amendment grounds even if the statute, as applied, would not be an overbroad application of that statute. See section 2 on pages 70-71 of your MBE Con Law outline: ""In order to prevent a “chilling effect” on protected speech (i.e., frightening people into not speaking for fear of prosecution), overbroad statutes may be challenged as “facially invalid” even by those who are validly regulated on behalf of those who are not. Broadrick v. Okla. , 413 U.S. 601 (1973)."" This doesn't remove the requirement for standing, however. The challenging individual must still have standing -- they would if, for example, they were regulated or prosecuted by the law. Here, the campaign volunteer isn't regulated by the law at all because it only regulates candidates themselves. Hope this helps, -Bryan  Samuel Gordon @ 2022-07-06 15:32:35 wrote: I was confused on this question because the answer said that there was no standing because there was no case or controversy, but I thought that any could challenge a facially invalid first amendment violation. Does a person need to violate a statute before they can challenge it facially?"	"RE: Who has standing to bring a facial challenge?"		NULL	738438	1737	336226	245688	"2022-07-07 13:10:55"	"2022-07-07 12:52:13"	0	0	0	1	"Bryan Cox"	"Sure thing, Samuel, and good luck studying!    Samuel Gordon @ 2022-07-07 12:52:13 wrote:  Hi Bryan, thanks that helps I think I was combining those two things in my head.    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAWQuestion ID: 10436  Hello Samuel,  I think what you're talking about is the principle that some