Hafsa	Tout	"2022-07-07 12:35:23"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	313	"Hi! I can't find this anywhere in the outlines or my lecture notes or flashcards, but I got part of the answer wrong in a practice civpro/conflict of laws question because I was sure I had learned a principle that a defendant waives his right to challenge jurisdiction (or something else?) over a dispute if he substantially participates in the litigation. So if, for example, he doesn't raise a certain defense or objection in his answer but then proceeds to discovery and produces evidence for the plaintiff, etc... Does this concept of substantial participation in the litigation come up anywhere or was I mistaken?"	"Waiving defenses/civpro"	Essay		738423	1737	400503	245688	"2022-07-07 23:22:43"	"2022-07-07 14:48:07"	1	313	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Hafsa,  You're probably thinking of waiving any objection to personal jurisdiction. If you appear and defend, and never raise lack of personal jurisdiction, then you'll have been deemed to waive it.  Subject-matter jurisdiction can be challenged at any time. However, if a party litigated subject-matter jurisdiction in the original proceeding, all the way up on appeal, then they won't be able to collaterally attack that in a separate proceeding because issue preclusion will apply.  I think you're thinking of one of those two principles.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Hafsa Tout @ 2022-07-07 12:35:23 wrote:  Hi! I can't find this anywhere in the outlines or my lecture notes or flashcards, but I got part of the answer wrong in a practice civpro/conflict of laws question because I was sure I had learned a principle that a defendant waives his right to challenge jurisdiction (or something else?) over a dispute if he substantially participates in the litigation. So if, for example, he doesn't raise a certain defense or objection in his answer but then proceeds to discovery and produces evidence for the plaintiff, etc... Does this concept of substantial participation in the litigation come up anywhere or was I mistaken?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Melisa	Hood	"2022-07-07 07:23:07"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	356	"Hi Lindsey,So if the question says charged, we presume the defendant has been indicted? When I read this question, my understanding was he had just been arrested and charged by the police, then was placed in the holding cell to be interrogated post-arrest. Hence my confusion on this question.Thanks,MelisaAdmin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDUREQuestion ID: 356Hi Melisa, Post-indictment statements that a defendant makes to a police informant are inadmissible when the police intentionally create a situation likely to induce the defendant into making incriminating statements about the crime for which he was indicted without the assistance of counsel. United States v. Henry, 447 U.S. 264, 274–275 (1980). There is no Sixth Amendment violation, however, if the police place an informant in the defendant's cell simply to listen and report the defendant's statements, without questioning the defendant. Kuhlmann v. Wilson, 477 U.S. 436, 456 (1986). Here, the police placed the man in a holding cell in the police station with an undercover police officer who was posing as a man arrested for drunken driving. The undercover officer asked the man several questions in an attempt to elicit information about the crime and discover where the man's accomplices might be hiding. So, because the police intentionally placed the informant in the cell to create a situation likely to induce the defendant into making incriminating statements, then there was a sixth amendment violation. If the informant was placed in the cell to simply listen and report what is said, then there would be no violation. As for the fifth amendment, Miranda warnings are not required if the suspect being questioned is not aware that the interrogator is a police officer. Illinois v. Perkins, 496 U.S. 292, 294 (1990). The 5th Amendment/Miranda rules only apply for custodial interrogation. If there is no warning given and the informant is only listening and not questioning, then there is no 5th Amendment/Miranda violation. Also, Miranda warnings are not required if the suspect being questioned is not aware that the interrogator is a police officer. Illinois v. Perkins, 496 U.S. 292, 294 (1990). Example: The police placed an undercover officer, posing as a criminal, in the defendant’s jail cell, and the undercover officer engaged the defendant in a conversation designed to elicit details of the crime for which the defendant was suspected. Such statements were admissible in the absence of Miranda warnings. Illinois v. Perkins, supra. I hope this clarifies! Lindsey  Melisa Hood @ 2022-07-06 16:42:16 wrote: I have a quick question about MBE simulated question 102, id 356. The answer said it violated his right to counsel under the 6th Amendment. Yet, the facts say he was arrested and charged with the crime, then placed in a holding cell. Wouldn't this have violated his 5th amendment right to counsel as he had not yet been arraigned? I also thought that interrogation was not a critical stage as it typically happens prior to being arraigned and when the alleged defendant is arrested and charged. Have I missed something completely on this question?  Thank you.  Melisa"	"RE: MBE Simulated Exam PM session question 2"	Follow-up	NULL	738150	1737	395158	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-07 07:23:07"	1	356	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Melisa,  Yes, an arrest and formal charge is sufficient to trigger the 6th Amendment. So, if the fact pattern says that he was &ldquo;arrested and charged,&rdquo; then the 6th Amendment right to counsel has attached.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Melisa Hood @ 2022-07-07 07:23:07 wrote:  Hi Lindsey,    So if the question says charged, we presume the defendant has been indicted? When I read this question, my understanding was he had just been arrested and charged by the police, then was placed in the holding cell to 