Matthew	Seafield	"2022-07-07 01:14:43"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	NULL	"Hi Anna,Thanks! I was misunderstanding the definition of ""consumer buyer."" This is helpful.Best,MattAdmin wrote:Lecture: NULLSubject Outline: SECURED TRANSACTIONSHi Matthew! It is important to be precise with the terminology—a consumer buyer is not the same as a “consumer.” UCC § 1-201(b)(11) defines a consumer as “an individual who enters into a transaction primarily for personal, family, or household purposes.”  A consumer could be a BOCB; a consumer buyer cannot be a BOCB. For UCC Article 9 purposes, in order to determine whether or not a buyer of a particular good that is subject to perfected security interest takes the good free from that interest (as either a consumer buyer or a BOCB), it is necessary to properly classify the type of seller the buyer is purchasing the good from. The seller of that good may be classified as a consumer seller OR a seller (whether it is an individual person or some form of business entity) who is in the business of selling goods of that kind. The terms are mutually exclusive.  Hope this helps! Best,  Anna  Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-06 17:26:13 wrote: Hi Anna,  Yes, that makes sense. Thank you. So could a consumer buyer also be a buyer in the ordinary course of business if that consumer buyer bought the goods from a consumer seller who is in the business of selling goods of that kind? I understand how they are different in most circumstances, but I am just not sure whether they are necessarily mutually exclusive.  Best, Matthew  Admin wrote: Subject Outline: SECURED TRANSACTIONS Hi Matthew!  The distinction between a Consumer Buyer and the BOCB turns on who is the seller.  A consumer buyer is a person who (1) buys consumer goods for value (2) for his own personal/family/household use (3) from a consumer seller (4) without knowledge of the security interest. This is often referred to as the “garage sale” rule—so generally, if you buy something from someone of Craigslist, you’d be a consumer buyer. See Secured Transactions § IV.C.3.  A BOCB is a person who (1) buys goods (2) in the ordinary course (3) from a seller who is in the business of selling goods of that kind (4) in good faith and (5) without knowledge that the sale violates the rights of another in the same goods. So, if you purchase something from a store or business, you’re a BOCB. See Secured Transactions § IV.C.2.   Hope this helps!  Best,  Anna  Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-05 18:13:20 wrote: Can a Buyer be both a Consumer Buyer and a Buyer in the Ordinary Course of Business (""BOCB"")?"	"RE: RE: Secured Transactions"		NULL	738113	1737	302806	435564	"2022-07-07 08:55:01"	"2022-07-07 01:14:43"	0	0	0	1	"Anna Rittgers"	"Glad to help! Best, -A    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-07 01:14:43 wrote:  Hi Anna,    Thanks! I was misunderstanding the definition of ""consumer buyer."" This is helpful.    Best,  Matt    Admin wrote:  Lecture: NULLSubject Outline: SECURED TRANSACTIONS  Hi Matthew!  It is important to be precise with the terminology&mdash;a consumer buyer is not the same as a &ldquo;consumer.&rdquo; UCC &sect; 1-201(b)(11) defines a consumer as &ldquo;an individual who enters into a transaction primarily for personal, family, or household purposes.&rdquo;   A consumer could be a BOCB; a consumer buyer cannot be a BOCB.  For UCC Article 9 purposes, in order to determine whether or not a buyer of a particular good that is subject to perfected security interest takes the good free from that interest (as either a consumer buyer or a BOCB), it is necessary to properly classify the type of seller the buyer is purchasing the good from. The seller of that good may be classified as a consumer seller OR a seller (whether it is an individual person or some form of business entity) who is in the business of selling goods of that kind. The terms are mutually exclusive.   Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-06 17:26:13 wrote:  Hi Anna,    Yes, that makes sense. Thank you. So could a consumer buyer also be a buyer in the ordinary course of business if that consumer buyer bought the goods from a consumer seller who is in the business of selling goods of that kind? I understand how they are different in most circumstances, but I am just not sure whether they are necessarily mutually exclusive.    Best,  Matthew    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: SECURED TRANSACTIONS  Hi Matthew!    The distinction between a Consumer Buyer and the BOCB turns on who is the seller.    A consumer buyer is a person who (1) buys consumer goods for value (2) for his own personal/family/household use (3) from a consumer seller (4) without knowledge of the security interest. This is often referred to as the &ldquo;garage sale&rdquo; rule&mdash;so generally, if you buy something from someone of Craigslist, you&rsquo;d be a consumer buyer. See Secured Transactions &sect; IV.C.3.    A BOCB is a person who (1) buys goods (2) in the ordinary course (3) from a seller who is in the business of selling goods of that kind (4) in good faith and (5) without knowledge that the sale violates the rights of another in the same goods. So, if you purchase something from a store or business, you&rsquo;re a BOCB. See Secured Transactions &sect; IV.C.2.      Hope this helps!    Best,   Anna    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-05 18:13:20 wrote:  Can a Buyer be both a Consumer Buyer and a Buyer in the Ordinary Course of Business (""BOCB"")?"	"Matthew Seafield"
Israel	"Del Mundo"	"2022-07-07 00:26:01"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	9790	"The answer explanation provides that there is complete diversity between the parties. How is this the case if the corporation is incorporated in one state and maintains a physical presence in another state?"	"Citizenship of Corporations"	"Mult. Choice"		738092	1737	380871	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-07 00:28:21"	1	9790	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Israel,  A corporation will be considered a citizen of the state of incorporation and the state where its principal place of business -- the nerve center/HQ -- is located. It does not take on the citizenship of other states where the corporation has physical presence. The example I like to use to illustrate is that, let's say, a corporation has a 10-person headquarters in Connecticut, and is incorporated in Delaware. Only 10 people, but it's the C-suite (CEO, CFO, COO, etc.) where all decisions are ultimately made. But the business of that corporation is operating retail stores in downtown New York City -- let's say literally thousands of people work for this company in downtown New York. That corporation's main physical presence is certainly in New York, but it is not a citizen of New York. It is only a citizen of Connecticut (PPOB -- the nerve center) and Delaware (state of incorporation). In this fact pattern, that is State B for both incorporation and PPOB.  Hope this helps!  Lindsey    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-07-07 00:26:01 wrote:  The answer explanation provides that there is complete diversity between the parties. How is this the case if the corporation is incorporated in one state and maintains a physical presence in another state?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Matthew	Seafield	"2022-07-06 23:33:02"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	NULL	"That makes sense. Thank you, Anna!Admin wrote:Lecture: NULLSubject Outline: MBE TORTSHi Matthew, ""Good Samaritan"" statutes vary among the states where they are adopted, but they generally only cover volunteers who renders aid to someone who is ill or injured. Good Samaritan statutes provide an exception to medical malpractice liability. Medical malpractice is not the same as ordinary negligence. Medical malpractice is medical negligence—any act or omission by a doctor that deviates from accepted norms of practice that causes an injury to hispatient. The elements to a medical malpractice claim are: (1) the doctor has a duty to provide care/treatment to the patient; (2) this duty was breached by the doctor’s failure to adhere to the standards of care (2) the breach caused the patient injury (4) the injury is measurable in damages.  Traditionally, doctors were held to a “local custom” standard for duty of care towards their patients: did the doctor’s actions comport with those doctors customarily employed in same/similar locale? While some jurisdictions retain the traditional rule, a majority apply a national standard of care to physicians. In addition, doctors have a specific duty to obtain informed consent from their patients—to explain risks of medical procedures before the patient consents to treatment. Torts Outline § D.2.d.2 covers this in more detail (including exceptions). Hope this helps! Best,  Anna   Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-06 20:25:54 wrote: Hi Anna,  Thank you! What about when a doctor performs care for a fee (ie, when they are staffed at a hospital and/or the patient comes to them in return for payment). This would presumably not be ""on a voluntary basis"", correct? Thus, is it possible for such a doctor to be liable for medical malpractice under a theory of ordinary negligence?  Best, Matt  Admin wrote: Subject Outline: MBE TORTS Hi Matthew!  In the states that have enacted Good Samaritan statutes, doctors and other medical personal are exempted from liability for ordinary negligence when they voluntarily render emergency care. However, they are NOT exempt from liability for gross negligence. See Torts Outline § IV.B.4.a.  Hope this helps!  Best,  Anna  Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-05 22:33:53 wrote: Is gross negligence required under the ""Good Samaritan Rule"" for medical malpractice? Or does mere negligence suffice?"	"RE: RE: Medical Malpractice"		NULL	738054	1737	302806	435564	"2022-07-07 00:17:05"	"2022-07-06 23:33:02"	0	0	0	1	"Anna Rittgers"	"You're welcome! Good luck with your studies!  -A    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-06 23:33:02 wrote:  That makes sense. Thank you, Anna!    Admin wrote:  Lecture: NULLSubject Outline: MBE TORTS  Hi Matthew,  ""Good Samaritan"" statutes vary among the states where they are adopted, but they generally only cover volunteers who renders aid to someone who is ill or injured. Good Samaritan statutes provide an exception to medical malpractice liability.  Medical malpractice is not the same as ordinary negligence. Medical malpractice is medical negligence&mdash;any act or omission by a doctor that deviates from accepted norms of practice that causes an injury to hispatient. The elements to a medical malpractice claim are: (1) the doctor has a duty to provide care/treatment to the patient; (2) this duty was breached by the doctor&rsquo;s failure to adhere to the standards of care (2) the breach caused the patient injury (4) the injury is measurable in damages.   Traditionally, doctors were held to a &ldquo;local custom&rdquo; standard for duty of care towards their patients: did the doctor&rsquo;s actions comport with those doctors customarily employed in same/similar locale? While some jurisdictions retain the traditional rule, a majority apply a national standard of care to physicians. In addition, doctors have a specific duty to obtain informed consent from their patients&mdash;to explain risks of medical procedures before the patient consents to treatment. Torts Outline &sect; D.2.d.2 covers this in more detail (including exceptions).  Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna     Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-06 20:25:54 wrote:  Hi Anna,    Thank you! What about when a doctor performs care for a fee (ie, when they are staffed at a hospital and/or the patient comes to them in return for payment). This would presumably not be ""on a voluntary basis"", correct? Thus, is it possible for such a doctor to be liable for medical malpractice under a theory of ordinary negligence?    Best,  Matt    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE TORTS  Hi Matthew!    In the states that have enacted Good Samaritan statutes, doctors and other medical personal are exempted from liability for ordinary negligence when they voluntarily render emergency care. However, they are NOT exempt from liability for gross negligence. See Torts Outline &sect; IV.B.4.a.    Hope this helps!    Best,    Anna    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-05 22:33:53 wrote:  Is gross negligence required under the ""Good Samaritan Rule"" for medical malpractice? Or does mere negligence suffice?"	"Matthew Seafield"
David	Salgado	"2022-07-06 22:47:50"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"		"Hi,I'm a little confused about whether a mistake of fact is a defense to malice crimes (common law murder and arson). Could you please clarify this for me?Best, David S."	"Mistake of Fact and Malice Crimes"	General		738029	1737	404018	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-06 23:42:39"	1	0	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi David,  If the mistake or ignorance of fact is offered to negate the existence of general intent or malice, it must be a reasonable mistake or ignorance, i.e. the type of mistake or ignorance that a reasonable person would have made under the circumstances. So, that mistake of fact must be honest AND reasonable. It has to be an honest mistake, meaning it is not enough that a reasonable person could have been mistaken. A person cannot later claim they were mistaken when they actually knew the situation all along.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    David Salgado @ 2022-07-06 22:47:50 wrote:  Hi,    I'm a little confused about whether a mistake of fact is a defense to malice crimes (common law murder and arson). Could you please clarify this for me?    Best,     David S."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Matthew	Seafield	"2022-07-06 20:25:54"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	NULL	"Hi Anna,Thank you! What about when a doctor performs care for a fee (ie, when they are staffed at a hospital and/or the patient comes to them in return for payment). This would presumably not be ""on a voluntary basis"", correct? Thus, is it possible for such a doctor to be liable for medical malpractice under a theory of ordinary negligence?Best,MattAdmin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE TORTSHi Matthew!  In the states that have enacted Good Samaritan statutes, doctors and other medical personal are exempted from liability for ordinary negligence when they voluntarily render emergency care. However, they are NOT exempt from liability for gross negligence. See Torts Outline § IV.B.4.a.  Hope this helps!  Best,  Anna  Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-05 22:33:53 wrote: Is gross negligence required under the ""Good Samaritan Rule"" for medical malpractice? Or does mere negligence suffice?"	"RE: Medical Malpractice"	Follow-up	NULL	737915	1737	302806	435564	"2022-07-06 23:28:32"	"2022-07-06 20:25:54"	1	0	TORTS	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Matthew,  ""Good Samaritan"" statutes vary among the states where they are adopted, but they generally only cover volunteers who renders aid to someone who is ill or injured. Good Samaritan statutes provide an exception to medical malpractice liability.  Medical malpractice is not the same as ordinary negligence. Medical malpractice is medical negligence&mdash;any act or omission by a doctor that deviates from accepted norms of practice that causes an injury to hispatient. The elements to a medical malpractice claim are: (1) the doctor has a duty to provide care/treatment to the patient; (2) this duty was breached by the doctor&rsquo;s failure to adhere to the standards of care (2) the breach caused the patient injury (4) the injury is measurable in damages.   Traditionally, doctors were held to a &ldquo;local custom&rdquo; standard for duty of care towards their patients: did the doctor&rsquo;s actions comport with those doctors customarily employed in same/similar locale? While some jurisdictions retain the traditional rule, a majority apply a national standard of care to physicians. In addition, doctors have a specific duty to obtain informed consent from their patients&mdash;to explain risks of medical procedures before the patient consents to treatment. Torts Outline &sect; D.2.d.2 covers this in more detail (including exceptions).  Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna     Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-06 20:25:54 wrote:  Hi Anna,    Thank you! What about when a doctor performs care for a fee (ie, when they are staffed at a hospital and/or the patient comes to them in return for payment). This would presumably not be ""on a voluntary basis"", correct? Thus, is it possible for such a doctor to be liable for medical malpractice under a theory of ordinary negligence?    Best,  Matt    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE TORTS  Hi Matthew!    In the states that have enacted Good Samaritan statutes, doctors and other medical personal are exempted from liability for ordinary negligence when they voluntarily render emergency care. However, they are NOT exempt from liability for gross negligence. See Torts Outline &sect; IV.B.4.a.    Hope this helps!    Best,    Anna    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-05 22:33:53 wrote:  Is gross negligence required under the ""Good Samaritan Rule"" for medical malpractice? Or does mere negligence suffice?"	"Matthew Seafield"
Amna	Haque	"2022-07-06 17:48:38"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	"10038, 9894"	"I'm struggling to see why the analysis applies differently between these two questions. The dormant commerce clause applies to both, and Congress has specifically authorizes discrimination towards out-of-state residents explicitly. When does the equal protection analysis factor in?"	"Difference between Question ID#10038 and #9894?"	"Mult. Choice"		737761	1737	394355	395418	"2022-07-07 09:46:07"	"2022-07-06 18:21:11"	1	10038	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Andreanna Jones (Ed)"	"Hi Amna,    Great question! The first thing we must consider is the call of the question in 10038 and in 9894. In 10038, the call of the question asks, ""Assuming that the state statute is consistent with federal statutes regulating the financial services industry, is it constitutional?"" However, in 9894, the call of the question here states that the group sought a declaratory judgment that the regulation violated the Dormant Commerce Clause. Therefore, the scope of 9894 is much narrower than 10038. So when analyzing 10038, you must consider all constitutional violations as contemplated by the provided answer choices&mdash;not just the Dormant Commerce Clause.    Congress has exclusive authority over interstate commerce. The statute mentioned in 10038 permitted any regulation if it was consistent with federal statutes regulating the industry. Here, Congress permitted the state to enact any law regarding the regulation and taxation of persons in the financial services industry. Because Congress has exclusive authority over interstate commerce, it may explicitly permit states to act in ways that would otherwise violate the Dormant Commerce Clause. But because this deals with state taxation of commerce, we must consider whether it violates other constitutional provisions. In section VII.B.1.b.&mdash; Violation of other constitutional provisions of the MBE Constitutional Law outline, it states that "" A discriminatory tax on out-of-state businesses, even if authorized by Congress and therefore allowed under the Commerce Clause, may still violate the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment, if it cannot satisfy the rational basis test."" So, in 10038, although the state tax on the out-of-state financial services industry would be permissible under the dormant commerce clause, it is unconstitutional under the equal protection clause because promotion of domestic business by discriminating against nonresident competitors is not a legitimate state purpose.    But 9894 deals with prohibiting out-of-state recreational hunters from hunting elk within the state. Because Congress permitted states to act in ways that would otherwise violate the Dormant Commerce Clause, this provision was constitutional. So, while the courts ruled on a state department's regulation, holding it invalid, Congress, which has authority over interstate commerce can create a law allowing what was deemed in violation of the Dormant Commerce Clause. Note that the call of the question here states that the group sought a declaratory judgment that the regulation violated the Dormant Commerce Clause. So, this question only dealt with the dormant commerce clause&mdash;not whether it violated one's rights under the Equal Protection clause. I hope this helps!    Best,  Ann    Amna Haque @ 2022-07-06 17:48:38 wrote:  I'm struggling to see why the analysis applies differently between these two questions. The dormant commerce clause applies to both, and Congress has specifically authorizes discrimination towards out-of-state residents explicitly. When does the equal protection analysis factor in?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Matthew	Seafield	"2022-07-06 17:26:13"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	NULL	"Hi Anna,Yes, that makes sense. Thank you. So could a consumer buyer also be a buyer in the ordinary course of business if that consumer buyer bought the goods from a consumer seller who is in the business of selling goods of that kind? I understand how they are different in most circumstances, but I am just not sure whether they are necessarily mutually exclusive.Best,MatthewAdmin wrote:Subject Outline: SECURED TRANSACTIONSHi Matthew!  The distinction between a Consumer Buyer and the BOCB turns on who is the seller.  A consumer buyer is a person who (1) buys consumer goods for value (2) for his own personal/family/household use (3) from a consumer seller (4) without knowledge of the security interest. This is often referred to as the “garage sale” rule—so generally, if you buy something from someone of Craigslist, you’d be a consumer buyer. See Secured Transactions § IV.C.3.  A BOCB is a person who (1) buys goods (2) in the ordinary course (3) from a seller who is in the business of selling goods of that kind (4) in good faith and (5) without knowledge that the sale violates the rights of another in the same goods. So, if you purchase something from a store or business, you’re a BOCB. See Secured Transactions § IV.C.2.   Hope this helps!  Best,  Anna  Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-05 18:13:20 wrote: Can a Buyer be both a Consumer Buyer and a Buyer in the Ordinary Course of Business (""BOCB"")?"	"RE: Secured Transactions"	Follow-up	NULL	737732	1737	302806	435564	"2022-07-07 00:43:15"	"2022-07-06 17:26:13"	1	0	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Matthew!  It is important to be precise with the terminology&mdash;a consumer buyer is not the same as a &ldquo;consumer.&rdquo; UCC &sect; 1-201(b)(11) defines a consumer as &ldquo;an individual who enters into a transaction primarily for personal, family, or household purposes.&rdquo;   A consumer could be a BOCB; a consumer buyer cannot be a BOCB.  For UCC Article 9 purposes, in order to determine whether or not a buyer of a particular good that is subject to perfected security interest takes the good free from that interest (as either a consumer buyer or a BOCB), it is necessary to properly classify the type of seller the buyer is purchasing the good from. The seller of that good may be classified as a consumer seller OR a seller (whether it is an individual person or some form of business entity) who is in the business of selling goods of that kind. The terms are mutually exclusive.   Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-06 17:26:13 wrote:  Hi Anna,    Yes, that makes sense. Thank you. So could a consumer buyer also be a buyer in the ordinary course of business if that consumer buyer bought the goods from a consumer seller who is in the business of selling goods of that kind? I understand how they are different in most circumstances, but I am just not sure whether they are necessarily mutually exclusive.    Best,  Matthew    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: SECURED TRANSACTIONS  Hi Matthew!    The distinction between a Consumer Buyer and the BOCB turns on who is the seller.    A consumer buyer is a person who (1) buys consumer goods for value (2) for his own personal/family/household use (3) from a consumer seller (4) without knowledge of the security interest. This is often referred to as the &ldquo;garage sale&rdquo; rule&mdash;so generally, if you buy something from someone of Craigslist, you&rsquo;d be a consumer buyer. See Secured Transactions &sect; IV.C.3.    A BOCB is a person who (1) buys goods (2) in the ordinary course (3) from a seller who is in the business of selling goods of that kind (4) in good faith and (5) without knowledge that the sale violates the rights of another in the same goods. So, if you purchase something from a store or business, you&rsquo;re a BOCB. See Secured Transactions &sect; IV.C.2.      Hope this helps!    Best,   Anna    Matthew Seafield @ 2022-07-05 18:13:20 wrote:  Can a Buyer be both a Consumer Buyer and a Buyer in the Ordinary Course of Business (""BOCB"")?"	"Matthew Seafield"
Melisa	Hood	"2022-07-06 16:42:16"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	356	"I have a quick question about MBE simulated question 102, id 356. The answer said it violated his right to counsel under the 6th Amendment. Yet, the facts say he was arrested and charged with the crime, then placed in a holding cell. Wouldn't this have violated his 5th amendment right to counsel as he had not yet been arraigned? I also thought that interrogation was not a critical stage as it typically happens prior to being arraigned and when the alleged defendant is arrested and charged. Have I missed something completely on this question?Thank you.Melisa"	"MBE Simulated Exam PM session question 2"	"Mult. Choice"		737668	1737	395158	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-06 17:16:36"	1	356	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Melisa,  Post-indictment statements that a defendant makes to a police informant are inadmissible when the police intentionally create a situation likely to induce the defendant into making incriminating statements about the crime for which he was indicted without the assistance of counsel. United States v. Henry, 447 U.S. 264, 274&ndash;275 (1980). There is no Sixth Amendment violation, however, if the police place an informant in the defendant's cell simply to listen and report the defendant's statements, without questioning the defendant. Kuhlmann v. Wilson, 477 U.S. 436, 456 (1986). Here, the police placed the man in a holding cell in the police station with an undercover police officer who was posing as a man arrested for drunken driving. The undercover officer asked the man several questions in an attempt to elicit information about the crime and discover where the man's accomplices might be hiding. So, because the police intentionally placed the informant in the cell to create a situation likely to induce the defendant into making incriminating statements, then there was a sixth amendment violation. If the informant was placed in the cell to simply listen and report what is said, then there would be no violation. As for the fifth amendment, Miranda warnings are not required if the suspect being questioned is not aware that the interrogator is a police officer. Illinois v. Perkins, 496 U.S. 292, 294 (1990). The 5th Amendment/Miranda rules only apply for custodial interrogation. If there is no warning given and the informant is only listening and not questioning, then there is no 5th Amendment/Miranda violation. Also, Miranda warnings are not required if the suspect being questioned is not aware that the interrogator is a police officer. Illinois v. Perkins, 496 U.S. 292, 294 (1990). Example: The police placed an undercover officer, posing as a criminal, in the defendant&rsquo;s jail cell, and the undercover officer engaged the defendant in a conversation designed to elicit details of the crime for which the defendant was suspected. Such statements were admissible in the absence of Miranda warnings. Illinois v. Perkins, supra.  I hope this clarifies!  Lindsey    Melisa Hood @ 2022-07-06 16:42:16 wrote:  I have a quick question about MBE simulated question 102, id 356. The answer said it violated his right to counsel under the 6th Amendment. Yet, the facts say he was arrested and charged with the crime, then placed in a holding cell. Wouldn't this have violated his 5th amendment right to counsel as he had not yet been arraigned? I also thought that interrogation was not a critical stage as it typically happens prior to being arraigned and when the alleged defendant is arrested and charged. Have I missed something completely on this question?    Thank you.    Melisa"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Samuel	Gordon	"2022-07-06 15:32:35"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	10436	"I was confused on this question because the answer said that there was no standing because there was no case or controversy, but I thought that any could challenge a facially invalid first amendment violation. Does a person need to violate a statute before they can challenge it facially?"	"Who has standing to bring a facial challenge?"	"Mult. Choice"		737549	1737	336226	245688	"2022-07-06 23:45:08"	"2022-07-06 16:17:49"	1	10436	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Samuel,  I think what you're talking about is the principle that someone can challenge a statute as being overbroad on first amendment grounds even if the statute, as applied, would not be an overbroad application of that statute. See section 2 on pages 70-71 of your MBE Con Law outline:  ""In order to prevent a &ldquo;chilling effect&rdquo; on protected speech (i.e., frightening people into not speaking for fear of prosecution), overbroad statutes may be challenged as &ldquo;facially invalid&rdquo; even by those who are validly regulated on behalf of those who are not. Broadrick v. Okla. , 413 U.S. 601 (1973).""  This doesn't remove the requirement for standing, however. The challenging individual must still have standing -- they would if, for example, they were regulated or prosecuted by the law. Here, the campaign volunteer isn't regulated by the law at all because it only regulates candidates themselves.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Samuel Gordon @ 2022-07-06 15:32:35 wrote:  I was confused on this question because the answer said that there was no standing because there was no case or controversy, but I thought that any could challenge a facially invalid first amendment violation. Does a person need to violate a statute before they can challenge it facially?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Natalie	Dolarian	"2022-07-06 14:40:24"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	2379	"I still don't understand why/how there is additional consideration to modify this contract after reading the explanation. And I thought that accord  satisfaction only applies when the amount owed is disputed or the contract is satisfied through a different type of consideration? Thanks in advance."	"Where is the additional consideration?"	"Mult. Choice"		737459	1737	350209	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-06 14:42:14"	1	2379	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Natalie,  In 2379, the new consideration is the exchange of $2k for the removal of the mold. The removal of the mold is not a part of the original contract, so the contractor didn't already have a duty to remove it (no preexisting duty). The parties agreed to modify the original contract (to include the mold removal for an additional $2k), but the homeowner is now seeking to avoid the modification. So, the key here is that the homeowner is not seeking to void the contract. He is merely trying to avoid paying the modification to the contract. Therefore, we need to find an answer that focuses on the enforceability of the modification. Because the homeowner agreed to the modification, and there is consideration for it, the modification is enforceable. The homeowner could have refused, and then if the contractor refused to continue with the contract, he would be in breach and the homeowner could sue.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Natalie Dolarian @ 2022-07-06 14:40:24 wrote:  I still don't understand why/how there is additional consideration to modify this contract after reading the explanation. And I thought that accord  satisfaction only applies when the amount owed is disputed or the contract is satisfied through a different type of consideration? Thanks in advance."	"Lindsey Hallam"
