Kyla	Randle	"2022-07-05 19:30:21"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	"Question 4980"	"I am still confused on how the defendant was not subject to personal jurisdiction after being personally served. Was it because they were not personally served in the forum state?"	"Civ pro"	"Mult. Choice"	"civ pro"	736856	1737	336618	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-05 20:24:58"	1	4980	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Kyla,  This question is tricky, because it is not testing the method of service of process, but is testing whether service of process confers personal jurisdiction when a defendant is not subject to service of process under the law of the forum state (i.e., the forum state's law does not permit out-of-state service for this action). A federal court must generally determine personal jurisdiction as if it were a court of the state in which the federal court sits. In this question, according to forum state law, the defendant is not subject to service of process for this action in her home state. So service of process (even if accomplished in a method acceptable under the federal rules) in her home state will not confer personal jurisdiction over the defendant.  Hope this helps!  Lindsey    Kyla Randle @ 2022-07-05 19:30:21 wrote:  I am still confused on how the defendant was not subject to personal jurisdiction after being personally served. Was it because they were not personally served in the forum state?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
