e gets $300,000 or $225,000, etc. in different scenarios). I was thinking that if the decedent's estate was worth less than that, it would be hard to apply the rules in any kind of exam question because the numbers wouldn't add up right. So I assumed that exam questions would always necessarily have a fact pattern where the estate is over, for example, $500,000 or somewhere around that amount so that we could subtract the numbers reasonably if we needed to.    I did a practice essay where the remainder of a decedent's estate was less than $100,000 and the answer included a rule I hadn't come across before about pro rata abatement but didn't discuss the intestacy rules for surviving spouse because it wasn't relevant to the fact pattern. I guess my question is, how do we apply the UPC rules for intestate succession for surviving spouses on the exam if the value of the estate we're given is less than $150,000 (which is the lowest amount that a spouse takes under intestacy-UPC)? Or should that not be a concern since the facts will give us an amount above that?    I hope this makes sense, and thank you in advance!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
David	Salgado	"2022-07-03 19:47:13"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"		"Hi, When must a witness be given the opportunity to explain a statement that is used to impeach him? I'm having a good deal of trouble narrowing down this concept. Respectfully,David Salgado"	"Evidence/Impeachment: When Must a Witness Be given the Opportunity to Explain"	General		735447	1737	404018	159111	"2022-07-04 12:39:40"	"2022-07-03 20:02:03"	1	0	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Kathleen Schandler"	"Hi David,  The witness must be given, at some point in the proceedings, an opportunity to explain or deny the allegedly inconsistent statement. The opportunity need not come before introduction of the statement under the FRE.  Best,  Katie    David Salgado @ 2022-07-03 19:47:13 wrote:  Hi,     When must a witness be given the opportunity to explain a statement that is used to impeach him? I'm having a good deal of trouble narrowing down this concept.     Respectfully,    David Salgado"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Alana	Jones	"2022-07-03 16:57:18"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"		"Hello,What are elements of common law second-degree murder? I don't think the lecture talked about it."	"Criminal law"	General		735362	1737	420384	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-03 19:49:33"	1	0	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Alana,  Homicide is the killing of one person by another and encompasses murder and manslaughter. At common law, there are no degrees of murder. So, if you are meant to determine the degree of the murder, the question will have to give you a statute to use that defines each degree. If the question only says ""murder"" and does not define it, then you are to use the common law. If you&rsquo;re supposed to talk about degrees, then you will be given a statute. So, there&rsquo;s no second-degree common law murder. Second-degree murder is a homicide committed with the necessary malicious intent: the intent to kill, the intent to do great bodily injury, or a depraved-heart murder. It&rsquo;s similar to common law murder, but remember, it is defined by a statute.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Alana Jones @ 2022-07-03 16:57:18 wrote:  Hello,  What are elements of common law second-degree murder? I don't think the lecture talked about it."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Maya	Goldman	"2022-07-03 13:56:36"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	5889	"Hi,In the handout for property, lecture 6 on RAP violations, there is an example of a RAP violation that reads: ""Oliver conveys, “to Anna so long as the property is used as a farm, then to Ben.” Anna has a fee simple subject to an executory interest and Ben has an executory interest. This conveyance violates RAP. It is possible that Ben’s executory interest will vest more than 21 years after Anna’s or Ben’s death."" Thus, Ben has no interest and Oliver has a possibility of reverter. I don't understand how this fact pattern is different from the one in Question ID 5889, which uses the same ""so long as"" language. The explanation for the answer to that question says that the conveyance doesn't violate RAP. How is this different from the language in the handout? Thanks!Best,Maya 		 	 	 		"	"RAP question"	"Mult. Choice"	"Property #6 on RAP"	735239	1737	362920	159111	"2022-07-04 11:22:28"	"2022-07-03 15:15:18"	1	5889	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Kathleen Schandler"	"Hi Maya,    5889 is not that similar to the example in the lecture handout because they have different future interests.  The lecture example: The future interest is an executory interest (because it is not in the grantor, but a third party)  5889: The future interest is in the grantor. The future interest is a possibility of reverter.    RAP only applies to:  1) contingent remainders  2) executory interests  3) vested remainder subject to open.    Therefore RAP does not apply to 5889, but does apply to lecture example.  Twenty years ago, a grantor conveyed farmland by warranty deed to a charity that organizes community gardening &ldquo;so long as the land is used for growing food.&rdquo;    Maya Goldman @ 2022-07-03 13:56:36 wrote:  Hi,    In the handout for property, lecture 6 on RAP violations, there is an example of a RAP violation that reads: ""Oliver conveys, &ldquo;to Anna so long as the property is used as a farm, then to Ben.&rdquo; Anna has a fee simple subject to an executory interest and Ben has an executory interest. This conveyance violates RAP. It is possible that Ben&rsquo;s executory interest will vest more than 21 years after Anna&rsquo;s or Ben&rsquo;s death."" Thus, Ben has no interest and Oliver has a possibility of reverter. I don't understand how this fact pattern is different from the one in Question ID 5889, which uses the same ""so long as"" language. The explanation for the answer to that question says that the conveyance doesn't violate RAP. How is this different from the language in the handout? Thanks!    Best,    Maya"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-07-02 17:21:28"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	10393	"How can you get strict scrutiny under equal protection when it's not one of the strict scrutiny suspect classes? The rule is the to get strict scrutiny, it needs to be one of the strict scrutiny suspect classes. Here, it's not one of those suspect classes. And it's not a heightened scrutiny suspect class. So doesn't it have to be rational basis under equal protection? HOWEVER, voting is a fundamental right under due process. So due process could get this fact pattern to strict scrutiny."	"Fundamental rights -- equal protection"	"Mult. Choice"		734879	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-02 18:48:07"	1	10393	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  I think I answered this question in my previous answer, but please let me know if you have any further questions. But keep in mind that when a fundamental right of a certain class of people is being infringed upon, then you would discuss the EP clause. And Kramer v. Union Free School District No. 15, 395 U.S. 621 (1969) requires the application of strict scrutiny in this fact pattern.  Lindsey      Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-07-02 17:21:28 wrote:  How can you get strict scrutiny under equal protection when it's not one of the strict scrutiny suspect classes? The rule is the to get strict scrutiny, it needs to be one of the strict scrutiny suspect classes. Here, it's not one of those suspect classes. And it's not a heightened scrutiny suspect class. So doesn't it have to be rational basis under equal protection? HOWEVER, voting is a fundamental right under due process. So due process could get this fact pattern to strict scrutiny."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-07-02 17:16:36"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	10393	"The outlines say that voting is a fundamental right under substantive due process. Since property ownership isn't a protected class, shouldn't it be rational basis under equal protection? But under substantive due process, it's a fundamental right that triggers strict scrutiny. What am I not understanding?"	"Substantive due process -- voting"	"Mult. Choice"		734876	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-02 18:48:25"	1	10393	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  This question is tricky. Here, the Due Process Clause is applicable. If this were an essay question you could certainly raise it and you will be given points for it. However, this is the MBE and it is not the best answer provided and so it would still be incorrect for the purposes of the exam. The question asks for the best way to challenge the method of electing the local school board. As the explanation states, substantive due process relates more to the situation where the government tries to take this right away from a specific individual through a quasi-judicial or adjudicatory proceeding. If, on a question, a fundamental right is being infringed upon for all persons, the issue is likely one of substantive due process. If the right is being denied to only a particular class of persons, then equal protection is in play. The question at issue deals with the latter. Furthermore, while property ownership is generally not a valid ground upon which to restrict the right to vote, there are situational exceptions to this rule (e.g. special purpose entities). However, the Equal Protection Clause generally requires the application of strict scrutiny to a restriction of voting to a particular class of persons, which generally results in the invalidation of the restriction. Kramer v. Union Free School District No. 15, 395 U.S. 621 (1969) (state law that restricted voting in school board election to property owners and parents with school-aged children struck down).  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-07-02 17:16:36 wrote:  The outlines say that voting is a fundamental right under substantive due process. Since property ownership isn't a protected class, shouldn't it be rational basis under equal protection? But under substantive due process, it's a fundamental right that triggers strict scrutiny. What am I not understanding?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
