Regina	Fragale	"2022-07-02 13:24:29"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	"Question ID# 9826"	"Here, the explanation of the answer provides ""the agency created this rule to addresssociety'sbroad history of discrimination against racial minority groups—not thestate'sown specific history of racial discrimination."" But, the question provided ""The purpose of the rule was to help redress the historical discrimination against these groups in the state.""Please explain. Thank you."	"Question about multiple choice"	"Mult. Choice"		734669	1737	366301	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-02 13:49:50"	1	9826	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Regina,  Programs that favor racial or ethnic minorities are also subject to strict scrutiny. Adarand Constructors, Inc. v. Pena, 515 U.S. 200 (1995) (overruling application of the intermediate standard to federal discrimination). For a governmental affirmative action program based on race to survive, the relevant governmental entity must show more than a history of societal discrimination. The government&mdash;whether federal, state, or local&mdash;must itself be guilty of specific past discrimination against the group it is seeking to favor, and the remedy must be narrowly tailored to end that discrimination and eliminate its effects. In other words, the elimination of past discrimination in a particular governmental institution is a compelling state interest; attempting to remedy general societal injustice through affirmative action is not. In this question, the state agency created the rule to help redress the historical discrimination against these groups in the state and to help them achieve economic parity with other groups in society. Because this isn&rsquo;t saying that the rule was created to address the State's own specific history of racial discrimination, it doesn&rsquo;t survive strict scrutiny. Note that it states that there was a history of discrimination against these groups in the State, but it doesn&rsquo;t say that the State had a specific history of racial discrimination against these groups. For this rule to survive strict scrutiny, the facts would have to say that the State had a specific history of racial discrimination, and the rule&rsquo;s purpose was to help remedy that specific history &ndash; there would need to be direct evidence of the State&rsquo;s specific discrimination against these groups.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Regina Fragale @ 2022-07-02 13:24:29 wrote:  Here, the explanation of the answer provides ""the agency created this rule to addresssociety'sbroad history of discrimination against racial minority groups&mdash;not thestate'sown specific history of racial discrimination."" But, the question provided ""The purpose of the rule was to help redress the historical discrimination against these groups in the state.""    Please explain. Thank you."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-02 12:18:36"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	TRUSTS	2204	"The notes at the bottom of the essay state that the remainder interest fails. Why is this? I thought charitable trust were not subject to RAP and thus could not fail?"	trusts	Essay		734595	1737	413801	159137	"2022-07-02 15:48:18"	"2022-07-02 13:40:51"	1	2204	"WILLS AND DECEDENTS' ESTATES"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Nick!  The note is not referring to the RAP. It is saying that if cy pres did not apply, the interest would fail and return to the testator's estate. The note is only applicable to the extent cy pres did not apply in the jurisdiction.  Steve    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-02 12:18:36 wrote:  The notes at the bottom of the essay state that the remainder interest fails. Why is this? I thought charitable trust were not subject to RAP and thus could not fail?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Israel	"Del Mundo"	"2022-07-01 23:54:38"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"Does a federal court need to have specific personal jurisdiction over the defendant, or general personal jurisdiction?"	"In Personam Jurisdiction"	General		734429	1737	380871	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-07-02 00:09:08"	1	0	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Israel,  I&rsquo;m going through the entire analysis for personal jurisdiction because I think it will help. Personal jurisdiction analysis begins with a two-prong test: Is the exercise of personal jurisdiction statutorily authorized (this is typically, but not always, a long-arm statute); and Is the exercise of jurisdiction in this case constitutionally permissible (i.e. does it comport with due process -- ""traditional notions of fair play and substantial justice."") A long-arm statute is a statute that says that jurisdiction may be exercised whenever it is constitutionally permissible. In this case, the analysis collapses into, basically, just the second item. When it comes to the second item, there are certain bases on which -- based on history -- exercise of jurisdiction definitely comports with due process. These are the voluntary presence, consent, etc. bases. If, however, the defendant is served with process outside of the state, then you have to look at the defendant's contacts with the forum state to determine if jurisdiction is appropriate. General and specific jurisdiction are two methods of analyzing contacts. General jurisdiction requires systematic and continuous contacts that render the defendant ""at home"" in the forum state, such that it would satisfy traditional notions of fair play and substantial justice for any lawsuit to be maintained against the defendant. Specific jurisdiction requires only that there be minimum contacts with the forum state, which, due to being related to the subject matter of the litigation, it comports with traditional notions of fair play and substantial justice to allow this particular litigation to be maintained. The claim must either arise from the activity within the state or the defendant must be essentially at home in the forum state for a claim that does not arise from the particular contacts to be maintained against them. So, the federal court could have personal jurisdiction under general jurisdiction or specific jurisdiction over an out of state defendant.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-07-01 23:54:38 wrote:  Does a federal court need to have specific personal jurisdiction over the defendant, or general personal jurisdiction?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
