Zahraa	Nasser	"2022-07-01 14:40:40"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	9454	"Hello!One of the exceptions to the 11th Amendment shown in the chart in the explanation is if the state officer is being sued for injunctive relief. However, the explanation below says that it doesn't matter if they're being sued for monetary or injunctive relief. Can you please direct me to the differentiating distinction?Thank you!Zahraa"	"Exceptions to 11th Amendment "	"Mult. Choice"		733995	1737	370966	435073	"2022-07-05 08:23:12"	"2022-07-01 16:22:39"	1	9454	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Amy Grover"	"Good Morning,    I hope that this message finds you well.    With this analysis it is important to identify who is being sued, where that person (or entity) is being sued, and under what law that person is being sued. Under the Eleventh Amendment, a state (or an official thereof) cannot be sued in federal court solely for a violation of state law.    Here, there is a legal representative of a person living in a mental facility. The facility is owned and operated by the state. There is a state law requiring the person running the facility (a state official) to provide the ""least-restrictive-environment"" possible for the people in the facility. The representative sued the official in federal court to enforce a state law. Because this is prohibited by the Eleventh Amendment, the federal judge should grant the official's motion.    Had the representative sued the official in federal court to enforce a federal statute (or prevent the enforcement of a state statute that violated federal law), then it is likely that the official could have been sued for injunctive relief. Additionally, if the representative had sued the official in state court to enforce the state law, then it also would have been all right.    If you would like some more information, &sect; I.A.3 of the Themis MBE Constitutional outline goes into some more nuances.    I hope this helps!    Amy G.      Zahraa Nasser @ 2022-07-01 14:40:40 wrote:  Hello!    One of the exceptions to the 11th Amendment shown in the chart in the explanation is if the state officer is being sued for injunctive relief. However, the explanation below says that it doesn't matter if they're being sued for monetary or injunctive relief. Can you please direct me to the differentiating distinction?    Thank you!  Zahraa"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-07-01 13:17:14"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	5077	"So if a corporation is (1) incorporated in a US state, but (2) has its principal place of business in a foreign country, the corporation will be seen as a foreign party, not as a US citizen?"	"civ pro"	"Mult. Choice"		733915	1737	413801	397534	"2022-07-06 00:24:28"	"2022-07-01 16:10:56"	1	5077	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Devin Mock"	"Hi Nick,  This question is probably a bit outside the scope of what you can expect from the Bar Examiners, but if a corporation was incorporated in a US state, it would not be a foreign party. The corporation would be a citizen of the US state where it was incorporated and the foreign country where the principal place of business is located. (See MBE Civil Procedure Outline &sect; I.C.3.b.1) Corporations).  Best of luck!  Devin    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-07-01 13:17:14 wrote:  So if a corporation is (1) incorporated in a US state, but (2) has its principal place of business in a foreign country, the corporation will be seen as a foreign party, not as a US citizen?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ashley	Bishel	"2022-07-01 12:20:46"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	10196	"Does it matter that this was involuntary manslaughter? I assumed this meant it was a criminal charge, so the sovereign immunity wouldn't apply because it wasn't a civil suit? "	"criminal charges?"	"Mult. Choice"		733854	1737	397350	436051	"2022-07-01 22:16:57"	"2022-07-01 12:56:44"	1	10196	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Ashley,    No, the type of crime is generally irrelevant so long as the federal officer was acting within their official capacities. The doctrine of sovereign immunity shields the federal government (and its officers) from both civil lawsuits and state criminal charges unless Congress consents.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Ashley Bishel @ 2022-07-01 12:20:46 wrote:  Does it matter that this was involuntary manslaughter? I assumed this meant it was a criminal charge, so the sovereign immunity wouldn't apply because it wasn't a civil suit? "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Max	Lupin	"2022-06-30 21:37:29"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"Hello,Several of the materials state that in order for an organization to have standing, it’s members must have standing (representational standing). Is direct organizational standing excluded from the topics tested on the UBE or should I separately review direct organizational standing?"	"Organizational Standing"	General		733530	1737	418912	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-30 21:46:43"	1	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Max,  An organization may bring an action when it has suffered an injury. But, if the organization is suing on behalf of its members (since a litigant generally has no standing to bring a lawsuit based on legal claims of a third party) if: i) Its members would have standing to sue in their own right; and ii) The interests at stake are germane to the organization's purpose.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Max Lupin @ 2022-06-30 21:37:29 wrote:  Hello,    Several of the materials state that in order for an organization to have standing, it&rsquo;s members must have standing (representational standing). Is direct organizational standing excluded from the topics tested on the UBE or should I separately review direct organizational standing?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
