Faith	Tan	"2022-06-30 17:03:19"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	7539	"Good afternoon,I have a question about when the prosecution may bring in specific instances of conduct during cross-examination. In Question 7539, the defense opened the door to character evidence with a character witness who gave opinion/reputation testimony. When can the prosecution bring in specific instances of conduct? I thought that once the defense has opened the door on the defendant's character, the prosecution may bring up specific instances. Is this limited only to the witness who testified initially about the defendant's character? Or can the prosecution bring up specific instances when cross-examining anyone who testifies once the door has been opened?Thank you for your help!"	"Question about specific instances of conduct on cross-examination"	"Mult. Choice"		733338	1737	354634	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-30 17:12:43"	1	7539	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Faith,  You can cross-examine the character witness about specific acts because this is impeachment by contradiction. For example, let's say that a character witness says ""the defendant is peaceful, in my opinion."" The prosecution impeaches by asking if the witness knows about the defendant's involvement in a fight. That impeaches the witness's character testimony -- if they answer yes, then you could ask ""So why, if they were in a fight, do you think they're peaceful?"" Or if they say they don't know about it, then you've impeached them by attacking whether they have enough knowledge to have an accurate opinion on the subject. But in this question, the question isn't directed at the witness. It's directed at the defendant. You can't impeach the prior witness by going at the defendant who is now on the stand -- that's not proper impeachment. So, the prosecution could have asked the character witness on cross-examination, but not the defendant.  Hope this helps!  Lindsey    Faith Tan @ 2022-06-30 17:03:19 wrote:  Good afternoon,    I have a question about when the prosecution may bring in specific instances of conduct during cross-examination. In Question 7539, the defense opened the door to character evidence with a character witness who gave opinion/reputation testimony. When can the prosecution bring in specific instances of conduct? I thought that once the defense has opened the door on the defendant's character, the prosecution may bring up specific instances. Is this limited only to the witness who testified initially about the defendant's character? Or can the prosecution bring up specific instances when cross-examining anyone who testifies once the door has been opened?    Thank you for your help!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Hafsa	Tout	"2022-06-30 15:51:48"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"Hi, I'm getting through the constitutional law lectures now and the outline lists citizenship status as a suspect classification alongside race, ethnicity, and national origin. At the same time there's a note in the lecture handout on page 26 that says, ""Citizenship status is not a suspect classification. Even so, states cannot deny undocumented children public education."" And the list of suspect classes only included the first three (race, ethnicity, and nat'l origin) so I'm a little confused about where citizenship fits in for the purposes of the bar and conlaw analyses we'll be expected to make.Thank you!"	"Is citizenship status a suspect classification?"	"Lecture+(Handout and/or Outline)"		733235	1737	400503	369936	"2022-07-01 15:24:51"	"2022-06-30 17:11:28"	2	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Colten Hall"	"Hi Hafsa,  This area of the law is just a bit of a mess.  Race, ethnicity, national origin are considered suspect and therefore require closer judicial examination.  In some cases--if the classification is by state law, for example, alienage is included as a suspect class.  Classifications based on status as a lawful resident of the United States (as opposedto a citizen) are subject to a variety of different standards, depending on the level ofgovernment and the nature of the classification.  The Court will generally apply the strict scrutiny test and strike down state laws that discriminate against aliens, such as laws prohibiting aliens from owning land, obtaining commercial fishing licenses, or being eligible for welfare benefits or civil service jobs.  BUT, undocumented aliens are not a suspect classification, even if it is a state law, because SCOTUS said ""their presence in this country in violation of federal law is not a 'constitutional irrelevancy.'""   Nevertheless, depriving them of education is not rationally related to asubstantial goal of the state.  So, include alienage as suspect for state laws, not federal, and only if it is based on lawful alienage. Then, don't forget the exceptions that apply--read through the Outline for a better discussion of those, p. 52.  Best,  C    Hafsa Tout @ 2022-06-30 15:51:48 wrote:  Hi, I'm getting through the constitutional law lectures now and the outline lists citizenship status as a suspect classification alongside race, ethnicity, and national origin. At the same time there's a note in the lecture handout on page 26 that says, ""Citizenship status is not a suspect classification. Even so, states cannot deny undocumented children public education."" And the list of suspect classes only included the first three (race, ethnicity, and nat'l origin) so I'm a little confused about where citizenship fits in for the purposes of the bar and conlaw analyses we'll be expected to make.    Thank you!        "	"Anindita Dutta"
Kyla	Randle	"2022-06-30 15:34:00"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"WILLS AND DECEDENTS' ESTATES"	1984	"Under the practice essay, the notes sates thefollowing:If Husband’s daughter is entitled to the $40,000 bequest to Husband, there will be $115,000 of general legacies to abate proportionally when distributing the $60,000.IWas wondering where the 115,000 was coming from and what this note really means?"	Wills	Essay	essay	733214	1737	336618	159137	"2022-06-30 17:48:35"	"2022-06-30 17:18:33"	1	1984	"WILLS AND DECEDENTS' ESTATES"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Kyla!  This is an alternative answer that the examiners would accept instead of the main answer. The main answer explains that the gift to Husband lapsed because he died before the Testator here. In some states, though, an anti-lapse provision might apply, which is what the alternative answer seems to be positing. If it did, then daughter would be entitled to the $40K bequest (succeeding to it from what would have gone to Husband). You add the 40K gift to the 75K gift (25,000 each) to Church, Library, and School to equal $115,000. Since there is only $60K of actual money in the estate to divide up, Daughter, Church, Library, and School would only get a percentage of that $60K based on what their original gift would be.   I hope this helps.  Steve    Kyla Randle @ 2022-06-30 15:34:00 wrote:    Under the practice essay, the notes sates thefollowing:If Husband&rsquo;s daughter is entitled to the $40,000 bequest to Husband, there will be $115,000 of general legacies to abate proportionally when distributing the $60,000.IWas wondering where the 115,000 was coming from and what this note really means?  "	"Anindita Dutta"
