Victor	Hiltner	"2022-06-30 10:50:17"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	5320	"Hi there,I just finished MEE practice essay 5320, which is a civil procedure essay, and I am writing for clarification on the intersection between Erie and Rule 23. The essay answer for part 2 of this question states that a class action can be maintained, despite a state law precluding statutory damages for class actions, so long as Rule 23 is met. I could not find this information in the outline, and I am confused as to how this relates to the typical choice of law analysis.That is, where a state law says ""no statutory damages for class actions,"" that seems like the type of law that, if not applied, would encourage forum shopping and lead to the inequitable administration of justice (contrary to Erie)—particularly in a situation as here, where the class action is seeks statutory damages alone.Could you clarify what the answer means when it says that a class action can still be ""maintained"" if it meets Rule 23? Does this mean the state law is inapplicable and statutory damages are available? Does this Rule 23 analysis somehow supersede the typicalErie analysis? I'm sure I am missing something here.Thank you!Best,Victor Hiltner"	"Class Actions, Erie & Bar of Statutory Damages"	Essay		732908	1737	342082	435745	"2022-07-03 17:54:20"	"2022-06-30 11:16:20"	1	5320	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Laura Wakefield"	"Hello,  Keep in mind that the point of Erie is to apply the state law if there is no federal law on point. If there is federal law on point, then the federal law applies even if it contradicts the state law. The state law at issue in this question is that there are no statutory damages for class actions. There is federal law on point - Rule 23 - which lays out the requirements of a class action in a case arising under diversity jurisdiction. Because the federal requirements for a class action are met, the state bar on class actions doesn&rsquo;t apply. This is what the explanation means when it says that the class action can be maintained; the class action continues to exist because federal law supersedes the state prohibition on class actions in cases seeking statutory damages.  Hope this helps!  Laura     Victor Hiltner @ 2022-06-30 10:50:17 wrote:  Hi there,    I just finished MEE practice essay 5320, which is a civil procedure essay, and I am writing for clarification on the intersection between Erie and Rule 23. The essay answer for part 2 of this question states that a class action can be maintained, despite a state law precluding statutory damages for class actions, so long as Rule 23 is met. I could not find this information in the outline, and I am confused as to how this relates to the typical choice of law analysis.    That is, where a state law says ""no statutory damages for class actions,"" that seems like the type of law that, if not applied, would encourage forum shopping and lead to the inequitable administration of justice (contrary to Erie)&mdash;particularly in a situation as here, where the class action is seeks statutory damages alone.    Could you clarify what the answer means when it says that a class action can still be ""maintained"" if it meets Rule 23? Does this mean the state law is inapplicable and statutory damages are available? Does this Rule 23 analysis somehow supersede the typicalErie analysis? I'm sure I am missing something here.    Thank you!    Best,  Victor Hiltner"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Jenae	Longenecker	"2022-06-30 09:12:43"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"CONFLICT OF LAWS"		"In the professor's third example (on page 4 of the handout), he concludes that this is a false conflict because West Carolina doesn't have an interest. I understand why they don't have a loss-shifting interest, because neither of the parties are domiciliaries of their state. However, why wouldn't the state have an interest in prohibiting the kind of negligent conduct that led to the car accident?Thanks for your help!"	"Governmental Interest Analysis"	Handout	"Conflicts Lecture 2"	732849	1737	345376	159137	"2022-06-30 13:01:46"	"2022-06-30 09:22:01"	1	0	"CONFLICT OF LAWS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Jenae!  I think the professor's point here is that West Carolina has nostate domiciliary to benefit here. Under the governmental interest approach, the presumption is that the forum state will apply its own law. While you are right that there may be some interest for W. Carolina here because the accident took place there. No state would apply the W. Carolina law in this circumstance.  Steve    Jenae Longenecker @ 2022-06-30 09:12:43 wrote:  In the professor's third example (on page 4 of the handout), he concludes that this is a false conflict because West Carolina doesn't have an interest. I understand why they don't have a loss-shifting interest, because neither of the parties are domiciliaries of their state. However, why wouldn't the state have an interest in prohibiting the kind of negligent conduct that led to the car accident?    Thanks for your help!"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
