Summer	Stevens	"2022-06-29 16:38:09"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MULTISTATE PERFORMANCE TEST"	" 10042"	"I still don't understand why the fast-food chain wins here. It seems like the culinary school recorded first, was a bonafide purchaser, and didn't have notice of the other purchase (because it hadn't happened at the time of their recording). Am I just reading this question wrong? I don't understand how the previous owner's failure to record impacts the culinary school when they did everything right."	"Wild Deed vs. Race-Notice"	"Mult. Choice"		732406	1737	347554	159111	"2022-06-30 14:18:43"	"2022-06-29 19:05:48"	1	10042	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Kathleen Schandler"	"Hi Summer,  Only BFPs are entitled to prevail against a prior transferee under ""notice"" and ""race-notice"" statues. To attain this status a person must satisfy three requirements (i) be a purchaser (ii) take without notice and (iii) pay valuable consideration. The notice discussion is there to determine if the buyer is a BFP and thus can use to the statue to prevail. A ""wild deed"" is a recorded deed that is not connected to the chain of title. It does not give constructive notice because the subsequent BFP cannot feasibly find it. Therefore the fast food chain would be a BFP and then we would go to our race-notice statue to determine who has title.    Notice statutes protect SUBSEQUENT purchasers against PRIOR grantees. Thus a race notice statute would not help school (a prior grantee) against fast-food (a subsequent purchaser).  I hope this helps!    Summer Stevens @ 2022-06-29 16:38:09 wrote:  I still don't understand why the fast-food chain wins here. It seems like the culinary school recorded first, was a bonafide purchaser, and didn't have notice of the other purchase (because it hadn't happened at the time of their recording). Am I just reading this question wrong? I don't understand how the previous owner's failure to record impacts the culinary school when they did everything right."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Danny	Dvorak	"2022-06-29 15:29:30"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	9535	"Hello,I am having a bit of difficulty squaring question 9535 with the explanation in 9454. In 9454, the explanation says:TheEleventh Amendment prohibitsforeign governments and private parties from suing a state in federal court without the state's consent. This immunity extends tosuits against state officialsfor aviolation of state law—even if the remedy that is sought isinjunctive reliefinstead of monetary damages (as seen here).In 9535, the employer filed a suit in federal court seeking to enjoin a state official from enforcing a state law. Is this allowed because the employer was challenging the state law on its face?Thanks,Danny"	"Squaring Two Questions"	"Mult. Choice"		732330	1737	410822	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-29 19:03:53"	1	9535	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Danny,  First, subject matter jurisdiction of the court is different from whether there is an 11th Amendment prohibition on what the plaintiff is seeking. In 9535, the question is asking whether the court had jurisdiction to hear the case. Now with regard to the rule stated in 9454, a citizen of the same state or a different state may sue an appropriate state official in federal court for prospective relief of an equitable nature. That includes injunctive relief. However, the federal court cannot entertain an action against a state government officer for violating state law. So, the exception applies only to federal law, not state law. Here, she is suing the official in federal court based on a violation of state law. She is not claiming that the injunction is needed for a violation of federal law. This is why this exception does not apply to this fact pattern. So, the 11th amendment prohibits the action of a federal court when the basis for the action is a violation of state law. In 9535, a citizen is filing an action against the attorney general seeking an injunction to prevent the attorney general from enforcing the state statute and the citizen is claiming that the law is unconstitutional. However, we don&rsquo;t know on what basis the citizen is claiming the law is constitutional (probably because the eleventh amendment issue isn&rsquo;t being tested here). So, as stated above, when a state official, rather than the state itself, is named as the defendant in an action brought in federal court, the state official may be enjoined from enforcing a state law that violates federal law or may be compelled to act in accord with federal law despite state law to the contrary. Ex parte Young, 209 U.S. 123 (1908), Edelman v. Jordan, 415 U.S. 651 (1974). Thus, if the citizen is claiming that the state law violated federal law, then attorney general may be enjoined from enforcing it. If not, then the person needs to file in state court.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Danny Dvorak @ 2022-06-29 15:29:30 wrote:  Hello,    I am having a bit of difficulty squaring question 9535 with the explanation in 9454. In 9454, the explanation says:    TheEleventh Amendment prohibitsforeign governments and private parties from suing a state in federal court without the state's consent. This immunity extends tosuits against state officialsfor aviolation of state law&mdash;even if the remedy that is sought isinjunctive reliefinstead of monetary damages (as seen here).    In 9535, the employer filed a suit in federal court seeking to enjoin a state official from enforcing a state law. Is this allowed because the employer was challenging the state law on its face?    Thanks,  Danny"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Vikram	Rajan	"2022-06-29 13:26:19"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"		"Do felonies that a suspect intends to commit inside a dwelling count as lesser included offenses of burglary? I just answered an MBE question for Crim Law (3rd set, question 11), that appears to have separated larceny from burglary as crimes that a suspect could be found guilty of. There is added complexity to the question, so I'm not sure if this is correct. Asked differently, can a person be convicted of both burglary and the underlying felony that they intended to and successfully did commit?"	"Lesser Included Offenses of Burglary"	General		732184	1737	415485	159137	"2022-06-29 18:42:48"	"2022-06-29 16:49:23"	1	0	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Vikram!  If the underlying felony is completed, it does not merge with the burglary. See page 29 of the full MBE outline.  Steve    Vikram Rajan @ 2022-06-29 13:26:19 wrote:  Do felonies that a suspect intends to commit inside a dwelling count as lesser included offenses of burglary? I just answered an MBE question for Crim Law (3rd set, question 11), that appears to have separated larceny from burglary as crimes that a suspect could be found guilty of. There is added complexity to the question, so I'm not sure if this is correct. Asked differently, can a person be convicted of both burglary and the underlying felony that they intended to and successfully did commit?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-06-29 13:04:23"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	2991	"Does this also apply to impeaching witnesses with a judgment of a prior felony conviction that does NOT involve character for truthfulness? Can a witness NOT be asked on examination about a prior felony conviction but then be impeached by introduction of that felony into evidence?"	evidence	"Mult. Choice"		732162	1737	413801	206578	"2022-07-01 21:02:55"	"2022-06-29 18:54:33"	1	2991	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Phil Bullimore"	"Hi Nick,  Evidence of conviction of a crime that does not involve dishonesty can be used for impeachment only if the crime is punishable by death or imprisonment for more than one year and generally only if the conviction is 10 or fewer years old. For criminal defendant, the evidence is only admissible if the probative value outweighs the prejudicial effect, but for other witnesses, the evidence is permitted unless the probative value is SUBSTANTIALLY outweighed by the prejudicial effect. The evidence may be entered after cross-examination and without asking the person about it.  I hope this is helpful!  Best,  Max    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-06-29 13:04:23 wrote:  Does this also apply to impeaching witnesses with a judgment of a prior felony conviction that does NOT involve character for truthfulness? Can a witness NOT be asked on examination about a prior felony conviction but then be impeached by introduction of that felony into evidence?"	"Anindita Dutta"
