Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-27 23:04:47"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"But Congress can impose adirect federal tax(e.g., a tax onreal property) only if it is:apportioned proportionatelyamong the states based on each state's populationI'm having trouble understanding what apportioned proportionately among the states based on each state's population means. Can you give an example of a tax that is apportioned proportionately and one that isn't?"	"Direct federal taxes"	General		730900	1737	421938	436051	"2022-06-29 17:01:17"	"2022-06-28 19:20:38"	1	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Ty,    All this means is that if the federal government imposes a tax upon the states, it cannot be a &ldquo;flat tax&rdquo; and must instead be levied based on each of the state&rsquo;s populations. There are no modern direct federal taxes that are apportioned proportionately, perhaps due to Congress&rsquo; reluctance to enact these taxes and the Supreme Court&rsquo;s hesitance to find that any federal taxes are direct. If you run into a practice problem that deals with direct federal tax, feel free to try to answer it to the best of your ability and send another message with your question and question ID.    Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-27 23:04:47 wrote:  But Congress can impose adirect federal tax(e.g., a tax onreal property) only if it is:    apportioned proportionatelyamong the states based on each state's population    I'm having trouble understanding what apportioned proportionately among the states based on each state's population means. Can you give an example of a tax that is apportioned proportionately and one that isn't?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-27 21:07:59"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	9795	"Why doesn't this default to recklessness? A prior question's explanation provided: ""When a statute does not specify the requisite mental state, the minimumrequired mental stateaccording to the MPC isrecklessness"""	"Mens Rea"	Essay		730798	1737	425061	436051	"2022-06-28 23:36:14"	"2022-06-28 18:31:43"	1	9795	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Kevin Farnan"	"Hello Jonathan,    A strict-liability crime, by definition, is a crime that does not require a mens rea and proof of an actus reus is sufficient for a conviction. Offenses requiring no mens rea are generally disfavored, and courts have held that there must be some clear indication of legislative intent to dispense with the mens rea element of a crime. One clear indication is the severity of the penalty, where crimes with light penalties are more likely to be strict liability offenses. Regulatory offenses are more likely to be strict liability offenses, such as firearms regulations, traffic offenses, and food or drug regulations. Here, we are dealing with a traffic violation with a relatively light penalty, which fits into the category of strict liability.    If you can provide me with the question ID of the prior question, I can help you with the distinction if you need further guidance.     Hope this helps, and bon voyage!  - KJ    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-27 21:07:59 wrote:  Why doesn't this default to recklessness? A prior question's explanation provided: ""When a statute does not specify the requisite mental state, the minimumrequired mental stateaccording to the MPC isrecklessness"""	"Lindsey Hallam"
