Natalie	Dolarian	"2022-06-27 00:29:10"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	9623	"Thanks!Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE EVIDENCEQuestion ID: 9623Hi Natalie, There are two types of spousal privilege: spousal immunity and confidential marital communications. Under spousal immunity, the general rule is that the spouse of a criminal defendant may not be called as a witness by the prosecution, nor may a married person be compelled to testify against his spouse in any criminal proceeding. In federal courts and in a majority of state courts, the witness spouse holds the privilege and may choose to testify but cannot be compelled to do so. However, under confidential marital communications, communication made between spouses while they were married is privileged if the communication was made in reliance on the sanctity of marriage. The majority view, which is followed by most federal courts, is that the privilege is held by both spouses. Here, the defendant cannot prevent his wife from testifying against him at all. The wife could testify about things she personally witnessed or has personal knowledge about, should she so choose, as she is the holder of the privilege under spousal immunity. However, she cannot testify as to the confidential communication the husband shared with her about her husband's former employer, as it was a communication shared between spouses while married (and this privilege extends beyond the termination of the marriage—though here, they were only separated). Because both parties hold this privilege, the defendant-spouse may prevent her from testifying as to the confidential communication. I hope this helps! Lindsey  Natalie Dolarian @ 2022-06-26 01:36:49 wrote: I'm 80% sure Prof. Sherman taught this in a way that conflicts with this answer. In my notes, exam tip 4 says: ""Remember that under the federal system, the witness spouse holds the privilege; the defendant cannot prevent the spouse from waiving their privilege if they choose to testify against their spouse."" I must be reading the question and answer wrong..."	"RE: Spousal privilege"		NULL	729900	1737	350209	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-27 00:29:10"	0	0	0	1	"Lindsey Hallam"	"You're welcome!    Natalie Dolarian @ 2022-06-27 00:29:10 wrote:  Thanks!    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE EVIDENCEQuestion ID: 9623  Hi Natalie,  There are two types of spousal privilege: spousal immunity and confidential marital communications. Under spousal immunity, the general rule is that the spouse of a criminal defendant may not be called as a witness by the prosecution, nor may a married person be compelled to testify against his spouse in any criminal proceeding. In federal courts and in a majority of state courts, the witness spouse holds the privilege and may choose to testify but cannot be compelled to do so. However, under confidential marital communications, communication made between spouses while they were married is privileged if the communication was made in reliance on the sanctity of marriage. The majority view, which is followed by most federal courts, is that the privilege is held by both spouses. Here, the defendant cannot prevent his wife from testifying against him at all. The wife could testify about things she personally witnessed or has personal knowledge about, should she so choose, as she is the holder of the privilege under spousal immunity. However, she cannot testify as to the confidential communication the husband shared with her about her husband's former employer, as it was a communication shared between spouses while married (and this privilege extends beyond the termination of the marriage&mdash;though here, they were only separated). Because both parties hold this privilege, the defendant-spouse may prevent her from testifying as to the confidential communication.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Natalie Dolarian @ 2022-06-26 01:36:49 wrote:  I'm 80% sure Prof. Sherman taught this in a way that conflicts with this answer. In my notes, exam tip 4 says: ""Remember that under the federal system, the witness spouse holds the privilege; the defendant cannot prevent the spouse from waiving their privilege if they choose to testify against their spouse."" I must be reading the question and answer wrong..."	"Natalie Dolarian"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-26 20:55:13"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	9549	"Why isn't this a wingspan search? Clearly the pursue was within the arrestee's wingspan. The arrest will lawful. There was no warrant to search the pursue, so it's a warrantless search. And the pursue was within her immediate surroundings."	"Wingspan search"	"Mult. Choice"		729801	1737	425061	245688	"2022-06-27 22:47:43"	"2022-06-27 17:36:31"	1	9549	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Jonathan,  This fact pattern is based on Arizona v. Gant. A search incident to arrest can have two purposes: (1) officer safety, and (2) seizure of evidence of crime that could otherwise be destroyed. However, once the arrestee is secured in a patrol car, the justifications for such a search evaporate. See section (4) on page 13 of your MBE Crim Pro outline.  The vehicle can still be searched if there's probable cause to believe there's evidence of crime in the vehicle -- that's just the basic automobile exception at work -- but when the arrest is for a warrant, or for (in this case) speeding, there's nothing to indicate that such probable cause exists.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-26 20:55:13 wrote:  Why isn't this a wingspan search? Clearly the pursue was within the arrestee's wingspan. The arrest will lawful. There was no warrant to search the pursue, so it's a warrantless search. And the pursue was within her immediate surroundings."	"Anindita Dutta"
