'm not aware of any case law that extends Palmer's reasoning to any other exception.  One difference is that business records end up getting in via a business records affidavit, whereas for a past recollection recorded the witness is on the stand and has to first try to remember -- thus will be subject to cross. So that's probably one reason that the logic doesn't extend here.  It's not that you're overthinking it, it's just that the bar exam only tests law that is fairly clearly established.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Jordan Leskera @ 2022-06-25 19:52:10 wrote:  Does a document made in anticipation of litigation have any effect on the Past Recollection Recorded exception to the Rule Against Hearsay? In other words, is the reasoning in Palmerapplicable to Past Recollection Recorded?    I do not think I'm confusing the Business Record Exception with Past Recollection Recorded. I understand the Business Record Exception, and the holding in Palmer(records prepared in anticipation of litigation, such as an EEs accident report, may not qualify under the business record exception due to a lack of trustworthiness). The record in this problem is not a business record because it was not kept in the course of a regularly conducted activity of the business; and the EEs making of the record was not a regular practice.    I understand the test for Past Recollection Recorded: if a witness has inadequate memory to testify and a record exists, then the witness may read the record if: (1) the record concerns a matter about which the witness once had knowledge; (2) the record was prepared or adopted by the witness when the matter was fresh; (3) the record accurately reflects the witness's knowledge; and (4) the witness testifies he has insufficient memory of the event to testify fully and accurately, even after consulting the writing while on the stand. This test is satisfied in the problem, but the EE specifically made the record in anticipation of litigation. It seems fundamentally unfair to allow a witness with potential bias (eg, a desire to keep his job) to a party to introduce evidence he made due to the potential of untruthfulness.    Please help me clear this up. Am I just overthinking this?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-25 15:37:35"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	9705	"I thought the lecture/outline said that mistake of fact is a defense for specific-intent crimes. But the explanation here (intuitively) says otherwise. Apparently I'm not understanding the mistake of fact defense from the lecture/outline. Can you address my misunderstanding?"	"Mistake of fact defense"	"Mult. Choice"		729176	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-25 15:38:56"	1	9705	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  Mistake of fact is a defense to specific intent crimes when the mistake negates the state of mind required (even if the mistake is unreasonable). So, ignorance or mistake as to a matter of fact will affect criminal guilt only if it shows that the defendant did not have the state of mind required for the crime. Example: A, hunting in the woods, shoots at what he reasonably believes to be a deer. In fact, it is B, who is killed. A's mistake of fact establishes that he did not have the state of mind required for murder. Compare: A, hunting in the woods, shoots through the tress at a figure he believes is his enemy B, intending to kill him. In fact, the figure is C, who is killed. A is guilty for murdering C despite his mistake of fact as to C's identify, because A's mistake does not negate his intent to kill a person. In this question, the mistake of fact regarding the plants did not negate the daughter's state of mind. She still intended to kill her parents and took a substantial step toward doing so. As such, this mistake of fact would not negate her specific intent to kill her parents, so it would not be a defense to attempted murder here.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-25 15:37:35 wrote:  I thought the lecture/outline said that mistake of fact is a defense for specific-intent crimes. But the explanation here (intuitively) says otherwise. Apparently I'm not understanding the mistake of fact defense from the lecture/outline. Can you address my misunderstanding?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jenae	Longenecker	"2022-06-24 16:20:29"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"		"Outline says ""Evidence of an existing statutory or regulatory violation or a reasonable plan supported by a valid public interest will justify the issuance of a warrant.""What kind of plan does this refer to? Who is making the plan?"	"Administrative Searches"	Outline		728667	1737	345376	435070	"2022-06-27 13:14:59"	"2022-06-24 18:08:23"	1	0	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"^Krista Corley"	"Hi Jenae,  This section of the Outline is referring to administrative search warrants. Administrative search warrants are issued so that a valid public interest can be upheld, or when there is evidence of a statutory or regulatory violation.   The type of plan this statement is referring to is an administrative search, and the government is making the plan. This includes government searches of gun shops, automobile junkyards, wiretapping, drug testing of railroad employees, inventory searches of items in protective custody, border searches, etc.  For a traditional search warrant, an officer must have more than reasonable suspicion that evidence of illegal conduct will be found before a court can issue a search warrant.  The standard is lower for an administrative search warrant. For example, the government may believe statutory violations are taking place (i.e., clerks are failing to check ID&rsquo;s for age limits at liquor stores). Or perhaps there is a valid public interest in searching airplane passengers before boarding planes, without any probable cause that a particular passenger has engaged in (or is conspiring to engage in) criminal activity during travel. As a result, an administrative search warrant could be issued based on the government&rsquo;s plan to search plane passengers based on a valid public interest.  If you haven&rsquo;t already, you may consider reading section I.C.4(g) of the Criminal Procedure Outline on administrative, special needs, and inventory searches. There are many good examples discussed and it may provide additional context for you.  I hope this helps!  -Krista     Jenae Longenecker @ 2022-06-24 16:20:29 wrote:  Outline says ""Evidence of an existing statutory or regulatory violation or a reasonable plan supported by a valid public interest will justify the issuance of a warrant.""  What kind of plan does this refer to? Who is making the plan?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Max	Lupin	"2022-06-24 13:47:24"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	"Test 2 no 5"	"Hello, I realize the specific question inquired about (question 5 of con law practice test 2) does specify that we should assume that no other regulatory scheme exists, but in general, will multiple choice questions ask one to ignore the existence of actual federal statutory schemes (and should one ignore them if the question does not ask)? I ask because I know that in reality courts are split on whether the food drug and cosmetic act occupies the field of regulated products under it, so the answer referring to field preemption is at least viable under actual federal law (although admittedly not the specific question here)."	"Ignoring actual federal statutory law "	"Mult. Choice"		728466	1737	418912	435724	"2022-06-25 22:59:21"	"2022-06-24 15:26:25"	1	9164	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Colleen Scrocca"	"  Dear Max,  These instructions could occur in both the multiple choice and essay questions. Generally, when instructions like this are given it is because there is either a specific rule or regulation they want you to focus on without distraction or the question could potentially be too broad without narrowing it without instructions providing a focus.  If the question does not provide instructions like this then I would not ignore anything, state or federal, that may factor into your answer. That being said, especially with multiple choice questions, don&rsquo;t allow yourself to get to distracted by rabbit holes that you over-think your answer. Multiple choice questions are intended to be a short fact patter that allows them to narrow onto one topic to be tested on that question. If you feel like you are thinking too deeply step back and try to figure out what general legal topic is that being tested. It&rsquo;s not uncommon with the multiple-choice questions there are technically two answers that are correct you need to pick the one that is &ldquo;more correct&rdquo;.   This caution against over-thinking is especially relevant to topics you may have real-world experience with or extensive study (beyond the law-school classes). It&rsquo;s easy to see nuances or find threads in questions that may &ldquo;technically&rdquo; be correct, but end up leading you to a wrong answer. If this is the case for you on any of these topics, be mindful of this tendency and dial it back to what the question is asking that the typical recent law graduate may know.  With the essays, when you outline you answer you should plan to discuss or at least mention the things that relate to the question. Even if this is something that you will ultimately determine does not apply, mention it. If you don&rsquo;t mention it the graders don&rsquo;t know that it was considered and dismissed. They will have to assume you didn&rsquo;t remember it.  It&rsquo;s difficult to talk about these things in a general way, but I hope you get what I&rsquo;m saying.   I hope this helps.  Best of Luck,  Kelley    Max Lupin @ 2022-06-24 13:47:24 wrote:  Hello, I realize the specific question inquired about (question 5 of con law practice test 2) does specify that we should assume that no other regulatory scheme exists, but in general, will multiple choice questions ask one to ignore the existence of actual federal statutory schemes (and should one ignore them if the question does not ask)? I ask because I know that in reality courts are split on whether the food drug and cosmetic act occupies the field of regulated products under it, so the answer referring to field preemption is at least viable under actual federal law (although admittedly not the specific question here)."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ashley	Mastro	"2022-06-24 13:31:04"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	6454	"The answer addresses why claim preclusion does not apply, but not why issue preclusion does not apply. I don't understand why issue preclusion does not apply. If the passenger is suing for personal injuries from the crash and its already been decided the driver was not negligent, then hasn't this issue already been decided?"	"Issue Preclusion "	"Mult. Choice"		728457	1737	424994	159111	"2022-06-25 13:07:42"	"2022-06-24 15:24:09"	1	6454	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Kathleen Schandler"	"Hi Ashley,  We know the question is only asking us about issue preclusion because of the call of the question: ""Can the truck driver successfully preclude the re-litigation of his fault in the accident?""  Collateral estoppel is narrower than res judicata. Res judicata focuses on something relatively large - the scope of a ""cause of action."" If it applies, the result is usually to bar the claimant from asserting a second case. Collateral estoppel, in contrast, focuses on something relatively narrow - an issue that was litigated and determined in the first case, and that is relevant in a second case. With collateral estoppel, the issue is deemed established in the second case without need to proffer evidence on it. So you need to see if you are trying to get an entire case to go away so that there is no second case at all, or an issue to not have to be relitigated in a second case.  I hope this helps!  Regards, Katie    Ashley Mastro @ 2022-06-24 13:31:04 wrote:  The answer addresses why claim preclusion does not apply, but not why issue preclusion does not apply. I don't understand why issue preclusion does not apply. If the passenger is suing for personal injuries from the crash and its already been decided the driver was not negligent, then hasn't this issue already been decided?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Kyla	Randle	"2022-06-23 23:15:13"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"		"Hello,I just wanted to clarify the right to counsel vs. the right to remain silent under the 5th amendment. If a person asserts unambiougsly the right to remain silent does the person have to also assert the right to an attorney or are they combined? If they are not combined, what is the difference between the two as far as interrogation. If the person asserts the right to remain silent, the officers can still return to question the defendant after a certain amount of time. Does this mean that if the person invokes the right to counsel, the officers cannot approach the defendant AT ALL unless they're with their lawyer or they choose to do so voluntarily? Sorry if this is confusing."	"Right to counsel v. right to remain silent"	General	"Criminal procedure "	728138	1737	336618	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-23 23:19:32"	1	0	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Kyla,  No. To invoke the right to counsel under the Fifth Amendment, a suspect must make a specific, unambiguous statement asserting his desire to have counsel present. As with the Fifth Amendment right to counsel, the defendant must make a specific, unambiguous statement asserting his desire to remain silent. So, these two rights are separate. If a suspect makes an ambiguous statement regarding the right to counsel, the police are not required to end the interrogation or to ask questions or clarify whether the suspect wants to invoke the right. Davis v. United States, 512 U.S. 452 (1994). However, once that right to counsel is invoked, all interrogation must stop until counsel is present. Edwards v. Arizona, 451 U.S. 477, 484 (1981). If the suspect voluntarily initiates communication with the police after invoking his right to counsel, a statement made by the suspect, such as a statement that the suspect spontaneously blurts out, can be admissible because it is not made in response to interrogation. In addition, police may re-open interrogation of a suspect who has asserted his Fifth Amendment right to counsel if there has been a 14-day or more break in custody (such as the release back into the general prison population of a suspect who has been incarcerated for another crime). In such circumstances, the officers must give fresh Miranda warnings and get a valid waiver before beginning questioning. Maryland v. Shatzer, 559 U.S. 98 (2010). If a defendant invokes his Miranda right to remain silent, the interrogator(s) must &ldquo;scrupulously honor&rdquo; that request (e.g., immediately cease interrogation, allow for a significant passage of time, give a second set of warnings). However, if after the defendant is released from custody, the defendant indicates a desire to speak to police, then a subsequent interrogation would be lawful, as long as the defendant was not coerced. The defendant must again receive fresh Miranda warnings.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Kyla Randle @ 2022-06-23 23:15:13 wrote:  Hello,  I just wanted to clarify the right to counsel vs. the right to remain silent under the 5th amendment. If a person asserts unambiougsly the right to remain silent does the person have to also assert the right to an attorney or are they combined? If they are not combined, what is the difference between the two as far as interrogation. If the person asserts the right to remain silent, the officers can still return to question the defendant after a certain amount of time. Does this mean that if the person invokes the right to counsel, the officers cannot approach the defendant AT ALL unless they're with their lawyer or they choose to do so voluntarily? Sorry if this is confusing."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Kyla	Randle	"2022-06-23 21:39:45"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	"Question 9687"	"I was wondering why legal impossibility could not be a defense. I thought legal impossibility was when the crime committed is not actually a crime. In this case, the store was giving away 2 free plants and he took 2 free plants so it was not illegal therefore it was not a crime. I just would like a clarification on legal impossibility to see if my understanding was right."	"Criminal law MBQ practice quiz 2"	"Mult. Choice"		728070	1737	336618	397561	"2022-06-26 19:26:51"	"2022-06-23 23:11:48"	1	9687	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Nicole Werner"	"Hi Kyla:    Impossibility is not a defense to attempt if the crime attempted is factually impossible to commit due to circumstances unknown to the defendant. If, however, the act intended is not a crime (i.e., a legal impossibility), then the defendant is not guilty of attempt. In such a case, even when statutes purport to have done away with the impossibility defense, there is always a provision that allows for legal impossibility.    In this fact pattern, it is factually impossible for the gardener to commit the crime (larceny) attempted because, unknown to him, the plants were free. The act intended (stealing plants from the garden center) would be a crime under other circumstances, so it is not a legal impossibility.    Good luck!    Nicole    Kyla Randle @ 2022-06-23 21:39:45 wrote:  I was wondering why legal impossibility could not be a defense. I thought legal impossibility was when the crime committed is not actually a crime. In this case, the store was giving away 2 free plants and he took 2 free plants so it was not illegal therefore it was not a crime. I just would like a clarification on legal impossibility to see if my understanding was right."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-23 20:23:28"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	"10083 and 10067"	"10083 says that interlocutory exceptions are appeals at the discretion of appeals court. 10067 says that interlocutory exceptions are appeals as of right. What am I misunderstanding?"	"Interlocutory appeals"	"Mult. Choice"		728018	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-23 23:07:10"	1	10083	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  It will depend on the actual interlocutory order. Although most interlocutory orders, such as the denial of a summary judgment motion, a motion to dismiss, or the granting of a new trial motion, are not immediately appealable, 28 U.S.C. &sect; 1292(a) makes certain equitable orders reviewable immediately as a matter of right, including: i) An order granting, modifying, refusing, or dissolving an injunction; ii) An order appointing or refusing to appoint a receiver; and iii) A decree determining the rights and liabilities of the parties to admiralty cases in which appeals from final decrees are allowed. So, the orders in this list, are as of right. Under 28 U.S.C. &sect; 1292(b), if a district court certifies (i) that an order involves a controlling question of law as to which there is substantial ground for difference of opinion, and (ii) that an immediate appeal from the order may materially advance the ultimate termination of the litigation, then a court of appeals has discretion to permit an appeal to be taken from such order. So, this is discretionary. Also, a court of appeals has the discretion to permit an appeal from a district court order granting or denying class action certification.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey        Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-23 20:23:28 wrote:  10083 says that interlocutory exceptions are appeals at the discretion of appeals court. 10067 says that interlocutory exceptions are appeals as of right. What am I misunderstanding?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-23 19:07:37"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"How do I figure out if I apply the United States v. O'Brien test (the regulation is within the government's power to enact, etc.) or the time, place, or manner test (are content-neutral as to both subject matter and viewpoint, etc.)?"	"Regulation of speech in public forum"	General		727982	1737	421938	245688	"2022-06-25 17:31:11"	"2022-06-23 23:00:25"	1	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Ty,  The time, place, and manner restrictions apply when the location regulated is a public forum or limited public forum. The O'Brien test applies more broadly, regardless of where the regulated speech is occurring, but it only applies to symbolic speech, which is conduct that has an expressive nature -- e.g. burning draft cards.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-23 19:07:37 wrote:  How do I figure out if I apply the United States v. O'Brien test (the regulation is within the government's power to enact, etc.) or the time, place, or manner test (are content-neutral as to both subject matter and viewpoint, etc.)?    "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Max	Lupin	"2022-06-23 18:20:40"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"Hi, I had a couple of questions arising from the con law lectures.Is there a cutoff date for changes in constitutional law prior to the exam? As in are cases decided through the end of this term fair game on the exam (especially with respect to abortion, but also other rights)? Or will they not generally ask questions like that?Is there anything we should know about Whole Women's Health v. Jackson (or more generally about exceptions to the availability of injunctive relief against government officers under Ex Parte Young? I realize this is more of a federal courts/jurisdiction question, but the professor stated in passing that such relief was always available to prevent the enforcement of an unconstitutional law, which seemed like an oversimplification—is that a safe assumption on the exam?Finally, the professor did not mention religion as a suspect classification during his discussion of the Equal Protection Clause—I realize that a lot of religion questions are better analyzed through the First Amendment's religion clauses, but my understanding had been that religion was a suspect classification and laws discriminating against members of a religion (especially outside of contexts where free exercise and establishment are implicated) were analyzed using strict scrutiny under 14A's EPC clause (or 5A DPC for federal govt.). Is this correct? Or is this just not necessary for the exam?Thank you!"	"Con law questions"	General		727935	1737	418912	159076	"2022-06-27 14:53:03"	"2022-06-23 18:25:57"	0	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Sophie Dye (Ed)"	"Hi, Max:  You won't need to know anything from this term for the bar exam. It's always been true that the examiners give a 6-month to 1-year grade period, but they actually affirmatively announced that this would be the case this summer, due to the significance of these rulings. You can find that announcement here.  I also wouldn't, at this time, worry too much about Whole Woman's Health v Jackson. I think it's going to take practitioners, legal experts, and judges some time to suss out all the implications here and I don't think the examiners would ask examinees to do it. On the exam, if you see this issue at all, I imagine it will involve a straightforward case of a state official acting in an executive (not judicial) capacity.  As for religion, it's often mentioned alongside other suspect classes and is considered to be a suspect class (e.g. Griffin v Illinois, Burlington N. R.R. Co. v. Ford, New Orleans v Drake) but there hasn't really been a decision on those grounds. Cases involving religion usually arise under the First Amendment and are analyzed that way. And really, the cases are going to arise under either the Free Exercise or Establishment clauses. The government would either be infringing on the Free Exercise clause by singling out some kind of behavior, or Establishment by favoring one religion over another, or religion over nonreligion. But given the state of flux of the Establishment Clause after today's ruling, it would be nice to have a straightforward strict scrutiny analysis to fall back on! And, I wonder if that's the future of the issue. But for now, it's safe to stick to analyzing cases that involve religion under the First Amendment.  I hope this is helpful! Good luck on your continued studies!  Mercedes    Max Lupin @ 2022-06-23 18:20:40 wrote:  Hi, I had a couple of questions arising from the con law lectures.    Is there a cutoff date for changes in constitutional law prior to the exam? As in are cases decided through the end of this term fair game on the exam (especially with respect to abortion, but also other rights)? Or will they not generally ask questions like that?    Is there anything we should know about Whole Women's Health v. Jackson (or more generally about exceptions to the availability of injunctive relief against government officers under Ex Parte Young? I realize this is more of a federal courts/jurisdiction question, but the professor stated in passing that such relief was always available to prevent the enforcement of an unconstitutional law, which seemed like an oversimplification&mdash;is that a safe assumption on the exam?    Finally, the professor did not mention religion as a suspect classification during his discussion of the Equal Protection Clause&mdash;I realize that a lot of religion questions are better analyzed through the First Amendment's religion clauses, but my understanding had been that religion was a suspect classification and laws discriminating against members of a religion (especially outside of contexts where free exercise and establishment are implicated) were analyzed using strict scrutiny under 14A's EPC clause (or 5A DPC for federal govt.). Is this correct? Or is this just not necessary for the exam?    Thank you!"	"Anna Allen"
Israel	"Del Mundo"	"2022-06-23 17:55:26"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	NULL	"The question ID number is 9633. Thank you!Admin wrote:Lecture: NULLSubject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYHi Israel! Could you send me the question identification number for that question and I can take a look? Thank you! Steve  Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-23 15:35:35 wrote: Hello,  I am a bit confused. One of the answers to the MBE practice questions indicated that a third party had both a vested remainder and an executory interest following a defeasible life estate. Is this accurate?  Thank you!   Admin wrote: Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTY Hi Israel! Executory interests. So, for example,A conveys Blackacre “to B for life, but if B remarries, then to C.” B has a defeasible life estate. C has an executory interest. Steve  Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-20 22:35:55 wrote: What future interests follow a defeasible life estate if a third party holds the future interest?"	"RE: RE: Defeasible Life Estate"	"Mult. Choice"	NULL	727907	1737	380871	159137	"2022-06-23 20:43:29"	"2022-06-23 17:55:26"	1	9633	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Israel!  Thanks for sending. This is not your typical defeasible life estate. It is an usual example. The owner here devised her residence to the companion ""for life or until she vacates the premises, and then to my nephew."" This means that the companion received a defeasible life estate and the nephew received two future interests in the residence&mdash;a vested remainder -- based on the ""until she vacates language""-- and an executory interest -- based on the ""for life"" language. It is just strange phrasing that you don't often see in practice questions. The conveyance says ""for life or until she vacates the premises."" That creates two possible events with different consequences for each, which means two different interests for the nephew. They won't conflict because one of those events would happen first. Either she vacates the premises or she dies. Whichever happens first controls.  Hope this helps.  Steve    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-23 17:55:26 wrote:  The question ID number is 9633. Thank you!    Admin wrote:  Lecture: NULLSubject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTY  Hi Israel!  Could you send me the question identification number for that question and I can take a look?  Thank you!  Steve    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-23 15:35:35 wrote:  Hello,    I am a bit confused. One of the answers to the MBE practice questions indicated that a third party had both a vested remainder and an executory interest following a defeasible life estate. Is this accurate?    Thank you!      Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTY  Hi Israel!  Executory interests. So, for example,A conveys Blackacre &ldquo;to B for life, but if B remarries, then to C.&rdquo; B has a defeasible life estate. C has an executory interest.  Steve    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-20 22:35:55 wrote:  What future interests follow a defeasible life estate if a third party holds the future interest?"	"Israel Del Mundo"
