Nick	Wolfe	"2022-06-23 15:06:03"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"		"This is the silliest message ever, but I have Adaptibar for a supplement and there is a discrepancy between two questions. There were two questions, one on Themis and one on Adaptibar, asking if an undercover cop in a shared jail cell with a felon gets the felon to confess to a crime, whether the felon's Miranda rights were violated. Themis said there was no violation, but Adapitabr says there was a violation. I am having trouble because I do not know which is the correct answer. Do you have access to Adaptibar? The Themis question was #9574 and the Adaptibar question was #963. If this is an insane question/request please just ignore:)Thank you,"	"Crim pro "	"Mult. Choice"		727738	1737	413801	159077	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-23 15:43:13"	1	9574	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Anna Allen (Ed)"	"  Hi Nick,    I cannot comment on third-party materials, but I can give you some guidance on how Themis approaches this substantive issue. As a very broad policy consideration, the 5th Amendment protection against self-incrimination is concerned with police intimidation and coercion. Over time, this has evolved to require that police provide Miranda warnings before a custodial interrogation, unless an exception to Miranda applies.    In question 9574, the gang member was certainly in custody and he was also subject to &ldquo;interrogation&rdquo; because the officer&rsquo;s comments were likely to elicit an incriminating response. However, the undercover police exception applies, so Miranda warnings were not required. See the MBE Criminal Procedure Outline, Section II.B.3. Exceptions to the Miranda Requirement.    That makes sense considering the main policy consideration: the gang member was not being intimidated or coerced into a confession by police officers exerting their authority because he didn&rsquo;t even know that he was speaking to an officer.     BUT, note that the analysis is different under the 6th Amendment right to counsel. Once the right to counsel is triggered (not seen in question 9574), the police cannot set up this same scenario to try to elicit statements. See the MBE Crim Pro Outline, Section III.C.4. Admissibility of a Defendant's Statements to Informants.    I hope that helps!  Anna    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-06-23 15:06:03 wrote:  This is the silliest message ever, but I have Adaptibar for a supplement and there is a discrepancy between two questions. There were two questions, one on Themis and one on Adaptibar, asking if an undercover cop in a shared jail cell with a felon gets the felon to confess to a crime, whether the felon's Miranda rights were violated. Themis said there was no violation, but Adapitabr says there was a violation. I am having trouble because I do not know which is the correct answer. Do you have access to Adaptibar? The Themis question was #9574 and the Adaptibar question was #963. If this is an insane question/request please just ignore:)    Thank you,"	"Anindita Dutta"
