michael	Swistara	"2022-06-23 09:47:49"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"			"Hi Themis,During Lecture Chapter 1 on Trusts, Professor Kramer and the outline both say that the vast majority of states do not allow for pet trusts. However, I believe that all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia do in fact have some version of a pet trust statute on the books (see: https://www.animallaw.info/content/map-states-companion-animal-pet-trust-laws). Just wanted to make sure that was corrected, unless of course I am mistaken here. Thanks! Best,Michael"	"Pet Trusts "	Lecture		727405	1737	424078	159071	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-23 15:30:06"	1	0	TRUSTS	0	"Diana Belair (Ed)"	"Hi Michael,  If you take a look at page 11 of your MEE Trusts outline, under a. Animal Trusts, it does say that all jurisdictions permit the creation of a trust for the care of one or more animals alive during the settlor's lifetime. However, an animal may not be the direct beneficiary. So, the beneficiary has to be a person or organization, but the purpose of the distributions to that beneficiary is to care for the animal.  You are correct that the professor misspeaks in his example when he says that the pet trust is not valid, because the beneficiary in the example is not the animal, but a person who will take care of the animal. I will add an editor's note to the handout and we will be able to correct this at the next lecture taping. Thank you for bringing this to our attention.  I hope this helps!  Diana    michael Swistara @ 2022-06-23 09:47:49 wrote:  Hi Themis,    During Lecture Chapter 1 on Trusts, Professor Kramer and the outline both say that the vast majority of states do not allow for pet trusts. However, I believe that all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia do in fact have some version of a pet trust statute on the books (see: https://www.animallaw.info/content/map-states-companion-animal-pet-trust-laws). Just wanted to make sure that was corrected, unless of course I am mistaken here. Thanks!     Best,  Michael"	"Anna Allen"
Jenae	Longenecker	"2022-06-22 16:53:17"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	"Question 9429"	"The man is asserting his own 5th amendment rights, not the corporation's. Why is he precluded from doing this in the face of criminal liability?Also, are business records and emails similar enough to oral testimony to be protected by the 5th amendment in the way that a diary would?"	"Diary vs. Business Record"	"Mult. Choice"		726886	1737	345376	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-22 17:55:51"	2	9429	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jenae,  For the privilege against self-incrimination, a person means an individual. Artificial entities such as corporations, partnerships, and labor unions may not assert the privilege, but a sole proprietorship may. The privilege does not extend to the custodian of corporate records (or a corporate officer), even if production would incriminate the custodian individually. Here, the grand jury is investigating a corporation for tax fraud (not the COO), and a subpoena was served on the COO, who acted as the custodian of the corporate records. It doesn&rsquo;t matter that production of these records might implicate the COO in criminal misconduct, as the custodian of the corporate records, the COO must produce them. The privilege protects only testimonial evidence. Nontestimonial physical evidence (such as a blood or urine sample, Breathalyzer test result, handwriting exemplar, voice sample, or other evidence of physical characteristics) is not protected. The privilege generally does not apply to an individual&rsquo;s voluntarily prepared business papers or to records required by law to be kept, such as tax returns. Fisher v. United States, 425 U.S. 391 (1976). So, it would depend on the nature of the document.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jenae Longenecker @ 2022-06-22 16:53:17 wrote:  The man is asserting his own 5th amendment rights, not the corporation's. Why is he precluded from doing this in the face of criminal liability?  Also, are business records and emails similar enough to oral testimony to be protected by the 5th amendment in the way that a diary would?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Ashley	Bishel	"2022-06-22 16:21:14"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	"ID# 9543"	"Is this not a hearsay exception under the business records exception because the witness statement would be hearsay within hearsay? "	"Hearsay? "	"Mult. Choice"		726853	1737	397350	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-22 18:03:50"	1	9543	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ashley,  In this question, the witness statement from the investigating officer's report that the light was green is not being introduced to prove that the light was, in fact, green. Instead, the witness statement is being introduced to show that while the witness is testifying at trial that the light is red, the witness had previously stated to the officer that the light was green. Said another way, it is being introduced to demonstrate that the witness has taken inconsistent positions on this issue, which calls into question the witness's credibility. Thus, the statement is being used for impeachment purposes but not to ultimately establish what color the light was. So, it is possible that the investigator's report would be admissible by the defendant through another rule of evidence, but not for the purposes of impeachment. The defendant sought only to introduce the evidence as impeachment evidence here, so the hearsay exceptions wouldn&rsquo;t apply here.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ashley Bishel @ 2022-06-22 16:21:14 wrote:  Is this not a hearsay exception under the business records exception because the witness statement would be hearsay within hearsay? "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jenae	Longenecker	"2022-06-22 16:03:29"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	"Question ID# 9430"	"Both offenses are related to the destruction of the same building and have overlapping facts. Where is the line for when an attorney needs to be present?"	"Crim Pro"	"Mult. Choice"		726825	1737	345376	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-22 16:04:52"	1	9430	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jenae,  The Sixth Amendment right attaches automatically at all critical stages of a prosecution, which is basically everything after the government indicts or otherwise formally charges the defendant. Unlike with the 5th Amendment Right to Counsel, the 6th is offense specific. This means that simply reading the Miranda warnings to the defendant and obtaining a waiver are not sufficient to protect his interests. Since we are at a ""critical stage"" in the prosecution, counsel must be present. However, presence of counsel is required when asking about the ""critical stage"" crime; here that would be the arson. Since the defendant is not on trial for the theft, that crime is not a critical stage, therefore presence of counsel is not required. Now, two crimes committed in one criminal transaction are deemed to be the same offense for Sixth Amendment purposes unless each offense requires proof of an element that the other does not. If a defendant's conduct may be prosecuted as two or more crimes, then the Blockburger test is applied to determine whether the crimes constitute the same offense for double jeopardy purposes. Here, arson and theft are different crimes, therefore inquiry into the theft does not impact the defendant's 6th Amendment Rights concerning the arson case. In this case then, the statement is admissible against the defendant even though counsel was not present. If this right applied to this interrogation, even the act of reading the defendant his Miranda rights and requesting a waiver (without his counsel present) would have violated that Sixth Amendment right since it had already attached.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jenae Longenecker @ 2022-06-22 16:03:29 wrote:  Both offenses are related to the destruction of the same building and have overlapping facts. Where is the line for when an attorney needs to be present?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
