Jenae	Longenecker	"2022-06-22 11:44:33"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"		"Ch 4 Example 32(B) asks whether the admission of a photo array is jeopardized by the fact that the defendant's lawyer wasn't present. Professor Karlan says there is a problem, but earlier she said (and the handout reiterates) that there is no right to have your attorney present at a photo array. Is this inconsistent or am I missing something?"	"Photo Array"	Handout	"Ch 4: The Sixth Amendment Right to Counsel; Identification Procedures"	726511	1737	345376	159111	"2022-06-22 19:41:28"	"2022-06-22 12:24:32"	1	0	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	0	"Kathleen Schandler"	"Hi Jenae,  This example includes two line ups, the first a photo line up shown to Oscar (where the defendant does not have a right to counsel -but with which there still may be an issue) and then a second line up shown to Preeta (here defendant would have the right counsel - since it is a post-charge line up)  B then asks us:B) Is Oscar&rsquo;s identification inadmissible at Ingrid&rsquo;s trial because Ingrid&rsquo;s lawyer was not present?   The accused does not have a right to counsel at photo identifications. However, as in the case of lineups, the accused may have a due process claim regarding the photo identification. A defendant can attack an identification as denying due process when the identification is unnecessarily suggestive and there is a substantial likelihood of misidentification.  I hope this helps!  Best,  Katie    Jenae Longenecker @ 2022-06-22 11:44:33 wrote:  Ch 4 Example 32(B) asks whether the admission of a photo array is jeopardized by the fact that the defendant's lawyer wasn't present. Professor Karlan says there is a problem, but earlier she said (and the handout reiterates) that there is no right to have your attorney present at a photo array. Is this inconsistent or am I missing something?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
