Isaac	Markow	"2022-06-21 21:34:25"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"Hi!I'm in the midst of watching the Constitutional Law Essay Writing Workshop's second lecture. In that lecture, Professor Ide-Don covers takings under the 5th Amendment. He says that a regulatory taking can occur even when it's only a partial taking - that is, when the government regulation only affects some economic use of the land, but some economic use is still available. However, earlier today, I listened to Professor Jeffries discuss the Takings Clause, and when he talks about regulatory takings, he says that if there is a regulation (as opposed to a physical taking), it's generally not a ""taking"" for 5th Amendment purposes unless it leaves no economically viable use for the property in question. He emphasizes that while many regulations can dramatically affect the value of property, mere drops in economic value don't lead to a taking, and thus the government will not need to provide just compensation.These professors' positions are diametrically opposed. I was wondering whether you can help provide some clarity on the correct approach. Thank you!--Isaac"	"5th Amendment Takings Question"	General		726182	1737	424564	159137	"2022-06-22 10:44:39"	"2022-06-21 22:54:36"	1	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Isaac!  I fully understand the confusion here and why you'd think these statements are opposed to each other, but they actually are not. Under the Takings Clause, the government generally finds a regulatory taking only when there is no economically viable use of the property. With partial takings, the government generally does not find a taking. However, it ispossible. As a result you need to go through the analysis as laid out in the Ide-Don workshop lecture to determineifa taking has occurred. A way to handle this is to go through the analysis and (unless the facts show otherwise) construe the answer so the government finds no taking.    Isaac Markow @ 2022-06-21 21:34:25 wrote:  Hi!    I'm in the midst of watching the Constitutional Law Essay Writing Workshop's second lecture. In that lecture, Professor Ide-Don covers takings under the 5th Amendment. He says that a regulatory taking can occur even when it's only a partial taking - that is, when the government regulation only affects some economic use of the land, but some economic use is still available. However, earlier today, I listened to Professor Jeffries discuss the Takings Clause, and when he talks about regulatory takings, he says that if there is a regulation (as opposed to a physical taking), it's generally not a ""taking"" for 5th Amendment purposes unless it leaves no economically viable use for the property in question. He emphasizes that while many regulations can dramatically affect the value of property, mere drops in economic value don't lead to a taking, and thus the government will not need to provide just compensation.    These professors' positions are diametrically opposed. I was wondering whether you can help provide some clarity on the correct approach. Thank you!    --Isaac"	"Lindsey Hallam"
