Vikram	Rajan	"2022-06-21 14:02:16"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	10499	"Looking at my outlines and thinking back to the memory of another problem I got wrong, I thought that horizontal privity required that the real covenant be established at the time that a parcel of land is subdivided. While it intuitively makes sense to me that neighbors can create a real covenant, I thought I got a previous MBE question wrong about this when two neighbors agreed to burden their properties and then assigned or devised their properties, with the answer saying something about there not being horizontal privity. Here, though, the facts are similar and there is horizontal privity.Can you please clarify my understanding on horizontal privity?"	"Horizontal Privity"	"Mult. Choice"		725774	1737	415485	435070	"2022-06-22 18:04:14"	"2022-06-21 22:34:19"	1	10499	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"^Krista Corley"	"Hi Vikram,   I think you&rsquo;re on the right track. To begin with, you&rsquo;re correct that neighbors can enter into agreements regarding the use of their land. That agreement between neighbors can only be enforced between the two neighbors as a real covenant (suit for damages) or an equitable servitude (injunction). For the agreement between the neighbors to be enforced upon subsequent property owners, there are several requirements.   Horizontal privity is a requirement that applies to a burden (not a benefit) that runs with the land. In the example question, horizontal privity must apply to the rancher&rsquo;s burden of maintaining the small road constructed on the property line.   For horizontal privity to exist, the original two neighbors who enter into an agreement (i.e., a real covenant or equitable servitude) must have privity of estate at the time the agreement was made. This means that there must be some shared property interest at the time the agreement is made. See Real Property Outline VI.B.5(a) &ndash; Horizontal privity.   Sometimes the shared property interest will be the sale of a piece of land from one party to another with an agreement that the land be used (or not used) in an agreed upon manner. This situation might be what you saw in the previous question you mentioned, where a parcel of land was subdivided. For both parties to have a shared property interest at the time the agreement was made, the agreement would need to be made at the time of a sale. If one party sells a piece of land to another, and then they agree to a real covenant, the parties didn&rsquo;t have a shared property interest at the time the agreement was made, thus horizontal privity wouldn&rsquo;t exist.   Here, both parties owned a portion of land where the road was built. The neighbors shared a property interest in the land where the road was built, at the time the agreement was made. Therefore, they had privity of estate at the time the agreement was made, and horizontal privity exists.   I hope this helps!  -Krista    Vikram Rajan @ 2022-06-21 14:02:16 wrote:  Looking at my outlines and thinking back to the memory of another problem I got wrong, I thought that horizontal privity required that the real covenant be established at the time that a parcel of land is subdivided. While it intuitively makes sense to me that neighbors can create a real covenant, I thought I got a previous MBE question wrong about this when two neighbors agreed to burden their properties and then assigned or devised their properties, with the answer saying something about there not being horizontal privity. Here, though, the facts are similar and there is horizontal privity.    Can you please clarify my understanding on horizontal privity?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Zahraa	Nasser	"2022-06-21 11:44:11"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	9793	"Hello,The photograph here was from a newspaper. Is the rule that only the text in a newspaper is self-authenticating and not the photos?Thanks!Zahraa"	"Evidence Self-Authentication question"	"Mult. Choice"		725636	1737	370966	435564	"2022-06-22 22:35:13"	"2022-06-21 15:56:20"	1	9793	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Zahraa!  Yes, that is correct. The text of the newspaper is self-authenticating under FRE 902. But, authenticating a photograph can only be done through the testimony of someone with sufficient foundation of the person or thing depicted (in this case, both) to state that the photograph is a fair and accurate representation of that person or thing. In question 9793, a newspaper was not sufficient evidence in this case. The owner of the necklace had to testify to authenticate the photo. See Evidence Outline &sect; IV.A.1.d.  Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna    Zahraa Nasser @ 2022-06-21 11:44:11 wrote:  Hello,    The photograph here was from a newspaper. Is the rule that only the text in a newspaper is self-authenticating and not the photos?    Thanks!  Zahraa"	"Anindita Dutta"
