Cate	Baskin	"2022-06-21 11:03:08"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	"1983 "	"Hi there - I'm very confused about why the contract modification between Designer and Retailer is indeed a modification rather than an accord and satisfaction. I thought that the conditional language indicated it to be an accord and when Retailer did not perform by the 25th, there was no satisfaction but since the original K date of performance had not yet passed, then D had to wait until the normal time for yearly payment to sue for breach of K (since the original K was not discharged).Overall, I'm just confused how to tell the difference between a full K modification and an accord/satisfaction situation because I thought it was the latter in this essay.Thank you."	"Difference between Accord/Satisfaction and Contract Modification"	Essay		725590	1737	420821	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-21 17:50:53"	1	1983	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Cate,  There are two parts to an accord and satisfaction: (1) the accord and (2) the satisfaction. (1) The accord is the new agreement, but it does not discharge the original agreement. It only suspends the right to enforce the original contract until the accord is satisfied (or breached). (2) The satisfaction is the performance of the accord agreement. Satisfaction of the accord agreement, discharges both the original contract and the accord contract. If, however, the accord is not satisfied, the non-breaching party may sue under either the original un-discharged agreement or for breach of the accord agreement (but obviously the non-breaching party cannot recover under both agreements; the plaintiff must choose one). An accord is conditional. If it is not satisfied, the original contract is not discharged. An ordinary contract modification (i.e. substituted agreement), on the other hand, is not conditional. A modification replaces the original agreement with a new agreement. If the new agreement is not satisfied, the non-breaching party may only sue under the new, modified contract (the original contract does not exist anymore). So just remember that in an accord and satisfaction, the later agreement is conditional (i.e. ""if you do X, I will forget about the original contract""). Promising to do something else is not sufficient for excuse of performance by accord and satisfaction. The party must actually do it in order to discharge the original agreement. Another key is to remember with an accord and satisfaction is that there must be a dispute as to the amount owed. This is why the facts clearly state, ""I know that you owe me $20,000..."" and the other party agreed this was a good deal. There was no dispute, they just separately agreed to modify the contract. Also, the designer is seeking a solid commitment that will bind to the new performance, rather than opening either one up. They're not presenting it as an option between the two -- they want a commitment to this new performance now, so that they won't worry about raising the money elsewhere.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Cate Baskin @ 2022-06-21 11:03:08 wrote:  Hi there - I'm very confused about why the contract modification between Designer and Retailer is indeed a modification rather than an accord and satisfaction. I thought that the conditional language indicated it to be an accord and when Retailer did not perform by the 25th, there was no satisfaction but since the original K date of performance had not yet passed, then D had to wait until the normal time for yearly payment to sue for breach of K (since the original K was not discharged).    Overall, I'm just confused how to tell the difference between a full K modification and an accord/satisfaction situation because I thought it was the latter in this essay.    Thank you."	"Lindsey Hallam"
