Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-21 09:26:14"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	9720	"The MBE lecture uses the phrase ""insufficient evidence for a jury reasonably to find."" Why is that not translated to the this question?"	JMOL	"Mult. Choice"		725515	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-21 15:52:28"	1	9720	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  Under Rule 50(a), once a party has been fully heard on an issue at a jury trial, the court may grant a motion for judgment as a matter of law resolving the issue against a party if the court finds that there is insufficient evidence for a jury reasonably to find for that party. When evaluating a motion for judgment as a matter of law, the court should not weigh the evidence at all. If the plaintiff is able to produce a single shred of evidence that would support all the elements of the claim being present -- even if that evidence is ""meager"" -- then the court must let the jury decide. Here, the fact pattern says that ""The mayor's entire case rested on her own testimony establishing the prima facie elements of her claim and a properly authenticated and admitted copy of the allegedly defamatory publication."" Because the prima facie elements are established, that's enough. The case should go to the jury. If the plaintiff just forgets to introduce evidence on a particular element, that's when JMOL is appropriate -- e.g. if a plaintiff were to forget to introduce any evidence as to damages in a negligence claim, then JMOL would be appropriate.  Hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-21 09:26:14 wrote:  The MBE lecture uses the phrase ""insufficient evidence for a jury reasonably to find."" Why is that not translated to the this question?"	"Anindita Dutta"
