Amna	Haque	"2022-06-19 15:42:26"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2823	"Thank you for the response!As a follow-up question, do you have an example of a type of situation where a tenant would succeed on a constructive eviction claim for a commercial lease? Given that there's no implied duty to repair, I'm struggling to think of a situation where the tenant could prove all the elements of the claim.Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 2823Hi Amna, In problem ID 2823,there was no implied duty on the part of the landlord to repair the leased premises since it was a commercial lease and the facts did not state any specific duty in the lease to fix the air conditioner, the landlord was likely not required to make any such repairs. If it was a residential lease, the landlord would have that duty. Thus, even if the elements for a constructive eviction was present, since the landlord had no duty to make the repairs, the tenant will not succeed in a constructive eviction claim. This is becausewe would still need to prove that the landlord had a duty to fix whatever was interfering with the Plaintiff's possession or enjoyment of the leased property. If he had no duty, his act or inaction cannot be considered as an interference that would cause a constructive eviction. Hope this clarifies things! Best, Pam  Amna Haque @ 2022-06-16 23:59:59 wrote: I'm confused as to part 2 of the sample answer response. If I'm not mistaken, one of the elements of constructive eviction is to allow the landlord reasonable time to respond to/cure the tenant's complaint. Because constructive eviction (and the covenant of quiet enjoyment) can apply to commercial leases, doesn't this suggest that the landlord must have a duty to repair? If there's not duty to repair, how does that element bear at all on an analysis of commercial leases?  Thank you"	"RE: Real Property Essay Question 2823"	Follow-up	NULL	724193	1737	394355	369848	"2022-06-21 22:56:05"	"2022-06-19 15:42:26"	1	2823	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Pamela Prieto"	"Hi Amna,  You are welcome!  Example of a constructive eviction in a commercial lease: A entered into a commercial lease with B for the lease of B's building space for her business. In the lease, it specifically said that B's duty as a landlord included repairs with respect to the plumbing issues and leaks. If a pipe in the building burst and was causing a leak and flooding in the building space leased by A, B would have a duty to repair that. If he does not an A cannot use the leased space due to the continued leak, then this is considered as constructive eviction.  The difference of this example and problem 2823 is that the lease in this example specifically stated B's duty to repair leaks and plumbing issues. If it did not state that, then B would not have a duty to repair.  Hope this helps!  Best,  Pam    Amna Haque @ 2022-06-19 15:42:26 wrote:  Thank you for the response!    As a follow-up question, do you have an example of a type of situation where a tenant would succeed on a constructive eviction claim for a commercial lease? Given that there's no implied duty to repair, I'm struggling to think of a situation where the tenant could prove all the elements of the claim.    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 2823  Hi Amna,  In problem ID 2823,there was no implied duty on the part of the landlord to repair the leased premises since it was a commercial lease and the facts did not state any specific duty in the lease to fix the air conditioner, the landlord was likely not required to make any such repairs. If it was a residential lease, the landlord would have that duty. Thus, even if the elements for a constructive eviction was present, since the landlord had no duty to make the repairs, the tenant will not succeed in a constructive eviction claim. This is becausewe would still need to prove that the landlord had a duty to fix whatever was interfering with the Plaintiff's possession or enjoyment of the leased property. If he had no duty, his act or inaction cannot be considered as an interference that would cause a constructive eviction.  Hope this clarifies things!  Best,  Pam    Amna Haque @ 2022-06-16 23:59:59 wrote:  I'm confused as to part 2 of the sample answer response. If I'm not mistaken, one of the elements of constructive eviction is to allow the landlord reasonable time to respond to/cure the tenant's complaint. Because constructive eviction (and the covenant of quiet enjoyment) can apply to commercial leases, doesn't this suggest that the landlord must have a duty to repair? If there's not duty to repair, how does that element bear at all on an analysis of commercial leases?    Thank you"	"Amna Haque"
"Henry Atticus"	Ballesteros	"2022-06-19 11:56:02"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	2806	"In Essay PQ 2806, a consumer purchased from another consumer a bicycle in which there was a perfected security interest held by a third party. The consumer-to-consumer sale comported with the garage-sale exception, and so the buyer took the bike from the first consumer free of the security interest. Later, the consumer buyer gifted the bike to a friend. According to the sample answer, this friend took the bike subject to the original, perfected security interest--even though the consumer who transferred the bike to the friend had held ownership of the bike free of any security interest.My prior understanding was that once a consumer took a good free of a security interest, that security interest was essentially destroyed in the good. And so anyone to whom the consumer subsequently transferred or sold the good would also take the good free of whatever security interest had previously attached in that good. In the sample answer, however, it seems that the original security interest in the bike was ""resurrected"" once the consumer transferred the bike to his friend. Is it true that perfected security interests can be ""resurrected"" in goods in this way?"	"Resurrecting an SI in a transferred good"	Essay		724055	1737	413192	159137	"2022-06-19 14:18:04"	"2022-06-19 13:04:45"	1	2806	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Henry Atticus!  I think you are asking about the last part of the essay dealing with the check? The retailer can go after the check because the check is held by the buyer, not the friend. The friend is shielded from the retailer's security interest because the friend is a consumer buyer of the equipment. But this does not shield the original buyer, who now possesses proceeds from the sale of the collateral. So while the retailer has no recourse against the friend, the retailer still has recourse against the buyer.   Steve    Henry Atticus Ballesteros @ 2022-06-19 11:56:02 wrote:  In Essay PQ 2806, a consumer purchased from another consumer a bicycle in which there was a perfected security interest held by a third party. The consumer-to-consumer sale comported with the garage-sale exception, and so the buyer took the bike from the first consumer free of the security interest. Later, the consumer buyer gifted the bike to a friend. According to the sample answer, this friend took the bike subject to the original, perfected security interest--even though the consumer who transferred the bike to the friend had held ownership of the bike free of any security interest.    My prior understanding was that once a consumer took a good free of a security interest, that security interest was essentially destroyed in the good. And so anyone to whom the consumer subsequently transferred or sold the good would also take the good free of whatever security interest had previously attached in that good. In the sample answer, however, it seems that the original security interest in the bike was ""resurrected"" once the consumer transferred the bike to his friend. Is it true that perfected security interests can be ""resurrected"" in goods in this way?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
