Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-18 23:04:41"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"		"How do you tell the difference between obtaining possession vs. title?"	"Larceny by trick v. false pretenses"	General		723924	1737	421938	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-19 12:54:48"	1	0	"MBE CRIMINAL LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ty,  It can be tricky to distinguish taking title from taking possession, particularly in the case of personal property (other than, e.g., cars). Title is a legal interest (ownership) in something. Sometimes it can be evidenced by a physical document (like a deed), but it is not actually a document. If you purchase a tube of toothpaste, title (legal ownership) passes from the store to you. Now you have title over that tube of toothpaste, there is no physical document involved. If a friend buys a new blender and says to you ""here, you can have my old blender"", then her title over that blender passes to you. If you break into her house and steal her blender, all you've done is obtain possession of the blender, and not title, because you do not have a legal interest in that blender- it still belongs to your friend, and title is still with her. Try looking at it from the victim's point of view: What does the victim think is the nature of the transaction? There are no bright-line rules, but it can help to compare larceny by trick to false pretenses. For example, if I come up to your door and say that I'm a jewelry cleaner and trick you into giving me your expensive jewelry and promise to come back the next day with your super clean jewelry and then never come back, that is larceny by trick. Note that I stole your jewelry, but I didn't snatch it off your hand, or break and enter to get it, etc. I tricked you into handing it over. Since at this point the title of the jewelry isn't being passed- you believe you are still the owner and that I'm just doing an overnight clean, but I do have possession, that is what makes it larceny by trick instead of larceny by false pretenses (title must pass for false pretenses). Here's another example: Say D fraudulently induces V to give her money in payment for a laptop which D represents that she owns but is really owned by X, that is false pretenses because V is giving up title to property (her cash) in reliance on a false representation of material fact by D. Now try this one - D obtains V's car on the representation that she will return it in an hour. This is larceny by trick because no title passed from V to D. If, however, D obtains V's car by giving her a bad check for the purchase price, that is false pretenses. Title has transferred from V to D.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-18 23:04:41 wrote:  How do you tell the difference between obtaining possession vs. title?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-18 15:55:17"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	7106	"Why doesn't a superseding cause that breaks the chain of causation mean that the bodyguard isn't liable?"	"Superseding cause"	"Mult. Choice"		723717	1737	425061	397561	"2022-06-20 15:25:54"	"2022-06-18 19:09:22"	1	7106	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Nicole Werner"	"Hi Jonathan:    Criminal acts of third parties are generally regarded as unforeseeable superseding causes and therefore break the chain of causation between the original defendant&rsquo;s negligence and the plaintiff&rsquo;s harm. However, if the duty breached by the defendant is one of failing to use reasonable care to protect the plaintiff and the plaintiff is harmed by a criminal act, then the original defendant remains liable.    Here, the bodyguard was hired to protect the politician's safety, which would include potentially criminal acts. Therefore, the intervening criminal act would not be unforeseeable and break the chain of causation in this situation. That the bodyguard did not use reasonable care does not completely foreclose that an intervening cause could be superseding, but that intervening cause would have to be unforeseeable in the context of the duty owed.    Please see Torts Outline Section IV. E. 3. b. 2. b.    Good luck!    Nicole    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-18 15:55:17 wrote:  Why doesn't a superseding cause that breaks the chain of causation mean that the bodyguard isn't liable?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Israel	"Del Mundo"	"2022-06-18 13:59:02"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"I understand that the definition of merchant includes ""any businessperson when the transaction is of a commercial nature in some instances."" I was wondering if you could provide an example of a seller that satisfies this specific definition of ""merchant."" Thank you!"	Merchants	General		723650	1737	380871	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-18 18:59:40"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Israel,  For purposes of the firm offer rule, a merchant includes not only a person who regularly deals in the type of goods involved in the transaction or otherwise by his occupation holds himself out as having knowledge or skill peculiar to the practices or goods involved in the transaction, but also any businessperson when the transaction is of a commercial nature. UCC &sect; 2-104(1) cmt. 2. A law school bookstore selling books would be a merchant while a professor selling one book would not be. So, if it is something the individual is engaged with once or twice, does not make a living off of it, or the facts tell you they are not very familiar with it, then the person is not likely to be a merchant.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-18 13:59:02 wrote:  I understand that the definition of merchant includes ""any businessperson when the transaction is of a commercial nature in some instances."" I was wondering if you could provide an example of a seller that satisfies this specific definition of ""merchant."" Thank you!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-18 13:38:24"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	7346	"Is this explanation saying that no easement or covenant or profit can run with the land if not recorded?"	Easements/convenants/profits	"Mult. Choice"		723640	1737	425061	435564	"2022-06-20 12:45:12"	"2022-06-18 18:58:26"	0	7346	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Jonathan!  Not exactly. Like most legal questions, the answer will depend on the facts presented. The issue in question 7346 is whether the written agreement between the farmer and the woodlands owner is enforceable by the farmer&rsquo;s son against the subsequent owner--the developer--even though the farmer failed to record.  Easements that are not recorded are subject to extinguishment by recording acts unless it is reasonably necessary for the enjoyment of the dominant estate, it relates to an underground utility, or (if race-notice or notice jurisdiction), the easement discoverable by reasonable inspection or inquiry.   Real covenants that burden the land will be subject to applicable recording acts, as well.  As the explanation notes, the agreement created a profit &agrave; prendre&mdash;a non-possessory right to enter the land of another rand remove natural resources. Profits are analyzed like express easements; since the profit was granted but not recorded, then the recording act governs whether or not it is enforceable against subsequent owners.  It doesn&rsquo;t matter what jurisdiction governs Question 7346, because the farmer failed to record. The developer recorded his deed without notice of the profit, therefore the developer&rsquo;s interest shouldn&rsquo;t be encumbered by the profit.   Note that the question makes it clear that the developer had no notice about the profit (&ldquo;Neither the deed nor the owner of the woodlands mentioned the agreement with the farmer&rdquo;). Notice can be constructive (recorded) OR actual (just knowledge that the agreement exists). Had the woodlands owner actually told the developer about the profit, then in a notice or race-notice jurisdiction, the developer would have taken the property with notice about the encumbrance. (Then, however, the question would become whether or not the son would be able to enforce his interest, which turns on whether the interest was profit in gross (personal to the farmer) or profit appurtenant (tied to the land)).   Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna     Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-18 13:38:24 wrote:  Is this explanation saying that no easement or covenant or profit can run with the land if not recorded?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-18 12:34:50"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	5899	"""The obligation to deliver marketable title was not contained in the deed based on the facts provided."" Isn't marketable title implied? Is there a difference between an implied marketable title and marketable title that must be provided?"	"Marketable title"	"Mult. Choice"		723592	1737	425061	397561	"2022-06-20 14:06:02"	"2022-06-18 18:52:56"	1	5899	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Nicole Werner"	"Hi Jonathan:    Yes, the implied covenant of marketable title is included in every land sales contract, regardless of the deed delivered. However, under the theory of merger, only the covenants contained in the deed last past the contract phase. If a deed does not specifically list a covenant, it is not part of the deed. Here, there are no facts that say that this covenant was specifically included in the deed. Because the sale is over and the deed has passed, the land sale contract has been completed and no longer controls. The Neighbor cannot go back and rescind the contract, because the contract no longer exists, all that exists is the deed. It's not in the deed, so now the Neighbor loses out.    Good luck!    Nicole    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-18 12:34:50 wrote:  ""The obligation to deliver marketable title was not contained in the deed based on the facts provided."" Isn't marketable title implied? Is there a difference between an implied marketable title and marketable title that must be provided?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-18 10:52:30"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	10285	"The explanation says that a trespasser must have an intent to enter. Obviously, the golfer he did not have the intent to enter. Can you explain why Themis finds that the golfer intended to enter?"	Trespass	"Mult. Choice"		723523	1737	425061	435564	"2022-06-20 11:08:53"	"2022-06-18 18:45:12"	1	10285	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Jonathan!  I looked at the explanation for Question 10285, and it states &ldquo;However, though the golfer intentionally hit the ball, he lacked the intent to cause a physical invasion because he did not intend for the ball to enter the homeowner's property(Choices C  D).&rdquo;  I don&rsquo;t see in the Themis materials where it states that the golfer intended to enter--just that the golfer intended to hit the ball.   Trespass to land occurs when the defendant either intentionally enters the land (or cause something or someone to enter the land) or intentionally remains on land (or causes a thing or a person to remain).   The correct answer is B. The homeowner is unlikely to succeed because the golfer lacked the intent to cause a physical invasion of the homeowner&rsquo;s property.  Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-18 10:52:30 wrote:  The explanation says that a trespasser must have an intent to enter. Obviously, the golfer he did not have the intent to enter. Can you explain why Themis finds that the golfer intended to enter?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-18 10:48:39"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	10389	"The answer explanation says that the safety code is evidence that the jury can consider. So why would they need an expert? I know the code doesn't create a duty, and that it's only a recommendation. But nonetheless, the fact that the code may be considered by the jury seems like they wouldn't NEED the expert because the code is, nonetheless, evidence that the jury can consider."	"Regulatory statute"	"Mult. Choice"		723521	1737	425061	369936	"2022-06-20 19:16:32"	"2022-06-18 18:44:18"	1	10389	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Colten Hall"	"Hi Jonathan,   In order for the safety code to be admissible as evidence to prove custom, it must impose a penalty for a violation of a duty. In this problem, the facts state that the safety codes imposed no penalty for failure to use new materials. Furthermore, the safety codes in the problem merely gave a recommendation. Therefore, violation of those safety codes did not prove custom or a standard of care that would be dispositive evidence of breach upon deviation by defendant.  Best,  C    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-18 10:48:39 wrote:  The answer explanation says that the safety code is evidence that the jury can consider. So why would they need an expert? I know the code doesn't create a duty, and that it's only a recommendation. But nonetheless, the fact that the code may be considered by the jury seems like they wouldn't NEED the expert because the code is, nonetheless, evidence that the jury can consider."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Alexandria	Pollard	"2022-06-18 07:09:06"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"The commerce clause when it is commercial and economic presumes that it has a substantial effect on interstate commerce. Thus, shifting the burden to the challenger of the law does not have a substantial effect. What does the challenger have to show in order to overcome the presumption? It is the same rule: that in the aggregate it wouldn't have a substantial effect.if possible, could you give me an example? Thank you in advance."	"Con Law Commerce Clause question"	General	"Con Law- 3 "	723491	1737	335836	245688	"2022-06-18 12:50:12"	"2022-06-18 08:06:23"	1	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Alexandria,  This one is less about shifting the burden than it is about just presuming the fact. In Wickard v. Filburn the farmer argued that his 23 acres of wheat, grown primarily for personal use (and the rest sold in state), wouldn't have substantial impact on interstate commerce. The court said that such impact could be presumed, based on the prospects of allowing farmers in general to grow as much wheat as they liked. In other words, you don't need to get an economist expert witness in every case to defend the idea that economic activity will have substantial impact on interstate commerce, it's a inference that is presumed.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Alexandria Pollard @ 2022-06-18 07:09:06 wrote:  The commerce clause when it is commercial and economic presumes that it has a substantial effect on interstate commerce. Thus, shifting the burden to the challenger of the law does not have a substantial effect. What does the challenger have to show in order to overcome the presumption? It is the same rule: that in the aggregate it wouldn't have a substantial effect.    if possible, could you give me an example? Thank you in advance."	"Lindsey Hallam"
