Amna	Haque	"2022-06-16 23:59:59"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2823	"I'm confused as to part 2 of the sample answer response. If I'm not mistaken, one of the elements of constructive eviction is to allow the landlord reasonable time to respond to/cure the tenant's complaint. Because constructive eviction (and the covenant of quiet enjoyment) can apply to commercial leases, doesn't this suggest that the landlord must have a duty to repair? If there's not duty to repair, how does that element bear at all on an analysis of commercial leases?Thank you"	"Real Property Essay Question 2823"	Essay		722713	1737	394355	369848	"2022-06-18 14:08:55"	"2022-06-17 00:00:41"	1	2823	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Pamela Prieto"	"Hi Amna,  In problem ID 2823,there was no implied duty on the part of the landlord to repair the leased premises since it was a commercial lease and the facts did not state any specific duty in the lease to fix the air conditioner, the landlord was likely not required to make any such repairs. If it was a residential lease, the landlord would have that duty. Thus, even if the elements for a constructive eviction was present, since the landlord had no duty to make the repairs, the tenant will not succeed in a constructive eviction claim. This is becausewe would still need to prove that the landlord had a duty to fix whatever was interfering with the Plaintiff's possession or enjoyment of the leased property. If he had no duty, his act or inaction cannot be considered as an interference that would cause a constructive eviction.  Hope this clarifies things!  Best,  Pam    Amna Haque @ 2022-06-16 23:59:59 wrote:  I'm confused as to part 2 of the sample answer response. If I'm not mistaken, one of the elements of constructive eviction is to allow the landlord reasonable time to respond to/cure the tenant's complaint. Because constructive eviction (and the covenant of quiet enjoyment) can apply to commercial leases, doesn't this suggest that the landlord must have a duty to repair? If there's not duty to repair, how does that element bear at all on an analysis of commercial leases?    Thank you"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-16 22:38:48"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	2753	"Unlike claim preclusion, issue preclusion does not require strict mutuality of parties, but only that the party against whom the issue is to be precluded (or one in privity with that party) must have been a party to the original action (i.e., offensive collateral estoppel).For question 2, can't we just say Mom wasn't a party in the original action and therefore issue preclusion doesn't apply to her?"	"Issue Preclusion"	Essay		722650	1737	421938	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-16 23:52:57"	1	2753	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ty,  You&rsquo;re correct that issue preclusion does not require strict mutuality of parties, but only that the party against whom the issue is to be precluded (or one in privity with that party) must have been a party to the original action. Mother was not part of son's claim/action and the son's action did not represent any part of the mother's interest, nor were son and mother were in any sort of privity. Now do you mean only discuss the mutuality of parties&rsquo; requirement and not the other requirements for issue preclusion? If so, even if you find one requirement is not met, I would still analyze the remaining requirements (time permitting). By doing so, you can obtain a few more points, and if you&rsquo;re wrong about your analysis of that requirement, you&rsquo;re covered because you analyzed them all.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-16 22:38:48 wrote:  Unlike claim preclusion, issue preclusion does not require strict mutuality of parties, but only that the party against whom the issue is to be precluded (or one in privity with that party) must have been a party to the original action (i.e., offensive collateral estoppel).    For question 2, can't we just say Mom wasn't a party in the original action and therefore issue preclusion doesn't apply to her?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-16 22:17:43"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	2613	"For question/issue 2, why is the forum-selection clause valid? After removal, we are in district court in State A. This court should apply state A's law which does not recognize forum-selection clauses, right?"	"Change of Venue"	Essay		722639	1737	421938	206578	"2022-06-21 12:27:06"	"2022-06-16 23:50:09"	1	2613	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Phil Bullimore"	"  Hi Ty,  The federal law is controlling because it is a procedural matter. The transferee court should not apply the law of the transferor court because the parties have contractually waived their right to the application of that law by agreeing to be subject to the laws of the transferee venue. The Supreme Court case mentioned in the last paragraph of Section E.1.c. of the Civ Pro Outline is controlling on this issue.  I hope this helps!  Best,  Max    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-16 22:17:43 wrote:  For question/issue 2, why is the forum-selection clause valid? After removal, we are in district court in State A. This court should apply state A's law which does not recognize forum-selection clauses, right?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-16 17:36:23"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"		"Under the Implied Warranties section in the torts outline, it states ""the buyer may recover damages for personal injury and property damage, as well as for purely economic loss,"" but it also states under Privity Requirement that ""the majority of states have adopted Alternative A . . . it allows only the purchaser or a member of her family or household to recover for personal injury, but not property damage or pure economic loss."" So, can a buyer recover damages for property damage and pure economic loss?"	"Products-liability under warranty theories"	Outline		722441	1737	421938	159137	"2022-06-17 19:05:15"	"2022-06-16 19:30:32"	1	0	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Ty!  The alternative provisions provided by the UCC extend privity to non-buyers. Alternative A applies tomembersof the buyer's family or household and permits them to recover for personal injury, but for not property damage or pure economic loss. However, the buyer's recovery is not limited and is as stated in the preceding paragraph (b. Damages).    Thanks for raising this point! We have begun the process of making this correction. Apologies for any confusion.    Steve      Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-16 17:36:23 wrote:  Under the Implied Warranties section in the torts outline, it states ""the buyer may recover damages for personal injury and property damage, as well as for purely economic loss,"" but it also states under Privity Requirement that ""the majority of states have adopted Alternative A . . . it allows only the purchaser or a member of her family or household to recover for personal injury, but not property damage or pure economic loss."" So, can a buyer recover damages for property damage and pure economic loss?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-16 16:45:33"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"		"1. ""if the P has not been wholly compensated, it is now the usual rule that a release of one tortfeasor does not release the others but instead diminishes the claim against the others, ordinarily by the amount of compensation received from the released tortfeasor."" What is a release and/or release agreement? How does it work?2. ""Under strict products liability, each supplier has a right of indemnification against all previous suppliers in a distribution chain."" I'm having trouble understanding. Can you provide an example to illustrate this concept?"	Torts	General		722402	1737	421938	159137	"2022-06-16 18:41:44"	"2022-06-16 17:08:34"	2	0	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Ty!  Responses to your 2 questions are noted below.  Steve  ------------  1. ""if the P has not been wholly compensated, it is now the usual rule that a release of one tortfeasor does not release the others but instead diminishes the claim against the others, ordinarily by the amount of compensation received from the released tortfeasor."" What is a release and/or release agreement? How does it work? A release is a surrender of plaintiff&rsquo;s cause of action against the party to whom the release is given. As you noted, generally a release of one tortfeasor does not discharge other tortfeasors unless expressly provided in the release agreement. Rather, the claim against the others is reduced to the extent of the amount of consideration paid. Let's say that you are in a car accident and you sue three other drivers who hit you, A, B, and C. You think there are $1 million in damages owed to you in total. You settle with A for $100,000 and grant him a release as part of the settlement. The other two go to court against you and lose. The jury finds $1 million in total damages -- that would be reduced by the $100,000 you already received from A.    2. ""Under strict products liability, each supplier has a right of indemnification against all previous suppliers in a distribution chain."" I'm having trouble understanding. Can you provide an example to illustrate this concept?Each supplier of a defective product, when strict liability rules apply, is liable to an injured customer, but each supplier has a right of indemnification against all previous suppliers in the distribution chain. Let's say, for example, that you buy a defective product at Walmart. You sue Walmart and win on the basis of strict liability. Walmart can implead or later go after its supplier of the defective product to be reimbursed (indemnified) for what it had to pay you. That supplier could implead or later go after the manufacturer of the defective product to be reimbursed (indemnified) for what it had to pay the supplier.    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-16 16:45:33 wrote:  1. ""if the P has not been wholly compensated, it is now the usual rule that a release of one tortfeasor does not release the others but instead diminishes the claim against the others, ordinarily by the amount of compensation received from the released tortfeasor."" What is a release and/or release agreement? How does it work?    2. ""Under strict products liability, each supplier has a right of indemnification against all previous suppliers in a distribution chain."" I'm having trouble understanding. Can you provide an example to illustrate this concept?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Ashley	Bishel	"2022-06-16 15:27:30"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	9604	"Hi; the lecture and lecture outline say that a JMOL may be renewed within 28 days of a jury returning a verdict, while the answer for this question indicates that JMOL can be renewed within 28 dayes of the entry of judgment. Which is it? "	"Renewed JMOL"	"Mult. Choice"		722325	1737	397350	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-16 15:52:48"	1	9604	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ashley,  Under Rule 50(b), if the court does not grant a motion for judgment as a matter of law, then the court is considered to have submitted the action to the jury subject to the court&rsquo;s later deciding the legal questions raised by the motion. The movant may file a renewed motion for judgment as a matter of law no later than 28 days after the entry of judgment. If the motion addresses a jury issue not decided by a verdict, then the renewed motion must be filed no later than 28 days after the jury was discharged. Practically speaking, the date of the judgment will generally be the same date as the date of the jury verdict.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ashley Bishel @ 2022-06-16 15:27:30 wrote:  Hi; the lecture and lecture outline say that a JMOL may be renewed within 28 days of a jury returning a verdict, while the answer for this question indicates that JMOL can be renewed within 28 dayes of the entry of judgment. Which is it? "	"Anindita Dutta"
Kaycee	Miller	"2022-06-16 09:29:48"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	2806	"From the essay, the first issue was whether there was a perfect security interest. From my understanding of reading the call of the question and the fact pattern itself, the security interest was resolved and the issue was mainly the consumer-to-consumer exception. Is there any way you can explain the rationale of the why 1(a) is important to the essay and why I should've added it to my own answer"	"Essay - 1(a) issue question "	Essay		721965	1737	357799	159137	"2022-06-16 13:46:37"	"2022-06-16 13:21:08"	1	2806	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Kaycee!  So the call of the question asked:    Does the buyer own the bicycle free of the retailer&rsquo;s security interest? Explain.    A full and complete answer here would explain the nature of the retailer's security interest and then get into the exception that applied here. If you just jumped to the consumer buyer exception, there isn't enough context to explain why you even need an exception. That said, I may not be following how you structured your answer. If you still have questions or want to share your answer, I can take a look.  Hope this helps.  Steve    Kaycee Miller @ 2022-06-16 09:29:48 wrote:  From the essay, the first issue was whether there was a perfect security interest. From my understanding of reading the call of the question and the fact pattern itself, the security interest was resolved and the issue was mainly the consumer-to-consumer exception. Is there any way you can explain the rationale of the why 1(a) is important to the essay and why I should've added it to my own answer"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
