Danny	Dvorak	"2022-06-16 08:58:42"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	7463	"This makes sense and helps clarify, thanks so much!Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 7463Hi Danny! In question 7463, the applicable statute is a race jurisdiction—first to record wins.  Though the bank’s mortgage was a PMM, this is not the reason why the bank has priority. The priority attached to a PMM (whether or not it has been recorded) is only with respect to mortgages and liens against the mortgagor that predate the acquisition of the property. The uncle’s interest was acquired after the bank’s mortgage. The bank failed to record; the uncle properly recorded. So, in a race jurisdiction, if the uncle was a BFP, then the uncle should win. HOWEVER, the reason why the bank wins (why choice D is the correct answer) is that a mortgage is considered to be “paid value” only if it is given simultaneously with the loan. The uncle’s mortgage was granted several months after the loan was given to the buyer---so he would not be protected by the recording act, because he would not be considered a BFP. Therefore, first in time, first in right governs, and the bank would win. Hope this helps! Best,  Anna  Danny Dvorak @ 2022-06-13 19:08:42 wrote: Hello,  I am a bit confused by this answer and the explanation for why the PMM exception does not apply here. My understanding is that mortgages used to purchase real property generally have priority over other mortgages. Here, since the mortgage was taken out to purchase the property, it should trump the uncle's mortgage even though his was recorded first. I understand the explanation as to why he is not considered a purchaser, but I do not get why the PMM exception is also not correct."	"RE: Purchase-Money Mortgage Exception"		NULL	721938	1737	410822	435564	"2022-06-17 00:12:28"	"2022-06-16 08:58:42"	0	0	0	1	"Anna Rittgers"	"You're welcome! Good luck with your studies!  -A    Danny Dvorak @ 2022-06-16 08:58:42 wrote:  This makes sense and helps clarify, thanks so much!    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 7463  Hi Danny!  In question 7463, the applicable statute is a race jurisdiction&mdash;first to record wins.   Though the bank&rsquo;s mortgage was a PMM, this is not the reason why the bank has priority. The priority attached to a PMM (whether or not it has been recorded) is only with respect to mortgages and liens against the mortgagor that predate the acquisition of the property. The uncle&rsquo;s interest was acquired after the bank&rsquo;s mortgage. The bank failed to record; the uncle properly recorded. So, in a race jurisdiction, if the uncle was a BFP, then the uncle should win.  HOWEVER, the reason why the bank wins (why choice D is the correct answer) is that a mortgage is considered to be &ldquo;paid value&rdquo; only if it is given simultaneously with the loan. The uncle&rsquo;s mortgage was granted several months after the loan was given to the buyer---so he would not be protected by the recording act, because he would not be considered a BFP. Therefore, first in time, first in right governs, and the bank would win.  Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna    Danny Dvorak @ 2022-06-13 19:08:42 wrote:  Hello,    I am a bit confused by this answer and the explanation for why the PMM exception does not apply here. My understanding is that mortgages used to purchase real property generally have priority over other mortgages. Here, since the mortgage was taken out to purchase the property, it should trump the uncle's mortgage even though his was recorded first. I understand the explanation as to why he is not considered a purchaser, but I do not get why the PMM exception is also not correct."	"Danny Dvorak"
Leah	Beukelman	"2022-06-15 23:57:55"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	10050	"Hi - I came across two questions that have nearly identical facts but the answers were opposite and I'm not understanding why. The two question IDs are 10050 and 10513.I know that one is attractive nuisance because it is a child while the other plaintiff is an adult. However, I don't understand how the duty is breached in one question but not the other when basically identical steps were taken to prevent harm. Can you please explain to me why these two answers are different?Thank you!"	"Difference between 2 fact patterns"	"Mult. Choice"		721855	1737	412563	245688	"2022-06-16 23:13:31"	"2022-06-16 13:14:17"	1	10050	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Leah,  For an adult, there is a duty to warn of the particular artificial dangerous condition -- because an adult has the capacity to understand warnings, and to thereby choose whether to encounter the danger.  A child, in contrast, is generally not assumed to be able to comprehend warnings. That's one of the criteria of an attractive nuisance -- see item (ii) in section (d) on page 23 of your MBE Torts outline. So the duty is different, and it's a duty to use reasonable care to protect children from harm. The questionthere is only whether reasonable care was used, and putting up a fence that a child could not get over or around would be reasonable care, which satisfies the duty.  In the adult case, reasonable care isn't the only requirement -- there's also a duty to warn, which wasn't sufficiently done because there was no indication of the electrical wires.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Leah Beukelman @ 2022-06-15 23:57:55 wrote:  Hi - I came across two questions that have nearly identical facts but the answers were opposite and I'm not understanding why. The two question IDs are 10050 and 10513.    I know that one is attractive nuisance because it is a child while the other plaintiff is an adult. However, I don't understand how the duty is breached in one question but not the other when basically identical steps were taken to prevent harm. Can you please explain to me why these two answers are different?    Thank you!"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Leah	Beukelman	"2022-06-15 23:04:56"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	5386	"When a lease of goods meets the requirements to be considered a secured transaction subject to Article 9 (as it did in this essay question), would it usually be considered a PMSI?In this question the supplier (the lessor) did not perfect, but if it had would the lessor have had priority because this was a PMSI?Thank you!"	"Leases subject to Article 9"	Essay		721812	1737	412563	159137	"2022-06-16 12:06:10"	"2022-06-16 11:25:56"	1	5386	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Leah!  Yes. That's partially right. This is a PMSI, but it isn't automatically perfected. Only a PMSI in consumer goods gets automatic perfection. The scanner here is not a consumer good.  The examiners include a note at the bottom of the model answer which states:  &middot;An examinee might note that the security interest of the supplier is a purchase-money security interest. This is accurate but plays no part in the analysis inasmuch as the &ldquo;superpriority&rdquo; given by UCC Article 9 to purchase-money security interests applies only to perfected security interests and the security interest of the supplier is unperfected.  Hope this helps!  Steve    Leah Beukelman @ 2022-06-15 23:04:56 wrote:  When a lease of goods meets the requirements to be considered a secured transaction subject to Article 9 (as it did in this essay question), would it usually be considered a PMSI?    In this question the supplier (the lessor) did not perfect, but if it had would the lessor have had priority because this was a PMSI?    Thank you!  "	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Hyojeong	Son	"2022-06-15 21:39:56"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"HelloIf a married couple receive the interest of ""joint tenancy"", for example, by the language of ""O conveys Blackare to ""A and B as joint tenants with a right of survivorship"""" and A and B are married couple, do they obtain just Joint tenancy or tenancy by the entirety?Thank you!"	"Joint tenancy and tenancy by the entirety"	General		721768	1737	337791	283716	"2022-06-17 23:14:10"	"2022-06-16 00:09:13"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Hyojeong,    It would depend on whether or not the jurisdiction recognizes tenancy by the entirety. If so, A and B would be tenants by the entirety, presuming all of the additional elements for joint tenancy with the right of survivorship are met. See I.C.2 and I.C.3 of the MBE Real Property outline.    I hope this helps!    Best,          Timothy    Hyojeong Son @ 2022-06-15 21:39:56 wrote:  Hello  If a married couple receive the interest of ""joint tenancy"", for example, by the language of ""O conveys Blackare to ""A and B as joint tenants with a right of survivorship"""" and A and B are married couple, do they obtain just Joint tenancy or tenancy by the entirety?    Thank you!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Charles	Sloan-Hillier	"2022-06-15 21:26:14"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"			"I am reading the secured transactions graded essay (ID #3572) model answer, and I don't understand how Bank's interest attached. They didn't give business anything of value until they notified him that the loan was approved and then dispersed the $100,000. Before financing company's interest actually attached and perfected, all Bank did was promise Business they would look into a loan. They didn't give him any money or guarantee that the money was coming, and when business called, they did not answer. Where was the value given?"	"Secured Transactions Graded Essay Question"	Essay		721758	1737	418121	159137	"2022-06-17 09:05:08"	"2022-06-16 16:43:05"	1	3572	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Charles!  This is a tricky situation, but you need to be able to spot it because it could be tested again. Value was given by the bank on March 22nd.  What matters here is that you have two perfected security interests. It may not seem logical to you, but the rule in that situation is that the first to file OR perfect wins. Here, the bank was first to file, before the other party filed or perfected, so the bank wins.  Steve    Charles Sloan-Hillier @ 2022-06-15 21:26:14 wrote:  I am reading the secured transactions graded essay (ID #3572) model answer, and I don't understand how Bank's interest attached. They didn't give business anything of value until they notified him that the loan was approved and then dispersed the $100,000. Before financing company's interest actually attached and perfected, all Bank did was promise Business they would look into a loan. They didn't give him any money or guarantee that the money was coming, and when business called, they did not answer. Where was the value given?"	"Dena Ray"
