Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-15 00:39:44"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"		"A buyer is a BOCB if he: (i) buys goods, (ii) in the ordinary course of business, (iii) from a merchant who is in the business of selling goods of that kind, (iv) in good faith, and (v) without knowledge that the sale violates the rights of another in the same goods. What does ""in good faith"" mean?"	"Buyer in the ordinary course of business"	General		720926	1737	421938	283716	"2022-06-18 01:48:20"	"2022-06-15 14:25:12"	1	0	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Ty,      The outline and lecture handout do not address this with much detail as it is not likely to be very tested, if at all, on the bar. It is most important that you know the elements of the BOCB rule and how to apply them to the facts on the bar. The good faith requirement would generally be related to the without knowledge requirement, such that if the buyer purchases the goods, they should do so with honesty and fair dealing as to the transaction and knowledge they may have as to the rights of another. Again, as long as you know the general rule that good faith is a requirement for the BOCB elements, you should be prepared to answer a question on the issue if tested as such on the bar.    Keep up the good work!    Best,          Timothy        Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-15 00:39:44 wrote:  A buyer is a BOCB if he: (i) buys goods, (ii) in the ordinary course of business, (iii) from a merchant who is in the business of selling goods of that kind, (iv) in good faith, and (v) without knowledge that the sale violates the rights of another in the same goods. What does ""in good faith"" mean?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
