er potentially helpful note -- this doesn't fall into any of the categories described on page 42 of your MBE Evidence outline, items a through e, that are the ways that something will often be offered for something other than the proof of the matter asserted by the statement.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Julius Zavala @ 2022-06-14 21:22:37 wrote:  I am focusing on whether this qualifies as hearsay to begin with.  Of course, the 911 operator's written statement is an out-of-court statement. So that part of the hearsay definition is satisfied.  But the written statement from the 911 operator is asserting that the operator did not speak to the defendant's husband. The prosecution, however, is not offering the written statement for the truth of the matter asserted, that is, that the operator did not speak to the defendant's husband. Rather, the prosecution is offering the statement to establish that the husband called 911 and ultimately that the defendant murdered her husband. Therefore, this would not qualify as hearsay.  Am I understanding this correctly? What am I missing here?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
