Danny	Dvorak	"2022-06-14 10:25:48"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	2960	"Hello,Since many jurisdictions have the family purpose doctrine, should we assume that applies on the MBE? Would that not make answer choice A correct? Thanks!"	"Family Purpose Doctrine"	"Mult. Choice"		720185	1737	410822	435073	"2022-06-15 10:47:15"	"2022-06-14 15:58:50"	1	2960	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Amy Grover"	"  Good Morning,  I hope that this message finds you well.  You are correct that because the family-purpose doctrine applies in many jurisdictions that it should be considered when choosing an MBE answer choice. However, because it is not the majority rule, it should only be the correct answer when the question indicates the doctrine might be at issue (e.g., the question might say that the jurisdiction follows the family-purpose doctrine).  Here, the question does not indicate which rule is followed. Consequently, the majority rule is applied.  Under the majority rule for negligent entrustment, the owner of a vehicle may be liable for the driver's negligence if the owner knew or should have known of the driver's negligent propensities. Here, the teenager had never been negligent on the road, been ticketed, nor had he fallen asleep at the wheel. Therefore, his parents had no knowledge nor reason to know that the teenager would fall asleep while driving and are not liable for negligent entrustment.  If you would like some more information, &sect; IV.H.4 of the Themis MBE Torts outline goes into some more nuances.  I hope this helps!  Amy G.    Danny Dvorak @ 2022-06-14 10:25:48 wrote:  Hello,    Since many jurisdictions have the family purpose doctrine, should we assume that applies on the MBE? Would that not make answer choice A correct? Thanks!"	"Anindita Dutta"
