Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-13 20:04:14"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"		"REALLY basic questions: Does a plaintiff under a strict liability theory need to prove causation? What elements of negligence does strict liability eliminate?"	"Strict liability and causation"	General		719862	1737	425061	435724	"2022-06-14 13:59:26"	"2022-06-13 23:48:22"	1	0	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Colleen Scrocca"	"  Dear Jonathan,  Strict liability does not necessarily eliminate any elements of negligence.  Under strict liability, causation is generally decisive to the defendant&rsquo;s liability even without wrongful behavior and regardless of fault. Causation is not eliminated, but depending on the circumstances it is &ldquo;assumed&rdquo;. There still needs to be a correlation that concludes &ldquo;the plaintiff would not have been injured but for the defendant&rsquo;s conduct&rdquo;.   This correlation needs to be a proximate cause versus a remote cause. In general, this means the tort must be along the lines of the &ldquo;expected&rdquo; damage within the classification of that strict liability. I may be liable if my livestock escapes and eats my neighbor&rsquo;s crops (actions animals could be expected to do), but I wouldn&rsquo;t necessarily be liable for a cow attack on a human (something unexpected). Or someone who engages in abnormally dangerous activity is strictly liable for damage that comes within the risk that makes that activity dangerous. Or a product manufacturer/seller is liable for a defective product, but not if the client has used it in an abnormal manner.  There is reluctant to impose strict liability when there result is too remote or there is an intervening cause. All of these scenarios can throw the burden back onto the plaintiff instead of putting the assumption of liability on the defendant.  The courts also look at knowledge or foreseeability. A defendant&rsquo;s horse has a bite history but kicked the plaintiff. Plaintiff would need to show a known propensity to kick, not just attack  There are any number of other examples and &ldquo;slippery slope&rdquo; scenarios that could be examined here, but the general answer is that no elements of negligence are eliminated through strict liability, but they can make them &ldquo;assumed&rdquo; depending on the specific circumstances of the damage.  I hope this makes sense.  Kelley     Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-13 20:04:14 wrote:  REALLY basic questions: Does a plaintiff under a strict liability theory need to prove causation? What elements of negligence does strict liability eliminate?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Danny	Dvorak	"2022-06-13 19:08:42"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	7463	"Hello,I am a bit confused by this answer and the explanation for why the PMM exception does not apply here. My understanding is that mortgages used to purchase real property generally have priority over other mortgages. Here, since the mortgage was taken out to purchase the property, it should trump the uncle's mortgage even though his was recorded first. I understand the explanation as to why he is not considered a purchaser, but I do not get why the PMM exception is also not correct."	"Purchase-Money Mortgage Exception"	"Mult. Choice"		719818	1737	410822	435564	"2022-06-15 21:41:31"	"2022-06-13 19:14:57"	1	7463	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Danny!  In question 7463, the applicable statute is a race jurisdiction&mdash;first to record wins.   Though the bank&rsquo;s mortgage was a PMM, this is not the reason why the bank has priority. The priority attached to a PMM (whether or not it has been recorded) is only with respect to mortgages and liens against the mortgagor that predate the acquisition of the property. The uncle&rsquo;s interest was acquired after the bank&rsquo;s mortgage. The bank failed to record; the uncle properly recorded. So, in a race jurisdiction, if the uncle was a BFP, then the uncle should win.  HOWEVER, the reason why the bank wins (why choice D is the correct answer) is that a mortgage is considered to be &ldquo;paid value&rdquo; only if it is given simultaneously with the loan. The uncle&rsquo;s mortgage was granted several months after the loan was given to the buyer---so he would not be protected by the recording act, because he would not be considered a BFP. Therefore, first in time, first in right governs, and the bank would win.  Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna    Danny Dvorak @ 2022-06-13 19:08:42 wrote:  Hello,    I am a bit confused by this answer and the explanation for why the PMM exception does not apply here. My understanding is that mortgages used to purchase real property generally have priority over other mortgages. Here, since the mortgage was taken out to purchase the property, it should trump the uncle's mortgage even though his was recorded first. I understand the explanation as to why he is not considered a purchaser, but I do not get why the PMM exception is also not correct."	"Anindita Dutta"
Israel	"Del Mundo"	"2022-06-13 14:55:38"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"When is a benefit considered “material”? If it has a monetary value?"	"Material Benefit Rule"	General		719438	1737	380871	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-13 23:08:55"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Israel,  In a Material Benefit Rule scenario, one performs a service that is not requested by the other party and by performing that service, he/she confers material benefit in favor of the other. Thereafter, the person who received the benefit promises to pay. The promise is enforceable under the material benefit rule even if past consideration is considered as no consideration. So, the typical scenario arises when one party does something for another, the second party promises to pay after the fact. Under common law, the contract would not be enforced, because there is no consideration. However, under the material benefit rule, the first party is entitled to recover only the extent necessary to prevent injustice. If someone does something for someone as a gift, the material benefit rule does not apply. So, the modern trend/modern rule, which has been adopted by the Second Restatement, is just a different approach that allows the contract to be enforced (when the common law wouldn't).  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-13 14:55:38 wrote:  When is a benefit considered &ldquo;material&rdquo;? If it has a monetary value?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
