Elisabeth	Logan	"2022-06-13 13:10:36"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	3573	"In this sample answer, the engineer's report is discoverable because it is not covered by the work product doctrine. That part makes sense to me. However, the facts also say the customer doesn't want to hand over the report because it's an expert who will not be a witness at trial—and there was a rule that non-testifying expert reports are not discoverable. Is this an exception within an exception where the expert has to be obtained in anticipation of litigation in order for it to qualify as a non-testifying expert report?"	"Non-testifying Expert reports"	Essay		719307	1737	410878	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-13 19:21:15"	1	3573	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Elisabeth,  We don't even get to the sub-rule here. This is a complex question, so to explain, there are nested rules at play here: 1. The first rule is that, generally, all relevant evidence is discoverable. 2. As an exception to #1 above, if something is trial preparation material (i.e. it is prepared in anticipation of litigation, whether by an attorney or not), it is not discoverable. 3. As an exception to #2, if something that is trial preparation material is a report of an expert who is anticipated to testify at trial, it goes back to being discoverable. 4. But, if the expert is not expected to testify, then the report remains undiscoverable unless there are certain extenuating circumstances present. In this question, you never even get to trial preparation materials protection because the report was not prepared in anticipation or preparation for litigation. As such, you don't get into discussing the exceptions to that rule, since they aren't necessary to answer the question.  Hope this helps!  Lindsey    Elisabeth Logan @ 2022-06-13 13:10:36 wrote:  In this sample answer, the engineer's report is discoverable because it is not covered by the work product doctrine. That part makes sense to me. However, the facts also say the customer doesn't want to hand over the report because it's an expert who will not be a witness at trial&mdash;and there was a rule that non-testifying expert reports are not discoverable. Is this an exception within an exception where the expert has to be obtained in anticipation of litigation in order for it to qualify as a non-testifying expert report?"	"Anindita Dutta"
