Nick	Wolfe	"2022-06-13 11:25:42"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	9806	"Why isn't the phrase ""Don’t worry, i have car insurance"" admissible as nonhearsay under the admission by a party-opponent rule?"	evidence	"Mult. Choice"		719142	1737	413801	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-13 19:07:10"	1	9806	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Nick,  While it is a statement made by a party opponent, liability cannot be proven by statement regarding having insurance. So, although the statement may not be hearsay that doesn't change the fact that evidence that a person was or was not insured against liability is not admissible to prove whether the person acted negligently or otherwise wrongfully.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-06-13 11:25:42 wrote:  Why isn't the phrase ""Don&rsquo;t worry, i have car insurance"" admissible as nonhearsay under the admission by a party-opponent rule?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-06-13 11:16:55"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	9796	"For this question, why was the diary able to be introduced as evidence? The diary entry was written by the wife, not the husband-witness."	evidence	"Mult. Choice"		719133	1737	413801	159111	"2022-06-13 20:04:28"	"2022-06-13 19:31:21"	1	9796	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Kathleen Schandler"	"Hi Nick,  Here is it important to look at why the evidence is being offered. To impeach, not as substantive evidence. An adverse party is entitled to introduce any relevant portion of a recorded recollection into evidence. When an adverse party seeks to introduce a writing used to refresh a witness's memory, the writing typically will be admissible for only the purpose of impeaching the witness's credibility.  I hope this helps!  Best,  Katie    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-06-13 11:16:55 wrote:  For this question, why was the diary able to be introduced as evidence? The diary entry was written by the wife, not the husband-witness."	"Anindita Dutta"
