Zohaib	Mevawalla	"2022-06-11 18:46:13"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"Hi,Thank you in advance for your help.Does a tenancy by the entirety need all 4 unities of a joint tenancy plus the unity of marriage/person? Or does it just need the unity of marriage/person? Or does it need the unity of marriage/person and possession? The outline is a bit confusing.Sincerely,Zo"	"Concurrent Interests (TBE)"	General		718392	1737	348535	283716	"2022-06-15 01:56:10"	"2022-06-13 00:02:52"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Zohaib,    The same rules for joint tenancy apply to tenancy by the entirety, plus the joint tenants must be married when a deed is executed or the conveyance occurs (the fifth unity&mdash;unity of person). So, yes, the same unities as required for joint tenancy, but they must be married at the time the deed is executed/conveyance occurred. If not married at the time the deed is executed/conveyance occurred, then you're looking at a joint tenancy.     I hope this helps!     Best,          Timothy    Zohaib Mevawalla @ 2022-06-11 18:46:13 wrote:  Hi,    Thank you in advance for your help.    Does a tenancy by the entirety need all 4 unities of a joint tenancy plus the unity of marriage/person? Or does it just need the unity of marriage/person? Or does it need the unity of marriage/person and possession? The outline is a bit confusing.    Sincerely,  Zo"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-11 13:55:33"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"Looking back on my notes I took from MBE PQs, I wrote: ""An equitable servitude (covenant without privity) can only be enforced by the original parties or their successors in interest."" If this is true, can you distinguish between privity and ""successors in interest""? It seems to me that successors in interests means vertical privity."	"Equitable servitude"	General		718204	1737	425061	159137	"2022-06-13 08:55:16"	"2022-06-12 23:51:11"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Jonathan!  Courts enforce an equitable servitude not as an in personam right against the owner of the servient tenement, but as an equitable property interest in the land itself. There is, therefore, no need for privity of estate.  So, for example:  X and Y are neighboring landowners, neither having any rights in the other'sland. X promises Y, for herself, her heirs, successors, and assigns, that X'sparcel will never be used for other than residential purposes. Y records theagreement. X sells her property to Z. The burden created by this promise wouldnot run at law as a negative covenant because horizontal privity is missing.However, under an equitable servitude theory, the burden will run, and an injunction will issue against other than residential uses. Now imagine the same facts, but X transfers only a life estate to Z. Again, the burden would not run at law because of the absence of vertical privity. The burden would, however, be enforceable as an equitable servitude.  Steve    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-11 13:55:33 wrote:  Looking back on my notes I took from MBE PQs, I wrote: ""An equitable servitude (covenant without privity) can only be enforced by the original parties or their successors in interest."" If this is true, can you distinguish between privity and ""successors in interest""? It seems to me that successors in interests means vertical privity."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Elisabeth	Logan	"2022-06-11 11:28:35"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	2806	"Hello! In this problem, one of the facts was that the security agreement contained a clause that the debtor ""shall not sell or dispose of the collateral"" before the agreement was paid in full. I was looking through the outline for whether this has any effect, and couldn't easily find the answer. My thought is that it probably doesn't mean the debtor can't transfer the collateral, but that the secured party would still keep their interest in the proceeds. Just curious if this is something that would be helpful to include in the answer to a problem like this since I did not see it pop up in the sample answer."	"Clause re: not selling collateral"	Essay		718115	1737	410878	159137	"2022-06-12 20:08:32"	"2022-06-12 01:00:53"	1	2806	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Elisabeth!  You are correct. The secured party could go after the proceeds here, but the language has no effect on the buyer under the garage sale exception.  Good job thinking this through!  Steve    Elisabeth Logan @ 2022-06-11 11:28:35 wrote:  Hello! In this problem, one of the facts was that the security agreement contained a clause that the debtor ""shall not sell or dispose of the collateral"" before the agreement was paid in full. I was looking through the outline for whether this has any effect, and couldn't easily find the answer. My thought is that it probably doesn't mean the debtor can't transfer the collateral, but that the secured party would still keep their interest in the proceeds. Just curious if this is something that would be helpful to include in the answer to a problem like this since I did not see it pop up in the sample answer."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-10 20:40:18"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	5322	"In the essay referenced by the question ID, I don't see anywhere in the outlines or lecture handouts regarding the different outcomes of a lease's validity depending on whether the landlord is in a tenancy in common or joint tenancy. Can you point that out to me?"	"Landlord's death terminating lease"	Essay		717906	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-11 18:35:05"	1	5322	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  This issue boils down to one of the foundations of a joint tenancy: A joint tenant may only convey/lease/encumber his/her own joint-tenancy interest without the other joint tenant's consent. If the joint tenancy remains unsevered at a joint tenant's death (which is what 3b is noting), the right of survivorship also remains intact. At the moment of the death of one of the joint tenants, the property passes to the other joint tenant(s) immediately through the right of survivorship. Here, as soon as the husband passed away, his interest in the building was immediately transferred to the wife, who now owns it in its entirety. Because the lease was an agreement with the husband and tenant, and the husband no longer has an interest in the property, the lease is no longer valid and is terminated. The tenant would have to create a new lease with the wife because she is now the only one with a property interest in the building. Had the husband survived his wife, the tenant's lease would not have terminated but would have been effective for the full 10-year period, even if the husband had subsequently died or sold the property. The same consequences would have transpired had the husband mortgaged his joint tenancy interest, since, for part 3, it was presumed that a mortgage (like a lease) did not sever the joint tenancy. When concerning a tenancy in common, the tenant here does retain the same property rights as the husband but only for the term of the lease. When the husband dies, his ownership will pass to the proper heirs directed by will or intestacy. Although the ownership passes, the lease still remains valid for the lease term.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-10 20:40:18 wrote:  In the essay referenced by the question ID, I don't see anywhere in the outlines or lecture handouts regarding the different outcomes of a lease's validity depending on whether the landlord is in a tenancy in common or joint tenancy. Can you point that out to me?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-10 17:12:23"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2205	"I don't understand why the sample essay has a section on ""priority of interests."" In that section they state the ""first in time, first in right"" rule but that rule isn't applicable here because there's a notice-statute."	"Question ID: 2205"	Essay		717721	1737	421938	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-11 18:19:00"	1	2205	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ty,  Even when there is a recording statute, common law comes into play to govern interests that do not fall under the recording statutes, such as gifts. Grantor gave the land to Daughter as a gift, so she is not protected by any recording act, and her priority is governed by the common law first-in-time rule. When you have some interests that fall under the statute and some that do not, you should discuss the common law, because that governs the interests outside the statute. The call of the question asks you specifically what Daughter's interests are, and to answer that fully, you must mention the common law rule of first-in-time because the statute is inapplicable in determining her interest.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-10 17:12:23 wrote:  I don't understand why the sample essay has a section on ""priority of interests."" In that section they state the ""first in time, first in right"" rule but that rule isn't applicable here because there's a notice-statute."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-10 13:20:45"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"Why is the wine critic an invitee and not a licensee? How should I tell the difference in the future?"	"Question 10398"	"Mult. Choice"		717481	1737	421938	435724	"2022-06-11 20:09:47"	"2022-06-11 18:02:32"	1	9988	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Colleen Scrocca"	"  Dear Ty,The critic was on the property for a business purpose, likely to evaluate the wine/winery and provide a private or public opinion. He was there, as part of a tour group, performing his job. For this reason, he would be considered &ldquo;business visitor&rdquo; under the invitee category.  If the question had said he was a wine critic at the winery of a close friend for a cookout, he would likely be considered a licensee and on the land as a social guest. Although his job may be &ldquo;wine critic&rdquo; in this example, he was not there performing his job he was invited as a friend.  To tell these apart look to who is bringing the negligence action and why they were on the land. If they have a close relationship with the owner and were invited (the owner does not need to be there) then they are likely &ldquo;licensees&rdquo;.   If the person is on public land or is on a property as part of their job or as a potential customer then they are a more distant &ldquo;invitee&rdquo;.  You can read about the distinctions in the MBE Real Property Outline on page 24 Section IV(C)(3)(c) and (d).  I hope this helps.Best of Luck!Kelley    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-10 13:20:45 wrote:  Why is the wine critic an invitee and not a licensee? How should I tell the difference in the future?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Shelby	Robletto	"2022-06-09 17:44:45"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CRIMINAL PROCEDURE"	9458	"I am confused on why the court should grant this request. The rule says that juries can be anywhere within the 6-12 range, if the parties stipulate. Here, the plaintiff objected, yet the answer is that the court should grant the defendant's request anyway."	"Confused on Question's Correct Answer/Explanation"	"Mult. Choice"		716940	1737	336990	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-09 19:08:27"	1	9458	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Shelby,  I think as long as the juror size is between 6 and 12 members, the trial court has discretion to grant a parties&rsquo; request for a certain number even over an objection. So, seating 11 jurors wouldn&rsquo;t run afoul of this rule.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Shelby Robletto @ 2022-06-09 17:44:45 wrote:  I am confused on why the court should grant this request. The rule says that juries can be anywhere within the 6-12 range, if the parties stipulate. Here, the plaintiff objected, yet the answer is that the court should grant the defendant's request anyway."	"Anindita Dutta"
