Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-09 13:44:21"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"		NULL	"An unrelated essay question: I'm having trouble figuring out when I should define things as part of a rule statement. For example, a question asked if a specific co-tenancy situation is a joint tenancy or a tenancy in common. The sample answer included definitions of joint tenancy in tenancy in common. Another example: a question asked whether a secured party had interest in proceeds. The sample answer included the definition of what a proceed is. In my opinion, definitions of these basic concepts seem outside the scope of the question. When should I be defining legal concepts?Admin wrote:Hi Ty, In most states, a joint tenant may effect a severance by executing a contract to convey his property interest. In some states, a contract to convey property held in a joint tenancy that is executed by all of the joint tenants does not effect a severance. Severance occurs only upon the transfer of the property. In other states, severance occurs upon the execution of a contract to convey by all joint tenants. So, it depends on which approach is used. I hope this helps! Lindsey  Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-08 00:47:11 wrote: Why does a contract for sale, as opposed to the transfer of deed, sever joint tenancy? Prior to performing on the sales contract, ownership hasn't changed, right?"	"RE: Graded Essay 2"	Follow-up	NULL	716707	1737	421938	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-09 13:44:21"	1	0	"ESSAY WRITING"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ty,  I would always err on the side of defining the legal concepts. When I&rsquo;m grading essays, I tell students to think of the examiner as someone who has no legal knowledge, and you have to explain these concepts to that person. So, for example, when you&rsquo;re asked whether a co-ownership is a joint tenancy v. a tenancy in common, you definitely want to define each one - because you cannot really answer that question without defining them. There might be some questions you can answer without defining the legal terms, but it wouldn&rsquo;t take you that long to define it, and you could get a point or two for that definition, so it doesn&rsquo;t hurt to define them.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-09 13:44:21 wrote:  An unrelated essay question: I'm having trouble figuring out when I should define things as part of a rule statement. For example, a question asked if a specific co-tenancy situation is a joint tenancy or a tenancy in common. The sample answer included definitions of joint tenancy in tenancy in common. Another example: a question asked whether a secured party had interest in proceeds. The sample answer included the definition of what a proceed is. In my opinion, definitions of these basic concepts seem outside the scope of the question. When should I be defining legal concepts?    Admin wrote:  Hi Ty,  In most states, a joint tenant may effect a severance by executing a contract to convey his property interest. In some states, a contract to convey property held in a joint tenancy that is executed by all of the joint tenants does not effect a severance. Severance occurs only upon the transfer of the property. In other states, severance occurs upon the execution of a contract to convey by all joint tenants. So, it depends on which approach is used.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-08 00:47:11 wrote:  Why does a contract for sale, as opposed to the transfer of deed, sever joint tenancy? Prior to performing on the sales contract, ownership hasn't changed, right?"	"Ty Zhang"
Molly	Skjerven	"2022-06-09 12:43:12"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"		"Can a plaintiff recover nominal damages for IIED or false imprisonment? what about punative?"	"Intentional tort damages"	General		716636	1737	416239	369936	"2022-06-10 12:49:21"	"2022-06-09 23:20:15"	2	0	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Colten Hall"	"Hi Molly,  For false imprisonment it is not necessary to prove actual damages, except when the plaintiff is unaware of the confinement. Punitive damages may be imposed. For IIED the plaintiff must prove severe emotional distress beyond what a reasonable person could endure, so nominal damage are not allowed. Punitive is awarded in egregious cases.  Best,  C    Molly Skjerven @ 2022-06-09 12:43:12 wrote:  Can a plaintiff recover nominal damages for IIED or false imprisonment? what about punative?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Elizabeth	Ames	"2022-06-09 12:06:07"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	9547	"Hi Timothy, that's helpful. Thank you!Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 9547Hi Elizabeth,  When a party takes property subject to an existing mortgage, they run the risk of the original borrower/mortgagor defaulting on the mortgage, placing the property at risk of foreclosure. After default on the obligation, but prior to a foreclosure sale, the mortgagor may retain the property under the doctrine of equity of redemption by paying the amount of the loan obligation currently owed. In addition to being exercised by the mortgagor, the right of redemption may also be exercised by anyone whose right to mortgaged property stems from the mortgagor's interest in the property, such as a purchaser, as seen here. Therefore, the buyer would at least be able to redeem the property by paying the outstanding loan obligation owed and remaining in possession. However, this question illustrates the dangers in buying property subject to an outstanding mortgage--especially one in which the mortgagor is not personally liable for the debt.   Hope this helps!   Best,     Timothy  Elizabeth Ames @ 2022-06-06 10:58:48 wrote: Hello,  I just went through this question where a buyer who buys property subject to the mortgage can still have their property foreclosed if the mortgagor defaults. I'm wondering if in real life there is some sort of contract or something that buyers enter into with the former owner to protect themselves? It seems like a lot of risk, and if buying subject to the mortgage is the default, I don't understand why a buyer would agree to that.  Thank you! Elizabeth"	"RE: Question about foreclosure in the real world"	Follow-up	NULL	716587	1737	416413	283716	"2022-06-12 21:52:33"	"2022-06-09 12:06:07"	0	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	1	"Timothy Chessher"	"You're welcome!    Elizabeth Ames @ 2022-06-09 12:06:07 wrote:  Hi Timothy, that's helpful. Thank you!    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 9547  Hi Elizabeth,    When a party takes property subject to an existing mortgage, they run the risk of the original borrower/mortgagor defaulting on the mortgage, placing the property at risk of foreclosure. After default on the obligation, but prior to a foreclosure sale, the mortgagor may retain the property under the doctrine of equity of redemption by paying the amount of the loan obligation currently owed. In addition to being exercised by the mortgagor, the right of redemption may also be exercised by anyone whose right to mortgaged property stems from the mortgagor's interest in the property, such as a purchaser, as seen here. Therefore, the buyer would at least be able to redeem the property by paying the outstanding loan obligation owed and remaining in possession. However, this question illustrates the dangers in buying property subject to an outstanding mortgage--especially one in which the mortgagor is not personally liable for the debt.     Hope this helps!     Best,          Timothy    Elizabeth Ames @ 2022-06-06 10:58:48 wrote:  Hello,    I just went through this question where a buyer who buys property subject to the mortgage can still have their property foreclosed if the mortgagor defaults. I'm wondering if in real life there is some sort of contract or something that buyers enter into with the former owner to protect themselves? It seems like a lot of risk, and if buying subject to the mortgage is the default, I don't understand why a buyer would agree to that.    Thank you!  Elizabeth"	"Elizabeth Ames"
