therwise. Overall, I'm basically wondering for the future, where it may be the focus of a question, if I should be thinking along the lines of a no texting statute being designed to protect all drivers (and pedestrians etc.) and all accidents involving a collision with a driver who is texting."	"RE: Negligence per se question"	Follow-up	"Torts MBS Practice 1"	716560	1737	336226	245688	"2022-06-13 14:18:19"	"2022-06-09 11:27:18"	1	9477	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Samuel,  It's sort of a nebulous concept, but a ""class"" of people is a way to describe them. ""Drivers on the road"" are a class. Sure, you can define a class of ""drivers on the road that rear-end someone else"" as a different class, but there's really no basis to contemplate that kind of exclusion in the language of the statute. I would definitely think of classes, here, more broadly.    Samuel Gordon @ 2022-06-09 11:27:18 wrote:  Hi Bryan, thanks for the quick response and explanation. I was also wondering about more about how to think about the class of person and type of harm in negligence per se like I mentioned in the second part of my question.    Admin wrote:  Lecture: Torts MBS Practice 1Subject Outline: MBE TORTSQuestion ID: 9477  Hello Samuel,  What may be helpful on this question is to recognize that the negligence per se rule discusses theclass of person and thetype of harm, but doesnot discuss the ""method"" or ""manner"" of the harm occurring. The result here is better determined in causation because no causal link can be drawn (unless one argues that the texting driver could have seen the oncoming driver and dodged).  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Samuel Gordon @ 2022-06-08 13:25:11 wrote:  I was wondering, in a negligence per se question, how broadly I should be construing the class of people the statute was degined to protect and the type of harm suffered from plaintiff. When I initially read the question, I thought that the no texting while driving statute was designed to protect victims of drivers who were texting while driving and the type of harm contemplated was an accident caused by a driver who was texting. However, the answer explanation and the lecture reviewing the questions seems to construe the statute very broadly suggesting that it contemplates all car accidents and drivers involved in any accident with a texting driver.    I see why the contributory negligence claim fails since the texting driver didn't contribute to himself being rear ended, but I was confused when reading the explanation about answer choice A. To me it seemed that the taxi driver who rear ended a driver texting at a red light was not in the class of people that the statute was designed to protect since he rear ended a driver stopped at a red light who happened to be texting, but the explanation suggested otherwise. Overall, I'm basically wondering for the future, where it may be the focus of a question, if I should be thinking along the lines of a no texting statute being designed to protect all drivers (and pedestrians etc.) and all accidents involving a collision with a driver who is texting."	"Samuel Gordon"
Regina	Fragale	"2022-06-08 17:03:44"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2205	"Hello,Please explain why this jurisdiction is not a race-notice one.Please explain why there was not an issue in the sample answer whether the property was adeemed."	"Property essay in the practice essay exam"	"Mult. Choice"		716069	1737	366301	435564	"2022-06-09 18:39:57"	"2022-06-09 08:31:45"	2	2205	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Regina!   I&rsquo;ve answered both of your questions below:  1) A typical race-notice statue only protects a subsequent purchaser who lacks notice and records first. You&rsquo;ll see words like &ldquo;without notice, who shall first record&rdquo;   The statute in Essay 2205 reads, &ldquo;No conveyance or mortgage of real property shall be good against subsequent purchasers for value and without notice unless the same (meaning, the deed/mortgage of the proior conveyance) be recorded by law."" This a notice statute, because it does not require the subsequent BFP to record to in order to take priority over an earlier transaction.   2) Ademption could be discussed in two contexts: 1) when one of the contracting parties to a land sales contract dies before closing (see Real Property Outline &sect; III.D.4). OR 2) when discussing the failure of specific bequest in a will because the property is missing or destroyed (see Real Property Outline &sect; IV.C.1.a and, for more in-depth information, Wills and Decedents Estates Outline &sect; V.F)   Neither of these are at issue in Essay 2205; Oscar sold the property to Sam over 40 years ago, and there is no indication in the facts that Oscar made a specific bequest of that land in his will.   Your time will be limited on the exam, so to maximize your points, make sure you focus your analysis on the major issues (easements, priority of interests, constructive notice, inquiry notice) that will allow you to determine what rights, if any, the Purchaser, Daughter, and Railroad have in the land.  Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna    Regina Fragale @ 2022-06-08 17:03:44 wrote:  Hello,    Please explain why this jurisdiction is not a race-notice one.    Please explain why there was not an issue in the sample answer whether the property was adeemed."	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Regina	Fragale	"2022-06-08 16:59:04"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	1983	"Hello,Please explain in the contracts essay, why the analysis is of a modification issue. I thought the issue was about an accord - changing the performance.Please explain why the actual damages analysis focuses on the $35k. I thought the $35k was reliance damages, and the $15k was actual damages."	"Contracts essay in practice exam, 1983"	Essay		716060	1737	366301	245688	"2022-06-10 17:58:53"	"2022-06-08 23:24:30"	2	1983	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Regina,  In an accord and satisfaction, the parties will be allowing a substituted performance, but the counterparty will be able to sue either on the original performance or the new performance. When the intent of the parties instead is to fully discharge the original performance and substitute a new, exclusive performance, that won't be the case. Here, based on the fact pattern, that's the intent of the parties due to the nature of the deal to get the money by a particular date.  See section 2 on page 58 of your MBE Contracts outline: ""At common law, actual damages can be either direct or consequential."" So, consequential damages are a subcategory of actual damages, hence they're discussed as part of actual damages.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Regina Fragale @ 2022-06-08 16:59:04 wrote:  Hello,  Please explain in the contracts essay, why the analysis is of a modification issue. I thought the issue was about an accord - changing the performance.    Please explain why the actual damages analysis focuses on the $35k. I thought the $35k was reliance damages, and the $15k was actual damages."	"Lindsey Hallam"
