Molly	Skjerven	"2022-06-08 13:06:18"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"How do you know when a mortgage modification is materially prejudicial to a junior mortgage interest?"	"Mortgage modifications  "	General		715807	1737	416239	435564	"2022-06-09 10:14:57"	"2022-06-08 23:05:57"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Molly!  It depends on the facts in the question&mdash;it really just comes down to whether or not the modification would make it less likely for the junior interest to get paid.  If a modification to a senior mortgage would only increase the term of the mortgage, then this would not prejudice the junior interest.  But if a modification increases the total amount owed by the borrower to the senior mortgage (by increasing the principal or interest), the practical effect would be to decrease the value collateral available to satisfy the junior interest in a default. In this case, the subsequent modification by the senior interest (ie the additional loan amount) would not have priority over the junior interest.  Hope this helps!  Best,  Anna    Molly Skjerven @ 2022-06-08 13:06:18 wrote:  How do you know when a mortgage modification is materially prejudicial to a junior mortgage interest?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Sarah	Flagel	"2022-06-08 13:05:53"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	5322	"Would you clarify the answer to the last question of essay 5322? I thought that leases generally survive the death of the landlord so long as they are entered into prior to death (similar to how leases generally survive transfer in ownership). My answer indicated that as a joint tenant with right of survivorship, the wife took 100% ownership of the property when the husband died, but the tenant remained with all of the rights/responsibilities in his lease for the period of years. Please clarify if all leases terminate when the landlord dies or just joint tenancy leases and any nuances that may impact the analysis. Please also clarify if the analysis changes under different types of leases.Thank you,Sarah"	"5322 Essay - last question"	"Mult. Choice"		715806	1737	350016	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-08 23:05:26"	1	5322	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Sarah,  There is a split among the states that say that a lease doesn't sever the joint tenancy, on what happens if the lessor/joint tenant dies before the end of the lease. Some courts hold that because the lessor's own right to possession would cease on her death, so must the right of any lessee (i.e., the lessor could not convey more than she had). Others hold that the lease operates as a ""temporary severance,"" and the remaining joint tenant's survivorship rights are therefore postponed until the end of the lease. The examiners adopt the first view here. So, at the moment of the death of one of the joint tenants, the property passes to the other joint tenant(s) immediately through the right of survivorship. Here, as soon as the husband passed away, his interest in the building was immediately transferred to the wife, who now owns it in its entirety. Because the lease was an agreement with the husband and tenant, and the husband no longer has an interest in the property, the lease is no longer valid and is terminated. The tenant would have to create a new lease with the wife because she is now the only one with a property interest in the building. Had the husband survived his wife, the tenant's lease would not have terminated but would have been effective for the full 10-year period, even if the husband had subsequently died or sold the property. The same consequences would have transpired had the husband mortgaged his joint tenancy interest, since, for part 3, it was presumed that a mortgage (like a lease) did not sever the joint tenancy. So, the rule that ""a transfer of the landlord holds the new landlord to the same obligations as stated in the lease"" does not apply in this case since the rule does not apply when the land is held by joint tenants with the right of survivorship in a jurisdiction where the lease does not sever the joint tenancy and the lessor joint tenant dies. That rule applies to tenants in common and in jurisdictions where a lease by one joint tenant severs the joint tenancy (and thus, turns it into a tenancy in common). There are also other rules where a lease survives or is terminated depending on the type of lease. A tenancy for years and a periodic tenancy survive even if the landlord dies while a tenancy at will ends once the landlord dies, unless the lease specifically states otherwise. However, the rules regarding the type the property is held/type of tenancy (ex: joint tenancy, tenancy in common, tenancy by the entirety) would always prevail over the rules on the type of lease (ex: tenancy for years, periodic tenancy or tenancy at will). So, here, because of the right of survivorship that accompanies a joint tenancy, when the husband's died, his interest in the property is automatically extinguished transferred to his wife as the surviving joint tenant. Since the wife's interest was not subject to the lease, she does not have to honor the lease he entered into without her consent and the lease is automatically terminated because the husband's interest was extinguished.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Sarah Flagel @ 2022-06-08 13:05:53 wrote:  Would you clarify the answer to the last question of essay 5322? I thought that leases generally survive the death of the landlord so long as they are entered into prior to death (similar to how leases generally survive transfer in ownership). My answer indicated that as a joint tenant with right of survivorship, the wife took 100% ownership of the property when the husband died, but the tenant remained with all of the rights/responsibilities in his lease for the period of years. Please clarify if all leases terminate when the landlord dies or just joint tenancy leases and any nuances that may impact the analysis. Please also clarify if the analysis changes under different types of leases.  Thank you,  Sarah"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-08 00:47:11"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"			"Why does a contract for sale, as opposed to the transfer of deed, sever joint tenancy? Prior to performing on the sales contract, ownership hasn't changed, right?"	"Graded Essay 2"	Essay		715536	1737	421938	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-08 22:50:40"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ty,  In most states, a joint tenant may effect a severance by executing a contract to convey his property interest. In some states, a contract to convey property held in a joint tenancy that is executed by all of the joint tenants does not effect a severance. Severance occurs only upon the transfer of the property. In other states, severance occurs upon the execution of a contract to convey by all joint tenants. So, it depends on which approach is used.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-08 00:47:11 wrote:  Why does a contract for sale, as opposed to the transfer of deed, sever joint tenancy? Prior to performing on the sales contract, ownership hasn't changed, right?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-08 00:36:41"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	5322	"When a landlord sells a property it is still subject to any leases. Why wouldn't the property be subject to the lease when transferred to the wife?Would the tenant be able to sue husband's estate for breach of contract?Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 5322 Ty,  You are incorrect. On the death of the joint tenant husband, his interest terminates and the joint tenant wife’s interest is accordingly increased. Thus, the tenant’s lease with the husband would necessarily terminate. The husband (or his estate) has no interest to lease to the tenant at that point.  Hope this helps,  Kendra   Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-02 12:48:41 wrote: For question 3b, I'm confused why the lease terminates. I understand that the right of survivorship gives ownership of the building to the woman. Death of a party in a contract normally doesn't excuse performance, so the woman should have to continue to lease the building, right?"	"RE: Practice Essay Question"		NULL	715530	1737	421938	397056	"2022-06-08 11:21:15"	"2022-06-08 00:36:41"	0	0	0	0	"Kendra Frazier"	"Ty,  This is because of the wife's right of survivorship. There would be no viable breach of contract claim.    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-08 00:36:41 wrote:  When a landlord sells a property it is still subject to any leases. Why wouldn't the property be subject to the lease when transferred to the wife?    Would the tenant be able to sue husband's estate for breach of contract?    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 5322    Ty,   You are incorrect. On the death of the joint tenant husband, his interest terminates and the joint tenant wife&rsquo;s interest is accordingly increased. Thus, the tenant&rsquo;s lease with the husband would necessarily terminate. The husband (or his estate) has no interest to lease to the tenant at that point.   Hope this helps,   Kendra     Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-02 12