e exclusive control. I wondered why the sample answer did not address alternative causation as a way to prove causation. The facts state that each defendant made the chicken salad and the salad was tossed together. Shouldn't the burden then switch to the 3 defendants to prove that they were not negligent? Or does this rule not apply because we cannot prove that each of them were ACTUALLY negligent, since each defendant stated that they used proper care and the facts do not state that either one of them failed to use reasonable care.. Just a little confused and wanted to make sure that I did not apply this rule incorrectly."	"Lindsey Hallam"
