Israel	"Del Mundo"	"2022-06-07 14:45:42"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"When does a party “substantially perform” her obligations under the contract such that she may be entitled to damages (i.e., contract price less cost to obtain promised full performance)?"	"Substantial Performance"	General		714981	1737	380871	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-07 22:44:10"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Israel,  The concept of substantial performance is best understood by looking at whether you can make a good argument for or against the non-breaching party getting more or less what they wanted out of the contract. There is no hard and fast rule to dictate whether substantial performance has occurred. If the non-breaching party is not getting most of what they wanted out of the agreement, then there is not substantial performance. If a party has materially breached, he has not substantially performed. So, the overall principal is that the more the breach defeats the entire purpose of the contract and the expectations of the non-breaching party, the more likely it is to be considered material.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-07 14:45:42 wrote:  When does a party &ldquo;substantially perform&rdquo; her obligations under the contract such that she may be entitled to damages (i.e., contract price less cost to obtain promised full performance)?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
