Robert	Weiss	"2022-06-07 00:14:41"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	9590	"I'm confused about the explanation to this question -- the answer says there is here a tenancy at will, which is a tenancy that can be terminated by either the landholder or the tenant. On the other hand, it describes this tenancy at will as one in which only the landlord has an explicit right to terminate (with 30 days notice) and that courts will not read into that a right by the tenant to terminate at will. Isn't a tenancy at will by definition a tenancy agreement that eitehr party can terminate? if it is no longer the case that either party can terminate at will,can it still be called a tenancy at will, as the problem does?"	"Tenancy at Will"	"Mult. Choice"		714537	1737	413399	435564	"2022-06-08 21:19:56"	"2022-06-07 11:01:45"	1	9590	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Robert!  A tenancy at will can be terminated by either the landlord or the tenant.   However, the parties to a tenancy-at-will can agree to terms in the lease that only give one party the right (some courts will consider this a determinable leasehold instead of a tenancy-at-will). But when such an agreement is unconscionable, courts would just treat the lease as a tenancy-at-will that can be terminated by either party.  See Real Property Outline &sect; II.A.3.c.2.  Hope this helps!    Best,   Anna    Robert Weiss @ 2022-06-07 00:14:41 wrote:  I'm confused about the explanation to this question -- the answer says there is here a tenancy at will, which is a tenancy that can be terminated by either the landholder or the tenant. On the other hand, it describes this tenancy at will as one in which only the landlord has an explicit right to terminate (with 30 days notice) and that courts will not read into that a right by the tenant to terminate at will. Isn't a tenancy at will by definition a tenancy agreement that eitehr party can terminate? if it is no longer the case that either party can terminate at will,can it still be called a tenancy at will, as the problem does?"	"Dena Ray"
Alana	Jones	"2022-06-06 17:36:36"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE EVIDENCE"	"15 on PQ (2)"	"Hello,How can I tell when a question is asking me aboutconfidential marital communications or spousal privilege. For example the question below, I thought this was a spousal privilege but it was not.A defendant was on trial for the attempted murder of his employer. The prosecutor called the defendant's wife to the witness stand and asked her to recall anything the defendant said prior to leaving their home on the morning that theattempted murdertook place. The wifesought to testify that while they were in bed, the defendant stated, ""I've had enough of the way my employer treats me. Something has to be done."" The defendant objected to his wife's proposed testimony. The defendant and his wife had legally separated after the defendant was arrested.Is the wife's testimony admissible?ANo, because the defendant can prohibit his wife from testifying against him at all.BNo, because the wife's testimony concerns a confidential communication.CYes, because the defendant and his wife are legally separated.DYes, because the wife may choose to testify against the defendant."	"spousal privilege versus confidential marital communications"	"Mult. Choice"		714176	1737	420384	245688	"2022-06-07 22:24:06"	"2022-06-06 18:51:10"	1	0	"MBE EVIDENCE"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Alana,  It's a matter of knowing the distinctions between the two, and figuring out which, if either, applies, and which one may work better or have a stronger effect given the fact pattern.  For example, here, the spousal privilege isn't a great one to go with because under the majority rule, the witness spouse holds the privilege and can choose to testify if they wish. See section V.A.2.a.1.a. on page 31 of your MBE Evidence outline. If only the spousal privilege is available, then since the ""wifesought to testify..."" she would be able to.  The marital communications privilege, in contrast, is held by both spouses, and either onemay invoke it to prevent the testimony. The witness spouse can't do so unilaterally. So that's the more powerful privilege here, and leads to the result.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Alana Jones @ 2022-06-06 17:36:36 wrote:  Hello,    How can I tell when a question is asking me aboutconfidential marital communications or spousal privilege. For example the question below, I thought this was a spousal privilege but it was not.      A defendant was on trial for the attempted murder of his employer. The prosecutor called the defendant's wife to the witness stand and asked her to recall anything the defendant said prior to leaving their home on the morning that theattempted murdertook place. The wifesought to testify that while they were in bed, the defendant stated, ""I've had enough of the way my employer treats me. Something has to be done."" The defendant objected to his wife's proposed testimony. The defendant and his wife had legally separated after the defendant was arrested.  Is the wife's testimony admissible?          A  No, because the defendant can prohibit his wife from testifying against him at all.          B  No, because the wife's testimony concerns a confidential communication.          C  Yes, because the defendant and his wife are legally separated.          D  Yes, because the wife may choose to testify against the defendant.        "	"Anindita Dutta"
Regina	Fragale	"2022-06-06 15:39:44"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	4495	"Hello,Please explain in this essay why the U.S companies are not strictly liable under products liability for the manufacturing defect in the herbal tea. Thank you."	"Torts Practice Essay (ID 4495)"	Essay	n/a	714003	1737	366301	245688	"2022-06-06 22:46:52"	"2022-06-06 22:29:05"	1	4495	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Regina,  Strict liability still requires that a particular defendant's product can be shown to have caused the plaintiff's injury. See section B.1., item (iii) on page 55 of your MBE Torts outline:  ""(iii) The defect caused the plaintiff&rsquo;s injuries when the product was used in an intended or reasonably foreseeable way.""  Since the plaintiff cannot show which of the five companies' products caused his injury, and since none of the doctrines that would establish causation in the absence of directly proving causation apply, the companies cannot be held liable.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Regina Fragale @ 2022-06-06 15:39:44 wrote:  Hello,  Please explain in this essay why the U.S companies are not strictly liable under products liability for the manufacturing defect in the herbal tea. Thank you."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-06-06 13:10:21"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	"10050 and 10513"	"Can you explain the difference to me between problem 10050 and 10513? In 10050, a fence and warning signs still subjected the landowner to liability to the adult, but in 10513, signs and a fence were enough to protect a landowner from liability to a child?"	"Torts q"	"Mult. Choice"		713802	1737	413801	245688	"2022-06-07 20:51:17"	"2022-06-06 13:18:43"	1	10050	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Nick,  In the child case, the fence was high enough that it couldn't be climbed over, and was locked in a way that a child wouldn't be able to get in. That is enough to meet the duty of reasonable care to prevent injury to the child.  In the case of the adult, there's a somewhat counterintuitive difference in the duty, specifically to warn of dangerous artificial conditions (or prevent the adult from encountering them). The failure to warn there leads to liability.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-06-06 13:10:21 wrote:  Can you explain the difference to me between problem 10050 and 10513? In 10050, a fence and warning signs still subjected the landowner to liability to the adult, but in 10513, signs and a fence were enough to protect a landowner from liability to a child?"	"Beth Hooks"
Elizabeth	Ames	"2022-06-06 10:58:48"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	9547	"Hello,I just went through this question where a buyer who buys property subject to the mortgage can still have their property foreclosed if the mortgagor defaults. I'm wondering if in real life there is some sort of contract or something that buyers enter into with the former owner to protect themselves? It seems like a lot of risk, and if buying subject to the mortgage is the default, I don't understand why a buyer would agree to that.Thank you!Elizabeth"	"Question about foreclosure in the real world"	"Mult. Choice"		713608	1737	416413	283716	"2022-06-08 21:26:16"	"2022-06-06 22:18:25"	1	9547	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Elizabeth,    When a party takes property subject to an existing mortgage, they run the risk of the original borrower/mortgagor defaulting on the mortgage, placing the property at risk of foreclosure. After default on the obligation, but prior to a foreclosure sale, the mortgagor may retain the property under the doctrine of equity of redemption by paying the amount of the loan obligation currently owed. In addition to being exercised by the mortgagor, the right of redemption may also be exercised by anyone whose right to mortgaged property stems from the mortgagor's interest in the property, such as a purchaser, as seen here. Therefore, the buyer would at least be able to redeem the property by paying the outstanding loan obligation owed and remaining in possession. However, this question illustrates the dangers in buying property subject to an outstanding mortgage--especially one in which the mortgagor is not personally liable for the debt.     Hope this helps!     Best,          Timothy    Elizabeth Ames @ 2022-06-06 10:58:48 wrote:  Hello,    I just went through this question where a buyer who buys property subject to the mortgage can still have their property foreclosed if the mortgagor defaults. I'm wondering if in real life there is some sort of contract or something that buyers enter into with the former owner to protect themselves? It seems like a lot of risk, and if buying subject to the mortgage is the default, I don't understand why a buyer would agree to that.    Thank you!  Elizabeth"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-06 10:32:24"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MULTISTATE PERFORMANCE TEST"		"Why is US v. Robb only persuasive authority when it's from the Appellate court for the district we're in? Shouldn't that be mandatory authority? The instructions say that Franklin is in the 15th circuit."	"MPT practice 1 -- In re Hammond"	Essay		713592	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-06 18:58:46"	1	1801	"MULTISTATE PERFORMANCE TEST"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  Although the MPT takes place in a fictitious jurisdiction, it still follows the basic court structure of existing courts in the U.S. Remember that state courts operate independently of the federal courts. On a typical MPT, Franklin, Columbia, and Olympia are individual states with their own court systems. Franklin's courts include the District Court (the trial court), Court of Appeal, and Supreme Court. These states exist in the 15th Circuit, which is a federal system with its own court structure. In the MPT In Re Hammond, the dispute is occurring at the state level. Thus, the federal case U.S. v. Robb is merely persuasive. If the case was from the Supreme Court of Franklin, then it would be binding.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-06 10:32:24 wrote:  Why is US v. Robb only persuasive authority when it's from the Appellate court for the district we're in? Shouldn't that be mandatory authority? The instructions say that Franklin is in the 15th circuit."	"Anindita Dutta"
Emily	Motin	"2022-06-05 17:09:40"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	10355	"This question says the equal-dignities rule does not apply because the son was not acting as an agent. However, the answer that is identified as being correct says the son was acting as an agent. I am just hoping for some clarification. Thank you for your time.Sincerely,Emily"	"Equal dignities--defining an agent "	"Mult. Choice"		713279	1737	397583	435724	"2022-06-07 00:33:11"	"2022-06-06 08:56:54"	1	10355	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Colleen Scrocca"	"Dear Emily,  Great question!  The equal dignities rule says that when an act performed by an agent is required to be in writing the agent&rsquo;s authority must also be in writing. However, there is an exception for a person whose only act is signing a specific deed at the grantor&rsquo;s request. In that situation they may do so without written authorization, however they are still deemed to be acting as the grantor&rsquo;s agent. That was the case in this question.  This is on page 54 of the MBE Property Law outline IV(B)(2)(b)(4)(b)(i).  I hope this helps.   Best of Luck!  Kelley      Emily Motin @ 2022-06-05 17:09:40 wrote:  This question says the equal-dignities rule does not apply because the son was not acting as an agent. However, the answer that is identified as being correct says the son was acting as an agent. I am just hoping for some clarification. Thank you for your time.    Sincerely,  Emily"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-06-05 16:38:42"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	4276	"Which fact in this fact pattern alludes to the notion that the property was owned as tenants in common?"	"Property w                                "	"Mult. Choice"		713256	1737	413801	369848	"2022-06-07 01:42:06"	"2022-06-06 08:53:31"	1	4276	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Pamela Prieto"	"Hi Nick,  The facts in problem 4276 shows that the property was owned as tenants in common because although each person got the same percentage amount (50% for the mother and 50% to the daughter), the facts do not state that there was a ""right of survivorship."" If the 4 unities are present with the right of survivorship, the it is a joint tenancy. However, that is not the case here.  Hope this helps!  Best,  Pam      Nick Wolfe @ 2022-06-05 16:38:42 wrote:  Which fact in this fact pattern alludes to the notion that the property was owned as tenants in common?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Kaycee	Miller	"2022-06-05 15:12:51"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"What is the difference between Tenancy at Sufferance and Holdover tenant?I continuously keep mixing them up and getting questions wrong because I don't see a real difference between the concepts."	"Property Law - Holdover Tenant vs. Tenancy at Sufferance"	General		713214	1737	357799	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-05 22:08:35"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Kaycee,  A tenancy at sufferance only exists when a tenant holds over at the end of a valid lease. So, when a tenant becomes a holdover tenant, that tenancy is a tenancy at sufferance.  Hope this clarifies!  Lindsey    Kaycee Miller @ 2022-06-05 15:12:51 wrote:  What is the difference between Tenancy at Sufferance and Holdover tenant?    I continuously keep mixing them up and getting questions wrong because I don't see a real difference between the concepts."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-05 10:43:54"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"Why is this not a firm offer that with the 90 day limit?"	"Contracts, MBE PQ Session 4, question 7"	"Mult. Choice"		713067	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-05 21:53:34"	1	10170	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  The key difference here is between irrevocability under the firm-offer rule vs. revocation of an offer. You are correct that the chef's firm offer was irrevocable for a maximum of 90 days. However, this does not mean that the chef's offer was automatically revoked at the end of those 90 days. Rather, this means that the chef could revoke the offer after that time (it was no longer irrevocable). But, the chef did not revoke the offer. This, coupled with the fact that the chef said the offer applied to any order for ""this calendar year,"" means that the offer was still available at the end of November. The chef was free to revoke the offer at any time prior to acceptance, but did not do so. So let's say the facts are the same here (offer open until end of year), except that the chef attempts to revoke on day 80, and the other party attempts to accept on day 81. Now the firm offer rule comes into play, the revocation is invalid, a contract is formed. If the chef tries to revoke on day 91, and the offeree tries to order on day 92? Now the revocation is permissible because the firm offer period has expired, and no contract is formed.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-05 10:43:54 wrote:  Why is this not a firm offer that with the 90 day limit?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-04 22:00:59"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"Re the multiple choice question about a college student tutoring a high school student in math, and the tutor was owed a $500 bonus because the high school student got a good grade, but the high school student's mom couldn't afford the bonus so they agreed that the tutor would accept a bike in lieu of the bonus....the answer says that's accord and satisfaction, but how can that be a new contract? Wouldn't that just be a gift of a bike because you can't contract for past consideration? If it's a new contract, then the tutoring services was past consideration not part of this new contract. I just don't get how you can do an accord and satisfaction when one side's performance is complete, because that means one side's performance is no longer part of that new contract and thus impermitable past consideration."	"Accord and satisfaction"	"Mult. Choice"		712940	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-04 23:41:51"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  An accord is a separate agreement from the original contract in which one party agrees to accept a different performance than the one originally bargained for in the original contract. In general, an accord must be supported by consideration. Where the consideration is of a lesser value than the originally bargained for consideration in the prior contract, it will be sufficient if the new consideration is of a different type (here cash for a bike). The accord agreement alone will not discharge the prior contract. It merely suspends the right to enforce the original contract in accordance with the terms of the accord agreement. Satisfaction is the performance of the accord agreement. Its effect is to discharge not only the original contract but also the accord contract as well. Here, the money owed was satisfied in different form of payment (a bike) than was originally promised (cash). This constitutes consideration. In exchange for this consideration, the tutor is agreeing not to sue. Therefore, there was accord and satisfaction.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-04 22:00:59 wrote:  Re the multiple choice question about a college student tutoring a high school student in math, and the tutor was owed a $500 bonus because the high school student got a good grade, but the high school student's mom couldn't afford the bonus so they agreed that the tutor would accept a bike in lieu of the bonus....the answer says that's accord and satisfaction, but how can that be a new contract? Wouldn't that just be a gift of a bike because you can't contract for past consideration? If it's a new contract, then the tutoring services was past consideration not part of this new contract. I just don't get how you can do an accord and satisfaction when one side's performance is complete, because that means one side's performance is no longer part of that new contract and thus impermitable past consideration."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-04 18:28:52"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"FAMILY LAW"		"For the practice essay regarding the separation agreement and the child who turned out not the by the husband's, the lecture hand out says that unconsionability is found when the spouse did not waive fair and reasonable disclosure and did not have or could not have had adequate knowledge. But the same answer says that unconscionability is when a term is so unfair that no reasonable person would have agreed to it. Can you reconcile these two or tell me which is true? Thanks."	"Inconsistent rules"	Essay		712828	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-05 01:04:31"	1	0	"FAMILY LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  Can you please provide me with the question ID number to this question, so I can look it up?  Thanks!  Lindsey      Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-04 18:28:52 wrote:  For the practice essay regarding the separation agreement and the child who turned out not the by the husband's, the lecture hand out says that unconsionability is found when the spouse did not waive fair and reasonable disclosure and did not have or could not have had adequate knowledge. But the same answer says that unconscionability is when a term is so unfair that no reasonable person would have agreed to it. Can you reconcile these two or tell me which is true? Thanks."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Israel	"Del Mundo"	"2022-06-04 18:04:16"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"Under the UCC, what is the difference between identified goods and unidentified goods?"	"UCC Goods"	General		712820	1737	380871	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-04 20:04:50"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Israel,  An identified good means that the buyer and seller have identified the specific good that is the subject of the contract, such as a specific painting or specifically identified items of inventory (identified by serial numbers, for example). An example of a non-identified good would be much more general, such as various fruits and vegetables from a farmer, to be determined depending on the season. Another example of a non-identified good would if seller agrees to sell buyer 50 bags of sugar out of his 500 bags, but the specific 50 bags of sugar are not identified.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-04 18:04:16 wrote:  Under the UCC, what is the difference between identified goods and unidentified goods?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-04 17:57:25"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"FAMILY LAW"		"Page 28 of the MEE lecture books says that fraud or unconscionability will allow a marital agreement to be unenforceable. However, page 29 says that involuntariness or unconscionability will invalidate. Which is it?"	"Invalidating marital agreements"	General		712816	1737	425061	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-05 01:04:07"	1	0	"FAMILY LAW"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Jonathan,  A premarital agreement is enforceable if there has been full disclosure, the agreement is fair and reasonable, and it is voluntary. The UPAA requires that the party against whom enforcement is sought prove (1) involuntariness or (2) that the agreement was unconscionable when it was executed, that she did not receive or waive fair and reasonable disclosure, and she &ldquo;did not have, or reasonably could not have had, an adequate knowledge&rdquo; of the other&rsquo;s assets and obligations. UPAA &sect; 6(a). Voluntariness, fairness, and asset disclosure are relevant to enforceability in all jurisdictions, even in states that have not adopted the UPAA. However, in non-UPAA jurisdictions, courts can refuse to enforce on any ground. For separation agreements, the court generally will enforce so long as there is no fraud or unconscionable aspect.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-04 17:57:25 wrote:  Page 28 of the MEE lecture books says that fraud or unconscionability will allow a marital agreement to be unenforceable. However, page 29 says that involuntariness or unconscionability will invalidate. Which is it?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Victor	Hiltner	"2022-06-04 17:47:03"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	10000	"Hello!I hope this message finds you well. I'm writing with a question regarding the manner in which a joint tenancy may be severed and, specifically, when the unity of interests is destroyed. Problem 24 of 34 of the Property MBE PQs Session 3 raised this question for me because, simply put, if this situation does not destroy the unity of interests then I'm not sure what would.I understand that the youngest son's conveyance destroyed the unity of title and severed the joint tenancy between him and the two older sons. However, because this same conveyance was to the oldest son, the conveyance also gave that oldest son a greater interest in the same property than the middle son. While the oldest son and the middle son would otherwise be joint tenants, my understanding was that the fact that they now have uneven interests in the same property would make them tenants in common.The problem answer suggests that even though the oldest son's total interest in the property (2/3) is not equal to that of the middle son's (1/3), the oldest son can simultaneously be a joint tenant as to his original 1/3 interest, and then a tenant in common (I suppose with the other brother and himself?) as to the 1/3 interest he received from the youngest son. This does not make sense to me.Could you help clarify this for me? What am I missing here?Thank you for your help!Best,Victor Hiltner"	"Severance of Joint Tenancy "	"Mult. Choice"		712804	1737	342082	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-05 21:38:14"	1	10000	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Victor,  The three brothers owned the property as joint tenants with the right of survivorship. When the joint tenancy with right to survivorship was created, it met the requirements of the unity of possession, interest, time, and title. A joint tenant may only convey his/her own joint-tenancy interest without the other joint tenant's consent. Therefore, a conveyance by only one joint tenant will only affect and sever the unities as to that tenant's property interest. A severance of a joint tenancy does not automatically convert into a tenancy in common if there are more than two joint tenants. The severance of the youngest brother selling his share to the oldest brother did not affect the joint tenancy of all the brothers' shares. The only parcel that was affected was the parcel that was sold. The portion from the younger brother to the older brother was converted into a tenancy in common, but the original share of the older brother and the share of the middle brother remained a joint tenancy with right to survivorship. So, the recipient of that interest (the older brother) now possesses an interest in a tenancy in common, in addition to whatever other interest he had (in this case, a joint tenancy interest).  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Victor Hiltner @ 2022-06-04 17:47:03 wrote:  Hello!    I hope this message finds you well. I'm writing with a question regarding the manner in which a joint tenancy may be severed and, specifically, when the unity of interests is destroyed. Problem 24 of 34 of the Property MBE PQs Session 3 raised this question for me because, simply put, if this situation does not destroy the unity of interests then I'm not sure what would.    I understand that the youngest son's conveyance destroyed the unity of title and severed the joint tenancy between him and the two older sons. However, because this same conveyance was to the oldest son, the conveyance also gave that oldest son a greater interest in the same property than the middle son. While the oldest son and the middle son would otherwise be joint tenants, my understanding was that the fact that they now have uneven interests in the same property would make them tenants in common.    The problem answer suggests that even though the oldest son's total interest in the property (2/3) is not equal to that of the middle son's (1/3), the oldest son can simultaneously be a joint tenant as to his original 1/3 interest, and then a tenant in common (I suppose with the other brother and himself?) as to the 1/3 interest he received from the youngest son. This does not make sense to me.    Could you help clarify this for me? What am I missing here?    Thank you for your help!    Best,  Victor Hiltner"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-04 17:29:02"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"FAMILY LAW"		"Page 27 of the MEE lecture handout book for family law says that parental consent is not needed for an emergency medical procedure. But page 32 says that parental consent is almost always necessary for emergency medial care. Can you reconcile? Thanks."	"Parental consent for emergency medical"	Lecture		712791	1737	425061	245340	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-05 21:37:06"	1	0	"FAMILY LAW"	0	"Beth Hooks"	"Hi Jonathan,  Parental consent is not needed in an emergency. Page 27 is talking about the other parents' consent. For example, Husband and Wife are divorced and Child falls while in Wife's care and requires emergency surgery. Wife does not have to get Husband's consent in order for Child to be treated. Alternatively, Page 32 discusses the rights of a minor child to make decisions about their own medical care. Parental consent (either parent) is almost always required prior to emergency medical care. This means Child cannot go into the Emergency Room alone and receive treatment without a parent.  I hope this helps!  Beth    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-04 17:29:02 wrote:  Page 27 of the MEE lecture handout book for family law says that parental consent is not needed for an emergency medical procedure. But page 32 says that parental consent is almost always necessary for emergency medial care. Can you reconcile? Thanks."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-04 17:03:40"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"FAMILY LAW"		"If the child and either one or both parents move out of the original state where there's a custody order, do the parents have to go to the original state for modification or can they modify in the new state, assuming they've registered the custody order? And does it matter whether one or both parents moved out of the original state?"	"Child custody when parties move"	General		712769	1737	425061	159137	"2022-06-06 11:22:14"	"2022-06-05 21:35:45"	1	0	"FAMILY LAW"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Jonathan!  The original state retains jurisdiction and the order must be modified there.  Steve    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-04 17:03:40 wrote:  If the child and either one or both parents move out of the original state where there's a custody order, do the parents have to go to the original state for modification or can they modify in the new state, assuming they've registered the custody order? And does it matter whether one or both parents moved out of the original state?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Israel	"Del Mundo"	"2022-06-04 15:42:45"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"Does the preexisting duty rule apply to the common law of sales only (i.e., not UCC)?"	"Preexisting Duty Rule"	General		712726	1737	380871	245688	"2022-06-06 20:16:03"	"2022-06-04 17:38:12"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Israel,  The pre-existing duty rule does apply in both contexts. But, note that with the UCC, there is no consideration required for modification of a contract. Thus, to the extent that a modification-without-consideration under the UCC in some way, shape, or form uses the previous consideration under that contract as the consideration in the modified contract, the pre-existing duty rule does not make that a problem. But when creating the original contract under the UCC, you wouldn't be able to use a pre-existing duty to support consideration.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-06-04 15:42:45 wrote:  Does the preexisting duty rule apply to the common law of sales only (i.e., not UCC)?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Regina	Fragale	"2022-06-04 14:53:21"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	5322	"In the model answer fromReal Property Practice Essay (ID 5322), the below answer was provided:3b.At issue is whether the husband’s grant of the lease survives his death.(25%)At death, a joint tenant’s property passes automatically to the remaining joint tenants due to the right of survivorship.Here, assuming the lease did not sever the joint tenancy, the wife still has the right of survivorship after her husband passes. When the husband dies, then, the lease would terminate and the remaining property would pass automatically to her.I have reviewedthe materials under Landlord-Tenant and I still do not understand why the lease was terminated upon the landlord's death. I thought the new owner (wife, because of survivorship) assumes the lease as the new landlord.Please explain. Thank you."	"Question from Practice Property Essay Landlord-Tenant issue"	Essay	n/a	712702	1737	366301	435745	"2022-06-05 18:01:34"	"2022-06-04 23:37:38"	1	5322	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Laura Wakefield"	"Hello,  The issue here is not whether the death of the landlord automatically terminates the lease; rather, the issue is whether the lease survives a joint tenancy with a right of survivorship when the joint tenant who effectuated the lease dies. The reason this is an issue is because the right of survivorship means that the wife now owns the property outright. At this point, the landlord who entered into the contract with the commercial tenant no longer has a right to lease out his portion of the joint tenancy, so the lease is terminated.  I hope that clarifies things!  Laura      Regina Fragale @ 2022-06-04 14:53:21 wrote:  In the model answer fromReal Property Practice Essay (ID 5322), the below answer was provided:  3b.At issue is whether the husband&rsquo;s grant of the lease survives his death.(25%)  At death, a joint tenant&rsquo;s property passes automatically to the remaining joint tenants due to the right of survivorship.Here, assuming the lease did not sever the joint tenancy, the wife still has the right of survivorship after her husband passes. When the husband dies, then, the lease would terminate and the remaining property would pass automatically to her.  I have reviewedthe materials under Landlord-Tenant and I still do not understand why the lease was terminated upon the landlord's death. I thought the new owner (wife, because of survivorship) assumes the lease as the new landlord.  Please explain. Thank you."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-06-04 14:28:19"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	5386	"Hello,If a security agreement states that it covers ""all now and future owned inventory and equipment"" but the financing statement only states ""all inventory and equipment,"" is that acceptable to also covered the after-acquire inventory and equipment? I thought the after-acquired property had to be mentioned in both the security agreement and the financing statement, but in this essay question, it was only mentioned in the security agreement and not the financing statement, but the secured party was awarded priority in the after-acquired property.Thank you,nick"	"Question about after-acquired property "	Essay		712691	1737	413801	159137	"2022-06-05 16:00:28"	"2022-06-04 23:37:04"	1	5386	"SECURED TRANSACTIONS"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Nick!  A financing statement can be effective to cover after-acquired property if such property falls within the collateral described, whether or not after-acquired property is mentioned as such in the financing statement. See UCC &sect; 9-502, cmt. 2. If the security agreement covers it, that should be sufficient.  Steve    Nick Wolfe @ 2022-06-04 14:28:19 wrote:  Hello,    If a security agreement states that it covers ""all now and future owned inventory and equipment"" but the financing statement only states ""all inventory and equipment,"" is that acceptable to also covered the after-acquire inventory and equipment? I thought the after-acquired property had to be mentioned in both the security agreement and the financing statement, but in this essay question, it was only mentioned in the security agreement and not the financing statement, but the secured party was awarded priority in the after-acquired property.    Thank you,    nick    "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Emily	Motin	"2022-06-04 13:56:43"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE TORTS"	10201	"I am just hoping to get some clarification on this question. The question indicates that a herder left livestock on the land of the landowner. I am just wondering what additional facts would indicate the landowners right to possess the livestock so as to give rise to the landowner's strict liability for trespassing animals. Thank you for your time."	"Trespassing Animal Strict Liability"	"Mult. Choice"		712673	1737	397583	369936	"2022-06-06 22:39:52"	"2022-06-04 17:35:02"	1	10201	"MBE TORTS"	0	"Colten Hall"	"Hi Emily,  Think of possession as distinguished from the right to possess as akin to simply having something vs. having rights to it. If I lend you a pen, you may possess the pen for the time you're using it but I retain my right of possession over the pen. Same here with the goats. The landowner would need to be given the rights afforded to an owner--i.e., control over the goats, not simply be a caretaker of them.  Best,  C    Emily Motin @ 2022-06-04 13:56:43 wrote:  I am just hoping to get some clarification on this question. The question indicates that a herder left livestock on the land of the landowner. I am just wondering what additional facts would indicate the landowners right to possess the livestock so as to give rise to the landowner's strict liability for trespassing animals. Thank you for your time."	"Lindsey Hallam"
