Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-03 22:38:55"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	NULL	"Regarding your response to #3, how do you foreclose on only a part interest of a property. My understanding of a foreclosure is a forced sale of a home. But, you can't just sell part of a home right? Does the entire home get sold and the other tenants get their portion of sale? It doesn't seem intuitive to me that one person's lien can unilaterally cause a property owned by a number of people to be sold.Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYHi Ty! Responses to your 3 questions are noted below. Hope this helps you. Steve ---------- 1. What are absolute deeds? I read the outline, but still don't understand their significance/purpose.It is a mortgage alternative that some try to use to avoid the lengthy procedures required for foreclosure with a regular mortgage. A landowner needing to raise money may ""sell"" the land to a person who will pay cash and may give the ""buyer"" an absolute deed rather than a mortgage. This may seem to be safer than a mortgage loan to the creditor and may seem to have tax advantages. However, if a court concludes, by clear and convincing evidence, that the deed was really given for security purposes, they will treat it as an ""equitable"" mortgage and require that the creditor foreclose it by judicial action, like any other mortgage. This result will be indicated by the following factors: the existence of a debt or promise of payment by the deed’s grantor; the grantee’s promise to return the land if the debt is paid; the fact that the amount advanced to the grantor/debtor was much lower than the value of the property; the degree of the grantor’s financial distress; and the parties’ prior negotiations. 2. ""When real property is sold and then leased back to the seller the transaction may constitute the creation of a security interest in the property, a disguised mortgage, rather than a sale-leaseback arrangement."" Why? This is another way people try to get around the system.A landowner needing to raise money may sell his land to another for cash and may then lease the land back for a long period of time. As in the case of the absolute deed, the grantor/lessee may attack such a transaction later as a disguised mortgage. Factors that will lead the court to such a result are: the fact that the regular rent payments on the lease are virtually identical to payments that would be due on a mortgage loan; the existence of an option to repurchase by the grantor/lessee; and the fact that the repurchase option could be exercised for much less than the probable value of the property at that time, so that the repurchase would be very likely to occur.   3. How does a foreclosure work if there are cotenants? I see in the outline that ""the mortgagee may only foreclose on the undivided tenancy in common interest of the mortgagor, and the interests of other co-tenants to the property are not effected."" So, can the property be sold in a foreclosure action? Only the interest of the mortgagor can be foreclosed.    Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-03 12:15:49 wrote: 1. What are absolute deeds? I read the outline, but still don't understand their significance/purpose. 2. ""When real property is sold and then leased back to the seller the transaction may constitute the creation of a security interest in the property, a disguised mortgage, rather than a sale-leaseback arrangement."" Why?  3. How does a foreclosure work if there are cotenants? I see in the outline that ""the mortgagee may only foreclose on the undivided tenancy in common interest of the mortgagor, and the interests of other co-tenants to the property are not effected."" So, can the property be sold in a foreclosure action?  "	"RE: Mortgages/Foreclosure"		NULL	712465	1737	421938	159137	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-06-03 22:38:55"	0	0	0	0	"Steve Blum"		"Ty Zhang"
