Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-02 12:48:41"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	5322	"For question 3b, I'm confused why the lease terminates. I understand that the right of survivorship gives ownership of the building to the woman. Death of a party in a contract normally doesn't excuse performance, so the woman should have to continue to lease the building, right?"	"Practice Essay Question"	Essay		710976	1737	421938	397056	"2022-06-03 14:00:03"	"2022-06-02 16:36:40"	1	5322	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Kendra Frazier"	"  Ty,   You are incorrect. On the death of the joint tenant husband, his interest terminates and the joint tenant wife&rsquo;s interest is accordingly increased. Thus, the tenant&rsquo;s lease with the husband would necessarily terminate. The husband (or his estate) has no interest to lease to the tenant at that point.   Hope this helps,   Kendra     Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-02 12:48:41 wrote:  For question 3b, I'm confused why the lease terminates. I understand that the right of survivorship gives ownership of the building to the woman. Death of a party in a contract normally doesn't excuse performance, so the woman should have to continue to lease the building, right?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-02 09:13:19"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"I don't understand how an intended beneficiary cannot sue until his rights vest, and one of the ways his rights can vest is when he sues. That's saying that the intended beneficiary cannot sue until he sues, which means there's never a situation when he cannot sue. What am I missing?"	"Intended beneficiaries' rights vesting"	General		710750	1737	425061	159137	"2022-06-02 19:40:16"	"2022-06-02 16:35:14"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Jonathan!  The point here is that the promisor and promisee can change anything about the promise with no ability for the beneficiary to do anything up until the point that the beneficiary either: materially changes position in justifiable reliance on the rights created; manifests assent to the contract at one party&rsquo;s request; or files a lawsuit to enforce the contract.  So it is just a limit on the promisor and promisee.  Steve    Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-02 09:13:19 wrote:  I don't understand how an intended beneficiary cannot sue until his rights vest, and one of the ways his rights can vest is when he sues. That's saying that the intended beneficiary cannot sue until he sues, which means there's never a situation when he cannot sue. What am I missing?"	"Anindita Dutta"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-06-01 20:25:28"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	NULL	"Then, wouldn't people be incentivized to always foreclose on the most senior interest? Let's say you have 5 loans made on January 1, January 2, January 3, January 4, and January 5. If you have financial trouble, you would always choose to stop paying the January 1 loan, right? Because then if that interest gets foreclosed on, you won't have to pay the 4 subsequent loans. On the other hand, if you default on the January 5 loan and they foreclose on it, then you have to pay all loans 1 through 5 still. Am I understanding correctly?What if all 5 loans are in default? Which one would be the interest being foreclosed on?Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYTy, For example, let’s say a bank initiates a foreclosure proceeding on a debtor’s home because the debtor is in default on the bank’s loan, and the home is collateral on the bank’s loan. The bank’s loan is the interest being foreclosed on.  Interests junior to the bank’s loan (i.e., interests acquired after the interest being foreclosed on) are extinguished by the foreclosure. For example, let’s say the debtor took out a second mortgage on the home from a credit association. This interest is junior to the bank’s interest and is eliminated by the bank’s foreclosure – meaning, it no longer exists. In contrast, interests senior to the bank loan (in this example, there isn’t one) would survive the foreclosure sale.  Additionally, there are certain exceptions to the rule that first-in-time mortgages are senior to those that come after. See large Outline at 74-76 explaining these concepts.  Hope this helps,   Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-31 14:30:56 wrote: I'm having trouble understanding what happens to junior and senior interests during a foreclosure. For example, what does it mean that ""all interests that are junior to the mortgage that is foreclosed are generally destroyed?"" What is the ""mortgage that is foreclosed?"" What does ""destroyed"" mean? Would you be able to provide an example to help explain the foreclosure process with junior and senior interests?"	"RE: Foreclosure"	Follow-up	NULL	710541	1737	421938	397056	"2022-06-02 16:24:31"	"2022-06-01 20:25:28"	2	0	0	0	"Kendra Frazier"	"  Ty,     Following a first-mortgage foreclosure, all junior liens are eliminated, which means the liens are removed from the property&rsquo;s title. But the debt remains and the debtor&rsquo;s obligation remain in place. The debtor&rsquo;s obligation to repay the loan is not eliminated because the lien that was securing the loan is eliminated.     Additionally, the party who initiates the foreclosure proceeding &ndash; their interest is the one being foreclosed on.     Kendra     Ty Zhang @ 2022-06-01 20:25:28 wrote:  Then, wouldn't people be incentivized to always foreclose on the most senior interest? Let's say you have 5 loans made on January 1, January 2, January 3, January 4, and January 5. If you have financial trouble, you would always choose to stop paying the January 1 loan, right? Because then if that interest gets foreclosed on, you won't have to pay the 4 subsequent loans. On the other hand, if you default on the January 5 loan and they foreclose on it, then you have to pay all loans 1 through 5 still. Am I understanding correctly?    What if all 5 loans are in default? Which one would be the interest being foreclosed on?    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTY  Ty,  For example, let&rsquo;s say a bank initiates a foreclosure proceeding on a debtor&rsquo;s home because the debtor is in default on the bank&rsquo;s loan, and the home is collateral on the bank&rsquo;s loan. The bank&rsquo;s loan is the interest being foreclosed on.   Interests junior to the bank&rsquo;s loan (i.e., interests acquired after the interest being foreclosed on) are extinguished by the foreclosure. For example, let&rsquo;s say the debtor took out a second mortgage on the home from a credit association. This interest is junior to the bank&rsquo;s interest and is eliminated by the bank&rsquo;s foreclosure &ndash; meaning, it no longer exists. In contrast, interests senior to the bank loan (in this example, there isn&rsquo;t one) would survive the foreclosure sale.   Additionally, there are certain exceptions to the rule that first-in-time mortgages are senior to those that come after. See large Outline at 74-76 explaining these concepts.   Hope this helps,     Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-31 14:30:56 wrote:  I'm having trouble understanding what happens to junior and senior interests during a foreclosure. For example, what does it mean that ""all interests that are junior to the mortgage that is foreclosed are generally destroyed?"" What is the ""mortgage that is foreclosed?"" What does ""destroyed"" mean? Would you be able to provide an example to help explain the foreclosure process with junior and senior interests?"	"Ty Zhang"
Jonathan	Rosenthal	"2022-06-01 17:35:39"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"What does this mean: ""In general, the party can recover the contract price minus any amount that it will cost the other party to obtain the promised full performance.""?"	"Flashcard answer"	General		710401	1737	425061	435724	"2022-06-03 00:16:37"	"2022-06-01 18:15:21"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Colleen Scrocca"	"Dear Jonathan,This statement seems to be in relation to &ldquo;substantial performance&rdquo; of a contract.  This statement means that, assuming the substantial performance burden has been met, then the party that was contracted to perform and only &ldquo;substantially performed&rdquo; is entitled to receive the amount agreed upon in the contract minus what it will cost to bring the contract to &ldquo;full performance&rdquo; by another.  I hire a painter to paint my living room blue and he paints it green he has not substantially performed and I owe him nothing even though me may be out cost of supplies, time etc.  If I hire a painter to paint my living room blue and he paints it blue, but it is not a professional job and now I need to have another painter come in and fix his mistakes. Painter #1 could recover for &ldquo;substantial performance&rdquo; because he did paint, so he gets the contract price, but because I also need to pay painter #2 to fix mistakes the cost of painter #2 would come out of painter #1&rsquo;s contract/recovery amount.   Substantial performance does not usually apply to the sale of goods.  Substantial performance is discussed on page 47 of the MBE outline at Section VII(D)(2).  I hope this helps.Best of Luck!Kelley      Jonathan Rosenthal @ 2022-06-01 17:35:39 wrote:  What does this mean: ""In general, the party can recover the contract price minus any amount that it will cost the other party to obtain the promised full performance.""?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
