Zohaib	Mevawalla	"2022-05-31 13:25:34"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	NULL	"This does help; thank you!Admin wrote:Subject Outline: MBE CONTRACTS  SALESHello Zohaib, Q10013: The new contract would require some consideration to bind the new party. That consideration may be the performance due to the previous party to the contract. For example, if a contractor agrees to do certain work in exchange for money, and there's a novation, then the new contractor is going to be paid the money. Payment of that money is consideration for the new contractor. It isn't a pre-existing duty because the previous duty was to pay the original contractor, and this new duty is to pay the new contractor. Q9920: The rules for forming the option contract itself are subject to the same general rules as any other contract. However, if an option contract exists, the offer that it holds open has different rules that are set by the terms of the option contract itself. Here, though, there isn't an option contract in play. There's just an offer that is open until and unless revoked. Thus, the general rules on when an acceptance is effective apply, and the mailbox rule says that acceptance is effective upon being deposited, properly addressed, in the mail. Since that happened within the week and before the offeror revoked, the contract was formed at that moment. Hope this helps, -Bryan  Zohaib Mevawalla @ 2022-05-28 13:35:51 wrote: Q10013: Regarding Novation: what happens if no consideration is paid to the delegate but the other contracting party releases the delegator/i.e. agrees to Novation? Is the delegate full responsible for any liability despite her not receiving any consideration from the delegator?  Q9920: Regarding option contracts: Can an option contract only be accepted upon receipt? Also, how would the Friend in this question succeed when she didn't let the other party know within a week that she wanted to accept the contract? This question really confused me. Any insight you can share is greatly appreciated."	"RE: Two Questions - Contract Law"		NULL	709220	1737	348535	245688	"2022-06-01 01:16:43"	"2022-05-31 13:25:34"	0	0	0	1	"Bryan Cox"	"Sure thing, Zohaib, and good luck studying!    Zohaib Mevawalla @ 2022-05-31 13:25:34 wrote:  This does help; thank you!    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: MBE CONTRACTS  SALES  Hello Zohaib,  Q10013: The new contract would require some consideration to bind the new party. That consideration may be the performance due to the previous party to the contract. For example, if a contractor agrees to do certain work in exchange for money, and there's a novation, then the new contractor is going to be paid the money. Payment of that money is consideration for the new contractor. It isn't a pre-existing duty because the previous duty was to pay the original contractor, and this new duty is to pay the new contractor.  Q9920: The rules for forming the option contract itself are subject to the same general rules as any other contract. However, if an option contract exists, the offer that it holds open has different rules that are set by the terms of the option contract itself.  Here, though, there isn't an option contract in play. There's just an offer that is open until and unless revoked. Thus, the general rules on when an acceptance is effective apply, and the mailbox rule says that acceptance is effective upon being deposited, properly addressed, in the mail. Since that happened within the week and before the offeror revoked, the contract was formed at that moment.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Zohaib Mevawalla @ 2022-05-28 13:35:51 wrote:  Q10013: Regarding Novation: what happens if no consideration is paid to the delegate but the other contracting party releases the delegator/i.e. agrees to Novation? Is the delegate full responsible for any liability despite her not receiving any consideration from the delegator?    Q9920: Regarding option contracts: Can an option contract only be accepted upon receipt? Also, how would the Friend in this question succeed when she didn't let the other party know within a week that she wanted to accept the contract? This question really confused me. Any insight you can share is greatly appreciated."	"Zohaib Mevawalla"
Julius	Zavala	"2022-05-31 12:59:10"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"Regarding defeasible fee: is durational language considered a subset of conditional language?Example: O conveys Whiteacre to A, so long as it is used as a restaurant, then to B.A has a present interest in Whiteacre. If A stops using Whiteacre as a restaurant, it will automatically transfer to B. This would be a FSSEI, correct?"	"Real Property Ownership"	General		709193	1737	336927	369848	"2022-06-02 23:08:23"	"2022-05-31 15:22:53"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Pamela Prieto"	"Hi Julius,  Yes. It is a condition subsequent that ends the interest.A fee simple determinable islimited by specific durational language. This means it is a fee simple determinable if the grantor uses the words &ldquo;so long as,&rdquo; &ldquo;while,&rdquo; &ldquo;during,&rdquo; &ldquo;until&rdquo;.   In a fee simple determinable, the grantee's ownership over the property automatically terminates upon the happening of a stated event, and full ownership of the property is returned to the grantor or his successor in interest. Thus the grantor always has a possibility of reverter.  Yes, you are correct. In your example,A has a present interest in Whiteacre and if A stops using Whiteacre as a restaurant, it will automatically transfer to B.  Yes. It is a FSSEI (fee simple subject to executory interest).  The main difference of afee simple subject to executory interest and a fee simple subject to a condition subsequent is who the property will vest upon the happening of the event. For thefee simple subject to executory interest, it vests on (transfers to) a third party while for the fee simple subject to a condition subsequent, it vests on the grantor since it always includes the words ""right of re-entry/to re-enter"" or ""power to terminate"".  A fee simple subject to executory interest is an interest that will end upon the happening of some event and that future event will vest the property to a third party who is not the grantor. This means that that in order for it to be an executory interest, the happening of the condition/event cannot transfer and vest the property to the grantor. It should vest on a third party like your example.  Hope this helps!  Best,  Pam      Julius Zavala @ 2022-05-31 12:59:10 wrote:  Regarding defeasible fee: is durational language considered a subset of conditional language?    Example: O conveys Whiteacre to A, so long as it is used as a restaurant, then to B.    A has a present interest in Whiteacre. If A stops using Whiteacre as a restaurant, it will automatically transfer to B. This would be a FSSEI, correct?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
