Hyojeong	Son	"2022-05-30 20:23:58"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"		"Hello,I can't understanding the one of the requirement to regulate expressive conduct.Laws regulating expressive conduct could be upheld the the burden of expression is no greater than necessary among with other requirement.What does means ""the burden of expression is no greater than necessary""?Could you provide any example?Thank you!"	"Expressive conduct"	General		708776	1737	337791	245688	"2022-05-31 23:55:40"	"2022-05-31 09:16:10"	1	0	"MBE CONSTITUTIONAL LAW"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Hyojeong,  That is, more or less, an expression of the strict scrutiny standard. The law can be neither overbroad nor vague, otherwise its burden is too great. Those concepts are discussed on pages 70 and 71 of your MBE Contracts outline -- both those principals would fall under this criteria.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Hyojeong Son @ 2022-05-30 20:23:58 wrote:  Hello,  I can't understanding the one of the requirement to regulate expressive conduct.  Laws regulating expressive conduct could be upheld the the burden of expression is no greater than necessary among with other requirement.  What does means ""the burden of expression is no greater than necessary""?  Could you provide any example?  Thank you!"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-05-30 20:23:42"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"""K is unenforceable if consideration/performance under K is illegal."" ""K is void if it contemplates illegal conduct."" What is the difference between consideration/performance under K is illegal and K contemplates illegal conduct?"	Illegality	General		708775	1737	421938	245688	"2022-05-31 22:54:16"	"2022-05-31 09:15:34"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Ty,  The first is clear. ""Contemplates..."" includes situations like examples 2 and 3 on page 28 of your MBE Contracts outline. Here's example 3:  ""Example 3: Assume the same facts as those in Example 2 , except that the buyer tells the owner that he intends to use the rifle to kill his wife. The owner may not recover the price of the rifle from the buyer because the owner knew both that the buyer intended to put the rifle to illegal use and that the illegal use involved grave social harm.""  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-30 20:23:42 wrote:  ""K is unenforceable if consideration/performance under K is illegal."" ""K is void if it contemplates illegal conduct."" What is the difference between consideration/performance under K is illegal and K contemplates illegal conduct?"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Elisabeth	Logan	"2022-05-30 16:06:09"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	10042	"Hello! On this question, I am confused how the culinary school does not win under the race-notice statute. The culinary school did not have notice of any other purchasers of the property, and recorded its deed before the fast food chain recorded theirs. This seems like it would win under a race-notice statute. Does checking the chain of title and noticing that there must be a ""wild deed"" or failing to find a deed conveying the property to the individual selling it count as notice? Or does the wild deed just take this into an entirely separate area? That feels burdensome on the purchaser to ensure that the prior owner properly recorded their deed."	"Race-Notice Statute"	"Mult. Choice"		708660	1737	410878	283716	"2022-06-01 01:11:08"	"2022-05-31 08:45:16"	1	10042	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Elisabeth,    In determining who wins under a recording statute, we only look at the notice or recording of the ""subsequent"" purchaser. In a race-notice jurisdiction, the subsequent purchaser should not have notice only at the time he or she takes the property and he or she has to record first. Here, we only look at if the ""subsequent"" purchaser, the fast-food chain, had notice when it purchased the property and if it recorded first. In this case, the fast-food chain did not have notice of the recorded wild deed of the culinary school because it was not in the chain of title. The chef did not record the deed from the original owner to the chef, so there was a gap in the chain of title. When the chef conveyed the property to the culinary school, the culinary school recorded the deed but a person looking up the ownership of the property would not find the deed from the original owner to the chef. The deed from the chef to the culinary school is therefore a wild deed. The fast-food chain would have no knowledge of either the deed from the original owner to the chef or the deed from the chef to the culinary school (even though it was recorded). Further, the fast-food chain recorded its deed in the proper chain first. That is why the fast-food chain won. To protect the culinary school's interest, based on the race-notice jurisdiction here, the chef would have needed to record the deed, or the culinary school would have had to take actual possession of the property. That would have provided the fast-food chain with adequate notice.     I hope this helps!     Best,          Timothy    Elisabeth Logan @ 2022-05-30 16:06:09 wrote:  Hello! On this question, I am confused how the culinary school does not win under the race-notice statute. The culinary school did not have notice of any other purchasers of the property, and recorded its deed before the fast food chain recorded theirs. This seems like it would win under a race-notice statute. Does checking the chain of title and noticing that there must be a ""wild deed"" or failing to find a deed conveying the property to the individual selling it count as notice? Or does the wild deed just take this into an entirely separate area? That feels burdensome on the purchaser to ensure that the prior owner properly recorded their deed."	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Sam	Archie	"2022-05-30 08:45:29"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2823	"Hi - thank you for getting back to me.In regard to the question 1/quiet enjoyment. There are three slightly different definitions of quiet enjoyment (I now see, with the help of your answer, that some are talking about the implied and others the express).The lecture handout for Real Property on page 30 states ""quiet enjoyment is violated when the landlord, or someone connected to the landlord, renders the premises unsuitable for the intended purpose. The landlord must control common areas...and nuisance-like behavior.""Page 47 of the lecture handout has the Covenant of quiet enjoyment under future covenants as ""Grantor promises that the grantee's possession will not be disturbed by a third-party claim.""Page 27 has the has the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment and states, ""The tenant can withhold rent when the landlord takes actions that make the premises wholly or substantially unsuitable for their intended purposes, and the tenant is constructively evicted.""Are the definitions from page 27 and page 30 both speaking about the impliedcovenant of quiet enjoyment? And is page 27 just talking about the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment in relation to when someone can withhold rent? When I was looking at this question, the leasee informed the owner of his intended purpose (manufacturer and need for a/c), the a/c broke (I agree, only 3 times over 5 months, so not sure if that constitutes wholly or substantially unsuitable) and then the factors for constructive eviction were present, so I concluded that he was okay to withhold rent due to a violation of quiet enjoyment plus constructive eviction.I hope that clarifies my confusion a bit - thank you for your help!Sam ArchieAdmin wrote:Lecture: Real Property: Chapter 12Subject Outline: MBE REAL PROPERTYQuestion ID: 2823Hi Sam, I've answered your two questions below:  1. ""Quiet enjoyment"" means no interference with a person's possession of property.  In deeds, however, there must be an express covenant of quiet enjoyment. General Warrantee deeds contain this express future covenant, that the grantee’s possession will not be interfered with by a third party’s lawful claim for title.  In both residential and commercial leases, there is a covenant of quiet enjoyment that is implied. The landlord will not interfere with the tenant's possession of the leased premises. There is also a duty under this implied covenant for the landlord to take action against a tenant's nuisance-like behavior  control common areas. It is breached only when the landlord (or someone with superior title) prevents tenant from possessing the premises. Real Property Outline § II.C.4 goes into detail what constitutes active eviction or constructive eviction.  Additionally, leases contain a warrantee of habitability that is also implied in most residential leases. This requires the landlord to maintain the property such that it is reasonably suitable for residential use. A condition that substantially threatens a tenant’s health or safety violates this warrantee. This warrantee cannot be waived by the tenant. Real Property Outline § II.C.3 explains this in much greater detail. I’m not quite sure what you are asking here—did you mean to ask about the implied warrantee of habitability? The lease in Question 2823 was a commercial lease, so do not consider a warrantee of habitability unless the facts tell you otherwise. 2. The covenant of quiet enjoyment in the facts is the same as the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment in leases in your outline. It is only breached when someone disrupts the possession of the tenant. There can be actual eviction, or constructive eviction, but not every interference with the use and enjoyment of the premises amounts to a constructive eviction—temporary acts do not generally constitute constructive eviction. Tenant must give notice to landlord and adequate time to permit the landlord to fulfill his duty, and then the tenant must vacate the property in a reasonable time. See Real Property Outline § II.C.4.b.  Even though the tenant had specific needs for building temperature, it’s not likely that the A/C breakdown would constitute constructive eviction; there were repeated failures, but the building was only temporarily without A/C for 3 times (1st for 3 hours, 2nd for six hours, and 3rd for 10 hours) in five months. The tenant could have negotiated his specific A/C requirements with the landlord before signing the lease, but he failed to do so.  Hope this helps! Best,  Anna  Sam Archie @ 2022-05-26 17:37:14 wrote: Good Afternoon,  I recently watched the Real Property, Chapter 12 lecture and then completed the Real Property Essay PQ, ID 2823.  Within the lecture (and on the lecture handout) the Implied Covenant of Quiet Enjoyment is mentioned a couple of times. First as a future covenant (grantors promises that the grantee's possession will not be disturbed by a third-party claim), then as an implied covenant of quiet enjoyment (tenant can withhold rent when the landlord takes actions that make the premises wholly or substantially unsuitable for their indeed purposes, and the tenant is constructively evicted).  In Essay 2823, there is a covenant of quiet enjoyment in the lease. The sample answer only discusses the covenant of quiet enjoyment, and does not at all mention the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment (""Moreover, the covenant of quiet enjoyment is breached only when the landlord, someone claiming through the landlord, or someone with superior title disrupts the possession of the tenant). I thought the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment and constructive eviction would fit into this fact pattern.  I am wondering (1) is the covenant of implied warranty different from the implied covenant of implied warranty, and (2) if the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment cannot be denied to the tenant by the landlord, why was this not addressed in the sample answer/why was it not an applicable defense to the tenant to not pay his rent and assert a violation of this duty and constructive eviction?  Thanks,  Sam Archie"	"RE: Implied Covenant of Quiet Enjoyment"	Follow-up	"Real Property: Chapter 12"	708445	1737	348929	435564	"2022-05-31 14:14:41"	"2022-05-30 08:45:29"	1	2823	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Sam!  Yes. Remember, if the facts indicate a landlord-tenant issue, it is the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment (that the tenant can possess the property without interference by the landlord). To determine if there is actual or constructive eviction (and whether the tenant can withhold rent), the facts must show that the landlord breached the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment.  If there is a deed, the covenant of quiet enjoyment is a warranty by the seller/grantor that a third party will not have lawful claim for title of the property purchased by the purchaser/grantee.  Hope this clarifies the issue!  Best,  Anna      Sam Archie @ 2022-05-30 08:45:29 wrote:  Hi - thank you for getting back to me.    In regard to the question 1/quiet enjoyment. There are three slightly different definitions of quiet enjoyment (I now see, with the help of your answer, that some are talking about the implied and others the express).    The lecture handout for Real Property on page 30 states ""quiet enjoyment is violated when the landlord, or someone connected to the landlord, renders the premises unsuitable for the intended purpose. The landlord must control common areas...and nuisance-like behavior.""    Page 47 of the lecture handout has the Covenant of quiet enjoyment under future covenants as ""Grantor promises that the grantee's possession will not be disturbed by a third-party claim.""    Page 27 has the has the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment and states, ""The tenant can withhold rent when the landlord takes actions that make the premises wholly or substantially unsuitable for their intended purp