Israel	"Del Mundo"	"2022-05-29 14:03:09"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"How is (i) a quasi-contract different from (ii) a moral obligation plus a subsequent promise?"	"Consideration Substitutes"	General	"Consideration Substitutes (Promissory Liability)"	708077	1737	380871	159137	"2022-05-29 14:50:52"	"2022-05-29 14:07:55"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Israel!  It really isn't that different. The moral consideration plus subsequent promise falls under the so-called material benefit rule of the Second Restatement (Section 86). But you are correct that you could look at this as quasi-contract.  Good job thinking this through.  Steve    Israel Del Mundo @ 2022-05-29 14:03:09 wrote:  How is (i) a quasi-contract different from (ii) a moral obligation plus a subsequent promise?"	"Beth Hooks"
Nick	Wolfe	"2022-05-28 13:42:43"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	9520	"Would the result still be the same if there had been no ""due on sale"" clause in the first place? Is a buyer assumes the mortgage, is the original debtor released from liability?"	"Question #9520"	"Mult. Choice"		707753	1737	413801	435745	"2022-05-29 16:46:06"	"2022-05-29 09:06:48"	1	9520	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Laura Wakefield"	"Hello,  If a buyer assumes a mortgage, the original debtor is still liable for the debt. You can find this in the big outline at V.C.1.a (&ldquo;Mortgagor&rsquo;s liability&rdquo;). As such, the investor is liable for the unpaid portion of the mortgage unless they are released by the bank from the mortgage. If the due on sale clause had not been waived, the investor would&rsquo;ve had to pay the debt when they sold the land to the developer and there would not have been a mortgage from the investor for the developer to assume. Because the due on sale clause was waived, the mortgage transfer functioned as if there had never been a due on sale clause, meaning the investor remained liable for the unpaid debt.  Hope this helps!  Laura      Nick Wolfe @ 2022-05-28 13:42:43 wrote:  Would the result still be the same if there had been no ""due on sale"" clause in the first place? Is a buyer assumes the mortgage, is the original debtor released from liability?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Zohaib	Mevawalla	"2022-05-28 13:35:51"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	"Q10013; Q9920"	"Q10013: Regarding Novation: what happens if no consideration is paid to the delegate but the other contracting party releases the delegator/i.e. agrees to Novation? Is the delegate full responsible for any liability despite her not receiving any consideration from the delegator?Q9920: Regarding option contracts: Can an option contract only be accepted upon receipt? Also, how would the Friend in this question succeed when she didn't let the other party know within a week that she wanted to accept the contract? This question really confused me. Any insight you can share is greatly appreciated."	"Two Questions - Contract Law"	"Mult. Choice"		707748	1737	348535	245688	"2022-05-29 16:29:06"	"2022-05-29 09:06:27"	2	9920	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Zohaib,  Q10013: The new contract would require some consideration to bind the new party. That consideration may be the performance due to the previous party to the contract. For example, if a contractor agrees to do certain work in exchange for money, and there's a novation, then the new contractor is going to be paid the money. Payment of that money is consideration for the new contractor. It isn't a pre-existing duty because the previous duty was to pay the original contractor, and this new duty is to pay the new contractor.  Q9920: The rules for forming the option contract itself are subject to the same general rules as any other contract. However, if an option contract exists, the offer that it holds open has different rules that are set by the terms of the option contract itself.  Here, though, there isn't an option contract in play. There's just an offer that is open until and unless revoked. Thus, the general rules on when an acceptance is effective apply, and the mailbox rule says that acceptance is effective upon being deposited, properly addressed, in the mail. Since that happened within the week and before the offeror revoked, the contract was formed at that moment.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    Zohaib Mevawalla @ 2022-05-28 13:35:51 wrote:  Q10013: Regarding Novation: what happens if no consideration is paid to the delegate but the other contracting party releases the delegator/i.e. agrees to Novation? Is the delegate full responsible for any liability despite her not receiving any consideration from the delegator?    Q9920: Regarding option contracts: Can an option contract only be accepted upon receipt? Also, how would the Friend in this question succeed when she didn't let the other party know within a week that she wanted to accept the contract? This question really confused me. Any insight you can share is greatly appreciated."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Katie	Schelli	"2022-05-28 10:18:15"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"Example 42 reads ""Oliver conveys 'to my grandchildren who reach 21.'"" He has 3 living grandchildren under the age of 21. The conveyance is said to violate RAP because Oliver could have more children and grandchildren that exceed the 21-year limit. Thus, the entire conveyance is stricken and his grandchildren then have no interest.In the Assessment question after the lecture, it states that if a conveyance partially violates RAP, then the part that violates is void and the part that does not remains in effect. Applying this concept to Example 42, I would think Oliver's conveyance would be valid for the grandchildren who are alive or any grandchildren born that could reach 21 before 21 years after Oliver's death, but the conveyance would be void for any grandchildren born after Oliver's death.In short, why isn't the conveyance in Example 42 partially valid as to any grandchildren who may reach 21 years old before 21 years after Oliver's death, and only void as to grandchildren who have not been born at the time of Oliver's death?Thank you in advance for any insight!"	"Chapter 6 - RAP Violations; Partial Validity"	Handout		707668	1737	401597	159137	"2022-05-29 10:58:15"	"2022-05-29 09:00:38"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Katie!  There is great appeal to your approach, which is why many states have adopted the ""wait and see"" approach to the RAP. But under common law, you don't look to the actual facts, unfortunately for the existing grandchildren.  What I think the ""partial"" approach would allow is something different. So if the bequest was O to ""my grandchildren who reach 21, then to X."" You'd strike the first part, which is the offending interest, and just give the property to X.  Steve    Katie Schelli @ 2022-05-28 10:18:15 wrote:  Example 42 reads ""Oliver conveys 'to my grandchildren who reach 21.'"" He has 3 living grandchildren under 