Sara	Rosenburg	"2022-05-27 18:28:37"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	10000	"Hi! Why is it that, when the youngest son transfers his property interest in the joint tenancy to the oldest son, the oldest son retains a 1/3 joint tenancy and a 1/3 tenancy in common? It seems to me that, once the oldest son owns a 2/3 interest in the property overall as compared to the middle son's remaining 1/3 interest, the unity of interest is destroyed. Without the unity of interest, wouldn't the older and middle sons become tenants in common with a 2/3 and 1/3 interest in the property, respectively?Thanks for your help!"	"MBE Real Property PQ3 #24"	"Mult. Choice"		707501	1737	414681	283716	"2022-06-01 00:26:55"	"2022-05-27 20:09:51"	1	10000	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Timothy Chessher"	"Hi Sara,    When the joint tenancy with right to survivorship was created, it met the requirements of the unity of possession, interest, time, and title. A severance of a joint tenancy does not automatically convert into a tenancy in common if there are more than two joint tenants. As is the case in this question. Here, the occurring severance of the youngest brother selling his share to the oldest brother did not affect the joint tenancy of all the brothers' shares. Here, the only parcel that was affected was the parcel that was sold. The portion from the younger brother to the older brother was converted into a tenancy in common, but the original share of the older brother and the share of the middle brother remained a joint tenancy with right to survivorship. Had the middle brother died, the older brother would have ownership of all three shares. But under the facts, when the older brother died, his original share passed to the middle brother as a joint tenancy with right to survivorship, and his purchased share remaining as a tenancy in common.     I hope this helps!    Best,          Timothy    Sara Rosenburg @ 2022-05-27 18:28:37 wrote:  Hi! Why is it that, when the youngest son transfers his property interest in the joint tenancy to the oldest son, the oldest son retains a 1/3 joint tenancy and a 1/3 tenancy in common? It seems to me that, once the oldest son owns a 2/3 interest in the property overall as compared to the middle son's remaining 1/3 interest, the unity of interest is destroyed. Without the unity of interest, wouldn't the older and middle sons become tenants in common with a 2/3 and 1/3 interest in the property, respectively?    Thanks for your help!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
