Sarah	Flagel	"2022-05-26 18:18:27"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"FAMILY LAW"	3407	"Dear Sir/Madam,I'm trying to understand the differing response to the Family Law Practice Essay #3407 regarding the marital-residence-sale proceeds modification of property division. The first question on the topic is regarding which state can get jurisdiction over the claim and the second is whether the court will grant a modification.I remembered that property division is not subject to modification after the divorce is finalized. Per the answer to question #3, this appears to be true. But I don't understand the answer to the earlier question on jurisdiction. If a court cannot modify property division under these circumstances, shouldn't it follow that no court has jurisdiction to hear the claim? Essentially, shouldn't both answers be the same?Thank you in advance for your help.Best,Sarah"	"Jx over modification of property division under family law"	Essay		706820	1737	350016	159137	"2022-05-26 20:17:42"	"2022-05-26 19:07:13"	1	3407	"FAMILY LAW"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Sarah!  It is really a difference between jurisdiction and the merits.Remember the first part of the question is only asking about jurisdiction, not the merits of the claim. You are correct that the proceedings would likely eventually be dismissed because a property division order is not modifiable, as it is based on the parties' assets at the time of divorce. Changes in the parties' circumstances after divorce are not considered once the award has been entered. A ruling on the merits of modification is different, though, from a question on jurisdiction to hear the case. Because 1(b) does not require an analysis of the merits of the husband's request (but only whether the court has authority to hear it- Civ Pro elements and fact that state courts have subject matter jurisdiction over domestic relations issues), the answer does not analyze the differences between spousal support and property division. Once you get to 2(c), which asks for an analysis of the merits of husband's motion, then the sample answer properly compares spousal support vs. property division.  Hope this helps!  Steve    Sarah Flagel @ 2022-05-26 18:18:27 wrote:  Dear Sir/Madam,  I'm trying to understand the differing response to the Family Law Practice Essay #3407 regarding the marital-residence-sale proceeds modification of property division. The first question on the topic is regarding which state can get jurisdiction over the claim and the second is whether the court will grant a modification.  I remembered that property division is not subject to modification after the divorce is finalized. Per the answer to question #3, this appears to be true. But I don't understand the answer to the earlier question on jurisdiction. If a court cannot modify property division under these circumstances, shouldn't it follow that no court has jurisdiction to hear the claim? Essentially, shouldn't both answers be the same?  Thank you in advance for your help.  Best,  Sarah"	"Anindita Dutta"
Sam	Archie	"2022-05-26 17:37:14"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	2823	"Good Afternoon,I recently watched the Real Property, Chapter 12 lecture and then completed the Real Property Essay PQ, ID 2823.Within the lecture (and on the lecture handout) the Implied Covenant of Quiet Enjoyment is mentioned a couple of times. First as a future covenant (grantors promises that the grantee's possession will not be disturbed by a third-party claim), then as an implied covenant of quiet enjoyment (tenant can withhold rent when the landlord takes actions that make the premises wholly or substantially unsuitable for their indeed purposes, and the tenant is constructively evicted).In Essay 2823, there is a covenant of quiet enjoyment in the lease. The sample answer only discusses the covenant of quiet enjoyment, and does not at all mention the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment (""Moreover, the covenant of quiet enjoyment is breached only when the landlord, someone claiming through the landlord, or someone with superior title disrupts the possession of the tenant). I thought the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment and constructive eviction would fit into this fact pattern.I am wondering (1) is the covenant of implied warranty different from the implied covenant of implied warranty, and (2) if the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment cannot be denied to the tenant by the landlord, why was this not addressed in the sample answer/why was it not an applicable defense to the tenant to not pay his rent and assert a violation of this duty and constructive eviction?Thanks,Sam Archie"	"Implied Covenant of Quiet Enjoyment"		"Real Property: Chapter 12"	706793	1737	348929	435564	"2022-05-28 13:39:56"	"2022-05-26 18:11:12"	2	2823	0	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Sam,  I've answered your two questions below:   1. ""Quiet enjoyment"" means no interference with a person's possession of property.   In deeds, however, there must be an express covenant of quiet enjoyment. General Warrantee deeds contain this express future covenant, that the grantee&rsquo;s possession will not be interfered with by a third party&rsquo;s lawful claim for title.   In both residential and commercial leases, there is a covenant of quiet enjoyment that is implied. The landlord will not interfere with the tenant's possession of the leased premises. There is also a duty under this implied covenant for the landlord to take action against a tenant's nuisance-like behavior  control common areas. It is breached only when the landlord (or someone with superior title) prevents tenant from possessing the premises. Real Property Outline &sect; II.C.4 goes into detail what constitutes active eviction or constructive eviction.   Additionally, leases contain a warrantee of habitability that is also implied in most residential leases. This requires the landlord to maintain the property such that it is reasonably suitable for residential use. A condition that substantially threatens a tenant&rsquo;s health or safety violates this warrantee. This warrantee cannot be waived by the tenant. Real Property Outline &sect; II.C.3 explains this in much greater detail.  I&rsquo;m not quite sure what you are asking here&mdash;did you mean to ask about the implied warrantee of habitability? The lease in Question 2823 was a commercial lease, so do not consider a warrantee of habitability unless the facts tell you otherwise.  2. The covenant of quiet enjoyment in the facts is the same as the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment in leases in your outline. It is only breached when someone disrupts the possession of the tenant. There can be actual eviction, or constructive eviction, but not every interference with the use and enjoyment of the premises amounts to a constructive eviction&mdash;temporary acts do not generally constitute constructive eviction. Tenant must give notice to landlord and adequate time to permit the landlord to fulfill his duty, and then the tenant must vacate the property in a reasonable time. See Real Property Outline &sect; II.C.4.b.   Even though the tenant had specific needs for building temperature, it&rsquo;s not likely that the A/C breakdown would constitute constructive eviction; there were repeated failures, but the building was only temporarily without A/C for 3 times (1st for 3 hours, 2nd for six hours, and 3rd for 10 hours) in five months. The tenant could have negotiated his specific A/C requirements with the landlord before signing the lease, but he failed to do so.   Hope this helps!  Best,   Anna    Sam Archie @ 2022-05-26 17:37:14 wrote:  Good Afternoon,    I recently watched the Real Property, Chapter 12 lecture and then completed the Real Property Essay PQ, ID 2823.    Within the lecture (and on the lecture handout) the Implied Covenant of Quiet Enjoyment is mentioned a couple of times. First as a future covenant (grantors promises that the grantee's possession will not be disturbed by a third-party claim), then as an implied covenant of quiet enjoyment (tenant can withhold rent when the landlord takes actions that make the premises wholly or substantially unsuitable for their indeed purposes, and the tenant is constructively evicted).    In Essay 2823, there is a covenant of quiet enjoyment in the lease. The sample answer only discusses the covenant of quiet enjoyment, and does not at all mention the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment (""Moreover, the covenant of quiet enjoyment is breached only when the landlord, someone claiming through the landlord, or someone with superior title disrupts the possession of the tenant). I thought the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment and constructive eviction would fit into this fact pattern.    I am wondering (1) is the covenant of implied warranty different from the implied covenant of implied warranty, and (2) if the implied covenant of quiet enjoyment cannot be denied to the tenant by the landlord, why was this not addressed in the sample answer/why was it not an applicable defense to the tenant to not pay his rent and assert a violation of this duty and constructive eviction?    Thanks,    Sam Archie"	"Anindita Dutta"
