ter perceiving that person is not hearsay and may be admissible as substantive evidence by the testimony of the declarant-witness. Even if the witness has no memory of the prior identification, it will be admissible because the witness is subject to cross-examination about the prior identification.  Here, the victim identified the defendant&rsquo;s voice as that of the robber after perceiving the robber&rsquo;s voice. In addition, the victim testified at trial, so he is subject to cross-examination. Therefore, the victim's statement is a prior statement of identification and is non-hearsay. ""  So the police officer is allowed to testify about this even though the victim is available to testify? Doesn't the victim being available make this hearsay when it is coming from the officer because the rule says this kind of ID is admissible ""by the testimony of the declarant-witness"" so wouldn't it be hearsay coming from the officer?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-05-24 13:31:20"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"FAMILY LAW"	NULL	"""However, Adam and Cindy’s marriage then becomesvoidable—valid only until one spouse seeks to legally void the marriage, based on the grounds listed above.""I'm still confused here. You stated that ""removing the impediment simply moves the marriage to category ofvoidable marriage,"" but also ""the grounds for a voidable marriage are age, impotence, intoxication, fraud/duress, and lack of intent to marry."" So, is ""marriage with removed impediment (prior marriage)"" also a ground for voidable marriage and should be included in the list? But, you also state in the above quote that Adam and Cindy's marriage is voidable only ""based on the grounds above (not including marriage with removed impediment (prior marriage))."" Does that mean all marriages are considered voidable?Admin wrote:Subject Outline: FAMILY LAWHi Ty! I’ve answered your two questions separately: Question 1 – Defenses to annulment Family Law Outline § II.A discusses two types of relationships that can be annulled: a void marriage and a voidable marriage. Although the terminology is very similar, they are in fact two very distinct things.  A void marriage is treated as it has never happened. It will not be legally recognized for any purpose, and does not require judicial action to be dissolved. The three categories of void marriage are: prior existing marriage, incest, and mental incapacity. Family Law Outline § II.A.1.  If there is a void marriage (prior existing marriage, incest, or mental incapacity), the only way to defend against an annulment action is to deny the existence of the impediment. Family Law Outline § II.A.5. You can’t remove the impediment of incest (after all, blood relations are blood relations), so that’s set-in stone. The impediment of mental incapacitation is also unlikely to be removed. However, the impediment of a prior marriage could be removed simply by divorcing the spouse of the prior marriage. Removing the impediment simply moves the marriage to category of voidable marriage.  A voidable marriage is valid until one spouse seeks to legally void the marriage. There must be a judicial decree to dissolve the marriage. The grounds for a voidable marriage are age, impotence, intoxication, fraud/duress, and lack of intent to marry. Family Law Outline § II.A.2. Example: Adam marries Bethany. A few years later, he marries Cindy. Cindy does not know about Adam’s prior marriage and believes in good-faith that she entered into a legal marriage with Adam. Adam and Cindy’s marriage is void as a matter of law. Adam then divorces Bethany. The impediment of prior marriage is removed, so Adam and Cindy’s marriage would no longer be void as a matter of law. However, Adam and Cindy’s marriage then becomes voidable—valid only until one spouse seeks to legally void the marriage, based on the grounds listed above.  Question 2 – Children’s capacity to contract Family Law Outline § VI.D goes into detail about some of the special protections (and also limitations) the law imposes on children. For instance, while children can convey property, they cannot execute a valid will. Children are also treated differently in tort law  criminal law. A minor can enter into a legal contract, but because minors are deemed to lack the legal capacity to be held to contractual duties, courts generally will not enforce these contracts.  This does NOT mean that they are incapable of contracting: it simply means that any contract entered into by the minor is voidable at any time by the minor until the age of majority. However, the minor can still choose to hold the other party to the terms of the contract. See Contracts Outline § I.E.6.a. There are a few exceptions—if a minor contracts for necessities, and these necessities are supplied to the minor, the minor can’t just void the contract; they must pay (albeit an amount limited to the reasonable value) for the service or/good provided to them. See Contracts Outline § I.E.6.a.1. There are also some statutory exceptions: for example, an education loan made to a minor may be fully enforceable by the lender. See Contracts Outline § I.E.6. a.2.  Hope this helps! Best, Anna  Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-23 14:08:20 wrote: 1. According to the final outline, under Defenses to Annulment, ""when a marriage is void, the only way to defend against the annulment is to deny the existence of the impediment ... removing the impediment merely makes the marriage voidable, but it will not necessarily prevent the annulment."" I don't understand why removing an impediment would still make the marriage voidable.  2. Under Rights and Obligations of Children, ""children may ... enter into contracts as minors,"" but in our Contracts lecture we learned that individuals under the age of 18 do not have the capacity to contract. Would you please help clarify as these statements seem contradictory?"	"RE: Family Law"	Follow-up	NULL	705120	1737	421938	435564	"2022-05-24 15:16:34"	"2022-05-24 13:31:20"	2	0	"FAMILY LAW"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Ty!   There are only three ways to end a marriage: death, divorce, and annulment. Divorce is the legal dissolution of a valid marriage. Annulment voids a marriage and declares it as having never been valid.  A void marriage is not a valid marriage. It is annulled as a matter of law&mdash;it is treated as though it never happened. You don&rsquo;t need file a judicial action to have it annulled.  A voidable marriage is considered a valid marriage until one spouse seeks to annul it, but there must be a judicial decree in order to do so. Grounds for a voidable marriage are age, impotence, intoxication, fraud/duress, lack of intent to marry. If a marriage is annulled, it is treated as though it never happened.   If grounds for annulment do not exist, the marriage cannot be annulled. Instead, the parties must file fordivorce in order to dissolve the marriage.  1)You asked, &ldquo;Does that mean all marriages are considered voidable?&rdquo;  No.If there are no grounds for annulment, the only way to dissolve the marriage is by divorce.   To have a marriage annulled, the party seeking annulment must have grounds to obtain the annulment.A voidable marriage is simply a marriage that can be annulled. It doesn&rsquo;t have to be annulled; voidable marriage are valid marriages unless and until one spouse seeks to void it. The parties may have grounds to annul the marriage but decide to remain married.  2) You asked, &ldquo;So, is ""marriage with removed impediment (prior marriage)"" also a ground for voidable marriage and should be included in the list?&rdquo;  No. The only grounds for annulment for a voidable marriage are age, intoxication, fraud/duress, and lack of intent.Family Law Outline &sect; II.A (pgs. 4-6) explains annulment and the grounds for annulment in detail:   a) Age: A party who is under the age of consent to marry and who did not seek the consent of his parents or the court may apply to have the marriage annulled. However, if the party who was not of legal age attains such age and continues to live with party as a married couple, many courts will prohibit the filing of a annulment based on age.     b) Impotence: A marriage is voidable if one party is &ldquo;naturally and incurably&rdquo; impotent, unless the other party knew about the condition before the marriage.    c) Intoxication: If either party was under the influence of drugs or alcohol at the time of marriage, which made that party incapable of contracting into a marriage, then that marriage may be annulled. In most jurisdictions, however, the parties must be able to demonstrate that they did not ratify the marriage by continuing to voluntarily live with each other after the ceremony.    d) Fraud, misrepresentation, duress, coercion, or force - the marriage was the result of a fraud that goes to the essence of a marriage. The fraud must be based on present facts. Most courts require that the parties immediately cease living together once the fraud is discovered.    e) Lack of intent: Most jurisdictions permit annulment when the parties participated in the marriage ceremony as an act of jest or hilarity and do not have the requisite intention to be bound by the act. This also includes cases in which the parties, in advance, agree to only some, but not all, of the conventional aspects of marriage, including sexual and emotional fidelity, economic interdependence, and commitment to the relationship. Often seen in cases with immigration issues, this type of marriage is commonly referred to as a &ldquo;limited purpose&rdquo; marriage.    I hope this helps clarify things for you!    Best,   Anna      Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-24 13:31:20 wrote:  ""However, Adam and Cindy&rsquo;s marriage then becomesvoidable&mdash;valid only until one spouse seeks to legally void the marriage, based on the grounds listed above.""    I'm still confused here. You stated that ""removing the impediment simply moves the marriage to category ofvoidable marriage,"" but also ""the grounds for a voidable marriage are age, impotence, intoxication, fraud/duress, and lack of intent to marry."" So, is ""marriage with removed impediment (prior marriage)"" also a ground for voidable marriage and should be included in the list? But, you also state in the above quote that Adam and Cindy's marriage is voidable only ""based on the grounds above (not including marriage with removed impediment (prior marriage))."" Does that mean all marriages are considered voidable?    Admin wrote:  Subject Outline: FAMILY LAW  Hi Ty!  I&rsquo;ve answered your two questions separately:  Question 1 &ndash; Defenses to annulment  Family Law Outline &sect; II.A discusses two types of relationships that can be annulled: a void marriage and a voidable marriage. Although the terminology is very similar, they are in fact two very distinct things.    A void marriage is treated as it has never happened. It will not be legally recognized for any purpose, and does not require judicial action to be dissolved. The three categories of void marriage are: prior existing marriage, incest, and mental incapacity. Family Law Outline &sect; II.A.1.    If there is a void marriage (prior existing marriage, incest, or mental incapacity), the only way to defend against an annulment action is to deny the existence of the impediment. Family Law Outline &sect; II.A.5. You can&rsquo;t remove the impediment of incest (after all, blood relations are blood relations), so that&rsquo;s set-in stone. The impediment of mental incapacitation is also unlikely to be removed. However, the impediment of a prior marriage could be removed simply by divorcing the spouse of the prior marriage. Removing the impediment simply moves the marriage to category of voidable marriage.    A voidable marriage is valid until one spouse seeks to legally void the marriage. There must be a judicial decree to dissolve the marriage. The grounds for a voidable marriage are age, impotence, intoxication, fraud/duress, and lack of intent to marry. Family Law Outline &sect; II.A.2.  Example: Adam marries Bethany. A few years later, he marries Cindy. Cindy does not know about Adam&rsquo;s prior marriage and believes in good-faith that she entered into a legal marriage with Adam. Adam and Cindy&rsquo;s marriage is void as a matter of law. Adam then divorces Bethany. The impediment of prior marriage is removed, so Adam and Cindy&rsquo;s marriage would no longer be void as a matter of law. However, Adam and Cindy&rsquo;s marriage then becomes voidable&mdash;valid only until one spouse seeks to legally void the marriage, based on the grounds listed above.    Question 2 &ndash; Children&rsquo;s capacity to contract  Family Law Outline &sect; VI.D goes into detail about some of the special protections (and also limitations) the law imposes on children. For instance, while children can convey property, they cannot execute a valid will. Children are also treated differently in tort law  criminal law. A minor can enter into a legal contract, but because minors are deemed to lack the legal capacity to be held to contractual duties, courts generally will not enforce these contracts.    This does NOT mean that they are incapable of contracting: it simply means that any contract entered into by the minor is voidable at any time by the minor until the age of majority. However, the minor can still choose to hold the other party to the terms of the contract. See Contracts Outline &sect; I.E.6.a. There are a few exceptions&mdash;if a minor contracts for necessities, and these necessities are supplied to the minor, the minor can&rsquo;t just void the contract; they must pay (albeit an amount limited to the reasonable value) for the service or/good provided to them. See Contracts Outline &sect; I.E.6.a.1. There are also some statutory exceptions: for example, an education loan made to a minor may be fully enforceable by the lender. See Contracts Outline &sect; I.E.6. a.2.    Hope this helps!  Best,  Anna    Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-23 14:08:20 wrote:  1. According to the final outline, under Defenses to Annulment, ""when a marriage is void, the only way to defend against the annulment is to deny the existence of the impediment ... removing the impediment merely makes the marriage voidable, but it will not necessarily prevent the annulment."" I don't understand why removing an impediment would still make the marriage voidable.    2. Under Rights and Obligations of Children, ""children may ... enter into contracts as minors,"" but in our Contracts lecture we learned that individuals under the age of 18 do not have the capacity to contract. Would you please help clarify as these statements seem contradictory?"	"Ty Zhang"
