Elisabeth	Logan	"2022-05-22 16:23:53"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	9920	"Hello! In this question, the woman's acceptance via letter counted as an acceptance when she put it in the mail. However, a previous question stated that the mailbox rule does not apply in regards to option contracts, where the acceptance must be receivedby the date the offer expires. In this question, it was not received by that date. I am curious which way is correct, or if I happen to be misunderstanding the explanations? Thank you!"	"Mailbox Rule with Option Contracts"	"Mult. Choice"		704054	1737	410878	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-22 17:03:01"	1	9920	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Elisabeth,  The fact that the woman told the friend to let her know within the next couple of weeks whether she was interested doesn't make the offer irrevocable. For the offer to be irrevocable, there would need to be an option, which would require consideration, or a firm offer, which require the offeror be a merchant. Because there was neither an option or a firm offer, the woman could revoke the offer anytime before acceptance. So, the reason why friend will succeed in the breach of contract action is not because the offer was irrevocable, but because she mailed her acceptance before the woman revoked the offer.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Elisabeth Logan @ 2022-05-22 16:23:53 wrote:  Hello! In this question, the woman's acceptance via letter counted as an acceptance when she put it in the mail. However, a previous question stated that the mailbox rule does not apply in regards to option contracts, where the acceptance must be receivedby the date the offer expires. In this question, it was not received by that date. I am curious which way is correct, or if I happen to be misunderstanding the explanations? Thank you!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Julius	Zavala	"2022-05-21 15:37:54"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	9564	"Question ID# 9564I am confused as to whether the UCC or common law applies in this question.I believe the UCC would apply since the subject matter is a good. Is this correct? Is there any other reason the common law would not apply?"	"Whether UCC or Common Law applies"	"Mult. Choice"		703753	1737	336927	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-21 22:44:42"	1	9564	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Julius,  The UCC applies here because it involves the sale of a good. However, option contracts are available under both the common law and the UCC. Option contracts require consideration. If consideration is provided, the offer becomes irrevocable. If there is no consideration provided, then there is no option contract under the common law or the UCC, and the offer can be revoked at any time. Firm offers are available only under the UCC. Firm offers do not require consideration but do require (i) the offeror is a merchant, (ii) there is an assurance that the offer is to remain open, and (iii) the assurance is contained in a signed writing from the offeror. If these requirements are met, a merchant's offer is irrevocable for the time stated in the offer, or a period not to exceed 90 days. Again, firm offers are different than option contracts because firm offers do not require consideration. A merchant is someone who regularly deals in the type of goods involved in the transaction or otherwise by his occupation holds himself out has having knowledge or skill particular to the practices or goods involved in the transaction. It also includes any businessperson when the transaction is of a commercial nature. Here, a chemistry professor is selling an autographed first edition novel. She is not in the business of regularly dealing in autographed first edition novels; she's just an individual selling a book to a co-worker. Because the professor isn't a merchant, the UCC firm offer rule doesn't apply. And since the colleague did not provide consideration for the option, no option contract was formed.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Julius Zavala @ 2022-05-21 15:37:54 wrote:  Question ID# 9564  I am confused as to whether the UCC or common law applies in this question.  I believe the UCC would apply since the subject matter is a good. Is this correct? Is there any other reason the common law would not apply?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
