Alexander	Hall	"2022-05-20 12:38:16"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	"Question ID# 10012"	"This question presented the issue where the uncle loaned the niece money to pay for law school. After many years she was unable to pay it. She agrees, after the statute of limitations has passed, to repay the debt regardless. I understand the law behind the exception to the requirement for consideration in certain situation to repay debts, but in this situation, isn't the original agreement unenforceable in the first place? The question does not mention anything other than the fact that the uncle gave the niece money, that would imply there was no consideration from him, and that there is no enforceable contract. The correct answer here implies that the second agreement to repay the loan is enforceable without consideration, even though the original agreement to repay would not be since there was no consideration. Is the promise to repay enough for consideration? Am I missing something, or is the question flawed?"	"Confusion about consideration"	"Mult. Choice"		703194	1737	389755	369848	"2022-05-23 10:10:00"	"2022-05-20 20:19:10"	1	10012	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Pamela Prieto"	"Hi Alexander,  No, there was consideration for the original contract. Each party had an obligation under the contract - the uncle's was to lend $50,000 and the niece's was the promise to repay the $50,000. Yes, a promise to pay in exchange for a loan is considered as consideration.  Furthermore, a new promise to pay a debt after the statute of limitations has run is in itself is always enforceable without any new consideration like in Problem 10012, when the niece said ""I know I still owe you $50,000. I will repay you $50,000 if I get a law firm job.&rdquo;A promise to repay a past debt does not require the obligee to assert that he or she will not plead the statute of limitations as a defense.   Hope this clarifies things!  Best,  Pam    Alexander Hall @ 2