Alana	Jones	"2022-05-20 11:46:31"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"What is the difference between easement appurtenant and easement affirmative?"	Easement	General		703139	1737	420384	159137	"2022-05-21 11:11:22"	"2022-05-20 20:16:16"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Steve Blum"	"Hi Alana!  These are really different concepts. See page 80 of the full MBE Real Property outline. An appurtenant easement simply means that the easement is tiedto the land. In other words, the benefits of an easement must corresponddirectly to the use and enjoyment of the possessor of the dominant estate. This would be the opposite of an easement in gross, which is an easementgranted to benefit a particular person (as opposed to the land).Example: A owns lakefront property and grants B, who lives in a town across thelake, an easement to gain access to the lake at a certain point on A&rsquo;s property. Acreated an easement in gross because it benefits B, not any land owned by B.An affirmative easement simply means that the easement gives the holder the right to make affirmative use of another&rsquo;s property (e.g., the right to cross another&rsquo;s land to access a highway). Both an easement in gross and an appurtenant easement could be affirmative.  Hope this helps you.  Steve    Alana Jones @ 2022-05-20 11:46:31 wrote:  What is the difference between easement appurtenant and easement affirmative?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Alana	Jones	"2022-05-20 10:01:25"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	3	"Question is:Which of the following statements regarding the transfer of a deed is TRUE??AThe grantor or his agent must physically deliver the deed to the grantee.BYou Selected:The grantee is generally presumed to have accepted the deed, provided the transfer is for value.CA grantor must intend to make a future transfer of a property interest to the grantee at the time of transfer.DThe grantor’s intent must be explicit.I understand why B is correct and why A  D are wrong, but can you please explain why C is also wrong?"	"Transfer of deed"	AQ	17	703064	1737	420384	435564	"2022-05-20 13:46:58"	"2022-05-20 12:49:31"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Anna Rittgers"	"Hi Alana!  In order to be a valid transfer of property, A deed must be delivered and accepted. For delivery, the grantor must, at the time of transfer, demonstrate a present intent to transfer the property interest.  C is incorrect because it says a &ldquo;grantor must intend to make a future transfer of a property interest at the time of transfer&rdquo;.   Note that the interest itself could be a future interest (for example, a parent retains a life estate in a residence, with remainder interest to an adult child), but the grantor must presently intend to make a transfer of that property interest.   See Real Property Outline &sect; IV.B.1 for more information on delivery.  Hope this helps!  Best,  Anna    Alana Jones @ 2022-05-20 10:01:25 wrote:  Question is:  Which of the following statements regarding the transfer of a deed is TRUE?        ?      A    The grantor or his agent must physically deliver the deed to the grantee.          B    You Selected:The grantee is generally presumed to have accepted the deed, provided the transfer is for value.        C    A grantor must intend to make a future transfer of a property interest to the grantee at the time of transfer.        D    The grantor&rsquo;s intent must be explicit.    I understand why B is correct and why A  D are wrong, but can you please explain why C is also wrong?      "	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-05-19 15:35:35"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	114	"According to the lecture handout, a UCC 2-207 - Confirming Memo issue ""arises when the parties have a contract (usually by verbal agreement) and one party sends a confirming memo with additional terms."" Shouldn't a 2-207 analysis be relevant here? Is it because the quantity term in the confirming memo is a different term rather than an additional term? Exam Tip 2 in the lecture handout states that ""the new terms will very rarely come in."" It seems to me that per 2-207 analysis, the original quantity should hold, but per SOF analysis the new quantity should hold. What am I missing here?Admin wrote:Lecture: Statute of FraudsSubject Outline: MBE CONTRACTS  SALESQuestion ID: 114Hi Ty, UCC 2-207 comes into play when you have an acceptance that seeks to add new or different terms whereas in example 114, we have a verbal contract and then a confirmation of that agreement. So, with both, you’re trying to figure out the actual terms of the contract. But, in example 114, the question is really whether the oral agreement is enforceable (whether it satisfies the SOF). If the SOF is not satisfied, then the quantity term in the written confirmation controls. I hope this helps! Lindsey  Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-18 14:16:37 wrote: How do you reconcile Example 114 with a 2-207 analysis (different terms and confirming memo)? Quantity is an essential term in an agreement per the UCC, so it can't be knocked-out and gap-filled, correct? What would be the result?"	"RE: Example 114"	Handout	"Statute of Frauds"	702733	1737	421938	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-19 15:35:35"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ty,  I see what you&rsquo;re talking about in the lecture handout, and I don&rsquo;t know if I&rsquo;ve ever seen 2-207 tested in that context. Usually, it&rsquo;s tested in the context of example 57: I run a business on the side: Geis&rsquo;s Chainsaws. You send me a purchase order requesting a chainsaw for $400. On the back of this form is an indemnification provision saying &ldquo;seller agrees to indemnify buyer in the event of a lawsuit related to the chainsaw.&rdquo; I send back a confirming memo that has the opposite indemnity provision of the buyer&rsquo;s provision (purported acceptance to previous offer with different terms). That being said, the example that you reference is specifically testing the SOF, not 2-207. Sometimes there might be more than one rule that can apply to the lecture handout examples, but the examples don&rsquo;t discuss those other rules because it is only being used to illustrate one issue. Now, assuming 2-207 applies to this example, and also assuming both parties are merchants, when both parties are merchants, the courts in different jurisdictions disagree as to the result when different terms are included in the merchant offeree&rsquo;s acceptance. A few jurisdictions treat different terms the same as additional terms. Most, however, apply the &ldquo;knock-out&rdquo; rule, under which different terms in the offer and acceptance nullify each other and are &ldquo;knocked out&rdquo; of the contract. When gaps are created after applying the knock-out rule, the court uses Article 2&rsquo;s gap-filling provisions to patch the holes. Since quantity is an essential term under the UCC, it cannot be knocked out and replaced by a gap filler. So the contract would fail for indefiniteness&mdash;the parties failed to agree to a quantity or a means to determine quantity.  I hope this clarifies!  Lindsey    Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-19 15:35:35 wrote:  According to the lecture handout, a UCC 2-207 - Confirming Memo issue ""arises when the parties have a contract (usually by verbal agreement) and one party sends a confirming memo with additional terms."" Shouldn't a 2-207 analysis be relevant here? Is it because the quantity term in the confirming memo is a different term rather than an additional term? Exam Tip 2 in the lecture handout states that ""the new terms will very rarely come in."" It seems to me that per 2-207 analysis, the original quantity should hold, but per SOF analysis the new quantity should hold. What am I missing here?    Admin wrote:  Lecture: Statute of FraudsSubject Outline: MBE CONTRACTS  SALESQuestion ID: 114  Hi Ty,  UCC 2-207 comes into play when you have an acceptance that seeks to add new or different terms whereas in example 114, we have a verbal contract and then a confirmation of that agreement. So, with both, you&rsquo;re trying to figure out the actual terms of the contract. But, in example 114, the question is really whether the oral agreement is enforceable (whether it satisfies the SOF). If the SOF is not satisfied, then the quantity term in the written confirmation controls.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-18 14:16:37 wrote:  How do you reconcile Example 114 with a 2-207 analysis (different terms and confirming memo)? Quantity is an essential term in an agreement per the UCC, so it can't be knocked-out and gap-filled, correct? What would be the result?"	"Ty Zhang"
Alana	Jones	"2022-05-19 14:59:25"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"		"One of the assement questions on the lecture Concurrent Estates asked the main difference between joint tenancy and tenancy in common. I put possession and the answer was title I believe. I am confused why that is the answer because I thought in both joint tenancy  tenants in common the people who receive the interest must be given rights through the same instrument."	"Property- Tenants in common"	Lecture	"Real property"	702710	1737	420384	397561	"2022-05-19 23:41:51"	"2022-05-19 18:51:54"	1	0	"MBE REAL PROPERTY"	0	"Nicole Werner"	"Hi Alana:    The way the title is held is the biggest difference between joint tenancy and tenancy in common. In a tenancy in common, each joint tenant owns an equal share of the property, but there is no right of survivorship. Each tenant can unilaterally transfer, mortgage, or devise their interest in the property without affecting the interests of the other tenant. For example, if two tenants hold equal interest in a property in tenancy in common and one dies, the deceased&rsquo;s interest in the property is distributed per his will (or through intestate laws).    In a joint tenancy, the tenants have the right of survivorship. For example, if two tenants hold equal interest in a property in joint tenancy, if one of the tenant&rsquo;s dies, the deceased&rsquo;s interest in the property is terminated and automatically goes to the surviving tenant. (Please see Real Property Outline Sections I. C. 1. And I. C. 2.).    Good luck!    Nicole    Alana Jones @ 2022-05-19 14:59:25 wrote:  One of the assement questions on the lecture Concurrent Estates asked the main difference between joint tenancy and tenancy in common. I put possession and the answer was title I believe. I am confused why that is the answer because I thought in both joint tenancy  tenants in common the people who receive the interest must be given rights through the same instrument."	"Lindsey Hallam"
