Molly	Skjerven	"2022-05-18 15:28:34"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"			"In the Hammond MPT outline, it says that the case US v Robb is federal and persuasive but the way I read the jurisdiction information in the introduction made me believe it was binding because it came from a higher court in the same circut. Can you offer some clarity on how I should be understanding jurisdiction?"	"MPT In RE HAMMONED "	Essay		702147	1737	416239	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-18 17:12:48"	1	0	"MULTISTATE PERFORMANCE TEST"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Molly,  Although the MPT takes place in a fictitious jurisdiction, it still follows the basic court structure of existing courts in the U.S. Remember that state courts operate independently of the federal courts. On a typical MPT, Franklin, Columbia, and Olympia are individual states with their own court systems. Franklin's courts include the District Court (the trial court), Court of Appeal, and Supreme Court. These states exist in the 15th Circuit, which is a federal system with its own court structure. In the MPT In Re Hammond, the dispute is occurring at the state level in front of a grand jury in Gordon County. The issue is a state issue, involving Franklin's own Rules of Professional Conduct and Evidence. Thus, the federal case U.S. v. Robb is merely persuasive. If the case was from the Supreme Court of Franklin, then it would be binding.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Molly Skjerven @ 2022-05-18 15:28:34 wrote:  In the Hammond MPT outline, it says that the case US v Robb is federal and persuasive but the way I read the jurisdiction information in the introduction made me believe it was binding because it came from a higher court in the same circut. Can you offer some clarity on how I should be understanding jurisdiction?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
