Sarah	Castle	"2022-05-18 12:59:16"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	4	"I do not understand why the following statement regarding a unilateral contract is true ""The offeror cannot require the offeree to complete performance of the contract."" Is there a different way that you can explain this?           "	"Unilateral K Requirement of Complete Performance?"	General	"Chapter 3"	701989	1737	349986	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-18 15:35:56"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Sarah,  The offeree is not required to complete performance and can stop at any time. Example: You are swimming in the Alcatraz race, but you get tired and swim to a boat. Can I sue you for breach of contract? No; there&rsquo;s no agreement because there is no acceptance until performance is complete (so, no contract).  I hope this helps clarify!  Lindsey    Sarah Castle @ 2022-05-18 12:59:16 wrote:  I do not understand why the following statement regarding a unilateral contract is true ""The offeror cannot require the offeree to complete performance of the contract."" Is there a different way that you can explain this? "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Ty	Zhang	"2022-05-17 19:22:52"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	51	"The Mailbox Rule states that an acceptance sent by mail is effective when the letter is sent. Section 4 of the Acceptance lecture handout states that the Mailbox Rule does not apply ""to other types of communications (e.g., revocations, rejections)."" In Example 51, a rejection is mailed out, and an acceptance is mailed out afterward. The Mailbox Rule doesn't apply to rejections, so the rejection should only be valid upon receipt. Since the acceptance is sent prior to the receipt of the rejection, shouldn't there be a contract?"	"Example 51: Mailbox Rule"	Handout	Acceptance	701754	1737	421938	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-17 20:30:41"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ty,  If the offeree sends an acceptance and later sends a communication rejecting the offer, then the acceptance will generally control even if the offeror receives the rejection first. If a communication is sent rejecting the offer, and a later communication is sent accepting the contract, then the mailbox rule will not apply, and the first one to be received by the offeror will prevail. An acceptance or rejection is received when the writing comes into the possession of the offeror or her agent, or when it is deposited in her mailbox. The offeror need not actually read the communication that is received first for it to prevail. In example 51, you first send a rejection and then mail an acceptance. Because the rejection was mailed first, then the mailbox rule will not apply, and the first one to be received by the offeror will prevail. So, it will depend on which is received first.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Ty Zhang @ 2022-05-17 19:22:52 wrote:  The Mailbox Rule states that an acceptance sent by mail is effective when the letter is sent. Section 4 of the Acceptance lecture handout states that the Mailbox Rule does not apply ""to other types of communications (e.g., revocations, rejections)."" In Example 51, a rejection is mailed out, and an acceptance is mailed out afterward. The Mailbox Rule doesn't apply to rejections, so the rejection should only be valid upon receipt. Since the acceptance is sent prior to the receipt of the rejection, shouldn't there be a contract?"	"Lindsey Hallam"
