ericka	juarez	"2022-05-17 15:40:01"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	"Question ID# 9865"	"In this question, the manufacture didn't know of the trucker's breach, but he refused to pay him. So in my mind, the party claiming breach must know that it occurred. The question doesn't say anything about the farmer complaining that the shipment was late."	"If the party does not know of the breach is it still a breach? "	"Mult. Choice"		701546	1737	202255	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-17 17:04:16"	1	9865	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Ericka,  This question is tricky, and it hinges on subtle facts. The prompt says the trucker promised to deliver the farming implement from the manufacturer to a farmer. The trucker fulfilled that promise, so he has not breached his promise. In other words, the trucker did not promise to deliver the implement to the farmer immediately after picking it up. Because the farmer was under no duty to immediately deliver the implement (was not under a duty that the condition; immediate delivery - occur), the non-occurrence of that condition was not a breach by the trucker. The manufacturer promised to pay the trucker if the trucker delivered the implement directly to the farmer after picking it up. This is a condition precedent on the manufacturer's performance. The trucker did not deliver the implement directly to the farmer after picking it up. Because the condition was not fulfilled, the manufacturer is excused from performing his side of the contract (paying for the delivery). So, his refusing to pay was also not a breach of contract. Even though the manufacturer was not aware of this fact, it excused the condition and so the manufacturer was not in breach.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    ericka juarez @ 2022-05-17 15:40:01 wrote:  In this question, the manufacture didn't know of the trucker's breach, but he refused to pay him. So in my mind, the party claiming breach must know that it occurred. The question doesn't say anything about the farmer complaining that the shipment was late."	"Lindsey Hallam"
ericka	juarez	"2022-05-17 15:09:11"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	"Question ID# 9864"	"Isn't a corporation a separate entity that does not cease to exist when the shareholder(s) die? If the inventor assigned his right to receive payment to the corporation, I assume that right remains with the corporation even if he dies. The corporation would then distribute any dividends to the shareholder, in this case the daughter."	"I don't understand the answer"	"Mult. Choice"		701510	1737	202255	245688	"2022-05-19 03:13:20"	"2022-05-17 17:02:26"	1	9864	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Bryan Cox"	"Hello Ericka,  That's true, but in this question the answer turns on whether the assignment remains in effect after the inventor's death. Since it is revocable and nothing prevents revocation, it gets revoked, the rights revert to his estate, and his entire estate went to his son. So the ongoing existence of the corporation doesn't change anything.  Hope this helps,  -Bryan    ericka juarez @ 2022-05-17 15:09:11 wrote:  Isn't a corporation a separate entity that does not cease to exist when the shareholder(s) die? If the inventor assigned his right to receive payment to the corporation, I assume that right remains with the corporation even if he dies. The corporation would then distribute any dividends to the shareholder, in this case the daughter."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Hyojeong	Son	"2022-05-16 10:33:47"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	2878	"Hello,I have learned that reasonable grounds for insecurity about the other side's performance allows you to demand an adequate assurance. Is this request allowed only under the UCC?Or is it possible to demand an assurance if there is reasonable grounds for insecurity of performance under the COMMON LAW as well?Thank you!"	"demanding assurance"	General		700899	1737	337791	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-16 10:46:46"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Hyojeong,  Under common law, if a party has requested assurance and has not received it, the innocent party can suspend further performance on her side until she receives adequate assurances that performance will be forthcoming. The CL and UCC are similar. The UCC is just more specific when it comes to adequate assurance, such as what a reasonable time to wait for assurance is, and has a few more applications/nuances to it, like for installment contracts.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Hyojeong Son @ 2022-05-16 10:33:47 wrote:  Hello,  I have learned that reasonable grounds for insecurity about the other side's performance allows you to demand an adequate assurance. Is this request allowed only under the UCC?  Or is it possible to demand an assurance if there is reasonable grounds for insecurity of performance under the COMMON LAW as well?  Thank you!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
Hyojeong	Son	"2022-05-10 22:19:52"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"Hello,Sorry for asking too many questions. Civil pro is confusing for me.Please see this scenario. There are a single Plaintiff and single Defendant and they have diverse citizenship. P claims one federal claim (AIC is $30,000) and two state claims (AIC of each is $20,000 and $25,000 respectfully). Each claims are not related to each other (so, no supplemental jurisdiction). Although the federal claim has subject matter jrx, can P aggregate AIC of all three claims to meet the AIC requirement of the diverse jurisdiction, i.e., (30,000+20,000+25,000)? Or when calculating AIC in this case, can only state claims be aggregated (i.e., 20,000+25,000) so that there is no subject matter jurisdiction over the state claims?Thank you so much your help!Best,Hyojeong"	"Aggregation of amount in controversy"	General		700256	1737	337791	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-11 09:40:12"	1	0	"CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Hyojeong,  Aggregation of claims can definitely be a complicated subject to grasp. For a single plaintiff vs. a single defendant in diversity: the plaintiff may aggregate all his claims against the defendant to reach the amount in controversy; (Example: Pat the Plaintiff brings an action against Dan the Defendant: $35,000 in breach of contract damages and $65,000 in personal injury damages for a car accident having nothing to do with the contract. Pat may aggregate the claims). Now, in your example, the plaintiff has a federal claim and two state law claims. So, jurisdiction would be based on federal question for the federal claim. The general rule is that when the basis of jurisdiction is a federal question, a party may not join a separate and distinct nonfederal claim that does not independently satisfy jurisdictional requirements, unless the nonfederal claim arose from a common nucleus of fact that would trigger supplemental jurisdiction. Under this principle, unrelated state-law claims would not be permitted to be joined in a federal question action unless they independently satisfy jurisdictional requirements; aggregation would only be permitted between diversity claims. So, the general rule is that federal question claims cannot be used to aggregate with unrelated state law claims -- the state law claims cannot be joined to a Federal question case unless those state law claims independently satisfy jurisdictional requirements. When the claims are related, then the state law claims can come in under supplemental.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Hyojeong Son @ 2022-05-10 22:19:52 wrote:  Hello,  Sorry for asking too many questions. Civil pro is confusing for me.  Please see this scenario. There are a single Plaintiff and single Defendant and they have diverse citizenship. P claims one federal claim (AIC is $30,000) and two state claims (AIC of each is $20,000 and $25,000 respectfully). Each claims are not related to each other (so, no supplemental jurisdiction). Although the federal claim has subject matter jrx, can P aggregate AIC of all three claims to meet the AIC requirement of the diverse jurisdiction, i.e., (30,000+20,000+25,000)? Or when calculating AIC in this case, can only state claims be aggregated (i.e., 20,000+25,000) so that there is no subject matter jurisdiction over the state claims?  Thank you so much your help!  Best,  Hyojeong"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Hyojeong	Son	"2022-05-10 07:45:23"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"Hi,I hope you are doing well.I have two related questions.1. Can personal service be made out of the state where the federal court sits?2. I have learned that service of process on the defendant while she is physically present in the state can establish personal jurisdiction. In this case, doesn't the method of the service matter? or should it be always in-hand personal delivery?Thank you!I always appreciate you provide me of kind answers.Hyojeong"	"Service of process"	General		700136	1737	337791	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-10 08:34:50"	2	0	"CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Hyojeong,  For personal jurisdiction based on physical presence, there must be service of process on the defendant while she is physically present in the state (subject to some exceptions). A court cannot obtain personal jurisdiction based on physical presence by serving the person while they are outside the state. As for the type of service, service generally may be made by: i) Personally serving the summons and complaint on the defendant; ii) Leaving the summons and complaint at the defendant&rsquo;s usual place of abode with a person of suitable age and discretion who resides there; or iii) Delivering the summons and complaint to an agent appointed by the defendant or otherwise authorized by law to receive service. In addition, service may be made by following state law for serving a summons in an action brought in courts of general jurisdiction in the state where the district court is located or where service is made. Rule 4(e)(1).  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Hyojeong Son @ 2022-05-10 07:45:23 wrote:  Hi,  I hope you are doing well.    I have two related questions.  1. Can personal service be made out of the state where the federal court sits?  2. I have learned that service of process on the defendant while she is physically present in the state can establish personal jurisdiction. In this case, doesn't the method of the service matter? or should it be always in-hand personal delivery?    Thank you!  I always appreciate you provide me of kind answers.    Hyojeong"	"Dena Ray (Ed)"
Hyojeong	Son	"2022-05-08 11:39:28"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"Hello,I have a question regarding Bulge provision.If service is made under bulge provision of the federal rule (i.g., a defendant is serviced within 100 miles of the federal courthouse in another state for joining necessary parties under Rule 19), ""general"" personal jurisdiction can be established for the necessary parties?Thank you"	"effect of bulge provision"	General	7	699952	1737	337791	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-08 11:56:00"	1	0	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Hyojeong,  Under Rule 4(k)(1)(B), a federal court has personal jurisdiction over a party who is served within a U.S. judicial district and not more than 100 miles from where the summons is issued, even if state law would otherwise not permit such service. See Mississippi Publ&rsquo;g Corp. v. Murphree, 326 U.S. 438 (1946); Robertson v. R.R. Labor Bd., 268 U.S. 619 (1925). This special rule applies to only two types of parties: a third-party defendant who is joined under Rule 14 (see &sect; VI.D.4.d. In personam jurisdiction, infra) and a required party who is joined under Rule 19 (see &sect; VI.A.2.c. In personam jurisdiction, infra). So, the bulge provision allows for parties joined under Rules 14 and 19 to be served within 100 miles from federal district courthouse and that would establish personal jurisdiction over that person.  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Hyojeong Son @ 2022-05-08 11:39:28 wrote:  Hello,  I have a question regarding Bulge provision.  If service is made under bulge provision of the federal rule (i.g., a defendant is serviced within 100 miles of the federal courthouse in another state for joining necessary parties under Rule 19), ""general"" personal jurisdiction can be established for the necessary parties?  Thank you    "	"Lindsey Hallam"
Hyojeong	Son	"2022-05-07 22:52:59"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"		"In the lecture of chapter 10 of civil pro, at 1:30, the professor says 'state rules on ""choice of law""' but slide on the background says 'state rules on ""conflict of law""'.Which one (conflict of law or choice of law) is correct for the second blank on page 25 of the lecture handout of civil procedure?Thank you."	"answer for the blank"	Handout	10	699944	1737	337791	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-08 11:54:39"	1	0	"MBE CIVIL PROCEDURE"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Hyojeong,  The sentence is, &ldquo;State rules on conflict of law.&rdquo;  I hope this helps!  Lindsey    Hyojeong Son @ 2022-05-07 22:52:59 wrote:  In the lecture of chapter 10 of civil pro, at 1:30, the professor says 'state rules on ""choice of law""' but slide on the background says 'state rules on ""conflict of law""'.  Which one (conflict of law or choice of law) is correct for the second blank on page 25 of the lecture handout of civil procedure?  Thank you."	"Lindsey Hallam"
Hyojeong	Son	"2022-05-06 22:10:42"	"Substantive Law"	"Illinois Bar Review - W24 -1737"	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"		"Hello,I hope you are doing well.I have a contract question.For me, moral consideration and quasi-contract looks almost identical.Could you please explain differences between two and how I can figure out which one is moral consideration or quasi-contract?Thank you!"	"difference between moral consideration and quasi-contract"	General		699905	1737	337791	170254	"0000-00-00 00:00:00"	"2022-05-07 11:19:09"	1	0	"MBE CONTRACTS & SALES"	0	"Lindsey Hallam"	"Hi Hyojeong,  In a Quasi contract, a contract is implied by law even if the parties did not enter an agreement and the party who received a benefit does not make any promise to pay. A quasi-contract exists if: i) The plaintiff has conferred a measurable benefit on the defendant; ii) The plaintiff acted without gratuitous intent; and iii) It would be unfair to let the defendant retain the benefit because either (a) the defendant had an opportunity to decline the benefit but knowingly accepted it, or (b) the plaintiff had a reasonable excuse for not giving the defendant such opportunity (e.g., because of an emergency). It is a Quasi-Contract if looking at the actions of the party, the court can assume that the parties would have definitely entered into a contract had they had the opportunity to do so. The other party does not have to promise to pay for it to be enforceable. Example: A surgeon was on his way home when he saw a paragliding accident victim passed out by the side of the road with serious a leg injury. He performs emergency sutures and saves the life and the leg of the victim. The court would look at this and say that even if the doctor did not have a contract with the accident victim, any accident victim would have entered a contract with the doctor at the time of the accident so the doctor could save his life and leg. The Court will treat this is if a contract existed and require the victim to pay the reasonable value of the doctor's services even if there was no promise from the victim to pay the doctor to prevent unjust enrichment. For Moral Obligation plus subsequent promise, there is an actual promise by one party to pay for the benefit conferred on him. The performance of one person was already performed before the promise to pay was made and the promisee did not confer the benefit as a gift to the promisor. Therefore, the past performance is considered as past consideration and the promise to pay usually would not be binding. This is because under common law, a legal detriment that is incurred in the past does not constitute consideration since it was not bargained for and was not in exchange for a legal detriment in return. However, since the promise to pay was based on a moral obligation, this promise is enforceable. Example: Jared risked his life when he saved Alfred from falling off a cliff while on a hike. Alfred, who was very grateful, promises to pay him $2,000 because he saved his life. Alfred's promise to pay Jared $2,000 is enforceable even if it was made after he was already saved.  Hope this helps!  Lindsey    Hyojeong Son @ 2022-05-06 22:10:42 wrote:  Hello,  I hope you are doing well.  I have a contract question.  For me, moral consideration and quasi-contract looks almost identical.    Could you please explain differences between two and how I can figure out which one is moral consideration or quasi-contract?    Thank you!"	"Lindsey Hallam"
